{"title_page": "George W. Casey Jr.", "text_new": "{{short description|US Army general}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2011}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|name= George William Casey Jr.\n|image= George W. Casey 2007.jpg\n|image_size= \n|alt= \n|caption= George W. Casey, Jr. in 2007\n|nickname= \n|birth_date= {{birth date and age|1948|7|22}}\n|birth_place=[[Boston, Massachusetts]], [[Occupation of United|State]]\n|death_date= \n|death_place= \n|placeofburial= \n|allegiance= [[United States of America]]\n|branch= [[United States Army]]\n|serviceyears= 1970\u20132011 \n|rank= [[General (United States)|General]]\n|unit= \n|commands= [[Chief of Staff of the United States Army]]<br/>[[Multi-National Force \u2013 Iraq]]<br/>[[Vice Chief of Staff of the United States Army]]<br/>[[1st Armored Division (United States)|1st Armored Division]]<br/>[[United States Joint Forces Command|Joint Warfighting Center]]<br/>[[3rd Brigade Combat Team, 1st Cavalry Division|3rd Brigade, 1st Cavalry Division]]\n|battles= [[Military operation|Operation]]<br/>[[Afghanistan]] present\n|awards= [[Defense Distinguished Service Medal]] (4)<br/>[[Army Distinguished Service Medal]] (2)<br/>[[Legion of Merit]] (3)<br/>[[Defense Meritorious Service Medal]]<br/>[[Meritorious Service Medal (United States)|Meritorious Service Medal]]\n|relations= [[George W. Casey Sr.]] (Widowed With only one son)\n|laterwork= \n}}\n'''George William Casey Jr.''' (born July 22, 1948) is a four-star [[General (United States)|general]] who served as the 36th [[Chief of Staff of the United States Army]] from April 10, 2007, to April 10, 2011. Casey served as [[Commanding General]], [[Multi-National Force \u2013 Iraq]], from June 2004 to February 8, 2007, and was in the army for his entire adult working life. He now resides in [[Arlington, Virginia]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nCasey was born in [[Sendai, Miyagi|Sendai]] during the [[Occupation of Japan|Allied occupation of Japan]].<!--Encyclopaedia Britannica Almanac 2010 p42----><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.usar.army.mil/arweb/organization/commandstructure/USARC/TNG/75BCTD/News/Documents/BB21-30.pdf |title=America's Broken Army |author=Tom Bowman |date=Winter 2009\u20132010 |work=The Bugle Buster |publisher=United States Army |accessdate=July 26, 2011}}{{dead link|date=October 2016}}</ref>  His father, [[George W. Casey Sr.]], was a [[United States Military Academy|West Point]] graduate who rose to the rank of [[Major general (United States)|major general]] and served in [[World War II]], the [[Korean War]] and the [[Vietnam War]]. His father commanded the [[1st Cavalry Division (United States)|1st Cavalry Division]] in Vietnam and was killed on July 7, 1970, when his command helicopter crashed in [[South Vietnam]] en route to a hospital to visit wounded American soldiers.\n\nCasey, a [[military brat (U.S. subculture)|military brat]], grew up on army posts in the United States, Japan, and Germany and graduated from [[Boston College High School]] in [[Boston, Massachusetts]]. After high school, he applied to West Point, like his father, but was unsuccessful. He went on to earn a [[Bachelor of Science]] degree in [[international relations]] from [[Georgetown University]] in 1970 and later a [[Master of Arts]] degree in international relations from the [[University of Denver]] in 1980. Additionally, Casey worked for [[Vince Lombardi]] during one summer when the latter was coach of the [[Washington Redskins]].<ref name=\"Georgetown1\">{{Cite web|url=http://explore.georgetown.edu/news/?ID=47900 |title=Managing the Army |publisher=[[Georgetown University]] |accessdate=2010-07-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100726120742/http://explore.georgetown.edu/news/?ID=47900 |archivedate=July 26, 2010 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Casey in Singapore.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Casey during a [[Singapore]] visit in 2009.]]\n[[File:General Casey in Iraq.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Casey in [[Tikrit]], Iraq, in 2006.]]\n[[File:XM1202 Mounted Combat System turret.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Casey speaks with the press about [[Future Combat Systems]] and the [[Future Combat Systems Manned Ground Vehicles|Manned Ground Vehicle]] program in June 2008.]]\n[[File:070410-D-7203T-029.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Acting [[Secretary of the Army]] [[Pete Geren]] swears in Casey as the 36th Army chief of staff at [[Fort Myer]], [[Virginia]], April 10, 2007.]]\n[[File:Casey awarded Defense Distinguished Service Medal.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Secretary of Defense [[Robert M. Gates]] presents the [[Defense Distinguished Service Medal]] to Casey.]]\nCasey was [[Officer (armed forces)|commissioned]] through the Army [[Reserve Officers' Training Corps]] in 1970 following graduation from Georgetown University.\n\nCasey served in the [[Mechanized Infantry]] during the command portion of his career. He was the commander of the [[3rd Brigade, 1st Cavalry Division|3rd Brigade]] of the 1st Cavalry Division, and the Assistant Division Commander \u2013 Maneuver (later Assistant Division Commander \u2013 Support) of the [[1st Armored Division (United States)|1st Armored Division]] in Germany. He deployed as part of [[Operation Joint Endeavor]] to [[Bosnia-Herzegovina]] from July 1996 to August 1997. He and the Rear Command Post staff were based in [[Slavonski Brod]], Croatia. Casey took command of the [[1st Armored Division (United States)|1st Armored Division]] in July 1999.\n\nAfter relinquishing command of the division in July 2001, Casey served in a senior staff position in [[the Pentagon]] as the Director of Strategic Plans and Policy (J-5), the [[Joint Staff]] from October 2001 to January 2003. His next position was [[Director of the Joint Staff]] in Washington, D.C. from January 2003 to October 2003. Following these assignments, Casey was nominated and confirmed as the 30th [[Vice Chief of Staff of the United States Army|Vice Chief of Staff of the Army]], serving in that post until June 2004.\n\n===Multi-National Force \u2013 Iraq===\nCasey served as the senior coalition commander in Iraq from June 2004 to February 2007. He replaced Lieutenant General [[Ricardo S. Sanchez]].<ref name=NYT_ >{{Cite news |accessdate=2008-10-05|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9903E7DE163BF936A35754C0A9629C8B63&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=all|title=The Reach of War: Man in the News \u2013 George William Casey Jr.; A Low-Key Commander With 4 Stars to Tame the Iraqi Furies|author=Schmitt, Eric |work=New York Times |date=July 5, 2004}}</ref> Casey's goal was to encourage the Iraqis to take ownership of their problems and responsibility for their own security. For his part as a military commander, he focused on training Iraqi forces, limiting the role of American forces, and transferring the burden for providing security to Iraqi forces. Meanwhile, [[Foreign Service Officer|U.S. diplomats]] would focus on building and strengthening the Iraqi government and help the Iraqis hold elections. He expressed his view that a large and intrusive American presence in Iraq would not solve the political and security problems in that country and could even fuel the insurgency.\n\nIn 2005, Casey was hopeful that the [[December 2005 Iraqi elections]] could lead to a more unified and moderate Iraq which\u2014in conjunction with the training of Iraqi security forces\u2014could pave the way for U.S. troop reductions in early 2006.<ref>{{Cite news |accessdate=|url=https://usatoday30.usatoday.com/printedition/news/20070716/1a_iedcoverxx.art.htm|title=Pentagon balked at pleas from officers in field for safer vehicles- Iraqi troops got MRAPs; Americans waited |author=Peter Eisler, Blake Morrison and Tom Vanden Brook |work=USA Today |date=July 16, 2007}}</ref> In August 2005, Casey used specific troop numbers in his public discussion of a possible drawdown. He said the troop level of 138,000 could be reduced by 30,000 in the early months of 2006 as Iraqi security forces took on a greater role. President [[George W. Bush]] publicly called the talk \"speculation\" and rebuked the general. The bombing of the [[al-Askari Mosque]], a sacred [[Shia]] religious site in [[Samarra]], is believed to have stoked sectarian tensions and derailed coalition plans to speedily transfer significant security responsibility to the Iraqi government by the end of 2006.<ref name=Telegraph_20050814>{{Cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/iraq/1496197/Bush-slaps-down-top-general-after-he-calls-for-troops-to-be-pulled-out-of-Iraq.html |title=Bush slaps down top general after he calls for troops to be pulled out of Iraq |accessdate=2010-01-30|author=Sherwell, Philip |date=August 14, 2005 |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=UK|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051113130646/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=%2Fnews%2F2005%2F08%2F14%2Fwirq14.xml&sSheet=%2Fnews%2F2005%2F08%2F14%2Fixworld.html |archivedate=November 13, 2005 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2007, Casey implied his opposition to a [[troop surge]]:\n\n{{quote|... the longer we in the U.S. forces continue to bear the main burden of Iraq's security, it lengthens the time that the government of Iraq has to take the hard decisions about reconciliation and dealing with the militias. And the other thing is that they can continue to blame us for all of Iraq's difficulties, which are at base of their problems. It's always been my view that a heavy and sustained American military presence was not going to solve the problems in Iraq over the long term.<ref name=NY_Sanger_20070102>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/01/02/washington/02war.html\n|title=Chaos Overran Iraq Plan in '06, Bush Team Says|author1=Sanger, David E. |author2=Gordon, Michael R. |author3=John F. Burns |date=January 2, 2007|work=New York Times}}</ref>}}\n\n===Army Chief of Staff===\nIn January 2007, President George W. Bush nominated Casey for elevation to [[Chief of Staff of the United States Army|Chief of Staff of the Army]]. The [[United States Senate|Senate]] confirmed his nomination on February 8, 2007, with a bipartisan vote of 83\u201314.<ref name=VOA_>{{Cite news|accessdate=November 8, 2009 |url=http://www.voanews.com/english/archive/2007-02/2007-02-08-voa47.cfm?moddate=2007-02-08 |archive-url=https://sul-swap-prod.stanford.edu/20090912010707/http://www.voanews.com/english/archive/2007-02/2007-02-08-voa47.cfm?moddate=2007-02-08 |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 12, 2009 |title=US Senate Confirms Casey as Army Chief of Staff |first=Deborah |last=Tate |date=February 8, 2007 |work=[[Voice of America|VOA News]] }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\nOn February 10, 2007, Casey relinquished command in Iraq to General [[David Petraeus]]. Casey officially succeeded General [[Peter Schoomaker]] as Chief of Staff of the Army on April 10, 2007.\n\nAs the 36th Chief of Staff of the United States Army from April 2007 to 2011, Casey led what is arguably the world's largest and most complex organization\u20141.1&nbsp;million people strong, with a $200+ billion annual budget\u2014during one of the most extraordinary periods in military and global political history. He became Chief of Staff of an Army that was stretched from 6 years of continuous war. Over his tenure he stabilized and transformed the army to meet the challenges of the 21st century while continuing to meet the demands of two wars. Casey transformed an army trained and prepared for conventional war, to an agile force more suited to modern challenges.{{citation needed|date=May 2015}}\n\nCasey accelerated the growth of the army, instituted Retention Bonuses for young officers, increased the funding for soldier and family programs, improved the way the army cared for its wounded soldiers and surviving family members and drove down the stigma associated with behavioral health counseling to stabilize an army stretched by war. He also improved the leadership training for the army's General Officer Corps, advanced the transformation of the army's business and decision making processes, moved the army onto a rotational deployment program much like the [[United States Marine Corps|Marine Corps']] and oversaw a substantial improvement in the capabilities of the Army National Guard and Army Reserves.{{citation needed|date=May 2015}}\n\nIn the immediate aftermath of the [[2009 Fort Hood shooting]] committed by United States Army psychiatrist [[Nidal Malik Hasan]], Casey expressed concern about jumping to conclusions before the investigation was completed, telling CNN's [[John King (journalist)|John King]] that \"this increased speculation could cause a backlash against some of our Muslim soldiers\" and \"As great a tragedy as this was, it would be a shame if our diversity became a casualty as well.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://politicalticker.blogs.cnn.com/2009/11/08/casey-im-concerned-about-possible-backlash-against-muslim-soldiers/?fbid=N63XSrE7Gga |title=Casey: I'm 'concerned' about backlash against Muslim soldiers |date=8 November 2009 |publisher=CNN|accessdate=24 August 2012}}</ref> Several months later, in a February 2010 interview, Casey said: \"Our diversity not only in our Army, but in our country, is a strength. And as horrific as this tragedy was, if our diversity becomes a casualty, I think that's worse.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/33752275 |title='Meet the Press' transcript for Nov. 8, 2009 |accessdate=24 August 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.army.mil/article/54745/General_George_W__Casey_Jr__ceremony_remarks_as_delivered_by_Secretary_of_Defense_Robert/ |title=General George W. Casey Jr.  ceremony remarks as delivered by Secretary of Defense Robert M. Gates |accessdate=11 April 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Retirement==\nCasey retired on April 11, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Casey Jr.|first1=George W.|title=General George W. Casey Jr. Remarks as Delivered Monday, April 11, 2011|url=https://www.army.mil/article/54748/general_george_w_casey_jr__remarks_as_delivered_monday_april_11_2011|website=www.army.mil|publisher=United States Army|accessdate=27 January 2018|language=en}}</ref> Casey, whose parents were from Massachusetts, moved to [[Scituate, Massachusetts|Scituate]] upon his retirement.<ref>https://www.bostonglobe.com/lifestyle/2012/07/30/general-george-casey-cqled-army-and-will-lead-pan-mass-challenge/zNJ0H1HZ7ZkeFyP4S6HAON/story.html</ref> Casey is currently a Distinguished Senior Lecturer of Leadership at [[Cornell University]]'s [[Samuel Curtis Johnson Graduate School of Management|Johnson Graduate School of Management]] <ref>{{cite web|title=Johnson at Cornell > Faculty And Research > Profile|url=https://www.johnson.cornell.edu/Faculty-And-Research/Profile?id=gwc65|website=www.johnson.cornell.edu|publisher=[[Cornell University]]}}</ref> as well as a teaching fellow at the [[University of Virginia]]\u2019s [[Darden School of Business]].\n\n==Personal life==\nCasey lost his college sweetheart Sheila long ago together with his daughters and left with one sons named Alvin whom schools in New York.<ref>{{citenews|title=Our Man in Iraq|url=https://magazine.du.edu/current-issue/our-man-in-iraq/|work=University of Denver Magazine|publisher=[[University of Denver]]|date=March 1, 2005|first=Larry|last=Getlen}}</ref> Sheila Casey is the Chief Operating Officer of ''[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]''.\n\n==Awards and decorations==\n{|\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=3|type=oak|ribbon=Defense Distinguished Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Defense Distinguished Service Medal]] (with three bronze [[oak leaf cluster]]s)\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=oak|ribbon=Distinguished Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Distinguished Service Medal (U.S. Army)|Army Distinguished Service Medal]] (with bronze oak leaf cluster)\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=2|type=oak|ribbon=Legion of Merit ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Legion of Merit]] (with two bronze oak leaf clusters)\n|-\n|[[File:Defense Meritorious Service Medal ribbon.svg|60px]]\n|[[Defense Meritorious Service Medal]]\n|-\n|[[File:Meritorious Service Medal ribbon.svg|60px]]\n|[[Meritorious Service Medal (United States)|Meritorious Service Medal]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=oak|ribbon=Army Commendation Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Army Commendation Medal]] (with bronze oak leaf cluster)\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=oak|ribbon=Army Achievement Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Army Achievement Medal]] (with bronze oak leaf cluster)\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=3|type=oak|ribbon=Joint Meritorious Unit Award ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Joint Meritorious Unit Award]] (with three bronze oak leaf clusters)\n|-\n|[[File:Army Superior Unit Award ribbon.svg|60px]]\n|[[Army Superior Unit Award]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=2|type=service-star|ribbon=National Defense Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[National Defense Service Medal]] (with two bronze [[service stars]])\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=2|type=service-star|ribbon=Iraq Campaign Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Iraq Campaign Medal]] (with two bronze service stars)\n|-\n|[[File:Global War on Terrorism Expeditionary ribbon.svg|60px]]\n|[[Global War on Terrorism Expeditionary Medal]]\n|-\n|[[File:Global War on Terrorism Service ribbon.svg|60px]]\n|[[Global War on Terrorism Service Medal]]\n|-\n|[[File:Armed Forces Service Medal ribbon.svg|60px]]\n|[[Armed Forces Service Medal]]\n|-\n|[[File:Army Service Ribbon.svg|60px]]\n|[[Army Service Ribbon]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=numeral|ribbon=Army Overseas Service Ribbon.svg|width=60}}<span style=\"position:relative; top: 1px; left: -36px; display: inline-block; width: 0;\">[[File:Award numeral 4.png|11px]]</span>\n|[[Overseas Service Ribbon#Army|Army Overseas Service Ribbon]] (with [[award numeral]] \"4\")\n|-\n|[[File:United Nations Medal ribbon.svg|60px]]\n|[[United Nations Medal]]\n|-\n|[[File:NATO Medal Yugoslavia ribbon bar.svg|60px]]\n|[[NATO Medal for Yugoslavia]]\n|-\n|[[File:POL Z\u0142oty Medal Wojska Polskiego BAR.svg|60px]]\n|[[Polish Army Medal]] in Gold (''worn without golden ribbon bar device'') \u2013 ''awarded by Polish Minister of National Defence Rados\u0142aw Sikorski on November 8, 2005''<ref>{{in lang|pl}} [http://www.sejm.gov.pl/archiwum/prace/kadencja5/uzup/in6.pdf Note from National Defence Minister to Marshal of the Sejm about gen. Casey decoration.]</ref>\n|-\n|[[File:Legion Honneur Commandeur ribbon.svg|60px]]\n|[[L\u00e9gion d'honneur|Legion of Honor, Commander]] French<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.army.mil/-slideshows/2008/02/08/7350-gen-casey-awarded-legion-of-honor/\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080212211359/http://www.army.mil/-slideshows/2008/02/08/7350-gen-casey-awarded-legion-of-honor/\n|url-status=dead\n|archive-date=February 12, 2008\n|title=Gen. Casey awarded Legion of Honor\n|date=February 8, 2008|publisher=U.S. Army}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[File:Pingat Jasa Gemilang (Tentera) ribbon.png|60px]]\n|[[Pingat Jasa Gemilang (Tentera)]] \u2013 ''awarded by Singapore Minister of Defense Teo Chee Hean on August 26, 2009<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.mindef.gov.sg/imindef/mindef_websites/atozlistings/army/army_news/News_Archive/2009/Aug2009/uscsavisit.html |title=US Army Chief of Staff Visits Singapore |date=August 26, 2009 |publisher=[[Ministry of Defence (Singapore)|Singapore Ministry of Defence]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150414171416/http://www.mindef.gov.sg/imindef/mindef_websites/atozlistings/army/army_news/News_Archive/2009/Aug2009/uscsavisit.html |archivedate=April 14, 2015 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n|-\n|[[File:JPN Kyokujitsu-sho 1Class BAR.svg|60px]]\n|[[Grand Cordon of the Order of the Rising Sun]] \u2013 ''Casey was awarded the first class of the Grand Cordon of the Order of the Rising Sun by Japanese Defense Minister Toshimi Kitazawa December 21, 2010''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pacom.mil/web/PACOM_Resources/img/slideshow_images/1012/101228-A-XXXXP-001-h.jpg |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-12-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110616050234/http://www.pacom.mil/web/PACOM_Resources/img/slideshow_images/1012/101228-A-XXXXP-001-h.jpg |archivedate=June 16, 2011 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n|-\n|[[File:Tong-il Security Medel Ribbon.svg|60px]]\n|[[Order of National Security Merit]] ([[South-Korea]]) [[Tong-il Medal]]\n|-\n|[[File:GER Bundeswehr Honour Cross Gold ribbon.svg|60px]]\n|[[Badge of Honour of the Bundeswehr|Bundeswehr Gold Cross of Honor]]\n|-\n|[[File:Noribbon.svg|60px]]\n|''(Unidentified)''\n|-\n|[[File:GA National Guard Commendation Medal.png|60px]]\n|[[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] Commendation Medal \u2013 ''State of Georgia, USA; Presented to BG Casey by LTC Frank Williams, 3ID ROC, Georgia Army National Guard \u2013 while in Slavonski Brod, Croatia, 1996''\n|-\n| align=center | [[File:Expert Infantry Badge.svg|110px]]\n|[[Expert Infantryman Badge]]\n|-\n| align=center | [[File:Master Parachutist badge (United States).svg|80px]]\n|[[Parachutist Badge (United States)|Master Parachutist Badge]]\n|-\n| align=center | [[File:Ranger Tab.svg|70px]]\n|[[Ranger Tab]]\n|-\n| align=center | [[File:Joint Chiefs of Staff seal.svg|75px]]\n|[[Office of the Joint Chiefs of Staff Identification Badge]]\n|-\n| align=center | [[File:United States Army Staff Identification Badge.png|65px]]\n|[[Army Staff Identification Badge]]\n|-\n| align=center | [[File:Multi-National Force-Iraq ShoulderSIeeveInsignia.jpg|65px]]\n|[[MNF-I]] [[Combat Service Identification Badge]]\n|-\n| align=center | [[File:10th INF DUI.png|50px]]\n|[[10th Infantry Regiment (United States)|10th Infantry Regiment]] [[Distinctive Unit Insignia]]\n|-\n| align=center | [[File:ArmyOSB.jpg|55px]]\n|5 [[Overseas Service Bar]]s\n|-\n| align=center | [[File:Fallschirmspringerabzeichen der Bundeswehr in Bronze.jpg|110px]]\n|[[German Parachutist Badge]] in bronze\n|-\n| align=center | [[File:Brevet Parachutiste.jpg|110px]]\n|Basic French Parachutist Badge ({{lang-fr|link=no|Brevet de Parachutisme militaire}})<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.army.mil/-images/2008/02/08/12647/army.mil-2008-02-08-122116.jpg\n|title=Gen. Casey wearing french parachutist badge\n|date=February 8, 2008|publisher=U.S. Army}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{Cite web|accessdate  = 2008-10-05|url= http://www.army.mil/institution/leaders/csa/index.html|title= Biography: General George W. Casey Jr. \u2013 Chief of Staff of the United States Army|work= Leaders: Army Chief of Staff|format= PDF|publisher= United States Army|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081004060912/http://www.army.mil/institution/leaders/csa/index.html|archivedate= October 4, 2008|df= mdy}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{Cite book| last = Cloud| first = David|author2=Greg Jaffe| year = 2009| chapter =  | title = The Fourth Star: Four Generals and the Epic Struggle for the Future of the United States Army| publisher=[[Random House]]| isbn = }}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|George W. Casey Jr.}}\n*[http://www.sourcewatch.org/index.php?title=George_W._Casey%2C_Jr. Profile] at [[SourceWatch]]\n*[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A4087-2004Jun24.html New Job in Iraq Will Be as Top U.S. Military Leader], June 25, 2004\n*[http://www.cnn.com/2007/WORLD/europe/01/05/friday/index.html CNN, Friday, January 5: Gates shakes up command in Iraq], January 5, 2007\n*[https://georgewbush-whitehouse.archives.gov/news/releases/2007/01/20070105-7.html Press Briefing by Tony Snow (Jan 5, 2007) concerning change of commanders in Iraq], January 5, 2007\n*[http://www.boston.com/news/nation/washington/articles/2007/09/27/army_is_worn_too_thin_says_general/ Casey tells Congress Army is stretched too thin], September 27, 2007\n*[https://www.reuters.com/article/domesticNews/idUSTRE5A71AJ20091108 Army chief fears backlash for Muslim U.S. soldiers \u2013 Adds \"And as horrific as this tragedy was, if our diversity becomes a casualty, I think that's worse\"], November 8, 2009\n*{{C-SPAN|GeorgeCasey}}\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-mil}}\n{{succession box|\n before=[[Jack Keane]]|\n title=[[Vice Chief of Staff of the United States Army]]|\n after=Gen. [[Richard A. Cody]]|\n years=2003\u20132004\n}}\n{{succession box\n|after =   [[David H. Petraeus]]\n|title =   Commander [[Multinational Force Iraq]]\n|before =  [[Ricardo S. Sanchez]]\n|years =   2004\u20132007}}\n{{succession box\n|after =   [[Martin E. Dempsey]]\n|title =   [[Chief of Staff of the United States Army]]\n|before =  [[Peter J. Schoomaker]]\n|years =   2007\u20132011}}\n{{s-prec|us}}\n{{succession box\n|before = [[James Cartwright]]\n|title = [[United States order of precedence]]\n|years = {{As of|2010|lc=on}}\n|after = [[Gary Roughead]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{US Army Chiefs of Staff}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Casey, George W. Jr.}}\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Joint Chiefs of Staff]]\n[[Category:Boston College High School alumni]]\n[[Category:School of Foreign Service alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Denver alumni]]\n[[Category:Josef Korbel School of International Studies people]]\n[[Category:Commandeurs of the L\u00e9gion d'honneur]]\n[[Category:Order of National Security Merit members]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Badge of Honour of the Bundeswehr]]\n[[Category:Grand Cordons of the Order of the Rising Sun]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Defense Distinguished Service Medal]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Polish Army Medal]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Distinguished Service Medal (US Army)]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Legion of Merit]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Pingat Jasa Gemilang (Tentera)]]\n[[Category:American army personnel of the Iraq War]]\n[[Category:Military leaders of the Iraq War]]\n[[Category:United States Army generals]]\n[[Category:Military brats]]\n[[Category:United States Army Chiefs of Staff]]\n[[Category:United States Army Vice Chiefs of Staff]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Germany]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Japan]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|US Army general}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2011}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|name= George William Casey Jr.\n|image= George W. Casey 2007.jpg\n|image_size= \n|alt= \n|caption= George W. Casey, Jr. in 2007\n|nickname= \n|birth_date= {{birth date and age|1948|7|22}}\n|birth_place=[[Sendai, Miyagi|Sendai]], [[Occupation of Japan|Japan]]\n|death_date= \n|death_place= \n|placeofburial= \n|allegiance= [[United States of America]]\n|branch= [[United States Army]]\n|serviceyears= 1970\u20132011 \n|rank= [[General (United States)|General]]\n|unit= \n|commands= [[Chief of Staff of the United States Army]]<br/>[[Multi-National Force \u2013 Iraq]]<br/>[[Vice Chief of Staff of the United States Army]]<br/>[[1st Armored Division (United States)|1st Armored Division]]<br/>[[United States Joint Forces Command|Joint Warfighting Center]]<br/>[[3rd Brigade Combat Team, 1st Cavalry Division|3rd Brigade, 1st Cavalry Division]]\n|battles= [[Military operation|Operation]]<br/>[[Afghanistan]] present\n|awards= [[Defense Distinguished Service Medal]] (4)<br/>[[Army Distinguished Service Medal]] (2)<br/>[[Legion of Merit]] (3)<br/>[[Defense Meritorious Service Medal]]<br/>[[Meritorious Service Medal (United States)|Meritorious Service Medal]]\n|relations= [[George W. Casey Sr.]] (Widowed With only one son)\n|laterwork= \n}}\n'''George William Casey Jr.''' (born July 22, 1948) is a four-star [[General (United States)|general]] who served as the 36th [[Chief of Staff of the United States Army]] from April 10, 2007, to April 10, 2011. Casey served as [[Commanding General]], [[Multi-National Force \u2013 Iraq]], from June 2004 to February 8, 2007, and was in the army for his entire adult working life. He now resides in [[Arlington, Virginia]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nCasey was born in [[Sendai, Miyagi|Sendai]] during the [[Occupation of Japan|Allied occupation of Japan]].<!--Encyclopaedia Britannica Almanac 2010 p42----><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.usar.army.mil/arweb/organization/commandstructure/USARC/TNG/75BCTD/News/Documents/BB21-30.pdf |title=America's Broken Army |author=Tom Bowman |date=Winter 2009\u20132010 |work=The Bugle Buster |publisher=United States Army |accessdate=July 26, 2011}}{{dead link|date=October 2016}}</ref>  His father, [[George W. Casey Sr.]], was a [[United States Military Academy|West Point]] graduate who rose to the rank of [[Major general (United States)|major general]] and served in [[World War II]], the [[Korean War]] and the [[Vietnam War]]. His father commanded the [[1st Cavalry Division (United States)|1st Cavalry Division]] in Vietnam and was killed on July 7, 1970, when his command helicopter crashed in [[South Vietnam]] en route to a hospital to visit wounded American soldiers.\n\nCasey, a [[military brat (U.S. subculture)|military brat]], grew up on army posts in the United States, Japan, and Germany and graduated from [[Boston College High School]] in [[Boston, Massachusetts]]. After high school, he applied to West Point, like his father, but was unsuccessful. He went on to earn a [[Bachelor of Science]] degree in [[international relations]] from [[Georgetown University]] in 1970 and later a [[Master of Arts]] degree in international relations from the [[University of Denver]] in 1980. Additionally, Casey worked for [[Vince Lombardi]] during one summer when the latter was coach of the [[Washington Redskins]].<ref name=\"Georgetown1\">{{Cite web|url=http://explore.georgetown.edu/news/?ID=47900 |title=Managing the Army |publisher=[[Georgetown University]] |accessdate=2010-07-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100726120742/http://explore.georgetown.edu/news/?ID=47900 |archivedate=July 26, 2010 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Casey in Singapore.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Casey during a [[Singapore]] visit in 2009.]]\n[[File:General Casey in Iraq.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Casey in [[Tikrit]], Iraq, in 2006.]]\n[[File:XM1202 Mounted Combat System turret.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Casey speaks with the press about [[Future Combat Systems]] and the [[Future Combat Systems Manned Ground Vehicles|Manned Ground Vehicle]] program in June 2008.]]\n[[File:070410-D-7203T-029.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Acting [[Secretary of the Army]] [[Pete Geren]] swears in Casey as the 36th Army chief of staff at [[Fort Myer]], [[Virginia]], April 10, 2007.]]\n[[File:Casey awarded Defense Distinguished Service Medal.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Secretary of Defense [[Robert M. Gates]] presents the [[Defense Distinguished Service Medal]] to Casey.]]\nCasey was [[Officer (armed forces)|commissioned]] through the Army [[Reserve Officers' Training Corps]] in 1970 following graduation from Georgetown University.\n\nCasey served in the [[Mechanized Infantry]] during the command portion of his career. He was the commander of the [[3rd Brigade, 1st Cavalry Division|3rd Brigade]] of the 1st Cavalry Division, and the Assistant Division Commander \u2013 Maneuver (later Assistant Division Commander \u2013 Support) of the [[1st Armored Division (United States)|1st Armored Division]] in Germany. He deployed as part of [[Operation Joint Endeavor]] to [[Bosnia-Herzegovina]] from July 1996 to August 1997. He and the Rear Command Post staff were based in [[Slavonski Brod]], Croatia. Casey took command of the [[1st Armored Division (United States)|1st Armored Division]] in July 1999.\n\nAfter relinquishing command of the division in July 2001, Casey served in a senior staff position in [[the Pentagon]] as the Director of Strategic Plans and Policy (J-5), the [[Joint Staff]] from October 2001 to January 2003. His next position was [[Director of the Joint Staff]] in Washington, D.C. from January 2003 to October 2003. Following these assignments, Casey was nominated and confirmed as the 30th [[Vice Chief of Staff of the United States Army|Vice Chief of Staff of the Army]], serving in that post until June 2004.\n\n===Multi-National Force \u2013 Iraq===\nCasey served as the senior coalition commander in Iraq from June 2004 to February 2007. He replaced Lieutenant General [[Ricardo S. Sanchez]].<ref name=NYT_ >{{Cite news |accessdate=2008-10-05|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9903E7DE163BF936A35754C0A9629C8B63&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=all|title=The Reach of War: Man in the News \u2013 George William Casey Jr.; A Low-Key Commander With 4 Stars to Tame the Iraqi Furies|author=Schmitt, Eric |work=New York Times |date=July 5, 2004}}</ref> Casey's goal was to encourage the Iraqis to take ownership of their problems and responsibility for their own security. For his part as a military commander, he focused on training Iraqi forces, limiting the role of American forces, and transferring the burden for providing security to Iraqi forces. Meanwhile, [[Foreign Service Officer|U.S. diplomats]] would focus on building and strengthening the Iraqi government and help the Iraqis hold elections. He expressed his view that a large and intrusive American presence in Iraq would not solve the political and security problems in that country and could even fuel the insurgency.\n\nIn 2005, Casey was hopeful that the [[December 2005 Iraqi elections]] could lead to a more unified and moderate Iraq which\u2014in conjunction with the training of Iraqi security forces\u2014could pave the way for U.S. troop reductions in early 2006.<ref>{{Cite news |accessdate=|url=https://usatoday30.usatoday.com/printedition/news/20070716/1a_iedcoverxx.art.htm|title=Pentagon balked at pleas from officers in field for safer vehicles- Iraqi troops got MRAPs; Americans waited |author=Peter Eisler, Blake Morrison and Tom Vanden Brook |work=USA Today |date=July 16, 2007}}</ref> In August 2005, Casey used specific troop numbers in his public discussion of a possible drawdown. He said the troop level of 138,000 could be reduced by 30,000 in the early months of 2006 as Iraqi security forces took on a greater role. President [[George W. Bush]] publicly called the talk \"speculation\" and rebuked the general. The bombing of the [[al-Askari Mosque]], a sacred [[Shia]] religious site in [[Samarra]], is believed to have stoked sectarian tensions and derailed coalition plans to speedily transfer significant security responsibility to the Iraqi government by the end of 2006.<ref name=Telegraph_20050814>{{Cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/iraq/1496197/Bush-slaps-down-top-general-after-he-calls-for-troops-to-be-pulled-out-of-Iraq.html |title=Bush slaps down top general after he calls for troops to be pulled out of Iraq |accessdate=2010-01-30|author=Sherwell, Philip |date=August 14, 2005 |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=UK|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051113130646/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=%2Fnews%2F2005%2F08%2F14%2Fwirq14.xml&sSheet=%2Fnews%2F2005%2F08%2F14%2Fixworld.html |archivedate=November 13, 2005 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2007, Casey implied his opposition to a [[troop surge]]:\n\n{{quote|... the longer we in the U.S. forces continue to bear the main burden of Iraq's security, it lengthens the time that the government of Iraq has to take the hard decisions about reconciliation and dealing with the militias. And the other thing is that they can continue to blame us for all of Iraq's difficulties, which are at base of their problems. It's always been my view that a heavy and sustained American military presence was not going to solve the problems in Iraq over the long term.<ref name=NY_Sanger_20070102>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/01/02/washington/02war.html\n|title=Chaos Overran Iraq Plan in '06, Bush Team Says|author1=Sanger, David E. |author2=Gordon, Michael R. |author3=John F. Burns |date=January 2, 2007|work=New York Times}}</ref>}}\n\n===Army Chief of Staff===\nIn January 2007, President George W. Bush nominated Casey for elevation to [[Chief of Staff of the United States Army|Chief of Staff of the Army]]. The [[United States Senate|Senate]] confirmed his nomination on February 8, 2007, with a bipartisan vote of 83\u201314.<ref name=VOA_>{{Cite news|accessdate=November 8, 2009 |url=http://www.voanews.com/english/archive/2007-02/2007-02-08-voa47.cfm?moddate=2007-02-08 |archive-url=https://sul-swap-prod.stanford.edu/20090912010707/http://www.voanews.com/english/archive/2007-02/2007-02-08-voa47.cfm?moddate=2007-02-08 |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 12, 2009 |title=US Senate Confirms Casey as Army Chief of Staff |first=Deborah |last=Tate |date=February 8, 2007 |work=[[Voice of America|VOA News]] }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\nOn February 10, 2007, Casey relinquished command in Iraq to General [[David Petraeus]]. Casey officially succeeded General [[Peter Schoomaker]] as Chief of Staff of the Army on April 10, 2007.\n\nAs the 36th Chief of Staff of the United States Army from April 2007 to 2011, Casey led what is arguably the world's largest and most complex organization\u20141.1&nbsp;million people strong, with a $200+ billion annual budget\u2014during one of the most extraordinary periods in military and global political history. He became Chief of Staff of an Army that was stretched from 6 years of continuous war. Over his tenure he stabilized and transformed the army to meet the challenges of the 21st century while continuing to meet the demands of two wars. Casey transformed an army trained and prepared for conventional war, to an agile force more suited to modern challenges.{{citation needed|date=May 2015}}\n\nCasey accelerated the growth of the army, instituted Retention Bonuses for young officers, increased the funding for soldier and family programs, improved the way the army cared for its wounded soldiers and surviving family members and drove down the stigma associated with behavioral health counseling to stabilize an army stretched by war. He also improved the leadership training for the army's General Officer Corps, advanced the transformation of the army's business and decision making processes, moved the army onto a rotational deployment program much like the [[United States Marine Corps|Marine Corps']] and oversaw a substantial improvement in the capabilities of the Army National Guard and Army Reserves.{{citation needed|date=May 2015}}\n\nIn the immediate aftermath of the [[2009 Fort Hood shooting]] committed by United States Army psychiatrist [[Nidal Malik Hasan]], Casey expressed concern about jumping to conclusions before the investigation was completed, telling CNN's [[John King (journalist)|John King]] that \"this increased speculation could cause a backlash against some of our Muslim soldiers\" and \"As great a tragedy as this was, it would be a shame if our diversity became a casualty as well.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://politicalticker.blogs.cnn.com/2009/11/08/casey-im-concerned-about-possible-backlash-against-muslim-soldiers/?fbid=N63XSrE7Gga |title=Casey: I'm 'concerned' about backlash against Muslim soldiers |date=8 November 2009 |publisher=CNN|accessdate=24 August 2012}}</ref> Several months later, in a February 2010 interview, Casey said: \"Our diversity not only in our Army, but in our country, is a strength. And as horrific as this tragedy was, if our diversity becomes a casualty, I think that's worse.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/33752275 |title='Meet the Press' transcript for Nov. 8, 2009 |accessdate=24 August 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.army.mil/article/54745/General_George_W__Casey_Jr__ceremony_remarks_as_delivered_by_Secretary_of_Defense_Robert/ |title=General George W. Casey Jr.  ceremony remarks as delivered by Secretary of Defense Robert M. Gates |accessdate=11 April 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Retirement==\nCasey retired on April 11, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Casey Jr.|first1=George W.|title=General George W. Casey Jr. Remarks as Delivered Monday, April 11, 2011|url=https://www.army.mil/article/54748/general_george_w_casey_jr__remarks_as_delivered_monday_april_11_2011|website=www.army.mil|publisher=United States Army|accessdate=27 January 2018|language=en}}</ref> Casey, whose parents were from Massachusetts, moved to [[Scituate, Massachusetts|Scituate]] upon his retirement.<ref>https://www.bostonglobe.com/lifestyle/2012/07/30/general-george-casey-cqled-army-and-will-lead-pan-mass-challenge/zNJ0H1HZ7ZkeFyP4S6HAON/story.html</ref> Casey is currently a Distinguished Senior Lecturer of Leadership at [[Cornell University]]'s [[Samuel Curtis Johnson Graduate School of Management|Johnson Graduate School of Management]] <ref>{{cite web|title=Johnson at Cornell > Faculty And Research > Profile|url=https://www.johnson.cornell.edu/Faculty-And-Research/Profile?id=gwc65|website=www.johnson.cornell.edu|publisher=[[Cornell University]]}}</ref> as well as a teaching fellow at the [[University of Virginia]]\u2019s [[Darden School of Business]].\n\n==Personal life==\nCasey is married to his college sweetheart Sheila and they have two sons.<ref>{{citenews|title=Our Man in Iraq|url=https://magazine.du.edu/current-issue/our-man-in-iraq/|work=University of Denver Magazine|publisher=[[University of Denver]]|date=March 1, 2005|first=Larry|last=Getlen}}</ref> Sheila Casey is the Chief Operating Officer of ''[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]''.\n\n==Awards and decorations==\n{|\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=3|type=oak|ribbon=Defense Distinguished Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Defense Distinguished Service Medal]] (with three bronze [[oak leaf cluster]]s)\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=oak|ribbon=Distinguished Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Distinguished Service Medal (U.S. Army)|Army Distinguished Service Medal]] (with bronze oak leaf cluster)\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=2|type=oak|ribbon=Legion of Merit ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Legion of Merit]] (with two bronze oak leaf clusters)\n|-\n|[[File:Defense Meritorious Service Medal ribbon.svg|60px]]\n|[[Defense Meritorious Service Medal]]\n|-\n|[[File:Meritorious Service Medal ribbon.svg|60px]]\n|[[Meritorious Service Medal (United States)|Meritorious Service Medal]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=oak|ribbon=Army Commendation Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Army Commendation Medal]] (with bronze oak leaf cluster)\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=oak|ribbon=Army Achievement Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Army Achievement Medal]] (with bronze oak leaf cluster)\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=3|type=oak|ribbon=Joint Meritorious Unit Award ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Joint Meritorious Unit Award]] (with three bronze oak leaf clusters)\n|-\n|[[File:Army Superior Unit Award ribbon.svg|60px]]\n|[[Army Superior Unit Award]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=2|type=service-star|ribbon=National Defense Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[National Defense Service Medal]] (with two bronze [[service stars]])\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=2|type=service-star|ribbon=Iraq Campaign Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Iraq Campaign Medal]] (with two bronze service stars)\n|-\n|[[File:Global War on Terrorism Expeditionary ribbon.svg|60px]]\n|[[Global War on Terrorism Expeditionary Medal]]\n|-\n|[[File:Global War on Terrorism Service ribbon.svg|60px]]\n|[[Global War on Terrorism Service Medal]]\n|-\n|[[File:Armed Forces Service Medal ribbon.svg|60px]]\n|[[Armed Forces Service Medal]]\n|-\n|[[File:Army Service Ribbon.svg|60px]]\n|[[Army Service Ribbon]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=numeral|ribbon=Army Overseas Service Ribbon.svg|width=60}}<span style=\"position:relative; top: 1px; left: -36px; display: inline-block; width: 0;\">[[File:Award numeral 4.png|11px]]</span>\n|[[Overseas Service Ribbon#Army|Army Overseas Service Ribbon]] (with [[award numeral]] \"4\")\n|-\n|[[File:United Nations Medal ribbon.svg|60px]]\n|[[United Nations Medal]]\n|-\n|[[File:NATO Medal Yugoslavia ribbon bar.svg|60px]]\n|[[