ard\u2019|last=Cumming|first=Ed|date=28 November 2015|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=29 June 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Ross McCall]], Scottish actor<ref>{{cite tweet|author=Ross McCall|user=maccageezer|number=900825312195264512|date=24 August 2017|title=I like our group in the #UCL. Not the group of death or the easiest, somewhere in the middle. A good test for us. #celtic|accessdate=25 August 2017}}</ref>\n* [[James McClean]], Irish footballer<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hitc.com/en-gb/2017/10/09/celtic-boss-brendan-rodgers-should-consider-west-broms-james-mcc/|title=Celtic boss Brendan Rodgers should consider West Brom's James McClean|last=Callaghan|first=Shane|date=9 October 2017|work=HITC|quote=It is no secret that West Bromwich Albion winger James McClean is a big Celtic fan.|accessdate=11 November 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Martine McCutcheon]], English singer, TV personality and actress<ref name=\"Famous Celtic fans\">{{cite news|url=http://www.scotlandnow.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/gallery/famous-celtic-fans-3989366|title=Famous Celtic fans|date=4 August 2014|work=Scotland Now|accessdate=9 August 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Conor McGregor]], Irish [[MMA]] fighter<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2017/08/17/conor-mcgregor-thanks-celtics-die-hard-support-champions-league/|title=Conor McGregor thanks Celtic's 'die-hard' support for Champions League banner|last=Davis|first=Callum|date=17 August 2017|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=25 August 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Ilir Meta]], [[President of Albania]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Ilir Meta, President of Albania, reveals support for Celtic|url=https://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/celtic/ilir-meta-president-of-albania-reveals-support-for-celtic-1-4963008|publisher=The Scotsman|accessdate=9 August 2019|date=11 July 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Mark Millar]], Scottish comic book writer and artist<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/local/edinburghandeastscotland/low/people_and_places/arts_and_culture/newsid_8283000/8283664.stm|title=Marvel's Mark Millar talks comics|date=14 October 2009|work=[[BBC News]]|quote=As a kid I loved comics and I loved films and it sort of struck me when I was about 11 or 12 that somebody must be writing and drawing these books which I'm enjoying so much and it just seemed a wee bit more attainable than playing for Celtic.|accessdate=25 August 2017|location=Edinburgh}}</ref>\n* [[Gary Mounfield]], bassist formerly of [[The Stone Roses]] and currently of Primal Scream<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.morrissey-solo.com/threads/johnny-marr-and-mani-stone-roses-interesting-story.39401/|title=Johnny Marr and Mani (Stone Roses) - interesting story|date=3 December 2004|work=Morrissey-Solo.com|accessdate=9 August 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Paolo Nutini]], Scottish singer<ref name=\"Famous Celtic fans\"/>\n* [[Daniel Portman]], Scottish actor<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/game-thrones-star-issues-brutal-16200883|title=Game of Thrones star issues one-word Celtic tweet as Neil Lennon lands job|last=Young|first=Graeme|date=25 May 2019|work=[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]]|accessdate=3 June 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Johnathan Rice]], Scottish-American singer-songwriter<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/mrjohnathanrice/status/595680579686944768?lang=en|title=Johnathan Rice on Twitter|last=Rice|first=Johnathan|date=5 May 2015|website=[[Twitter]]|accessdate=29 June 2019|quote=Just found out that they played a @jennyandjohnny song at Celtic Park in Glasgow during the last game. Beyond stoked}}</ref>\n* [[Wayne Rooney]], English footballer<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/rooney-finally-apologises-to-fans-and-says-he-would-never-have-joined-city-2143920.html|title=Rooney finally apologises to fans and says he would never have joined City|last=Herbert|first=Ian|date=26 November 2010|work=[[The Independent]]|quote=It is well known I follow Celtic...It is always a special moment [to score] at Rangers.|accessdate=25 August 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Tony Roper (actor)|Tony Roper]], Scottish actor, comedian and writer<ref>{{cite news|last1=McGuire|first1=Joe|title=Tony Roper: Even Rangers fans will enjoy Celts in Seville.. because Celtic get beat|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/whats-on/arts-culture-news/tony-roper-even-rangers-fans-3339764|date=2 April 2012|work=[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]]|accessdate=14 August 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Sheamus]], Irish professional wrestler<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wwe.com/worldwide/article/sheamus-message-celtic-football-club|title= Sheamus sends his support over to unbeaten Celtic F.C.|date=18 April 2017|work=[[WWE]]|accessdate=9 August 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Snoop Dogg]], American rapper<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2012/nov/19/snoop-dogg-celtic-football-club|title=Snoop Dogg considers investment in Celtic football club|date=19 November 2012|work=Scotland Now|accessdate=9 August 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Rod Stewart]], English singer<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/early-lead/wp/2012/11/08/champions-league-celtic-stuns-barcelona-and-rod-stewart-cries/|title=Champions League: Celtic stuns Barcelona and Rod Stewart cries|last=Brooks|first=Matt|date=8 November 2012|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=25 August 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Lawrence Tynes]], Scottish-born former [[American football]] player<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/2289683/Celtic-humour-keeps-Lawrence-Tynes-on-song.html|title=Celtic humour keeps Lawrence Tynes on song|last=Brown|first=Oliver|date=22 January 2008|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=9 April 2018}}</ref>\n* [[The View (band)|The View]], Scottish [[indie rock]] band<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/entertainment/music/music-news/the-views-guitarist-says-celtic-mad-bands-1094214|title=The View's guitarist says Celtic-mad bands are better than the rest|last=Rinaldi|first=David|date=6 February 2011|work=[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]]|accessdate=8 April 2018}}</ref>\n{{colend}}\n\n==Fanbase==\nCeltic was founded as a charity for poor Irish immigrants in Glasgow by [[Brother Walfrid]], a [[Marist Brothers|Marist Brother]] originally from [[County Sligo]], Ireland.<ref>{{cite book |title=Wherever Green Is Worn: The Story of the Irish Diaspora|last=Coogan|first=Pat |year=2002 |publisher=[[Palgrave Macmillan]]|location= |isbn=978-1-4039-6014-6|page=250 |url= }}<!--|accessdate=5 August 2011--></ref> Consequently, Celtic is strongly associated with Scotland's [[Irish Catholic]] community<ref>{{cite book |title=Football: A Sociology of the Global Game |last=Giulianotti|first=Richard |authorlink= |year=1999 |publisher=[[Wiley-Blackwell]]|location= |isbn=978-0-7456-1769-5 |page=18 |url= }}<!--|accessdate=5 August 2011--></ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Sport and National identity in the Post-War World|last=Smith|first=Adrian |authorlink= |author2=Dilwyn Porter |year=2004 |publisher=[[Routledge]]|location= |isbn=978-0-415-28301-4 |page=82 |url= }}<!--|accessdate=5 August 2011--></ref> and have a significant number of supporters in Ireland and among members of the [[Irish diaspora]] elsewhere.<ref name=\"fanbase\" />\n\n===Worldwide diaspora===\n[[File:The Brazen Head - geograph.org.uk - 1168772.jpg|thumb|This Celtic pub is located in [[The Gorbals]], an area of Glasgow where thousands of [[Irish migration to Great Britain#Irish in Scotland|Irish emigrants to Scotland]] settled]]\nCeltic has developed a fanbase in a number of countries around the world, with over 160 [[Supporters groups|supporters' clubs]] in over 20 countries around the world.<ref>[http://www.nafcsc.com/ The North American Federation of Celtic Supporters Clubs] lists some 125 clubs and the [http://www.aicsc.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=57&Itemid=56 Association of Irish Celtic Supporters Clubs] 40 more</ref> Research in 2003 by [[Capita|Capita Consulting]] in conjunction with the [[Cranfield Institute]] estimated the worldwide fan base as being around 13 million.<ref name=\"fanbase\">{{cite web |url=http://www.scotsman.com/business/companies/media-leisure/celtic-to-launch-credit-card-for-us-fans-1-1291697 |title=Celtic to launch credit card for US fans |work=The Scotsman |date=20 July 2003 |accessdate=6 July 2011}}</ref> This fanbase has extended to Japan since 2005, when Japanese international [[Shunsuke Nakamura]] joined the club,<ref name=\"Japan\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.goldsmiths.ac.uk/press-releases/pressrelease.php?releaseID=701 |title=Celtic football club a real hit with Japanese fans |publisher=Goldsmith, University of London |date=16 February 2009 |author=Dr Hiroki Ogasawara |accessdate=7 July 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120326072551/http://www.goldsmiths.ac.uk/press-releases/pressrelease.php?releaseID=701 |archivedate=26 March 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> although the Tokyo Celtic Supporters' Club had already been established in 2001.<ref>[http://www.celticfc.net/news/7266 Be there to welcome Naka back to Paradise] Celtic FC. 12-12-2014. Retrieved 17-12-2014.</ref> In 2009, marketing agency ''Sports Revolution'' reported that there were an estimated seven million Celtic supporters in Japan alone.<ref>{{cite web|title=Celtic to consider US franchise club |url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/competitions/premiership/celtic-to-consider-us-franchise-club-1-3927833|work=The Scotsman |date=26 October 2015 |accessdate=2 October 2016}}</ref>\nThere are Celtic supporters clubs in South Korea,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.celtickorea.com/|title=Celtic Korea|accessdate=15 August 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111018230349/http://www.celtickorea.com/|archivedate=18 October 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Sweden<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.svenskafans.com/europa/celtic/|title= Celtic Europa|accessdate=15 August 2011}}</ref> Croatia, Germany, Denmark and Norway<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.csc.com/nordic/ds/11706-nordic-locations |title=Nordic locations |accessdate=15 August 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161117063015/http://www.csc.com/nordic/ds/11706-nordic-locations |archive-date=17 November 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> while the club's profile in Kenya has been boosted by a team in [[Nairobi]]. [[Kibera]] Celtic, who were inspired by Celtic's charitable roots and use the profits from football to fund charitable initiatives in Kenya and throughout Africa.<ref name=\"Kenya\">{{cite news|url=http://188.92.90.105/newsstory.php?item=824 |title=Hoops hailed in Kibera |publisher=Celtic FC |date=16 March 2011 |accessdate=6 July 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120315203753/http://188.92.90.105/newsstory.php?item=824 |archivedate=15 March 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, it was estimated that Celtic had a fanbase of one million in the United States and Canada.<ref name=\"fanbase\" /> In 2002, former [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] director, [[Hugh Adam]], claimed that Celtic were \"the best-supported football club in North America\" and that the club's \"Irish connection\" was a determinant factor in their popularity.<ref>[http://sport.scotsman.com/top-stories/Adam-shakes-Ibrox-pillars-with.2299216.jp Adam shakes Ibrox pillars with warning of bankruptcy] ''[[The Scotsman]]''. 2 February 2002. Retrieved 7 August 2011.</ref> In 2004, ''[[The Sunday Times]]'', when commentating on several European teams who were touring in the [[U.S.]] at the time, stated that clubs such as [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]], [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]] and [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] attracted support in the United States only when touring the country. In contrast, Celtic were said to \"have such a strong pre-existing relationship with a huge expatriate following here that their support will endure.\"<ref name=\"2004tour\">{{Cite news |url =http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/article461389.ece |title=Celtic's US fanbase fails to bridge financial gap |work=The Sunday Times |date=25 July 2004 |accessdate=11 July 2011 |location=London}}</ref> There are around 80 Celtic supporters clubs in North America,<ref name=\"fanbase\" /> and nearly half of all U.S states have a Celtic supporters club.<ref name=\"2004tour\" />\n\nCeltic have also developed supporters clubs in Australia, South Africa, and elsewhere in the [[Southern Hemisphere]].<ref>{{cite web|title=BRISBANE CELTIC SUPPORTERS CLUB|url=http://www.brisbanecsc.com/|accessdate=13 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Attendance==\n[[File:Seville celtic fans.jpg|thumb|left|Celtic fans at the [[Estadio Ol\u00edmpico de Sevilla]].|200px]]\nCeltic's home stadium is [[Celtic Park]], located in [[Parkhead]] in the East End of [[Glasgow]]. It is the [[List of football (soccer) stadiums by capacity|sixth largest]] stadium in the United Kingdom and the largest football stadium in Scotland. Celtic Park's capacity has been 60,832 since the mid-1990s following redevelopment that turned it into an [[all-seater stadium]], then in 2002 was put down to 60,501 then in 2003 until the present 2013\u201314 season put down again to 60,355.<ref>{{cite news| url = http://www.scottishgrounds.co.uk/celtic.htm| title = Celtic Park (unofficial)| publisher = Scottish football grounds| accessdate = 8 July 2011| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160311162746/http://www.footballgroundguide.com/scotland//celtic.htm| archive-date = 11 March 2016| url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\nCeltic Park's average attendance for the [[2010-11 Celtic F.C. season|2010\u201311]] season was 48,968, the highest in [[2010-11 in Scottish football|Scottish football]] and the twelfth highest in Europe. Celtic's highest average attendance over the last ten seasons was 58,150 in the [[2005-06 Celtic F.C. season|2005\u201306 season]]. Over the next three seasons Celtic's average attendance remained above 57,000 before dropping to 45,582 during the [[2009-10 Celtic F.C. season|2009\u201310 season]].<ref name=\"average attendances\">{{cite news\n|url=http://www.scotprem.com/content/default.asp?page=home_Statistics  |title=2010/11 Average attendances in Scottish football  |publisher=Scottish premier league  |accessdate=7 July 2011  |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110612200756/http://www.scotprem.com/content/default.asp?page=home_Statistics  |archivedate=12 June 2011  |df=dmy }}</ref> A study of stadium attendance figures from 2013 to 2018 by the ''[[International Centre for Sports Studies|CIES Football Observatory]]'' ranked Celtic at 16th in the world during that period, with the proportion of the distribution of spectators in Scotland at 36.5%, the highest of any club in the leagues examined (Rangers were not far behind at 18th place globally and 27.4% of national audience share).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47929074|title=Celtic & Rangers among top 20 most watched clubs|work=BBC Sport|date=16 April 2019|accessdate=17 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Scottish Cup Final]] in 1937 between Celtic and [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]] at [[Hampden Park]] was watched by a crowd of 146,433,  which is a record for a club match in Europe.<ref name=\"CFCBriefHistory\">{{cite news |url=http://www.celticfc.net/about_briefhistory |title=Brief History |publisher=Celtic FC |accessdate=19 November 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111119014926/http://www.celticfc.net/about_briefhistory |archivedate=19 November 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref> In 1970, Celtic's 'home' leg of their two-legged [[UEFA Champions League|European Cup]] semi-final tie against [[Leeds United A.F.C.|Leeds United]] was played at Hampden Park to accommodate the expected large attendance.  A 136,505 crowd watched Celtic win 2\u20131 on the night,<ref name=\"lu2\">{{cite web|title=Matches 15 April 1970 - Celtic 2 Leeds United 1|url=http://www.mightyleeds.co.uk/matches/19700415.htm|publisher=The Mighty Mighty Whites|accessdate=6 October 2013}}</ref> a record attendance for a competitive European club tie that stands to this day.<ref>{{cite web|title=Season 1969-70|url=http://www.europeancuphistory.com/euro70.html|publisher=EUROPEAN CUP HISTORY.COM|accessdate=6 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe club's large travelling support make Celtic a popular choice of opponent for English-based footballers to select for [[testimonial match]]es. Over 5000 Celtic supporters turned for [[Peter Beardsley]]'s testimonial match at [[St James' Park]], Newcastle, in January 1999.<ref>{{cite news|title=Celtic take the honours as Beardsley grabs spotlight|url=http://www.thecelticwiki.com/page/1999-01-27%3A+Peter+Beardsley+Select+1-3+Celtic%2C+Peter+Beardsley%E2%80%99s+Testimonial|accessdate=18 March 2014|newspaper=The Glasgow Herald|date=28 January 1999}}</ref>  An estimated 15,000 Celtic supporters attended at [[Old Trafford]] for the testimonials of [[Bryan Robson]] in November 1990<ref>{{cite news|last=Shaw|first=Phil|title=Celtic steal the Robson show|url=http://image.wikifoundry.com/image/1/CrJf1h992AmxdfTNgQFwgQ520048/GW1055H320|accessdate=18 March 2014|newspaper=The Independent|date=21 November 1990}}</ref>  and for [[Ryan Giggs]] in August 2001.<ref>{{cite web|last=Carter|first=Jon|title=Defiant Celtic refuse to let Giggs savour testimonial|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/football/sport/story/195512.html|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=18 March 2014|date=2 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n===2003 UEFA Cup Final===\nIn 2003, Celtic reached the [[2003 UEFA Cup Final|UEFA Cup Final]], with the match ending 3\u20132 to [[F.C. Porto|FC Porto]]. An estimated 80,000 Celtic supporters travelled to Seville for the occasion.<ref name=FIFA1>[[The Bhoys from Seville]] FIFA, 15 December 2003</ref><ref name=EuropesBest>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/3189853.stm Celtic fans 'Europe's best'] BBC Sport, 28 August 2003</ref><ref name=Relish>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/6627343.stm Finalists relishing Hampden visit] BBC Sport, 4 May 2007</ref> Celtic fans received awards from [[UEFA]] and [[FIFA]] for their \"loyal and sporting behaviour\" at the match.<ref name=FIFA1/><ref name=OSMSeville>[http://observer.guardian.co.uk/gallery/0,8561,972767,00.html Celtic in Seville] Observer Sport Monthly</ref><ref name=\"Celtic Fair Play proposal\">[http://www.uefa.com/uefa/news/Kind=128/newsId=133442.html Celtic Fair Play proposal]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080519134453/http://www.uefa.com/uefa/news/Kind%3D128/newsId%3D133442.html |date=19 May 2008 }}, UEFA, 11 December 2003</ref><ref name=ESPNSeville>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=98023&cc=5739 Celtic 2\u20133 FC Porto] ESPN Soccernet, 21 May 2003</ref>\nUpon handing the award to Celtic fans FIFA president [[Sepp Blatter]] described them as being \"the greatest in the world\"<ref name=\"Leeds\">{{cite news |url=http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/leeds-united/latest-whites-news/leeds_united_fans_deserve_so_much_more_o_dea_interview_1_3661865 |title=Leeds United: Fans deserve so much more \u2013 O\u2019Dea INTERVIEW |publisher=[[Yorkshire Evening Post]] |date=9 August 2011 |accessdate=20 August 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110810230613/http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/leeds-united/latest-whites-news/leeds_united_fans_deserve_so_much_more_o_dea_interview_1_3661865 |archive-date=10 August 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/3313371.stm |title =  Celtic fans get Fifa award |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=12 December 2003 |accessdate=20 August 2011}}</ref>  The massive travelling support that followed Celtic over to Seville to watch them in the final became known as ''[[The Bhoys from Seville]]''.<ref name=\"play\">{{cite news|last1=McGuire|first1=Joe|title=Tony Roper: Even Rangers fans will enjoy Celts in Seville.. because Celtic get beat|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/whats-on/arts-culture-news/tony-roper-even-rangers-fans-3339764|accessdate=3 December 2016|work=Daily Record|date=2 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Old Firm rivalry==\n{{main|Old Firm}}\nCeltic's traditional rivals were the original [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] (founded in 1872 then liquidated in 2012); collectively, the two clubs were known as the [[Old Firm]]. The two have dominated Scottish football's history; between them, they have won the Scottish league championship 100 times since its inception in 1890 \u2013 all other clubs combined have won 19 championships.<ref>{{cite web|title=Scotland - List of Champions - Summary|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tabless/scotchamp.html#sall|website=RSSSF|accessdate=14 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe rivalry between the teams had various ethnic, religious and political associations, in that Celtic are associated with [[Irish Catholic]] origins<ref>{{cite book|title=Sport: A Critical Sociology|last=Giulianotti|first=Richard |authorlink= |year=264 |publisher=[[Polity (publisher)|Polity]]|location=|isbn=978-0-7456-2546-1|page=77 |url= }}<!--|accessdate=7 August 2011--></ref> and [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] with Scotland's [[Protestant]] and [[British Unionism|British Unionist]] communities.<ref>{{cite book|title=Religion and Society in Scotland Since 1707|last=Brown|first=Callum|authorlink=|year=1997|publisher=[[Edinburgh University Press]]|location=|isbn=978-0-7486-0886-7|page=194|url=}}<!--|accessdate=6 August 2011--></ref><ref name=\"britishfootball\">{{cite book|title=British Football & Social Exclusion|last=Wagg|first=Stephen|authorlink=|year=2002|publisher=[[Routledge]]|location=|isbn=978-0-7146-8204-4|page=158|url=}}<!--|accessdate=6 August 2011--></ref> A report prepared for [[Glasgow City Council]] in 2003 found that 74% of Celtic supporters described themselves as Roman Catholic and 10% as Protestant. For Rangers supporters, the figures were 5% and 65% respectively.<ref>NFO Social Research [http://www.glasgow.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/DA614F81-4F1B-4452-8847-F3FDE920D550/0/sectarianism03.pdf Sectarianism in Glasgow \u2013 Final Report] Glasgow City Council, January 2003</ref>\n\n\"The clubs have attracted the support of opposing factions in the [[The Troubles|political difficulties of Northern Ireland]], which intensified the rivalry in Scotland.\"<ref name=Deuchar1>{{cite web|url=http://www.glasgow.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/...4F1B.../sectarianism03.pdf |title=Territoriality and Sectarianism in Glasgow |publisher=Strathclyde University |first=Dr Ross |last=Deuchar |date=June 2008}}</ref> Anti-sectarian charity [[Nil by Mouth (charity)|Nil by Mouth]] notes that some supporters use songs, chants and banners on match days to express abuse or support towards the Protestant or Catholic faiths and proclaim support for Northern Irish-based terrorist groups such as the [[Provisional Irish Republican Army|IRA]] and [[Ulster Volunteer Force (1966)|UVF]].<ref name=HoS>{{cite web| url=http://nilbymouth.org/?page_id=28 |title=History of Sectarianism |publisher=Nil by Mouth |accessdate=27 January 2011 |year=2010}}</ref> A study in 2008 by the [[University of Strathclyde]] found that the Old Firm rivalry was \"strongly linked to the conflict in Northern Ireland\".<ref name=Deuchar1/>\n\nThere have been  about 400 Old Firm matches played.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2016/04/15/celtic-vs-rangers-the-old-firm-explained/|title=Celtic vs Rangers: The Old Firm explained|first=Roddy|last=Forsyth|date=15 April 2016|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref> The games have been described as having an \"atmosphere of hatred, religious tension and intimidation which continues to lead to violence in communities across Scotland.\"<ref name=\"HoS\"/> The rivalry has fuelled many assaults and even deaths on Old Firm Derby days. Admissions to hospital emergency rooms have been reported to increase ninefold over normal levels<ref name = \"wsc\">{{cite news |url=http://www.wsc.co.uk/content/view/2114/29/ |work=When Saturday Comes |date=April 2004 |last=Millen |first=Dianne |title=Firm Favourites: Old Firm |accessdate=28 January 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120524023534/http://www.wsc.co.uk/content/view/2114/29/ |archive-date=24 May 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and journalist [[Franklin Foer]] noted that in the period from 1996 to 2003, eight deaths in Glasgow were directly linked to Old Firm matches, and hundreds of assaults.<ref name = \"wsc\"/><ref>Foer, pp. 36\u201337</ref>\n\nOccurrences of serious crowd trouble between Celtic and Rangers supporters stretches as far back as the [[1909 Scottish Cup Final]], which was contested by the two sides.  The tie went to a replay after the first match ended in a 2\u20132 draw.  The replayed match also ended in a draw (1\u20131) after 90 minutes.  Despite public expectations, no [[Extra time#Association football|extra time]] was played and in response thousands of supporters from both sides invaded the pitch to vent their frustration, causing \u00a31,000 of damage (a substantial sum in the 1900s, equivalent to around \u00a3120,000 today).<ref>[https://www.officialdata.org/uk/inflation/1909?endYear=2020&amount=1000 \u00a31,000 in 1909 \u2192 \u00a3119,815 in 2020], UK Inflation Calculator (Official Inflation Data, Alioth Finance, 5 Feb. 2020) </ref> Both clubs petitioned the [[Scottish Football Association]] to have the tie abandoned and their demands were met when officials decided the match would not be replayed. The cup and all medals were withheld for that year.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Dart|first1=James|last2=Lutz|first2=Tom|title=Why no one won the Scottish Cup in 1909|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2007/mar/21/theknowledge.sport|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=4 April 2014|date=21 March 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Dunmore|first=Thomas|title=Past Pitch Invasions #2: 1909 Scottish Cup Final|url=http://pitchinvasion.net/blog/2007/08/25/past-pitch-invasions-2-1909-scottish-cup-final/|publisher=Pitch Invasion|accessdate=4 April 2014|date=25 August 2007}}</ref>\n\nBoth sets of fans fought an on-pitch battle in the aftermath of Celtic's 1\u20130 victory in the [[1980 Scottish Cup Final]] at [[Hampden Park]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/may/18/seven-deadly-sins-rangers-celtic-wrath|title=Firm enemies \u2013 Rangers and Celtic, 1909\u20132009|accessdate=28 January 2010|work=The Guardian |first=Kevin |last=McCarra |date=18 May 2009}}</ref> In January 1988, [[Mark Walters]] became the first black footballer to play for Rangers; he made his debut in an Old Firm game at Parkhead and was subjected to racial taunts from Celtic fans, some of whom also threw bananas towards the pitch.<ref>{{cite web|title=A black day for Scots football|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/a-black-day-for-scots-football-1-1430353|publisher=The Scotsman|accessdate=18 March 2014|date=29 December 2007}}</ref>   There was serious fan disorder during an Old Firm match played in May 1999 at Celtic Park; missiles were thrown by Celtic fans, including one which struck referee [[Hugh Dallas]], who needed medical treatment.<ref name = \"dallas\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/football/scottish_premier/334094.stm |title=Rangers make history out of chaos |publisher=BBC News |date=3 May 1999|accessdate=16 August 2010}}</ref> Rangers are renowned for their chanting of the sectarian song 'The Billy Boys' during every game.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://inews.co.uk/culture/television/billy-boys-peaky-blinders-gang-glasgow-billy-fullerton-true-story-season-5-494707|title=Billy Boys: the true story behind the Glasgow gang in Peaky Blinders|website=inews.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n===Sectarianism===\n{{Main|Sectarianism in Glasgow}}\nBoth clubs have taken measures to reduce sectarianism.<ref name=\"Deuchar1\"/> In 1996 Celtic launched their ''Bhoys Against Bigotry'' campaign, later followed by ''Youth Against Bigotry'' to \"educate the young on having ... respect for all aspects of the community&nbsp;\u2014 all races, all colours, all creeds\".<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/1593970.stm Bigotry puzzle for Old Firm] BBC News, 11 October 2001</ref> Celtic partnered with Rangers to form the 'Old Firm Alliance' in 2005, an initiative aimed at educating children from across Glasgow about issues like healthy eating and fitness, as well as awareness of anti-social behaviour, sectarianism and racism.<ref>{{cite web|title=Old Firm Alliance|url=http://spfl.co.uk/news/article/old-firm-alliance-2011-04-22/|website=SPFL|accessdate=14 March 2016|date=22 April 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Baird's Bar, Gallowgate - geograph.org.uk - 663604.jpg|thumb|several Celtic themed pubs are located in the streets around [[The Barras]] market east of Glasgow city centre]]\nIn March 2008, UEFA investigated Celtic fans for alleged sectarian singing at a match against [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/2295685/Uefa-inquiry-into-Celtic-sectarian-chants.html |title=Uefa inquiry into Celtic 'sectarian' chants |publisher=The Telegraph |date=29 March 2008 |accessdate=5 August 2011 |location=London |first=Ewing |last=Grahame}}</ref> However the case was dropped before the end of the month due to a lack of evidence.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/7318430.stm |title=UEFA drops Celtic chanting case |publisher=BBC Sport |date=31 March 2008 |accessdate=5 August 2011}}</ref> In November 2011, Celtic were again under investigation by UEFA for alleged offensive chants from their fans during their Europa League game against [[Rennes F.C.|Rennes]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/15706740.stm |publisher=BBC News |title=Celtic discover UEFA hearing date |date=14 November 2011}}</ref> On this occasion UEFA found the Celtic fans to have been guilty of \"illicit chanting\" and fined the club \u00a312,700.<ref>{{cite news|title=Celtic will not appeal against Uefa fine for 'illicit chanting'|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/16137728|accessdate=14 March 2016|work=BBC Sport|date=13 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2012, the general secretary of the Celtic Supporters Association said he was \"genuinely sorry\" after [[Twitter|tweeting]] that it was a \"problem\" that the Protestant workers who built the [[HMS Titanic|Titanic]] \"didn't sail on it\".<ref name=\"heraldscotland.com\">Celtic fan is warned over tweet [http://www.heraldscotland.com/mobile/news/home-news/celtic-fan-is-warned-over-tweet.17250343?_=5edd3a0aa3cdb121a661e572692225a656117876 Herald Scotland Published 9 April 2012]. Retrieved 14 August 2012</ref>\n\n==Irish republicanism==\nCeltic supporters have traditionally been associated with support for [[Irish republicanism]], and the flying of [[Irish tricolour|Irish flags]] at matches is common.<ref>{{cite book |title=Tribal Identities: Nationalism, Europe, Sport|last=Mangan|first=J.A. |year=1995 |publisher=[[Routledge]] |isbn=978-0-7146-4666-4|page=63 |url= }}</ref> Some groups of Celtic supporters also sing or chant [[Irish folk music|Irish folk]] and [[Irish rebel music|rebel]] songs,<ref>{{cite book |title=Fanatics: Power, Identity and Fandom in Football|last=Brown|first=Adam |year=1998 |publisher=[[Routledge]]  |isbn=978-0-415-18103-7 |page=209 }}</ref> which express support for the [[List of organisations known as the Irish Republican Army|IRA]].\nIn 2008 and 2010, there were protests by groups of fans over the team wearing the [[Poppy (flower)|poppy]] symbol for [[Remembrance Day]], as it is a divisive symbol in Ireland.<ref>{{cite news |title=Celtic fans jeer protesters for refusing to honour war dead |date=8 November 2008 |url=http://www.newsoftheworld.co.uk/scottish/scottish_news/66167/Booed-Bhoys.html |work=News of the World |accessdate = 10 September 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.digitalworldz.co.uk/main-site-news-81/190723-booed-bhoys.html |archivedate=9 November 2008}}{{subscription}}</ref><ref>[http://www.eveningtimes.co.uk/news/poppy-demo-fans-face-a-celtic-ban-1.1066962 Poppy demo fans face a Celtic ban] Evening Times, 9 November 2010</ref><ref name=\"Banner\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/9168655.stm |title=Celtic plan ban for anti-poppy protesters |date=8 November 2010|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=19 November 2010 }}</ref> Celtic have expressed disapproval of these protests, saying they are damaging to the image of the club and its fans, and that they will ban those involved.<ref name=\"Banner\"/><ref name=\"Sept11\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/2264181.stm |title=Celtic seek end to 'IRA chants' |publisher=BBC News |date=17 September 2002 |accessdate=25 October 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"QuinnWarn\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/5236284.stm |title=Quinn warns on offensive chants |work=BBC Sport |date=1 August 2006 |accessdate=15 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2011, Celtic were fined \u00a312,700 by UEFA for pro-IRA chanting from some Celtic supporters.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.scotsman.com/the-scotsman/sport/celtic_rule_out_appeal_for_uefa_fine_over_illicit_chanting_1_2007020 |work=The Scotsman |title=Celtic rule out appeal for uefa fine over illicit chanting |date=10 May 2012}}</ref> In response to this in their [[Europa League]] game against [[Udinese Calcio|Udinese]], Celtic fans were seen to have unveiled a banner reading \"Fuck UEFA\". The club condemned the act,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2011/dec/16/celtic-fans-banner-uefa?newsfeed=true |work=The Guardian |first=Ewan |last=Murray |title=These people are not Celtic supporters and we will weed them out |date=16 December 2011}}</ref> banning for life the supporter responsible for the display,<ref>{{cite news |title=UEFA imposes fine on Celtic for offensive behaviour |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/european/uefa-imposes-fine-on-celtic-for-offensive-banner-7594981.html |work=The Independent |accessdate=15 August 2012 |date=28 March 2012}}</ref> whilst UEFA fined Celtic \u20ac25,000 in relation to the incident and related events during the match.<ref>{{cite news |title=Celtic fined by UEFA over offensive banner in Europa League game against Udinese |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/celtic/9171633/Celtic-fined-by-Uefa-over-offensive-banner-in-Europa-League-game-against-Udinese.html |work=The Telegraph |accessdate=15 August 2012 |date=28 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Celtic fined \u00a321,000 by Uefa over banner in Udinese |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17539283 |work=BBC Sport |accessdate=15 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2013, the club were fined \u00a342,000 by [[UEFA]] for an \"incident of a non-sporting nature\" in relation to a display shown by a section of the Celtic support before their [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] group stage tie against Italian side [[AC Milan]]. The banners displayed by the Green Brigade ultras group showed portraits of Scottish hero William Wallace and Irish hunger striker Bobby Sands side by side along with the text: \"The terrorist or the dreamer? The savage or the brave? Depends on whose vote you're trying to catch or whose face you're trying to save\". After the disciplinary hearing, the club issued a statement in which they condemned the banners and stated that the actions of a \"small minority must stop\". After the incident, Celtic relocated 250 supporters from section 111 and issued temporary bans to over 100 more.<ref name=\"finban\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.glasgowtimes.co.uk/sport/17739764.matthew-lindsay-how-holyrood-and-ground-closures-can-rid-scottish-football-of-sectarianism/|title=How Holyrood and ground closures could finally rid Scottish football of sectarianism|website=Glasgow Times}}</ref>\n\n==The Green Brigade==\n{{main|Green Brigade}}\nThe '''Green Brigade''' are a group within the Celtic support who style themselves on the [[ultras]] groups found amongst many European and South American football supporters. They were formed in 2006 and describe themselves as \"a broad front of anti-fascist, anti-racist and anti-sectarian Celtic supporters\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/competitions/scottish-premier/8160406/Roddy-Forsyth-demented-atmosphere-in-Scottish-football-led-to-SPL-referees-calling-for-strike-action.html |title=Demented atmosphere in Scottish football led to SPL referees calling for strike action |first=Roddy |last=Forsyth |date=25 Nov 2010 |work=The Telegraph |accessdate=6 January 2011}}</ref> The Green Brigade have organised various displays at Celtic matches involving banners, flags and demonstrations which have been credited with improving the atmosphere at Celtic Park.<ref name=instrumental>{{cite news|url=http://www.eveningtimes.co.uk/sport/editor-s-picks/celtic-s-warning-to-green-brigade-1.1098695|title=Celtic\u2019s warning to Green Brigade|date=29 April 2011 |work=Evening Times|accessdate=3 June 2011}}</ref> In November 2012, the Green Brigade organised a full stadium pre-match card display against [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] to celebrate Celtic's 125th anniversary.<ref>{{cite news |title=Incredible pre-match display from supporters |url=http://www.celticfc.net/newsstory?item=3319 |work=Celtic F.C. |date=7 November 2012 |accessdate=8 November 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131112134748/http://www.celticfc.net/newsstory?item=3319 |archive-date=12 November 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The display featured a [[Celtic cross]], green and white hoops and ''125 Celtic'' in written form, with supporters earning the praise of club chairman [[Peter Lawwell]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Peter Lawwell congratulates team and support on collective effort |url=http://www.celticfc.net/newsstory?item=3325 |work=Celtic F.C. |date=8 November 2012 |accessdate=8 November 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131112134645/http://www.celticfc.net/newsstory?item=3325 |archive-date=12 November 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> They have however been criticised for some of their more controversial banners, such as the Poppy protest banner in 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-11709524 |title=Celtic poppy banner angers DUP MP Gregory Campbell |work=BBC News |date=8 Nov 2010 |accessdate=6 January 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eveningtimes.co.uk/news/poppy-demo-fans-face-a-celtic-ban-1.1066962 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120112121123/http://www.eveningtimes.co.uk/news/poppy-demo-fans-face-a-celtic-ban-1.1066962 |archivedate=12 January 2012 |title=Poppy demo fans face a Celtic ban |work=Evening Times |date=9 Nov 2010 |accessdate=6 January 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box\n|title=[[FIFA Fair Play Award]] Winners\n|before=Football communities of Japan and Korea Republic\n|after=[[Confedera\u00e7\u00e3o Brasileira de Futebol]]\n|years=2003}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Celtic F.C.}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n\n[[Category:Celtic F.C.]]\n[[Category:Association football supporters]]\n[[Category:Scottish society]]\n[[Category:Catholic Church in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Irish diaspora in Scotland]]\n", "name_user": "2a00:23c8:1e8a:a400:c883:3a5e:3415:d8fa", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Fans)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Celtic_F.C._supporters"}
{"title_page": "Tiger II", "text_new": "{{For|the aircraft also known as the Tiger II|Northrop F-5}}\n{{Infobox weapon\n |name= ''Panzerkampfwagen'' Tiger ''Ausf''. B\n |image= Bundesarchiv Bild 101I-680-8282A-06, Budapest, Panzer VI (Tiger II, K\u00f6nigstiger).jpg\n |image_size = 300\n |caption= Tiger II tank on paved street in Budapest, October 1944\n |origin=[[Nazi Germany]]\n |type= [[Heavy tank]]\n |is_vehicle= yes\n |service= 1944\u201345\n |wars= [[World War II]]\n |designer= [[Henschel & Son]] / [[Krupp]] (turret)\n |design_date= 1943\n |manufacturer=Henschel & Son / Krupp (turret)\n |unit_cost=800,000 [[Reichsmark]] ($300,000 USD) in 1944\u201345<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tanks-encyclopedia.com/ww2/nazi_germany/Panzer-VI_Konigstiger.php|title=Panzer VI Ausf.B K\u00f6nigstiger (1944)|website=www.tanks-encyclopedia.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-11-12}}</ref>\n |production_date= 1943\u201345\n |number= 492<ref name=\"Jentz96-288\"/>\n |variants=\n |weight= {{convert|68.5|t|abbr=out|lk=on}} (early turret)<br /> {{convert|69.8|t|abbr=out}} (production turret)<ref name=\"J&D1997.162-165\"/>\n |length= {{convert|7.38|m|ftin|0}} (hull)<br /> {{convert|10.286|m|ftin|0}} (with gun forward)<ref name=\"J&D1997.162-165\"/>\n |width= {{convert|3.755|m|ftin|0}}<ref name=\"J&D1997.162-165\"/>\n |height= {{convert|3.09|m|ftin|0}}<ref name=\"J&D1997.162-165\"/>\n |crew= 5 (commander, gunner, loader, radio operator, driver)\n |armour= {{convert|25|\u2013|185|mm|0|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"J&D1997.162-165\"/>\n |primary_armament= 1\u00d7 [[8.8 cm KwK 43]] L/71 <br /> Early Krupp design turret: 80 rounds<ref name=\"J&D23\">{{cite book|last1=Jentz|first1=Thomas|last2=Doyle|first2=Hilary|title=Kingtiger Heavy Tank 1942\u201345|date=1993|publisher=Osprey Publishing|isbn=185532282X|page=23}}</ref><br /> Production turret: 86 rounds<ref name=\"J&D23\"/>\n |secondary_armament= 2\u00d7 [[7.92 x 57 mm|7.92&nbsp;mm]] [[MG 34|Maschinengewehr 34]]<br /> 5,850 rounds<ref name=\"J&D1997.162-165\">Jentz and Doyle 1997, pp. 162\u2013165.</ref>\n |engine= V-12 [[Maybach HL230|Maybach HL 230 P30]] [[gasoline]]\n |engine_power= 700 PS (690 hp, 515 kW)<ref name=\"J&D28\">Jentz and Doyle 1993, p. 28 (figure D)</ref>\n |transmission= Maybach OLVAR EG 40 12 16 B (8 forward and 4 reverse)<ref name=\"J&D28\"/>\n |fuel_capacity={{convert|860|l|impgal}}<ref name=\"J&D1997.162-165\"/>\n |pw_ratio= 10 PS (7.5 kW) /tonne (8.97 hp/tonne)\n |suspension= [[torsion-bar]]\n |clearance={{convert|495|to|510|mm|ftin|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"J&D1997.162-165\"/>\n |vehicle_range= Road: {{convert|170|km|mi|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"J&D33\">Jentz and Doyle 1993, p. 33.</ref><br /> Cross country: {{convert|120|km|mi|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"J&D33\"/>\n |speed= Maximum, road: {{convert|41.5|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"J&D33\"/><br /> Sustained, road: {{convert|38|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"J&D33\"/><br /> Cross country: {{convert|15|to|20|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"J&D33\"/>}}\n\nThe '''Tiger II''' is a [[Nazi Germany|German]] [[heavy tank]] of the [[World War II|Second World War]]. The final official German designation was '''''Panzerkampfwagen'' Tiger ''Ausf''. B''',<ref group=notes>''[[Panzerkampfwagen]]'' \u2013 abbr: ''Pz.'' or ''Pz.Kfw.'' (English: \"[[armoured fighting vehicle]]\")<br /> ''Ausf\u00fchrung'' \u2013 abbr: ''Ausf.'' (English: variant).<br /> The full titles ''Panzerkampfwagen'' Tiger ''Ausf''. B and ''Panzerbefehlswagen'' Tiger ''Ausf''. B (for the command version) were used in training and maintenance manuals and in organisation and equipment tables. (Jentz and Doyle 1997)<br /> Also sometimes referred to as \"Pz. VI ''Ausf'' B\", not to be confused with \"Pz. VI ''Ausf'' H\", which was the [[Tiger I]].</ref> often shortened to '''Tiger B'''.<ref name=\"J&D16\">Jentz and Doyle 1993, p. 16.</ref> The ordnance inventory designation was [[Sonderkraftfahrzeug|''Sd.Kfz.'']] 182.<ref name=\"J&D16\"/> It is also known under the informal name '''''K\u00f6nigstiger'''''<ref name=\"J&D16\"/> (the [[German language|German]] name for the [[Bengal tiger]]), often translated literally as '''Royal Tiger''', or somewhat incorrectly as '''King Tiger''' by Allied soldiers, especially by American forces.<ref>Buckley 2004, p. 119.</ref><ref>Tank Spotter's Guide, Bovington 2011 p. 63</ref>\n\nThe Tiger II was the successor to the [[Tiger I]], combining the latter's thick armour with the [[armour sloping]] used on the [[Panther tank|Panther]] medium tank. The tank weighed almost 70 [[tonne]]s, and was protected by {{convert|100|to|185|mm|abbr=on}} of armour to the front.<ref name=\"J&Darmor\"/> It was armed with the long barrelled [[8.8 cm KwK 43|8.8 cm KwK 43 L/71]] anti-tank cannon.<ref group=notes>''Kampfwagenkanone'' \u2013 abbr: ''KwK'' (English: \"fighting vehicle cannon\")</ref> The chassis was also the basis for the [[Jagdtiger]] [[Casemate#Armoured vehicles|turretless]] [[Jagdpanzer]] anti-tank vehicle.<ref name=\"Schneider19\">Schneider 1990, p. 18.</ref>\n\nThe Tiger II was issued to [[German heavy tank battalion|heavy tank battalions]] of the [[German Army (1935\u20131945)|Army]] and the [[Waffen-SS]]. It was first used in combat by [[503rd Heavy Panzer Battalion]] during the Allied [[invasion of Normandy]] on 11 July 1944;<ref>Jentz and Doyle 1993, p. 37.</ref> on the [[Eastern Front (World War II)|Eastern Front]], the first unit to be outfitted with the Tiger II was the [[501st Heavy Panzer Battalion]], which by 1 September 1944 listed 25 Tiger IIs operational.<ref>Jentz and Doyle 1993, p. 40.</ref>\n\n==Development==\nDevelopment of a heavy tank design had been initiated in 1937; the initial design contract was awarded to [[Henschel & Son|Henschel]]. Another design contract followed in 1939, and was given to [[Ferdinand Porsche|Porsche]].<ref name=\"Jentz & Doyle 1993, p. 3\">Jentz & Doyle 1993, p. 3.</ref> Both prototype series used the same turret design from [[Krupp]]; the main differences were in the hull, transmission, suspension and automotive features.<ref name=\"Jentz & Doyle 1993, p. 3\"/>\n\n[[File:Chambois1.jpg|thumb|left|[[SHAEF]] commander Gen. [[Dwight D. Eisenhower|Eisenhower]] walks by an overturned Tiger II. The overlapping, non-interleaved steel-rim roadwheel arrangement is visible.]]\nThe Henschel version used a conventional hull design with sloped armour resembling the layout of the Panther tank. It had a rear-mounted engine and used nine steel-tired, eighty-centimeter-diameter overlapping road wheels per side with internal springing, mounted on [[Torsion bar suspension|transverse torsion bars]], in a similar manner to the original Henschel-designed Tiger I. To simplify maintenance, however, as when the same steel-tired road wheels were used on later Tiger I hulls, the wheels were only overlapping ''without'' being interleaved\u2014the full ''Schachtellaufwerk'' rubber-rimmed road-wheel system that had been in use on nearly all German half-tracks used the interleaved design, later inherited by the early production versions of the Tiger&nbsp;I<ref>Jentz and Doyle 1993, pp. 10\u201312.</ref> and Panther.\n\nThe Porsche hull designs included a rear-mounted turret and a mid-mounted engine. The suspension was the same as on the ''[[Elefant]]'' tank destroyer. This had six road wheels per side mounted in paired [[bogies]] sprung with short longitudinal torsion bars that were integral to the wheel pair; this saved internal space and facilitated repairs. One Porsche version had a gasoline-electric drive (fundamentally identical to a [[Diesel-electric transmission]], only using a gasoline-fueled engine as the [[Prime mover (locomotive)|prime mover]]), similar to a [[gasoline-electric hybrid]] but without a storage battery; two separate [[drivetrain]]s in parallel, one per side of the tank, each consisting of a hybrid drive train; gasoline engine\u2013[[electric generator]]\u2013electric motor\u2013drive [[sprocket]]. This method of propulsion had been attempted before on the [[VK4501|Tiger (P)]] (later ''Elefant'' prototypes) and in some US designs and was put into production in the WW1 [[Saint-Chamond (tank)|Saint-Chamond]] tank and the post-WW1 FCM [[Char 2C]]. The Porsche suspension components were later used on a few of the later ''[[Jagdtiger]]'' tank destroyers. Another proposal was to use hydraulic drives. Dr. Porsche's unorthodox designs gathered little favour.<ref>Jentz and Doyle 1993, pp. 8\u201310.</ref>\n\n==Design==\n[[File:Munster Koenigstiger Porscheturm Modell detail.jpg|thumb|left|alt=A tank turret with a front face which curves up and down. The sides are slanted vertically and curved laterally.|A model depicting the curved front of the first version of the Krupp turret (erroneously called \"Porsche turret\")<ref name=\":0\">{{Citation|title=Tank Chats#47 King Tiger |date= 2 March 2018|publisher=The Tank Museum|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QuDuBwAhRa4&t=337|access-date=24 January 2019}}</ref>]]\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 101I-680-8282A-09, Budapest, Panzersoldaten in Panzer VI (Tiger II).jpg|thumb|left|alt=A tank turret with an almost square, flat, vertical face, the sides are almost vertical, and curve laterally only slightly.|A clear view of the angular front of the \"production turret\" designed by Krupp (erroneously called \"Henschel turret\")<ref name=\":0\" /> taken during [[Operation Panzerfaust]] in [[Budapest]], 15 October 1944. The rough [[Zimmerit]] coating is evident, used to prevent magnetic mines from adhering to the tank's armour.]]\n\nHenschel won the design contract, and all Tiger IIs were produced by the firm.<ref>Jentz and Doyle 1993, p. 17</ref> Two turret designs were used in production vehicles. The initial design is often misleadingly called the Tiger II (P), after the \"Porsche\" turret due to the misbelief that it was designed by Porsche for their [[VK 4502 (P)|prototype]]; in fact it was the initial Krupp design for both prototypes.<ref name=\":0\" /> This turret had a rounded front and steeply sloped sides, with a difficult-to-manufacture curved bulge on the turret's left side to accommodate the commander's cupola. Fifty early turrets were mounted to Henschel's hull and used in action. In December 1943 the more common \"production\" turret, sometimes erroneously called the \"Henschel\" turret, was simplified with a significantly thicker flat face, no [[shot trap]] (created by the curved face of the earlier turret), and less-steeply sloped sides, which prevented the need for a bulge for the commander's cupola, and added additional room for ammunition storage.<ref>Jentz and Doyle 1993, pp. 13\u201316.</ref>\n\nThe turrets were designed to mount the [[8.8 cm KwK 43]] L/71 gun. Combined with the ''Turmzielfernrohr'' 9d (German \"turret telescopic sight\") monocular sight by Leitz, which all but a few early Tiger IIs used, it was a very accurate and deadly weapon. During practice, the estimated probability of a first-round hit on a {{convert|2|m|abbr=on}} high, {{convert|2.5|m|abbr=on}} wide target was 100 percent at {{convert|1000|m|mi|abbr=on}}, 95\u201397 percent at {{convert|1500|m|mi|abbr=on}} and 85\u201387 percent at {{convert|2000|m|mi|abbr=on}}, depending on ammunition type. Recorded combat performance was lower, but still over 80 percent at 1,000&nbsp;m, in the 60s at 1,500&nbsp;m and the 40s at 2,000&nbsp;m. Penetration of armoured plate inclined at 30 degrees was {{convert|202|and|132|mm|abbr=on}} at {{convert|100|m|yd|abbr=on}} and {{convert|2000|m|mi|abbr=on}} respectively for the [[Panzergranate 39|''Panzergranate'' 39/43]] projectile (PzGr\u2014[[armor-piercing shot and shell|armour-piercing shell]]), and {{convert|238|and|153|mm|abbr=on}} for the PzGr. 40/43 projectile between the same ranges. The ''Sprenggranate'' 43 (SpGr) high-explosive round was available for soft targets, or the ''Hohlgranate'' or ''Hohlgeschoss'' 39 (HlGr\u2014HEAT or [[High-explosive anti-tank warhead]]) round, which had {{convert|90|mm|abbr=on}} penetration at any range, could be used as a dual-purpose munition against soft or armoured targets.<ref name=\"J&D23-24\">Jentz and Doyle 1993, pp. 23\u201324</ref>\n\nPowered turret traverse was provided by the variable speed Boehringer-Sturm L4S hydraulic motor, which was driven from the main engine by a secondary drive shaft. A high and a low speed setting was available to the gunner via a lever on his right. The turret could be rotated 360 degrees at 6\u00ba/second in low gear independent of engine rpm, at 19\u00ba/second \u2014 [[Tiger I#Mobility and reliability|the same as with the Tiger I]] \u2014  with the high speed setting and engine at 2000 rpm, and over 36\u00ba/second at the maximum allowable engine speed of 3000 rpm. The direction and speed of traverse were controlled by the gunner through foot pedals, or a control lever near his left arm. If power was lost, such as when the tank ran out of fuel, the turret could be slowly traversed by hand, assisted by the loader who had an additional wheel, which could manually rotate the turret at a rate of one-half a degree per each revolution of the hand crank (i.e. 20\u00b0 turret rotation required 40 full cranks of the handwheel, and to turn the turret a full 360\u00b0 the gunner would be required to crank the handwheel 720 full revolutions).\n\n[[File:Tiger II mg 7802.jpg|thumb|alt=The overhanging rear face of a large tank, two laterally spaced exhaust pipes protrude from mountings, pointing upwards, curving away from the vehicle at their ends.|Rear view showing dual exhausts]]\nLike all German tanks, the Tiger II had a [[petrol engine]]; in this case the same 700 [[Horsepower#PS|PS]] (690&nbsp;hp, 515&nbsp;kW) V-12 [[Maybach HL230|Maybach HL 230 P30]] which powered the much lighter [[Panther tank|Panther]] and [[Tiger I]] tanks. The Tiger II was under-powered, like many other heavy tanks of World War II, and consumed a lot of fuel, which was in short supply for the Germans. The transmission was the Maybach OLVAR EG 40 12 16 Model B, giving eight forward gears and four reverse, which drove the steering gear. This was the Henschel L 801, a double radius design which proved susceptible to failure. Transverse torsion bar suspension supported the hull on nine axles per side. Overlapped {{convert|800|mm|abbr=on}} diameter road wheels with rubber cushions and steel tyres rode inside the tracks.<ref name=\"J&D11-12\">Jentz and Doyle 1993, pp. 11\u201312.</ref>\n\nLike the Tiger I, each tank was issued with two sets of tracks: a normal \"battle track\" and a narrower \"transport\" version used during rail movement. The transport tracks reduced the overall width of the load and could be used to drive the tank short distances on firm ground. The crew were expected to change to normal battle tracks as soon as the tank was unloaded. Ground pressure was 0.76&nbsp;kg/cm<sup>2</sup> (10.8 psi).<ref>Jentz and Doyle 1993, p. 13.</ref>\n\n===Command variant===\nThe command variant of the Tiger II was designated ''Panzerbefehlswagen'' Tiger ''Ausf. B''. It had two versions, ''Sd.Kfz''. 267 and ''Sd.Kfz''. 268. These carried only 63 rounds of 8.8&nbsp;cm ammunition to provide room to    accommodate the extra radios and equipment,<ref name=\"J&D16\"/> and had additional armour on the engine compartment. The ''Sd.Kfz''. 267 was to have used ''FuG'' 8 and ''FuG'' 5 radio sets, with the most notable external changes being a {{convert|2|m|ft|adj=mid|-long|spell=in}} rod antenna mounted on the turret roof and a ''Sternantenne D'' (\"Star antenna D\"), mounted on an insulated base (the 105&nbsp;mm ''Antennenfu\u00df Nr. 1''), which was protected by a large armoured cylinder. This equipment was located on the rear decking in a position originally used for deep-wading equipment.<ref name=\"J&D16\"/> The ''Sd.Kfz''. 268 used ''FuG'' 7 and ''FuG'' 5 radios with a two-metre rod antenna mounted on the turret roof and a 1.4 metre rod antenna mounted on the rear deck.<ref>Jentz and Doyle 1993, pp. 16\u201317.</ref>\n\n==Production==\nThe Tiger II was developed late in the war and built in relatively small numbers. Orders were placed for 1,500 Tiger IIs\u2014slightly more than the 1,347 [[Tiger I]] tanks produced\u2014but production was severely disrupted by Allied bombing raids.<ref name=\"Manchester68-498\">Manchester 1968, p. 498.</ref> Among others, five raids between 22 September and 7 October 1944 destroyed 95 percent of the floor area of the Henschel plant. It is estimated that this caused the loss in production of some 657 Tiger IIs.<ref name=\"J&D17\">Jentz and Doyle 1993, p. 17.</ref> Only 492 units were produced: one in 1943, 379 in 1944, and 112 in 1945. Full production ran from mid-1944 to the end of the war.<ref name=\"Jentz96-288\">Jentz 1996, p. 288.</ref> Each Tiger II produced needed 300,000 man hours to manufacture and cost over 800,000 Reichsmark or US$300,000 (adjusted for inflation, approximately $4.2 million in 2018) per vehicle. The vehicle was the costliest German tank to produce at the time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tanks-encyclopedia.com/ww2/nazi_germany/Panzer-VI_Konigstiger.php|title=Panzer VI Ausf.B K\u00f6nigstiger (1944)|website=www.tanks-encyclopedia.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-11-12}}</ref>\n\nThe Tiger II served as the basis for one production variant, the ''[[Jagdtiger]]'' [[casemate]]d [[tank destroyer]],<ref name=\"Schneider19\"/> and a proposed Grille 17/21/30/42 self-propelled mount for heavy guns which never reached production.<ref>{{cite web |last=Parada |first=George |url=http://www.achtungpanzer.com/pz13.htm#grille |title=Grille series |work=Achtung Panzer! |accessdate=2009-10-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080821073415/http://www.achtungpanzer.com/pz13.htm#grille |archivedate=2008-08-21 }}</ref>\n\n==Proposed upgrades==\nThe [[List of WWII Maybach engines|HL234]], an engine born from the developments initiated by attempting to convert the [[Maybach HL230]] to [[fuel injection]], would have increased the power from 700 to about 800 PS (hp). The Entwicklungskommission Panzer unanimously decided that HL234 be immediately included in the engine design and procurement program. The AK-7-200 was also explored as an alternative to the Maybach Olvar-B drive train, but ''[[Waffenamt]]'' research and development department ''Wa Pr\u00fcf 6'' found that it offered inferior driving characteristics and so the Maybach Olvar-B was retained.<ref name=\"J&D1997.144-154\">{{cite book|last1=Jentz|first1=Thomas|last2=Doyle|first2=Hilary|title=Germany's Tiger Tanks: VK45.02 to TIGER II Design, Production & Modifications|date=1997|publisher=Schiffer Publishing, Ltd|isbn=0764302248|pages=144\u2013154}}</ref> There was also a program using the Simmering-Graz-Pauker Sla.16 engine, but the war's constraint on supplies and capitulation resulted in the cancellation of this program.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}} Krupp proposed mounting a new main weapon, the [[10.5 cm]] KwK L/68. ''Wa Pr\u00fcf 6'' was not supportive of this as the Heer had not accepted the cannon itself. Other suggested improvements included stabilised sights, a stabilised main gun, an automatic ammunition feed, a [[Carl Zeiss AG]] [[stereoscopic]] [[rangefinder]], heated crew compartment, stowage <!-- stowage is the correct term, storage is wrong --> for an additional 12 rounds, and an [[Overpressure (CBRN protection)|overpressure]] and air filtration system to protect against poison gas. However, these also never got beyond the proposal stage or did not enter production before the war ended.<ref name=\"J&D1997.144-154\"/>\n\n==Specifications==\n* Gearbox: Maybach OLVAR EG 40 12 16 B (eight forward and four reverse)<ref name=\"J&D11-12\"/>\n* Radio: FuG 5, ''Befehlswagen'' (command tank) version: ''FuG'' 8 (''Sd.Kfz''. 267), ''FuG'' 7 (''Sd.Kfz''. 268)<ref name=\"J&D16\"/>\n* Ammunition: {{See also|8.8 cm KwK 43}}\n** 8.8&nbsp;cm \u2013 80 rounds (early turret),<ref name=\"J&D23\"/> 86 rounds (main production turret), usually 50% ''PzGr'' 39/43 and 50% SprGr 43, sometimes with a limited number of ''PzGr'' 40/43, or with the ''SprGr'' replaced by HlGr<ref name=\"J&D23\"/>\n**: ''PzGr'' 39/43 (Armour-piercing, hardened steel) (longer range, lower penetration, explosive filler)<ref name=\"J&D28\"/><ref name=\"J&D23-24\"/>\n**: ''PzGr'' 40/43 (Armour-piercing, tungsten carbide core) (shorter range, higher penetration, inert)<ref name=\"J&D28\"/><ref name=\"J&D23-24\"/>\n**: ''SprGr'' 43 (High explosive)<ref name=\"J&D28\"/>\n**: ''HlGr'' 39 (Hollow charge)<ref name=\"J&D28\"/>\n** 7.92mm \u2013 up to 5,850 rounds<ref name=\"J&D1997.162-165\"/>\n* Gun Sight: ''Turmzielfernrohr'' 9b/1 (TZF 9b/1) binocular to May 1944, then the 9d (TZF 9d) monocular.<ref>Jentz and Doyle 1993, p. 19.</ref>\n\n{| border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=1 style=\"border-top:3px double #999; border-collapse:collapse; text-align:left; font-size:normal;\" width=\"80%\" summary=\"\"\n|+ style=\"font-size:normal; text-align:left;\" | '''Armour layout:''' (all angles from horizontal)<ref name=\"J&Darmor\">Jentz and Doyle 1993, pp. 12, 15.</ref>\n|- style=\"vertical-align:bottom; border-bottom:1px solid #999;\"\n|-\n|Hull front ||(lower)|| {{convert|100|mm|abbr=on}} at 40\u00b0 || (upper) || {{convert|150|mm|abbr=on}} at 40\u00b0\n|-\n|Hull side ||(lower) || {{convert|80|mm|abbr=on}} at 90\u00b0 || (upper) || {{convert|80|mm|abbr=on}} at 65\u00b0\n|-\n|Hull rear || || {{convert|80|mm|abbr=on}} at 60\u00b0 || ||\n|-\n|Hull top || || {{convert|40|mm|abbr=on}} at 0\u00b0 || ||\n|-\n|Hull bottom ||(front)|| {{convert|40|mm|abbr=on}} at 90\u00b0 || (rear) || {{convert|25|mm|abbr=on}} at 90\u00b0\n|-\n|Turret front ||(production)||{{convert|180|mm|abbr=on}} at 80\u00b0 || (\"Porsche\") || {{convert|60|to|100|mm|abbr=on}}, rounded\n|-\n|Turret side ||(production) || {{convert|80|mm|abbr=on}} at 69\u00b0 || (\"Porsche\") || {{convert|80|mm|abbr=on}} at 60\u00b0\n|-\n|Turret rear ||(production) || {{convert|80|mm|abbr=on}} at 70\u00b0 || (\"Porsche\") || {{convert|80|mm|abbr=on}} at 60\u00b0\n|-\n|Turret top ||(production) || {{convert|44|mm|abbr=on}} at 0\u201310\u00b0 || (\"Porsche\") || {{convert|40|mm|abbr=on}} at 0\u201312\u00b0\n|\n|- style=\"border-top:3px double #999;\"\n| colspan=5 |\n|}\n\n==Operational history==\n\n===Organisation===\n{{See also|German heavy tank battalion}}\nApart from research, training, and a five-tank attachment to the [[Panzer Lehr]], the Tiger II was only issued to heavy tank battalions (''schwere Panzer-Abteilungen'') of the [[German Army (Wehrmacht)|German Army]] (''Heer''), or ''[[Waffen-SS]]''.<ref name=\"J&D36\">Jentz and Doyle 1993, p. 36.</ref>\n\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 146-1975-102-14A, Panzer VI (Tiger II, K\u00f6nigstiger).jpg|thumb|alt=A row of seven large tanks lined up with their long guns pointing up at an angle, as if saluting.|Tiger II tanks fitted with the narrower \"vehicle-transport tracks\" of the [[503rd Heavy Tank Battalion (Germany)|''Schwere Heeres Panzer Abteilung'' 503 (s.H.Pz.Abt. 503) 'Feldherrnhalle']] posing in formation for the [[Die Deutsche Wochenschau|Nazi German wartime-propaganda newsreel]] at the armour-training ground in Sennelager, Germany, prior to the unit's departure for Hungary]]\n\nA standard battalion (''Abteilung'') comprised 45 tanks:<ref name=\"J&D36\"/>\n{| border=1 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=3 style=\"line-height:normal; text-align:center; border-top:3px double #999; border-collapse:collapse;\"\n|- style=\"vertical-align:bottom; border-bottom:1px solid #999;\"\n|colspan=9 |Battalion command<br /> 3 \u00d7 Tiger II\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top; border-bottom:1px solid #999;\"\n|colspan=3 | 1st company command<br /> 2 \u00d7 Tiger II ||colspan=3 | 2nd company command<br />2 \u00d7 Tiger II ||colspan=3 | 3rd company command<br />2 \u00d7 Tiger II\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top; border-bottom:3px double #999;\"\n|1st platoon<br />4 \u00d7 Tiger II ||2nd platoon<br /> 4 \u00d7 Tiger II ||3rd platoon<br /> 4 \u00d7 Tiger II\n|1st platoon<br />4 \u00d7 Tiger II ||2nd platoon<br /> 4 \u00d7 Tiger II ||3rd platoon<br /> 4 \u00d7 Tiger II\n|1st platoon<br />4 \u00d7 Tiger II ||2nd platoon<br /> 4 \u00d7 Tiger II ||3rd platoon<br /> 4 \u00d7 Tiger II\n|-\n|}\n\nUnits that used the Tiger II were as follows:<ref>Jentz and Doyle 1993, pp. 37\u201342.</ref>\n:''Heer: (s.H.Pz.Abt)'' [[501st heavy tank battalion (Germany)|501]], [[502nd heavy tank battalion (Germany)|502]], [[503rd heavy tank battalion (Germany)|503]], [[504th heavy tank battalion (Germany)|504]], [[505th heavy tank battalion (Germany)|505]], [[506th heavy tank battalion (Germany)|506]], [[507th heavy tank battalion (Germany)|507]], [[508th heavy tank battalion (Germany)|508]], [[509th heavy tank battalion (Germany)|509]], [[510th heavy tank battalion (Germany)|510]], [[511th heavy tank battalion (Germany)|511]]\n:''SS: (s.SS.Pz.Abt)'' [[SS Heavy Panzer Battalion 101|501]], [[SS Heavy Panzer Battalion 102|502]], [[SS Heavy Panzer Battalion 103|503]]\n\n===Reliability and mobility===\n[[File:Bovington Tiger II grey bg.jpg|thumb|alt=A large, turreted tank with dull yellow, green and brown wavy camouflage, on display inside Bovington museum. The tracks are wide, and the frontal armour is sloped. The long gun overhangs the bow by several meters.|A camouflaged Tiger II in display in Bovington Tank museum. The long gun overhangs the bow by several meters.]]\n\nEarly Tiger IIs proved unreliable, owing principally to leaking seals and gaskets, and an overburdened drive train originally intended for a lighter vehicle.<ref name=\"J&D34\">Jentz and Doyle 1993, p. 34</ref> The double radius steering gear was initially particularly prone to failure.<ref name=\"J&D11\">Jentz and Doyle 1993, p. 11</ref> Lack of crew training could amplify this problem; drivers originally given only limited training on other tanks were often sent directly to operational units already on their way to the front.<ref name=\"J&D34\"/>\n\nThe [[501st heavy tank battalion (Germany)|''Schwere Heeres Panzer Abteilung'' 501]] (s.H.Pz.Abt. 501) arrived on the Eastern Front with only eight out of 45 tanks operational; these faults were mostly due to drive-train failures. The first five Tiger IIs delivered to the [[Panzer Lehr Division]] broke down before they could be used in combat, and were destroyed to prevent capture.<ref name=\"J&D35\">Jentz and Doyle 1993, p. 35.</ref>\n\nThe introduction of modified seals, gaskets and drive train components, as well as improved driver training and sufficient maintenance improved the tank's mechanical reliability.<ref>Jentz and Doyle 1993, p. 18.</ref> Statistics from 15 March 1945 show reliability rates of 59 percent for the Tiger, almost equal to the 62 percent of the [[Panzer IV]] and better than the 48 percent of the [[Panther Tank|Panther]] that were operational by this period.<ref name=\"J&D36\"/>\n\nNotwithstanding its initial reliability problems, the Tiger II was remarkably agile for such a heavy vehicle. Contemporary German records and testing results indicate that its tactical mobility was as good as or better than most German or Allied tanks.<ref>Jentz and Doyle 1993, pp. 33\u201334.</ref>\n\n===Combat history===\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 101I-721-0397-34, Frankreich, Panzer VI (Tiger II, K\u00f6nigstiger) crop.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.2|Tiger IIs (with the first version of the Krupp turret) on the move in France, June 1944]]\nThe first combat use of the Tiger II was by the 1st Company of the [[503rd Heavy Panzer Battalion]] (s.H.Pz.Abt. 503) during the [[Operation Overlord|Battle of Normandy]], opposing Operation [[Operation Atlantic|''Atlantic'']] between [[Troarn]] and [[Demouville]] on 18 July 1944. Two were lost in combat, while the company commander's tank became irrecoverably trapped after falling into a bomb crater created during Operation [[Operation Goodwood|''Goodwood'']].<ref name=\"Schneider133\">Schneider 2000, p. 133.</ref>\n\nOn the [[Eastern Front (World War II)|Eastern Front]], it was first used on 12 August 1944 by the [[501st Heavy Panzer Battalion]] (s.H.Pz.Abt. 501) resisting the [[Lvov\u2013Sandomierz Offensive]]. It attacked the Soviet bridgehead over the [[Vistula River]] near [[Baran\u00f3w Sandomierski]]. On the road to [[Ogl\u0119d\u00f3w]], three Tiger IIs were destroyed in an ambush by a few [[T-34|T-34-85s]].<ref>Zaloga 1994, p. 14.</ref> Because these German tanks suffered ammunition explosions, which caused many crew fatalities, main gun rounds were no longer allowed to be stowed within the turret, reducing capacity to 68.<ref>Schneider 2000, p. 46.</ref> Up to fourteen Tiger IIs of the 501st were destroyed or captured in the area between 11 and 14 August to ambushes and flank attacks by both Soviet T-34-85 and [[IS-2]] tanks, and ISU-122 assault guns in inconvenient sandy terrain. The capture of three operational Tiger IIs allowed the Soviets to conduct tests at Kubinka and to evaluate its strengths and weaknesses<ref>Sledgehammers: Strengths and Flaws of Tiger Tank Battalions in World War II. Christopher W. Wilbeck. Aberjona, 2004. p.135</ref>\n\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 101I-680-8283A-12A, Budapest, marschierende Pfeilkreuzler und Panzer VI.jpg|thumb|alt=A large tank with sloped frontal armour and a flat faced turret, by a column of marching soldiers wearing overcoats and helmets, in a wide city street. A large building to the rear shows the scars of battle.|A Tiger II of [[503rd Heavy Panzer Battalion|s.H.Pz.Abt. 503]] and Hungarian troops in a battle-scarred street in [[Buda]]'s Castle district, October 1944]]\nOn 15 October 1944, Tiger IIs of 503rd Heavy Panzer Battalion played a crucial role during ''[[Operation Panzerfaust]]'', supporting [[Otto Skorzeny]]'s troops in taking the Hungarian capital of [[Budapest]], which ensured that the country remained with the Axis until the end of the war. The 503rd then took part in the [[Battle of Debrecen]]. The 503rd remained in the Hungarian theater of operations for 166 days, during which it accounted for at least 121 Soviet tanks, 244 anti-tank guns and artillery pieces, five aircraft and a train. This was set against the loss of 25 Tiger IIs; ten were knocked out by Soviet troops and burned out, two were sent back to Vienna for a factory overhaul, while thirteen were blown up by their crews for various reasons, usually to prevent them from falling into enemy hands. [[Kurt Knispel]], the highest scoring tank ace of all time (162 enemy [[armoured fighting vehicle]]s destroyed), also served with the 503rd, and was killed in action on 29 April 1945 in his Tiger II.<ref name=\"Sz\u00e1mv\u00e9ber147\">Sz\u00e1mv\u00e9ber, 2000. p. 147.</ref>\n\nThe Tiger II was also used in significant numbers, distributed into four heavy panzer battalions, during the [[Ardennes Offensive]] (also known as the Battle of the Bulge) of December 1944.<ref>Schneider 2005, pp. 214\u2013216.</ref> At least 150 Tiger IIs were present, nearly a third of total production, and most were lost during the course of the offensive.<ref>Green, Michael. \"German Tanks of World War II\". May 14, 2000. Page 73.</ref> Famously, during the [[Battle of St. Vith]] an [[M8 Greyhound]] armoured car is alleged to have destroyed a Tiger II after getting in behind it on the Schonberg Road, firing three 37&nbsp;mm rounds into the rear armor of the Tiger from only {{convert|25|yd|m|abbr=on}} and setting it on fire: \"There was a muffled explosion, followed by flames which billowed out of the turret and engine port.\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Beevor |first=Antony |authorlink=Antony Beevor |title=Ardennes 1944: Hitler's last gamble |publisher=Viking |date=2015 |location=New York |page=172 |url= |doi= |isbn=978-0-670-02531-2}}</ref>  However, there is confusion in the unit history over whether he vehicle was a Tiger or Tiger II and German unit histories<ref>Schneider 2005, pp. 214\u2013216.</ref> indicate that there were no German heavy tanks lost or even present within 20 miles of St Vith at the time of the alleged incident.  Combined with the habit of American troops of reporting almost all German tanks they made contact with as \"Tigers\" it is more likely that this was a case of mistaken identity.\n\nSome Tiger IIs were also present during the Soviet [[Vistula\u2013Oder Offensive|Vistula\u2013Oder]]<ref>Schneider 2000, p. 47.</ref> and [[East Prussian Offensive]]s in January 1945,<ref>Schneider 2000, pp. 89\u201391.</ref> as well as the German [[Lake Balaton Offensive]] in Hungary in March 1945,<ref>Schneider 2005, p. 217.</ref> the [[Battle of the Seelow Heights]] in April 1945, and the [[Battle of Berlin]] at the end of the war.<ref>Schneider 2005, pp. 300\u2013303.</ref> On 12 January 1945, a column of Tiger IIs from 524th Heavy Panzer Battalion were involved in a short-range engagement with IS-2 tanks near the village of [[Lis\u00f3w, Kielce County|Lisow,]] with both the German and Soviet formations suffering heavy losses.<ref>IS-2 Heavy Tank 1944\u201373. Steven J. Zaloga. Bloomsbury Publishing, 2011. p.31</ref>\n\nThe [[103rd SS Heavy Panzer Battalion]] (s.SS Pz.Abt. 503) claimed approximately 500 kills in the period from January to April 1945 on the Eastern Front for the loss of 45 Tiger IIs (most of which were abandoned and destroyed by their own crews after mechanical breakdowns or for lack of fuel).<ref>Schneider 2005, pp. 304, 324.</ref>\n\n===Gun and armour performance===\n[[File:Tiger II punctured in front turret.jpg|thumb|left|alt=A head-on view of a large tank with a flat-faced turret. Its sloped bow armour is scarred with several fist-sized dents, and there is a fist-sized hole in the front of the turret|A Tiger II with fist-sized dents in its front armour and a hole in its turret.<ref>Pallud 2006, p. 152</ref>]]\nThe heavy armour and powerful long-range gun gave the Tiger II an advantage against all opposing [[Allies of World War II|Western Allied]] and [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] tanks attempting to engage it from head on. This was especially true on the Western Front where, until the arrival of the few [[M26 Pershing]]s in 1945 and the few [[M4 Sherman#Upgrades|M4A3E2 Sherman \"Jumbo\"s]] that were scattered around Europe after D-Day, neither the British nor US forces brought heavy tanks into service. A ''Wa Pr\u00fcf 1'' report estimated that the Tiger II's frontal aspect was impervious to the 122&nbsp;mm D-25T, the heaviest although not the best penetrating tank gun on the Allied side. On the other hand, an R.A.C 3.d. document of February 1945 estimated that the British [[Ordnance QF 17-pounder|QF 17-pounder (76.2 mm)]] gun, using [[armour-piercing discarding sabot]] shot was theoretically capable of penetrating the front of the Tiger II's turret and nose (lower front hull) at {{convert|1100|and|1200|yd|m|abbr=on}} respectively although, given the lack of a stated angle, this is presumably at the ideal 90 degrees angle.<ref name=\"KTHT34-36\">{{cite book|last1=Jentz|first1=Thomas|last2=Doyle|first2=Hilary|title=Kingtiger Heavy Tank 1942\u201345|date=1993|publisher=Osprey Publishing Ltd|isbn=185532282X|pages=34\u201336|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ATawrvkJBAUC&pg=PA35}}</ref> Some sources {{who|date=July 2018}} claimed that there is no proof that the glacis armour of the Tiger II was ever penetrated in combat.<ref>{{cite web |title = PzKpfw VI Tiger II |url = http://www.fprado.com/armorsite/tiger2.htm |work = The Armor Site! |publisher=Fabio Prado |accessdate = 23 November 2015}}</ref>{{better source|fprado.com is a tertiary source with unknown editorial oversight|date=July 2018}}\n\nAs a result of its thick frontal armour, flanking manoeuvres were most often used against the Tiger II to attempt a shot at the thinner side and rear armour, giving a tactical advantage to the Tiger II in most engagements.<ref name=\"Jary274\">Jarymowycz 2001, p. 274.</ref> Moreover, the main armament of the Tiger II was capable of knocking out any Allied tank frontally at ranges exceeding {{convert|2.5|km}}, well beyond the effective range of Allied tank guns.<ref name=\"Jary258\">Jarymowycz 2001, p. 258.</ref>\n\n===Soviet wartime testing===\n\nDuring August 1944, two Tiger Ausf B tanks were captured by the Soviets near [[Sandomierz]], and were soon moved to the testing grounds at [[Kubinka]]. During the transfer, the two tanks suffered from various mechanical breakdowns; the cooling system was insufficient for the excessively hot weather, where the engine tended to overheat and cause a consequential failure of the gearbox. The right suspension of one of the tanks had to be completely replaced, and its full functionality could not be re-established. The tank broke down again every 10\u201315&nbsp;km. The [[8.8 cm KwK 43]] gave positive results in penetration and accuracy, which were on par with the 122&nbsp;mm D-25T. It proved capable of passing completely through its \"colleague\", a Tiger Ausf B's turret at a range of 400 m. The armour of one vehicle was tested by firing at it with shells between 100 and 152&nbsp;mm calibre. The welding was, despite careful workmanship, significantly worse than on similar designs. As a result, even when shells did not penetrate the armour, there was often a large amount of [[spalling]] from the inside of the plates, which damaged the transmission and rendered the tank inoperable. Further testing showed that the armour plate itself exhibited deficiencies in quality compared to earlier German tanks such as the Tiger I and Panther. Lab testing found that the armour plates lacked molybdenum (ascribed to a loss of supply, being replaced by vanadium), resulting in low malleability.<ref name=\"Tigertest\"/>{{unreliable source?|date=April 2017}}\n\nThe expanded firing test states that the [[Armor-piercing shot and shell|\u0410\u0420]] projectiles from the [[100 mm field gun M1944 (BS-3)|100 mm BS-3]] and [[122 mm gun M1931 (A-19)|122 mm A-19]] gun penetrated a Tiger Ausf B's turret at ranges of 1000\u20131500 metres, which suggests a quality factor of 0.86 for the Tiger Ausf B's turret. The firing test against the Tiger B turret front, however, was conducted after removal of the gun and mantlet, and resulted in penetrations close to armour openings, such as vision slits and gun location. The penetrations to the right gun opening were influenced by previous 100&nbsp;mm projectile penetration hits or armour damage.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Bird|first1=Lorrin Rexford|last2=Livingston|first2=Robert D.|title=WWII Ballistics - Armour and Gunnery|date=2001|publisher=Overmatch Press|page=90|<!-- accessdate=22 January 2015 -->}}</ref> Some {{who|date=July 2018}} have said the tank's hull and turret side plates were penetrated by [[Armor-piercing shot and shell|\u0410\u0420 shot]] from domestic 85&nbsp;mm and American 76&nbsp;mm guns at ranges of {{convert|800|-|2000|m|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"Tigertest\">{{cite web |url=http://english.battlefield.ru/analytics/126-was-the-tiger-really-king.html |title=Was the Tiger really King?: Testing the King Tiger at Kubinka |work=The Russian Battlefield|accessdate= 2009-10-20 |date=19 September 2011 |quote=source: Tankomaster #6 1999.}}</ref>{{unreliable source?|date=April 2017}} The [[100 mm field gun M1944 (BS-3)|100 mm BS-3]] and [[122 mm gun M1931 (A-19)|122 mm A-19]] could also penetrate the weld joints of the front hull at ranges of 500\u2013600 metres after 3\u20134 shots.<ref name=\"Tekhnika molodezhi\">{{cite book|last1=Zheltov|first1=Igor|title= TankoMaster Special Issues 02, 2002: Isoif Stalin|publisher= Tekhnika molodezhi|page=33}}</ref>\n\nSome {{who|date=July 2018}} have said the large 122&nbsp;mm OF-471 (\u041e\u0424-471) [[High explosive|HE]] projectiles, equipped with a 3.8&nbsp;kg [[TNT]] charge, would easily crack and could even completely tear off the front armor plate at the seam weld, blow off the turret and driver sprocket<ref name=\"books.google.com.vn\"/><ref name=\"ReferenceB\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=MuGsf0psjvcC&pg=PA41&dq=is-2+powerful&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjVsremgMvSAhUIU7wKHaX5DswQ6AEIIDAB#v=onepage&q=is-2%20powerful&f=false The Encyclopedia of Weapons of World War II, Chris Bishop, P. 41]</ref>{{unreliable source?|date=April 2017}}, mechanical shock and explosion was often enough to knock out enemy heavy tanks without any armor penetration<ref name=\"books.google.com.vn\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=RLjQDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA5&dq=122mm+shell+effect&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=122mm%20shell%20effect&f=false Soviet Heavy Tanks: World War 2 In Review Special]</ref>{{unreliable source?|date=April 2017}}\n\n==Surviving vehicles==\n[[File:Koenigstiger Saumur F.jpg|thumb|alt=The side of a large tank with wide, wavy green and grey striped camouflage, as it drives past, the commander sitting in the cupola.|The working Tiger II of the ''Mus\u00e9e des Blind\u00e9s'' being displayed to the public, 2005]]The only working example is displayed at the ''[[Mus\u00e9e des Blind\u00e9s]]'', [[Saumur]], France. It has the production turret and is accessible to the public. This tank belonged to the 1st Company, [[101st SS Heavy Panzer Battalion]]. It was believed to have been abandoned by its crew on 23 August 1944, due to engine problems, at [[Brueil-en-Vexin]], near [[Mantes-la-Jolie]]. It was salvaged by the French Army in September 1944 and then stored in a factory in [[Satory]] before being transferred to the museum in 1975. Believed to have carried turret number 123, Colonel Michel Aubry, the founder of the museum, decided to put 233 on the turret in honour of the Tiger II that destroyed his Sherman tank at the end of the war. Unlike other captured German vehicles, this Tiger II was never used by the French Army.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://tank-photographs.s3-website-eu-west-1.amazonaws.com/tiger-II-heavy-tank-Konigstiger.html |title = Surviving WW2 King Tiger II Ausf. B Heavy Tank - Restored Preserved Panzers}}</ref>\nOther survivors include:\n[[File:Panzerkampfwagen VI Ausfuhrung B (Tiger II pre-production) front-left2 2017 Bovington.jpg|thumb|alt=A frontal view of a large, pale-yellow tank in a white museum gallery.. Its curved-faced turret is pointing forwards, the long gun overhangs the front by several meters.|The Bovington Tank Museum's prototype Tiger II on display at the Museum's  Tiger Collection Exhibition, 2017]]\n[[File:Tiger II La Gleize2008.jpg|thumb|alt=The side of a large tank, freshly painted in pale yellow, green and rust-brown camouflage, sitting in sunlight on a concrete plinth.|Tiger II at La Gleize, Belgium]]\n[[File:KingTigerPatton.jpg|thumb|alt=A side view of a large turreted tank in a museum, with sections of its superstructure and turret cut away.|Tiger II located at the Patton Museum of Cavalry and Armor, US]]\n[[File:SdKfz182.jpg|thumb|alt=A three quarters view of a large tank with a flat-faced turret, dull yellow, green and brown wavy camouflage, on display inside a museum. The frontal armour is sloped. The long gun overhangs the bow by several meters. Two waist-high cartridges sit on their bases in front of it.|Tiger II with the production turret, at the ''[[Deutsches Panzermuseum]]'', Germany]]\n* [[The Tank Museum|Bovington Tank Museum]], Dorset, UK. Tiger II with early production turret is on display. This vehicle was the second soft steel prototype made and did not see active service. This Tiger II's engine was removed for use in the restoration of [[Tiger 131]], the only working example of a Tiger I. A production turret Tiger II is on loan from the Defence Academy, Shrivenham, UK.\n* [[Defence Academy of the United Kingdom]], [[Shrivenham]], UK. Tiger II (production turret). This vehicle was from ''s.SS Pz.Abt. 501'', with hull number 280093, turret number 104, and has a comprehensive coating of [[Zimmerit]].<ref>Jentz and Doyle 1997, p.108.</ref> It was claimed by Sergeant Roberts of A Squadron, [[23rd Hussars]], [[11th Armoured Division]] in a Sherman tank near [[Beauvais]], although it had already been disabled and abandoned by its crew following damage to its tracks and final drive.<ref>Schneider 2005, p. 212.</ref> There is a photograph showing this vehicle after its final action in a beet field with its turret turned 90\u00b0.<ref>{{cite web |last=Parada |first=George |title=Tiger II Gallery 2 |url=http://www.achtungpanzer.com/gallery/ktgal2.htm |work=Achtung Panzer! |accessdate=2009-10-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100119054628/http://www.achtungpanzer.com/gallery/ktgal2.htm |archivedate=2010-01-19 }}</ref> This item is currently on display at [[The Tank Museum|Bovington Tank Museum]], in Dorset, UK.\n* [[The Wheatcroft Collection]], [[Leicestershire]], UK. A private collector, [[Kevin Wheatcroft]], is about{{citation needed|reason=dated information |date=June 2015}} to start a restoration/rebuild of a complete Tiger II. The project will include parts from many individual Tiger IIs, but many parts will be of new manufacture. Wheatcroft has stated that he has 70\u201380% of the original parts needed for a reconstruction and more parts are sourced continuously. Known and shown parts are a complete front glacis plate, [[8.8 cm KwK 43]] main armament, engine deck plates, approx. 1/3 hull (rear) in one part, a set of tracks, and approx. 2/3 of the left-side hull plate in two parts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wheatcroftcollection.com/tiger.html|title=Gallery of parts|publisher=Wheatcroft Collection |accessdate=2009-10-20}}</ref> The aim of the project is a complete Tiger II in running order.\n* [[Mantes-la-Jolie]], France. A more or less complete, but wrecked, Tiger II (production turret) is buried under regional road 913. Parts of the turret were recovered in a limited exploratory excavation in 2001. Further excavation is currently halted for financial reasons. There are plans to fully excavate and restore this Tiger II for a [[Vexin]] battle memorial.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vexinhistoirevivante.com/memorial_tigre.html |title=Memorial Vexin 44 |work=vexinhistoirevivante.com |language=French |accessdate=2009-10-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091021151031/http://www.vexinhistoirevivante.com/memorial_tigre.html |archivedate=2009-10-21 }}</ref>\n* [[Kubinka Tank Museum]], Russia. Tiger II (production turret) with turret number 002 (502) captured at Ogl\u0119d\u00f3w by the Red Army. The museum is open to the public.\n* [[La Gleize#Sights|December 44 Museum]], [[La Gleize]], Belgium. A cosmetically restored Tiger II (production turret) Hull number 280273, built in October 1944. Turret number 213 from ''s.SS Pz.Abt 501.'' Displayed at the entrance to DECEMBER 44 MUSEUM Collections, a museum devoted entirely to the [[Battle of the Bulge]]. This tank was abandoned in La Gleize on 24 December 1944, where the advance of [[Kampfgruppe Peiper]] was halted. The front part, about 1/3, of the gun barrel is restored with a Panther gun barrel and muzzle brake. It also has restored mudguards. It is stripped of exterior and internal fittings and most of the torsion bars are broken, but it still has its gearbox and engine in place.\n* [[Deutsches Panzermuseum]], [[Munster, Lower Saxony|Munster]], Germany. Tiger II (production turret) displayed in interior location accessible to public on payment of entrance fee. Hull number 280101. Originally bearing turret number 121 from s.SS.Pz.Abt 501 it was restored with a different number for unknown reasons.\n* National Armor & Cavalry Heritage Museum, Restoration Shop, [[Fort Benning, GA]], United States. Tiger II (production turret). Hull number 280243, built in September 1944. Turret number 332 from ''s.SS Pz.Abt. 501''. Abandoned near [[Trois-Ponts]], it was captured by the US Army on 24 December 1944. The left side was cut open for educational purposes at the [[Aberdeen Proving Ground]] in the late 1940s. Was on display at the former \"Patton Museum of Cavalry & Armor, Fort Knox KY, then under BRAC transferred to Fort Benning.\n* [[Schweizerisches Milit\u00e4rmuseum Full]], Switzerland. This Tiger II (production turret) was previously displayed in the Thun Tank Museum, and is now on loan to the Schweizerisches Milit\u00e4rmuseum Full (September 2006). It will be completely restored to running condition in a long-term project. This tank was given to Switzerland by France after the war. Hull number 280215 from ''s.H.Pz.Abt 506''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.koenigstiger.ch |title=Tiger II |work=Schweizerisches Milit\u00e4rmuseum Full |accessdate=2009-10-20}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of military vehicles of World War II]]\n* [[List of World War II military vehicles of Germany]]\n* [[List of Sd.Kfz. designations]]\n* [[List of WWII Maybach engines]]\n\n===Tanks of comparable role, performance and era===\n{{Div col|colwidth=25em}}\n* [[Great Britain|British]] [[Centurion tank|Centurion]] main battle tank - developed mid-World War II, entered service 1946\n* British [[Black Prince (tank)|Black Prince]] heavy tank - six prototypes built in May 1945; did not enter service\n* [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] [[IS tank family#IS-2|IS-2 model 1944]] heavy assault tank - entered service in 1944\n* Soviet [[IS tank family#IS-3|IS-3]] heavy tank - entered service in 1945\n* [[United States]] [[T32 heavy tank|T32]] heavy tank - prototype; did not enter service\n* United States [[M26 Pershing#Super Pershing 2|T26E1-1 \"Super Pershing\"]] heavy tank - single prototype M26 Pershing with extra armour and improved T13E1 L/73 90mm gun; fought in Western Europe during 1945\n* United States [[T29 Heavy Tank|T29]] heavy tank - prototype; did not enter service\n* [[France|French]] [[ARL 44]] - produced and served in limited numbers in the late 1940s and early 1950s\n* French [[AMX-50|AMX 50]] - several prototypes produced in the late 1940s and early 1950s\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==References==\n'''Informational notes'''\n{{Reflist|group=notes}}\n\n'''Citations'''\n{{Reflist|20em}}\n\n'''Bibliography'''\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite book | last = Buckley | first = John | title = British Armour in the Normandy Campaign, 1944 | publisher = F. Cass | location = London | year = 2004 | isbn = 978-0-7146-5323-5 }}\n* {{cite book |last=Ford |first=Roger |year=2012 |title=The World's Great Tanks: From 1916 to the Present Day |location=London |publisher=Amber Books Ltd |isbn=9781908696014 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Jarymowycz | first = Roman | title = Tank Tactics: from Normandy to Lorraine | publisher = L. Rienner Publishers | location = Boulder | year = 2001 | isbn = 978-1-55587-950-1 }}\n* {{cite book | last1 = Jentz | first1 = Thomas |last2 =Doyle |first2= Hilary | title = Germany's Tiger Tanks \u2013 Vk45 to Tiger II: Design, Production & Modifications | publisher = Schiffer Publishing | location = West Chester | year = 1997 | isbn = 978-0-7643-0224-4 }}\n* {{cite book | last1 = Jentz |first1 = Thomas |last2 = Doyle |first2= Hilary |title= Kingtiger Heavy Tank, 1942\u201345 |publisher= Osprey |series=New Vangaurd |location= London |year=1993 |isbn=978-1-85532-282-0 }}\n* {{cite book|last= Jentz|first= Thomas|title=Panzertruppen 2: The Complete Guide to the Creation & Combat Employment of Germany's Tank Force 1943\u20131945|publisher=Schiffer|year= 1996|isbn= 978-0-7643-0080-6 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Manchester | first = William | title = The Arms of Krupp, 1587\u20131968: The Rise and Fall of the Industrial Dynasty That Armed Germany at War | publisher = Back Bay Books | location = Boston | year = 2003 | isbn = 978-0-316-52940-2 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Pallud | first = Jean-Paul | title = R\u00fcckmarsch! : the German retreat from Normandy : then and now | publisher = Battle of Britain International Ltd | location = Old Harlow | year = 2006 | isbn = 978-1-870067-57-7 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Perrett | first = Bryan | title = Sturmartillerie and Panzerjager 1939\u201345 | publisher = Osprey | location = London | year = 2000 |series=New Vanguard | isbn = 978-1-84176-004-9 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Schneider | first = Wolfgang | title = Elefant Jagdtiger Sturmtiger: Rarities of the Tiger Family | publisher = Schiffer Publishing | location = West Chester | year = 1990 | isbn = 978-0-88740-239-5 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Schneider | first = Wolfgang | title = Tigers in Combat I | publisher = Stackpole Books | location = Mechanicsburg | year = 2000 | isbn = 978-0-8117-3171-3 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Schneider | first = Wolfgang | title = Tigers in Combat II | publisher = Stackpole Books | location = Mechanicsburg | year = 2005 | isbn = 978-0-8117-3203-1 }}\n* {{citation |last1=Spielberger |first1=Walter |last2= Doyle |first2= Hilary |date=2007 |title=Tigers I and II and their variants |location= Pennsylvania |publisher=Schiffer Publishing Ltd |isbn=978-0-7643-2780-3 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book | last = Sz\u00e1mv\u00e9ber | first = Norbert | title = Neh\u00e9zp\u00e1nc\u00e9losok. A n\u00e9met 503. neh\u00e9zp\u00e1nc\u00e9los-oszt\u00e1ly magyarorsz\u00e1gi harcai. | publisher = Hadt\u00f6rt\u00e9neti Lev\u00e9lt\u00e1r | location = | year = 2000 |language = Hungarian | isbn = 978-963-00-2526-3 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Wilbeck | first = Christopher | title = Sledgehammers: Strengths and Flaws of Tiger Tank Battalions in World War II | publisher = The Aberjona Press | year = 2004 | isbn = 978-0-9717650-2-3 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Zaloga | first = Steven | title = IS-2 Heavy Tank 1944\u20131973 | publisher = Osprey Publishing |series=New Vanguard | location = London | year = 1994 | isbn = 978-1-85532-396-4 }}\n* {{cite book |last=Zaloga |first=Steven J. |year=2015 |title=Armored Champion: The Top Tanks of World War II |location=Mechanicsburg, PA |publisher=Stackpole Books |isbn=978-0-8117-1437-2}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.panzerworld.net/tigerii.html Information about the Pz.Kpfw.Tiger Ausf.B \"Tiger II\" at Panzerworld]\n* [http://www.fprado.com/armorsite/tiger2.htm Tiger II at the Armorsite]\n* [http://www.lonesentry.com/articles/ttt_pantiger/index.html Pantiger, A Redesigned Tiger] (U.S. intelligence report, 1944)\n\n{{WWIIGermanAFVs}}\n{{Subject bar\n| portal1=Military of Germany\n| portal2=Tanks\n| portal3=World War II\n| commons=y\n| commons-search=Panzerkampfwagen VI Tiger II\n}}\n\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tiger Ii}}\n[[Category:Heavy tanks of Germany]]\n[[Category:World War II heavy tanks]]\n[[Category:World War II tanks of Germany]]\n[[Category:History of the tank]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the aircraft also known as the Tiger II|Northrop F-5}}\n{{Infobox weapon\n |name= ''Panzerkampfwagen'' Tiger ''Ausf''. B\n |image= Bundesarchiv Bild 101I-680-8282A-06, Budapest, Panzer VI (Tiger II, K\u00f6nigstiger).jpg\n |image_size = 300\n |caption= Tiger II tank on paved street in Budapest, October 1944\n |origin=[[Nazi Germany]]\n |type= [[Heavy tank]]\n |is_vehicle= yes\n |service= 1944\u201345\n |wars= [[World War II]]\n |designer= [[Henschel & Son]] / [[Krupp]] (turret)\n |design_date= 1943\n |manufacturer=Henschel & Son / Krupp (turret)\n |unit_cost=800,000 [[Reichsmark]] ($300,000 USD) in 1944\u201345<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tanks-encyclopedia.com/ww2/nazi_germany/Panzer-VI_Konigstiger.php|title=Panzer VI Ausf.B K\u00f6nigstiger (1944)|website=www.tanks-encyclopedia.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-11-12}}</ref>\n |production_date= 1943\u201345\n |number= 492<ref name=\"Jentz96-288\"/>\n |variants=\n |weight= {{convert|68.5|t|abbr=out|lk=on}} (early turret)<br /> {{convert|69.8|t|abbr=out}} (production turret)<ref name=\"J&D1997.162-165\"/>\n |length= {{convert|7.38|m|ftin|0}} (hull)<br /> {{convert|10.286|m|ftin|0}} (with gun forward)<ref name=\"J&D1997.162-165\"/>\n |width= {{convert|3.755|m|ftin|0}}<ref name=\"J&D1997.162-165\"/>\n |height= {{convert|3.09|m|ftin|0}}<ref name=\"J&D1997.162-165\"/>\n |crew= 5 (commander, gunner, loader, radio operator, driver)\n |armour= {{convert|25|\u2013|185|mm|0|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"J&D1997.162-165\"/>\n |primary_armament= 1\u00d7 [[8.8 cm KwK 43]] L/71 <br /> Early Krupp design turret: 80 rounds<ref name=\"J&D23\">{{cite book|last1=Jentz|first1=Thomas|last2=Doyle|first2=Hilary|title=Kingtiger Heavy Tank 1942\u201345|date=1993|publisher=Osprey Publishing|isbn=185532282X|page=23}}</ref><br /> Production turret: 86 rounds<ref name=\"J&D23\"/>\n |secondary_armament= 2\u00d7 [[7.92 x 57 mm|7.92&nbsp;mm]] [[MG 34|Maschinengewehr 34]]<br /> 5,850 rounds<ref name=\"J&D1997.162-165\">Jentz and Doyle 1997, pp. 162\u2013165.</ref>\n |engine= V-12 [[Maybach HL230|Maybach HL 230 P30]] [[gasoline]]\n |engine_power= 700 PS (690 hp, 515 kW)<ref name=\"J&D28\">Jentz and Doyle 1993, p. 28 (figure D)</ref>\n |transmission= Maybach OLVAR EG 40 12 16 B (8 forward and 4 reverse)<ref name=\"J&D28\"/>\n |fuel_capacity={{convert|860|l|impgal}}<ref name=\"J&D1997.162-165\"/>\n |pw_ratio= 10 PS (7.5 kW) /tonne (8.97 hp/tonne)\n |suspension= [[torsion-bar]]\n |clearance={{convert|495|to|510|mm|ftin|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"J&D1997.162-165\"/>\n |vehicle_range= Road: {{convert|170|km|mi|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"J&D33\">Jentz and Doyle 1993, p. 33.</ref><br /> Cross country: {{convert|120|km|mi|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"J&D33\"/>\n |speed= Maximum, road: {{convert|41.5|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"J&D33\"/><br /> Sustained, road: {{convert|38|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"J&D33\"/><br /> Cross country: {{convert|15|to|20|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"J&D33\"/>}}\n\nThe '''Tiger II''' is a [[Nazi Germany|German]] [[heavy tank]] of the [[World War II|Second World War]]. The final official German designation was '''''Panzerkampfwagen'' Tiger ''Ausf''. B''',<ref group=notes>''[[Panzerkampfwagen]]'' \u2013 abbr: ''Pz.'' or ''Pz.Kfw.'' (English: \"[[armoured fighting vehicle]]\")<br /> ''Ausf\u00fchrung'' \u2013 abbr: ''Ausf.'' (English: variant).<br /> The full titles ''Panzerkampfwagen'' Tiger ''Ausf''. B and ''Panzerbefehlswagen'' Tiger ''Ausf''. B (for the command version) were used in training and maintenance manuals and in organisation and equipment tables. (Jentz and Doyle 1997)<br /> Also sometimes referred to as \"Pz. VI ''Ausf'' B\", not to be confused with \"Pz. VI ''Ausf'' H\", which was the [[Tiger I]].</ref> often shortened to '''Tiger B'''.<ref name=\"J&D16\">Jentz and Doyle 1993, p. 16.</ref> The ordnance inventory designation was [[Sonderkraftfahrzeug|''Sd.Kfz.'']] 182.<ref name=\"J&D16\"/> It is also known under the informal name '''''K\u00f6nigstiger'''''<ref name=\"J&D16\"/> (the [[German language|German]] name for the [[Bengal tiger]]), often translated literally as '''Royal Tiger''', or somewhat incorrectly as '''King Tiger''' by Allied soldiers, especially by American forces.<ref>Buckley 2004, p. 119.</ref><ref>Tank Spotter's Guide, Bovington 2011 p. 63</ref>\n\nThe Tiger II was the successor to the [[Tiger I]], combining the latter's thick armour with the [[armour sloping]] used on the [[Panther tank|Panther]] medium tank. The tank weighed almost 70 [[tonne]]s, and was protected by {{convert|100|to|185|mm|abbr=on}} of armour to the front.<ref name=\"J&Darmor\"/> It was armed with the long barrelled [[8.8 cm KwK 43|8.8 cm KwK 43 L/71]] anti-tank cannon.<ref group=notes>''Kampfwagenkanone'' \u2013 abbr: ''KwK'' (English: \"fighting vehicle cannon\")</ref> The chassis was also the basis for the [[Jagdtiger]] [[Casemate#Armoured vehicles|turretless]] [[Jagdpanzer]] anti-tank vehicle.<ref name=\"Schneider19\">Schneider 1990, p. 18.</ref>\n\nThe Tiger II was issued to [[German heavy tank battalion|heavy tank battalions]] of the [[German Army (1935\u20131945)|Army]] and the [[Waffen-SS]]. It was first used in combat by [[503rd Heavy Panzer Battalion]] during the Allied [[invasion of Normandy]] on 11 July 1944;<ref>Jentz and Doyle 1993, p. 37.</ref> on the [[Eastern Front (World War II)|Eastern Front]], the first unit to be outfitted with the Tiger II was the [[501st Heavy Panzer Battalion]], which by 1 September 1944 listed 25 Tiger IIs operational.<ref>Jentz and Doyle 1993, p. 40.</ref>\n\n==Development==\nDevelopment of a heavy tank design had been initiated in 1937; the initial design contract was awarded to [[Henschel & Son|Henschel]]. Another design contract followed in 1939, and was given to [[Ferdinand Porsche|Porsche]].<ref name=\"Jentz & Doyle 1993, p. 3\">Jentz & Doyle 1993, p. 3.</ref> Both prototype series used the same turret design from [[Krupp]]; the main differences were in the hull, transmission, suspension and automotive features.<ref name=\"Jentz & Doyle 1993, p. 3\"/>\n\n[[File:Chambois1.jpg|thumb|left|[[SHAEF]] commander Gen. [[Dwight D. Eisenhower|Eisenhower]] walks by an overturned Tiger II. The overlapping, non-interleaved steel-rim roadwheel arrangement is visible.]]\nThe Henschel version used a conventional hull design with sloped armour resembling the layout of the Panther tank. It had a rear-mounted engine and used nine steel-tired, eighty-centimeter-diameter overlapping road wheels per side with internal springing, mounted on [[Torsion bar suspension|transverse torsion bars]], in a similar manner to the original Henschel-designed Tiger I. To simplify maintenance, however, as when the same steel-tired road wheels were used on later Tiger I hulls, the wheels were only overlapping ''without'' being interleaved\u2014the full ''Schachtellaufwerk'' rubber-rimmed road-wheel system that had been in use on nearly all German half-tracks used the interleaved design, later inherited by the early production versions of the Tiger&nbsp;I<ref>Jentz and Doyle 1993, pp. 10\u201312.</ref> and Panther.\n\nThe Porsche hull designs included a rear-mounted turret and a mid-mounted engine. The suspension was the same as on the ''[[Elefant]]'' tank destroyer. This had six road wheels per side mounted in paired [[bogies]] sprung with short longitudinal torsion bars that were integral to the wheel pair; this saved internal space and facilitated repairs. One Porsche version had a gasoline-electric drive (fundamentally identical to a [[Diesel-electric transmission]], only using a gasoline-fueled engine as the [[Prime mover (locomotive)|prime mover]]), similar to a [[gasoline-electric hybrid]] but without a storage battery; two separate [[drivetrain]]s in parallel, one per side of the tank, each consisting of a hybrid drive train; gasoline engine\u2013[[electric generator]]\u2013electric motor\u2013drive [[sprocket]]. This method of propulsion had been attempted before on the [[VK4501|Tiger (P)]] (later ''Elefant'' prototypes) and in some US designs and was put into production in the WW1 [[Saint-Chamond (tank)|Saint-Chamond]] tank and the post-WW1 FCM [[Char 2C]]. The Porsche suspension components were later used on a few of the later ''[[Jagdtiger]]'' tank destroyers. Another proposal was to use hydraulic drives. Dr. Porsche's unorthodox designs gathered little favour.<ref>Jentz and Doyle 1993, pp. 8\u201310.</ref>\n\n==Design==\n[[File:Munster Koenigstiger Porscheturm Modell detail.jpg|thumb|left|alt=A tank turret with a front face which curves up and down. The sides are slanted vertically and curved laterally.|A model depicting the curved front of the first version of the Krupp turret (erroneously called \"Porsche turret\")<ref name=\":0\">{{Citation|title=Tank Chats#47 King Tiger |date= 2 March 2018|publisher=The Tank Museum|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QuDuBwAhRa4&t=337|access-date=24 January 2019}}</ref>]]\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 101I-680-8282A-09, Budapest, Panzersoldaten in Panzer VI (Tiger II).jpg|thumb|left|alt=A tank turret with an almost square, flat, vertical face, the sides are almost vertical, and curve laterally only slightly.|A clear view of the angular front of the \"production turret\" designed by Krupp (erroneously called \"Henschel turret\")<ref name=\":0\" /> taken during [[Operation Panzerfaust]] in [[Budapest]], 15 October 1944. The rough [[Zimmerit]] coating is evident, used to prevent magnetic mines from adhering to the tank's armour.]]\n\nHenschel won the design contract, and all Tiger IIs were produced by the firm.<ref>Jentz and Doyle 1993, p. 17</ref> Two turret designs were used in production vehicles. The initial design is often misleadingly called the Tiger II (P), after the \"Porsche\" turret due to the misbelief that it was designed by Porsche for their [[VK 4502 (P)|prototype]]; in fact it was the initial Krupp design for both prototypes.<ref name=\":0\" /> This turret had a rounded front and steeply sloped sides, with a difficult-to-manufacture curved bulge on the turret's left side to accommodate the commander's cupola. Fifty early turrets were mounted to Henschel's hull and used in action. In December 1943 the more common \"production\" turret, sometimes erroneously called the \"Henschel\" turret, was simplified with a significantly thicker flat face, no [[shot trap]] (created by the curved face of the earlier turret), and less-steeply sloped sides, which prevented the need for a bulge for the commander's cupola, and added additional room for ammunition storage.<ref>Jentz and Doyle 1993, pp. 13\u201316.</ref>\n\nThe turrets were designed to mount the [[8.8 cm KwK 43]] L/71 gun. Combined with the ''Turmzielfernrohr'' 9d (German \"turret telescopic sight\") monocular sight by Leitz, which all but a few early Tiger IIs used, it was a very accurate and deadly weapon. During practice, the estimated probability of a first-round hit on a {{convert|2|m|abbr=on}} high, {{convert|2.5|m|abbr=on}} wide target was 100 percent at {{convert|1000|m|mi|abbr=on}}, 95\u201397 percent at {{convert|1500|m|mi|abbr=on}} and 85\u201387 percent at {{convert|2000|m|mi|abbr=on}}, depending on ammunition type. Recorded combat performance was lower, but still over 80 percent at 1,000&nbsp;m, in the 60s at 1,500&nbsp;m and the 40s at 2,000&nbsp;m. Penetration of armoured plate inclined at 30 degrees was {{convert|202|and|132|mm|abbr=on}} at {{convert|100|m|yd|abbr=on}} and {{convert|2000|m|mi|abbr=on}} respectively for the [[Panzergranate 39|''Panzergranate'' 39/43]] projectile (PzGr\u2014[[armor-piercing shot and shell|armour-piercing shell]]), and {{convert|238|and|153|mm|abbr=on}} for the PzGr. 40/43 projectile between the same ranges. The ''Sprenggranate'' 43 (SpGr) high-explosive round was available for soft targets, or the ''Hohlgranate'' or ''Hohlgeschoss'' 39 (HlGr\u2014HEAT or [[High-explosive anti-tank warhead]]) round, which had {{convert|90|mm|abbr=on}} penetration at any range, could be used as a dual-purpose munition against soft or armoured targets.<ref name=\"J&D23-24\">Jentz and Doyle 1993, pp. 23\u201324</ref>\n\nPowered turret traverse was provided by the variable speed Boehringer-Sturm L4S hydraulic motor, which was driven from the main engine by a secondary drive shaft. A high and a low speed setting was available to the gunner via a lever on his right. The turret could be rotated 360 degrees at 6\u00ba/second in low gear independent of engine rpm, at 19\u00ba/second \u2014 [[Tiger I#Mobility and reliability|the same as with the Tiger I]] \u2014  with the high speed setting and engine at 2000 rpm, and over 36\u00ba/second at the maximum allowable engine speed of 3000 rpm. The direction and speed of traverse were controlled by the gunner through foot pedals, or a control lever near his left arm. If power was lost, such as when the tank ran out of fuel, the turret could be slowly traversed by hand, assisted by the loader who had an additional wheel, which could manually rotate the turret at a rate of one-half a degree per each revolution of the hand crank (i.e. 20\u00b0 turret rotation required 40 full cranks of the handwheel, and to turn the turret a full 360\u00b0 the gunner would be required to crank the handwheel 720 full revolutions).\n\n[[File:Tiger II mg 7802.jpg|thumb|alt=The overhanging rear face of a large tank, two laterally spaced exhaust pipes protrude from mountings, pointing upwards, curving away from the vehicle at their ends.|Rear view showing dual exhausts]]\nLike all German tanks, the Tiger II had a [[petrol engine]]; in this case the same 700 [[Horsepower#PS|PS]] (690&nbsp;hp, 515&nbsp;kW) V-12 [[Maybach HL230|Maybach HL 230 P30]] which powered the much lighter [[Panther tank|Panther]] and [[Tiger I]] tanks. The Tiger II was under-powered, like many other heavy tanks of World War II, and consumed a lot of fuel, which was in short supply for the Germans. The transmission was the Maybach OLVAR EG 40 12 16 Model B, giving eight forward gears and four reverse, which drove the steering gear. This was the Henschel L 801, a double radius design which proved susceptible to failure. Transverse torsion bar suspension supported the hull on nine axles per side. Overlapped {{convert|800|mm|abbr=on}} diameter road wheels with rubber cushions and steel tyres rode inside the tracks.<ref name=\"J&D11-12\">Jentz and Doyle 1993, pp. 11\u201312.</ref>\n\nLike the Tiger I, each tank was issued with two sets of tracks: a normal \"battle track\" and a narrower \"transport\" version used during rail movement. The transport tracks reduced the overall width of the load and could be used to drive the tank short distances on firm ground. The crew were expected to change to normal battle tracks as soon as the tank was unloaded. Ground pressure was 0.76&nbsp;kg/cm<sup>2</sup> (10.8 psi).<ref>Jentz and Doyle 1993, p. 13.</ref>\n\n===Command variant===\nThe command variant of the Tiger II was designated ''Panzerbefehlswagen'' Tiger ''Ausf. B''. It had two versions, ''Sd.Kfz''. 267 and ''Sd.Kfz''. 268. These carried only 63 rounds of 8.8&nbsp;cm ammunition to provide room to    accommodate the extra radios and equipment,<ref name=\"J&D16\"/> and had additional armour on the engine compartment. The ''Sd.Kfz''. 267 was to have used ''FuG'' 8 and ''FuG'' 5 radio sets, with the most notable external changes being a {{convert|2|m|ft|adj=mid|-long|spell=in}} rod antenna mounted on the turret roof and a ''Sternantenne D'' (\"Star antenna D\"), mounted on an insulated base (the 105&nbsp;mm ''Antennenfu\u00df Nr. 1''), which was protected by a large armoured cylinder. This equipment was located on the rear decking in a position originally used for deep-wading equipment.<ref name=\"J&D16\"/> The ''Sd.Kfz''. 268 used ''FuG'' 7 and ''FuG'' 5 radios with a two-metre rod antenna mounted on the turret roof and a 1.4 metre rod antenna mounted on the rear deck.<ref>Jentz and Doyle 1993, pp. 16\u201317.</ref>\n\n==Production==\nThe Tiger II was developed late in the war and built in relatively small numbers. Orders were placed for 1,500 Tiger IIs\u2014slightly more than the 1,347 [[Tiger I]] tanks produced\u2014but production was severely disrupted by Allied bombing raids.<ref name=\"Manchester68-498\">Manchester 1968, p. 498.</ref> Among others, five raids between 22 September and 7 October 1944 destroyed 95 percent of the floor area of the Henschel plant. It is estimated that this caused the loss in production of some 657 Tiger IIs.<ref name=\"J&D17\">Jentz and Doyle 1993, p. 17.</ref> Only 492 units were produced: one in 1943, 379 in 1944, and 112 in 1945. Full production ran from mid-1944 to the end of the war.<ref name=\"Jentz96-288\">Jentz 1996, p. 288.</ref> Each Tiger II produced needed 300,000 man hours to manufacture and cost over 800,000 Reichsmark or US$300,000 (adjusted for inflation, approximately $4.2 million in 2018) per vehicle. The vehicle was the costliest German tank to produce at the time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tanks-encyclopedia.com/ww2/nazi_germany/Panzer-VI_Konigstiger.php|title=Panzer VI Ausf.B K\u00f6nigstiger (1944)|website=www.tanks-encyclopedia.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-11-12}}</ref>\n\nThe Tiger II served as the basis for one production variant, the ''[[Jagdtiger]]'' [[casemate]]d [[tank destroyer]],<ref name=\"Schneider19\"/> and a proposed Grille 17/21/30/42 self-propelled mount for heavy guns which never reached production.<ref>{{cite web |last=Parada |first=George |url=http://www.achtungpanzer.com/pz13.htm#grille |title=Grille series |work=Achtung Panzer! |accessdate=2009-10-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080821073415/http://www.achtungpanzer.com/pz13.htm#grille |archivedate=2008-08-21 }}</ref>\n\n==Proposed upgrades==\nThe [[List of WWII Maybach engines|HL234]], an engine born from the developments initiated by attempting to convert the [[Maybach HL230]] to [[fuel injection]], would have increased the power from 700 to about 800 PS (hp). The Entwicklungskommission Panzer unanimously decided that HL234 be immediately included in the engine design and procurement program. The AK-7-200 was also explored as an alternative to the Maybach Olvar-B drive train, but ''[[Waffenamt]]'' research and development department ''Wa Pr\u00fcf 6'' found that it offered inferior driving characteristics and so the Maybach Olvar-B was retained.<ref name=\"J&D1997.144-154\">{{cite book|last1=Jentz|first1=Thomas|last2=Doyle|first2=Hilary|title=Germany's Tiger Tanks: VK45.02 to TIGER II Design, Production & Modifications|date=1997|publisher=Schiffer Publishing, Ltd|isbn=0764302248|pages=144\u2013154}}</ref> There was also a program using the Simmering-Graz-Pauker Sla.16 engine, but the war's constraint on supplies and capitulation resulted in the cancellation of this program.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}} Krupp proposed mounting a new main weapon, the [[10.5 cm]] KwK L/68. ''Wa Pr\u00fcf 6'' was not supportive of this as the Heer had not accepted the cannon itself. Other suggested improvements included stabilised sights, a stabilised main gun, an automatic ammunition feed, a [[Carl Zeiss AG]] [[stereoscopic]] [[rangefinder]], heated crew compartment, stowage <!-- stowage is the correct term, storage is wrong --> for an additional 12 rounds, and an [[Overpressure (CBRN protection)|overpressure]] and air filtration system to protect against poison gas. However, these also never got beyond the proposal stage or did not enter production before the war ended.<ref name=\"J&D1997.144-154\"/>\n\n==Specifications==\n* Gearbox: Maybach OLVAR EG 40 12 16 B (eight forward and four reverse)<ref name=\"J&D11-12\"/>\n* Radio: FuG 5, ''Befehlswagen'' (command tank) version: ''FuG'' 8 (''Sd.Kfz''. 267), ''FuG'' 7 (''Sd.Kfz''. 268)<ref name=\"J&D16\"/>\n* Ammunition: {{See also|8.8 cm KwK 43}}\n** 8.8&nbsp;cm \u2013 80 rounds (early turret),<ref name=\"J&D23\"/> 86 rounds (main production turret), usually 50% ''PzGr'' 39/43 and 50% SprGr 43, sometimes with a limited number of ''PzGr'' 40/43, or with the ''SprGr'' replaced by HlGr<ref name=\"J&D23\"/>\n**: ''PzGr'' 39/43 (Armour-piercing, hardened steel) (longer range, lower penetration, explosive filler)<ref name=\"J&D28\"/><ref name=\"J&D23-24\"/>\n**: ''PzGr'' 40/43 (Armour-piercing, tungsten carbide core) (shorter range, higher penetration, inert)<ref name=\"J&D28\"/><ref name=\"J&D23-24\"/>\n**: ''SprGr'' 43 (High explosive)<ref name=\"J&D28\"/>\n**: ''HlGr'' 39 (Hollow charge)<ref name=\"J&D28\"/>\n** 7.92mm \u2013 up to 5,850 rounds<ref name=\"J&D1997.162-165\"/>\n* Gun Sight: ''Turmzielfernrohr'' 9b/1 (TZF 9b/1) binocular to May 1944, then the 9d (TZF 9d) monocular.<ref>Jentz and Doyle 1993, p. 19.</ref>\n\n{| border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=1 style=\"border-top:3px double #999; border-collapse:collapse; text-align:left; font-size:normal;\" width=\"80%\" summary=\"\"\n|+ style=\"font-size:normal; text-align:left;\" | '''Armour layout:''' (all angles from horizontal)<ref name=\"J&Darmor\">Jentz and Doyle 1993, pp. 12, 15.</ref>\n|- style=\"vertical-align:bottom; border-bottom:1px solid #999;\"\n|-\n|Hull front ||(lower)|| {{convert|100|mm|abbr=on}} at 40\u00b0 || (upper) || {{convert|150|mm|abbr=on}} at 40\u00b0\n|-\n|Hull side ||(lower) || {{convert|80|mm|abbr=on}} at 90\u00b0 || (upper) || {{convert|80|mm|abbr=on}} at 65\u00b0\n|-\n|Hull rear || || {{convert|80|mm|abbr=on}} at 60\u00b0 || ||\n|-\n|Hull top || || {{convert|40|mm|abbr=on}} at 0\u00b0 || ||\n|-\n|Hull bottom ||(front)|| {{convert|40|mm|abbr=on}} at 90\u00b0 || (rear) || {{convert|25|mm|abbr=on}} at 90\u00b0\n|-\n|Turret front ||(production)||{{convert|180|mm|abbr=on}} at 80\u00b0 || (\"Porsche\") || {{convert|60|to|100|mm|abbr=on}}, rounded\n|-\n|Turret side ||(production) || {{convert|80|mm|abbr=on}} at 69\u00b0 || (\"Porsche\") || {{convert|80|mm|abbr=on}} at 60\u00b0\n|-\n|Turret rear ||(production) || {{convert|80|mm|abbr=on}} at 70\u00b0 || (\"Porsche\") || {{convert|80|mm|abbr=on}} at 60\u00b0\n|-\n|Turret top ||(production) || {{convert|44|mm|abbr=on}} at 0\u201310\u00b0 || (\"Porsche\") || {{convert|40|mm|abbr=on}} at 0\u201312\u00b0\n|\n|- style=\"border-top:3px double #999;\"\n| colspan=5 |\n|}\n\n==Operational history==\n\n===Organisation===\n{{See also|German heavy tank battalion}}\nApart from research, training, and a five-tank attachment to the [[Panzer Lehr]], the Tiger II was only issued to heavy tank battalions (''schwere Panzer-Abteilungen'') of the [[German Army (Wehrmacht)|German Army]] (''Heer''), or ''[[Waffen-SS]]''.<ref name=\"J&D36\">Jentz and Doyle 1993, p. 36.</ref>\n\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 146-1975-102-14A, Panzer VI (Tiger II, K\u00f6nigstiger).jpg|thumb|alt=A row of seven large tanks lined up with their long guns pointing up at an angle, as if saluting.|Tiger II tanks fitted with the narrower \"vehicle-transport tracks\" of the [[503rd Heavy Tank Battalion (Germany)|''Schwere Heeres Panzer Abteilung'' 503 (s.H.Pz.Abt. 503) 'Feldherrnhalle']] posing in formation for the [[Die Deutsche Wochenschau|Nazi German wartime-propaganda newsreel]] at the armour-training ground in Sennelager, Germany, prior to the unit's departure for Hungary]]\n\nA standard battalion (''Abteilung'') comprised 45 tanks:<ref name=\"J&D36\"/>\n{| border=1 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=3 style=\"line-height:normal; text-align:center; border-top:3px double #999; border-collapse:collapse;\"\n|- style=\"vertical-align:bottom; border-bottom:1px solid #999;\"\n|colspan=9 |Battalion command<br /> 3 \u00d7 Tiger II\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top; border-bottom:1px solid #999;\"\n|colspan=3 | 1st company command<br /> 2 \u00d7 Tiger II ||colspan=3 | 2nd company command<br />2 \u00d7 Tiger II ||colspan=3 | 3rd company command<br />2 \u00d7 Tiger II\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top; border-bottom:3px double #999;\"\n|1st platoon<br />4 \u00d7 Tiger II ||2nd platoon<br /> 4 \u00d7 Tiger II ||3rd platoon<br /> 4 \u00d7 Tiger II\n|1st platoon<br />4 \u00d7 Tiger II ||2nd platoon<br /> 4 \u00d7 Tiger II ||3rd platoon<br /> 4 \u00d7 Tiger II\n|1st platoon<br />4 \u00d7 Tiger II ||2nd platoon<br /> 4 \u00d7 Tiger II ||3rd platoon<br /> 4 \u00d7 Tiger II\n|-\n|}\n\nUnits that used the Tiger II were as follows:<ref>Jentz and Doyle 1993, pp. 37\u201342.</ref>\n:''Heer: (s.H.Pz.Abt)'' [[501st heavy tank battalion (Germany)|501]], [[502nd heavy tank battalion (Germany)|502]], [[503rd heavy tank battalion (Germany)|503]], [[504th heavy tank battalion (Germany)|504]], [[505th heavy tank battalion (Germany)|505]], [[506th heavy tank battalion (Germany)|506]], [[507th heavy tank battalion (Germany)|507]], [[508th heavy tank battalion (Germany)|508]], [[509th heavy tank battalion (Germany)|509]], [[510th heavy tank battalion (Germany)|510]], [[511th heavy tank battalion (Germany)|511]]\n:''SS: (s.SS.Pz.Abt)'' [[SS Heavy Panzer Battalion 101|501]], [[SS Heavy Panzer Battalion 102|502]], [[SS Heavy Panzer Battalion 103|503]]\n\n===Reliability and mobility===\n[[File:Bovington Tiger II grey bg.jpg|thumb|alt=A large, turreted tank with dull yellow, green and brown wavy camouflage, on display inside Bovington museum. The tracks are wide, and the frontal armour is sloped. The long gun overhangs the bow by several meters.|A camouflaged Tiger II in display in Bovington Tank museum. The long gun overhangs the bow by several meters.]]\n\nEarly Tiger IIs proved unreliable, owing principally to leaking seals and gaskets, and an overburdened drive train originally intended for a lighter vehicle.<ref name=\"J&D34\">Jentz and Doyle 1993, p. 34</ref> The double radius steering gear was initially particularly prone to failure.<ref name=\"J&D11\">Jentz and Doyle 1993, p. 11</ref> Lack of crew training could amplify this problem; drivers originally given only limited training on other tanks were often sent directly to operational units already on their way to the front.<ref name=\"J&D34\"/>\n\nThe [[501st heavy tank battalion (Germany)|''Schwere Heeres Panzer Abteilung'' 501]] (s.H.Pz.Abt. 501) arrived on the Eastern Front with only eight out of 45 tanks operational; these faults were mostly due to drive-train failures. The first five Tiger IIs delivered to the [[Panzer Lehr Division]] broke down before they could be used in combat, and were destroyed to prevent capture.<ref name=\"J&D35\">Jentz and Doyle 1993, p. 35.</ref>\n\nThe introduction of modified seals, gaskets and drive train components, as well as improved driver training and sufficient maintenance improved the tank's mechanical reliability.<ref>Jentz and Doyle 1993, p. 18.</ref> Statistics from 15 March 1945 show reliability rates of 59 percent for the Tiger, almost equal to the 62 percent of the [[Panzer IV]] and better than the 48 percent of the [[Panther Tank|Panther]] that were operational by this period.<ref name=\"J&D36\"/>\n\nNotwithstanding its initial reliability problems, the Tiger II was remarkably agile for such a heavy vehicle. Contemporary German records and testing results indicate that its tactical mobility was as good as or better than most German or Allied tanks.<ref>Jentz and Doyle 1993, pp. 33\u201334.</ref>\n\n===Combat history===\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 101I-721-0397-34, Frankreich, Panzer VI (Tiger II, K\u00f6nigstiger) crop.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.2|Tiger IIs (with the first version of the Krupp turret) on the move in France, June 1944]]\nThe first combat use of the Tiger II was by the 1st Company of the [[503rd Heavy Panzer Battalion]] (s.H.Pz.Abt. 503) during the [[Operation Overlord|Battle of Normandy]], opposing Operation [[Operation Atlantic|''Atlantic'']] between [[Troarn]] and [[Demouville]] on 18 July 1944. Two were lost in combat, while the company commander's tank became irrecoverably trapped after falling into a bomb crater created during Operation [[Operation Goodwood|''Goodwood'']].<ref name=\"Schneider133\">Schneider 2000, p. 133.</ref>\n\nOn the [[Eastern Front (World War II)|Eastern Front]], it was first used on 12 August 1944 by the [[501st Heavy Panzer Battalion]] (s.H.Pz.Abt. 501) resisting the [[Lvov\u2013Sandomierz Offensive]]. It attacked the Soviet bridgehead over the [[Vistula River]] near [[Baran\u00f3w Sandomierski]]. On the road to [[Ogl\u0119d\u00f3w]], three Tiger IIs were destroyed in an ambush by a few [[T-34|T-34-85s]].<ref>Zaloga 1994, p. 14.</ref> Because these German tanks suffered ammunition explosions, which caused many crew fatalities, main gun rounds were no longer allowed to be stowed within the turret, reducing capacity to 68.<ref>Schneider 2000, p. 46.</ref> Up to fourteen Tiger IIs of the 501st were destroyed or captured in the area between 11 and 14 August to ambushes and flank attacks by both Soviet T-34-85 and [[IS-2]] tanks, and ISU-122 assault guns in inconvenient sandy terrain. The capture of three operational Tiger IIs allowed the Soviets to conduct tests at Kubinka and to evaluate its strengths and weaknesses<ref>Sledgehammers: Strengths and Flaws of Tiger Tank Battalions in World War II. Christopher W. Wilbeck. Aberjona, 2004. p.135</ref>\n\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 101I-680-8283A-12A, Budapest, marschierende Pfeilkreuzler und Panzer VI.jpg|thumb|alt=A large tank with sloped frontal armour and a flat faced turret, by a column of marching soldiers wearing overcoats and helmets, in a wide city street. A large building to the rear shows the scars of battle.|A Tiger II of [[503rd Heavy Panzer Battalion|s.H.Pz.Abt. 503]] and Hungarian troops in a battle-scarred street in [[Buda]]'s Castle district, October 1944]]\nOn 15 October 1944, Tiger IIs of 503rd Heavy Panzer Battalion played a crucial role during ''[[Operation Panzerfaust]]'', supporting [[Otto Skorzeny]]'s troops in taking the Hungarian capital of [[Budapest]], which ensured that the country remained with the Axis until the end of the war. The 503rd then took part in the [[Battle of Debrecen]]. The 503rd remained in the Hungarian theater of operations for 166 days, during which it accounted for at least 121 Soviet tanks, 244 anti-tank guns and artillery pieces, five aircraft and a train. This was set against the loss of 25 Tiger IIs; ten were knocked out by Soviet troops and burned out, two were sent back to Vienna for a factory overhaul, while thirteen were blown up by their crews for various reasons, usually to prevent them from falling into enemy hands. [[Kurt Knispel]], the highest scoring tank ace of all time (162 enemy [[armoured fighting vehicle]]s destroyed), also served with the 503rd, and was killed in action on 29 April 1945 in his Tiger II.<ref name=\"Sz\u00e1mv\u00e9ber147\">Sz\u00e1mv\u00e9ber, 2000. p. 147.</ref>\n\nThe Tiger II was also used in significant numbers, distributed into four heavy panzer battalions, during the [[Ardennes Offensive]] (also known as the Battle of the Bulge) of December 1944.<ref>Schneider 2005, pp. 214\u2013216.</ref> At least 150 Tiger IIs were present, nearly a third of total production, and most were lost during the course of the offensive.<ref>Green, Michael. \"German Tanks of World War II\". May 14, 2000. Page 73.</ref> Famously, during the [[Battle of St. Vith]] an [[M8 Greyhound]] armoured car is alleged to have destroyed a Tiger II after getting in behind it on the Schonberg Road, firing three 37&nbsp;mm rounds into the rear armor of the Tiger from only {{convert|25|yd|m|abbr=on}} and setting it on fire: \"There was a muffled explosion, followed by flames which billowed out of the turret and engine port.\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Beevor |first=Antony |authorlink=Antony Beevor |title=Ardennes 1944: Hitler's last gamble |publisher=Viking |date=2015 |location=New York |page=172 |url= |doi= |isbn=978-0-670-02531-2}}</ref>  However, there is confusion in the unit history over whether he vehicle was a Tiger or Tiger II and German unit histories<ref>Schneider 2005, pp. 214\u2013216.</ref> indicate that there were no German heavy tanks lost or even present within 20 miles of St Vith at the time of the alleged incident.  Combined with the habit of American troops of reporting almost all German tanks they made contact with as \"Tigers\" it is more likely that this was a case of mistaken identity.\n\nSome Tiger IIs were also present during the Soviet [[Vistula\u2013Oder Offensive|Vistula\u2013Oder]]<ref>Schneider 2000, p. 47.</ref> and [[East Prussian Offensive]]s in January 1945,<ref>Schneider 2000, pp. 89\u201391.</ref> as well as the German [[Lake Balaton Offensive]] in Hungary in March 1945,<ref>Schneider 2005, p. 217.</ref> the [[Battle of the Seelow Heights]] in April 1945, and the [[Battle of Berlin]] at the end of the war.<ref>Schneider 2005, pp. 300\u2013303.</ref> On 12 January 1945, a column of Tiger IIs from 524th Heavy Panzer Battalion were involved in a short-range engagement with IS-2 tanks near the village of [[Lis\u00f3w, Kielce County|Lisow,]] with both the German and Soviet formations suffering heavy losses.<ref>IS-2 Heavy Tank 1944\u201373. Steven J. Zaloga. Bloomsbury Publishing, 2011. p.31</ref>\n\nThe [[103rd SS Heavy Panzer Battalion]] (s.SS Pz.Abt. 503) claimed approximately 500 kills in the period from January to April 1945 on the Eastern Front for the loss of 45 Tiger IIs (most of which were abandoned and destroyed by their own crews after mechanical breakdowns or for lack of fuel).<ref>Schneider 2005, pp. 304, 324.</ref>\n\n===Gun and armour performance===\n[[File:Tiger II punctured in front turret.jpg|thumb|left|alt=A head-on view of a large tank with a flat-faced turret. Its sloped bow armour is scarred with several fist-sized dents, and there is a fist-sized hole in the front of the turret|A Tiger II with fist-sized dents in its front armour and a hole in its turret.<ref>Pallud 2006, p. 152</ref>]]\nThe heavy armour and powerful long-range gun gave the Tiger II an advantage against all opposing [[Allies of World War II|Western Allied]] and [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] tanks attempting to engage it from head on. This was especially true on the Western Front where, until the arrival of the few [[M26 Pershing]]s in 1945 and the few [[M4 Sherman#Upgrades|M4A3E2 Sherman \"Jumbo\"s]] that were scattered around Europe after D-Day, neither the British nor US forces brought heavy tanks into service. A ''Wa Pr\u00fcf 1'' report estimated that the Tiger II's frontal aspect was impervious to the 122&nbsp;mm D-25T, the heaviest although not the best penetrating tank gun on the Allied side. On the other hand, an R.A.C 3.d. document of February 1945 estimated that the British [[Ordnance QF 17-pounder|QF 17-pounder (76.2 mm)]] gun, using [[armour-piercing discarding sabot]] shot was theoretically capable of penetrating the front of the Tiger II's turret and nose (lower front hull) at {{convert|1100|and|1200|yd|m|abbr=on}} respectively although, given the lack of a stated angle, this is presumably at the ideal 90 degrees angle.<ref name=\"KTHT34-36\">{{cite book|last1=Jentz|first1=Thomas|last2=Doyle|first2=Hilary|title=Kingtiger Heavy Tank 1942\u201345|date=1993|publisher=Osprey Publishing Ltd|isbn=185532282X|pages=34\u201336|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ATawrvkJBAUC&pg=PA35}}</ref> Some sources {{who|date=July 2018}} claimed that there is no proof that the glacis armour of the Tiger II was ever penetrated in combat.<ref>{{cite web |title = PzKpfw VI Tiger II |url = http://www.fprado.com/armorsite/tiger2.htm |work = The Armor Site! |publisher=Fabio Prado |accessdate = 23 November 2015}}</ref>{{better source|fprado.com is a tertiary source with unknown editorial oversight|date=July 2018}}\n\nAs a result of its thick frontal armour, flanking manoeuvres were most often used against the Tiger II to attempt a shot at the thinner side and rear armour, giving a tactical advantage to the Tiger II in most engagements.<ref name=\"Jary274\">Jarymowycz 2001, p. 274.</ref> Moreover, the main armament of the Tiger II was capable of knocking out any Allied tank frontally at ranges exceeding {{convert|2.5|km}}, well beyond the effective range of Allied tank guns.<ref name=\"Jary258\">Jarymowycz 2001, p. 258.</ref>\n\n===Soviet wartime testing===\n\nDuring August 1944, two Tiger Ausf B tanks were captured by the Soviets near [[Sandomierz]], and were soon moved to the testing grounds at [[Kubinka]]. During the transfer, the two tanks suffered from various mechanical breakdowns; the cooling system was insufficient for the excessively hot weather, where the engine tended to overheat and cause a consequential failure of the gearbox. The right suspension of one of the tanks had to be completely replaced, and its full functionality could not be re-established. The tank broke down again every 10\u201315&nbsp;km. The [[8.8 cm KwK 43]] gave positive results in penetration and accuracy, which were on par with the 122&nbsp;mm D-25T. It proved capable of passing completely through its \"colleague\", a Tiger Ausf B's turret at a range of 400 m. The armour of one vehicle was tested by firing at it with shells between 100 and 152&nbsp;mm calibre. The welding was, despite careful workmanship, significantly worse than on similar designs. As a result, even when shells did not penetrate the armour, there was often a large amount of [[spalling]] from the inside of the plates, which damaged the transmission and rendered the tank inoperable. Further testing showed that the armour plate itself exhibited deficiencies in quality compared to earlier German tanks such as the Tiger I and Panther. Lab testing found that the armour plates lacked molybdenum (ascribed to a loss of supply, being replaced by vanadium), resulting in low malleability.<ref name=\"Tigertest\"/>{{unreliable source?|date=April 2017}}\n\nThe expanded firing test states that the [[Armor-piercing shot and shell|\u0410\u0420]] projectiles from the [[100 mm field gun M1944 (BS-3)|100 mm BS-3]] and [[122 mm gun M1931 (A-19)|122 mm A-19]] gun penetrated a Tiger Ausf B's turret at ranges of 1000\u20131500 metres, which suggests a quality factor of 0.86 for the Tiger Ausf B's turret. The firing test against the Tiger B turret front, however, was conducted after removal of the gun and mantlet, and resulted in penetrations close to armour openings, such as vision slits and gun location. The penetrations to the right gun opening were influenced by previous 100&nbsp;mm projectile penetration hits or armour damage.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Bird|first1=Lorrin Rexford|last2=Livingston|first2=Robert D.|title=WWII Ballistics - Armour and Gunnery|date=2001|publisher=Overmatch Press|page=90|<!-- accessdate=22 January 2015 -->}}</ref> Some {{who|date=July 2018}} have said the tank's hull and turret side plates were penetrated by [[Armor-piercing shot and shell|\u0410\u0420 shot]] from domestic 85&nbsp;mm and American 76&nbsp;mm guns at ranges of {{convert|800|-|2000|m|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"Tigertest\">{{cite web |url=http://english.battlefield.ru/analytics/126-was-the-tiger-really-king.html |title=Was the Tiger really King?: Testing the King Tiger at Kubinka |work=The Russian Battlefield|accessdate= 2009-10-20 |date=19 September 2011 |quote=source: Tankomaster #6 1999.}}</ref>{{unreliable source?|date=April 2017}} The [[100 mm field gun M1944 (BS-3)|100 mm BS-3]] and [[122 mm gun M1931 (A-19)|122 mm A-19]] could also penetrate the weld joints of the front hull at ranges of 500\u2013600 metres after 3\u20134 shots.<ref name=\"Tekhnika molodezhi\">{{cite book|last1=Zheltov|first1=Igor|title= TankoMaster Special Issues 02, 2002: Isoif Stalin|publisher= Tekhnika molodezhi|page=33}}</ref>\n\nSome {{who|date=July 2018}} have said the large 122&nbsp;mm OF-471 (\u041e\u0424-471) [[High explosive|HE]] projectiles, equipped with a 3.8&nbsp;kg [[TNT]] charge, would easily crack and could even completely tear off the front armor plate at the seam weld, blow off the turret and driver sprocket<ref name=\"books.google.com.vn\"/><ref name=\"ReferenceB\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=MuGsf0psjvcC&pg=PA41&dq=is-2+powerful&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjVsremgMvSAhUIU7wKHaX5DswQ6AEIIDAB#v=onepage&q=is-2%20powerful&f=false The Encyclopedia of Weapons of World War II, Chris Bishop, P. 41]</ref>{{unreliable source?|date=April 2017}}, mechanical shock and explosion was often enough to knock out enemy heavy tanks without any armor penetration<ref name=\"books.google.com.vn\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=RLjQDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA5&dq=122mm+shell+effect&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=122mm%20shell%20effect&f=false Soviet Heavy Tanks: World War 2 In Review Special]</ref>{{unreliable source?|date=April 2017}}\n\n==Surviving vehicles==\n[[File:Koenigstiger Saumur F.jpg|thumb|alt=The side of a large tank with wide, wavy green and grey striped camouflage, as it drives past, the commander sitting in the cupola.|The working Tiger II of the ''Mus\u00e9e des Blind\u00e9s'' being displayed to the public, 2005]]The only working example is displayed at the ''[[Mus\u00e9e des Blind\u00e9s]]'', [[Saumur]], France. It has the production turret and is accessible to the public. This tank belonged to the 1st Company, [[101st SS Heavy Panzer Battalion]]. It was believed to have been abandoned by its crew on 23 August 1944, due to engine problems, at [[Brueil-en-Vexin]], near [[Mantes-la-Jolie]]. It was salvaged by the French Army in September 1944 and then stored in a factory in [[Satory]] before being transferred to the museum in 1975. Believed to have carried turret number 123, Colonel Michel Aubry, the founder of the museum, decided to put 233 on the turret in honour of the Tiger II that destroyed his Sherman tank at the end of the war. Unlike other captured German vehicles, this Tiger II was never used by the French Army.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://tank-photographs.s3-website-eu-west-1.amazonaws.com/tiger-II-heavy-tank-Konigstiger.html |title = Surviving WW2 King Tiger II Ausf. B Heavy Tank - Restored Preserved Panzers}}</ref>\nOther survivors include:\n[[File:Panzerkampfwagen VI Ausfuhrung B (Tiger II pre-production) front-left2 2017 Bovington.jpg|thumb|alt=A frontal view of a large, pale-yellow tank in a white museum gallery.. Its curved-faced turret is pointing forwards, the long gun overhangs the front by several meters.|The Bovington Tank Museum's prototype Tiger II on display at the Museum's  Tiger Collection Exhibition, 2017]]\n[[File:Tiger II La Gleize2008.jpg|thumb|alt=The side of a large tank, freshly painted in pale yellow, green and rust-brown camouflage, sitting in sunlight on a concrete plinth.|Tiger II at La Gleize, Belgium]]\n[[File:KingTigerPatton.jpg|thumb|alt=A side view of a large turreted tank in a museum, with sections of its superstructure and turret cut away.|Tiger II located at the Patton Museum of Cavalry and Armor, US]]\n[[File:SdKfz182.jpg|thumb|alt=A three quarters view of a large tank with a flat-faced turret, dull yellow, green and brown wavy camouflage, on display inside a museum. The frontal armour is sloped. The long gun overhangs the bow by several meters. Two waist-high cartridges sit on their bases in front of it.|Tiger II with the production turret, at the ''[[Deutsches Panzermuseum]]'', Germany]]\n* [[The Tank Museum|Bovington Tank Museum]], Dorset, UK. Tiger II with early production turret is on display. This vehicle was the second soft steel prototype made and did not see active service. This Tiger II's engine was removed for use in the restoration of [[Tiger 131]], the only working example of a Tiger I. A production turret Tiger II is on loan from the Defence Academy, Shrivenham, UK.\n* [[Defence Academy of the United Kingdom]], [[Shrivenham]], UK. Tiger II (production turret). This vehicle was from ''s.SS Pz.Abt. 501'', with hull number 280093, turret number 104, and has a comprehensive coating of [[Zimmerit]].<ref>Jentz and Doyle 1997, p.108.</ref> It was claimed by Sergeant Roberts of A Squadron, [[23rd Hussars]], [[11th Armoured Division]] in a Sherman tank near [[Beauvais]], although it had already been disabled and abandoned by its crew following damage to its tracks and final drive.<ref>Schneider 2005, p. 212.</ref> There is a photograph showing this vehicle after its final action in a beet field with its turret turned 90\u00b0.<ref>{{cite web |last=Parada |first=George |title=Tiger II Gallery 2 |url=http://www.achtungpanzer.com/gallery/ktgal2.htm |work=Achtung Panzer! |accessdate=2009-10-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100119054628/http://www.achtungpanzer.com/gallery/ktgal2.htm |archivedate=2010-01-19 }}</ref> This item is currently on display at [[The Tank Museum|Bovington Tank Museum]], in Dorset, UK.\n* [[The Wheatcroft Collection]], [[Leicestershire]], UK. A private collector, [[Kevin Wheatcroft]], is about{{citation needed|reason=dated information |date=June 2015}} to start a restoration/rebuild of a complete Tiger II. The project will include parts from many individual Tiger IIs, but many parts will be of new manufacture. Wheatcroft has stated that he has 70\u201380% of the original parts needed for a reconstruction and more parts are sourced continuously. Known and shown parts are a complete front glacis plate, [[8.8 cm KwK 43]] main armament, engine deck plates, approx. 1/3 hull (rear) in one part, a set of tracks, and approx. 2/3 of the left-side hull plate in two parts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wheatcroftcollection.com/tiger.html|title=Gallery of parts|publisher=Wheatcroft Collection |accessdate=2009-10-20}}</ref> The aim of the project is a complete Tiger II in running order.\n* [[Mantes-la-Jolie]], France. A more or less complete, but wrecked, Tiger II (production turret) is buried under regional road 913. Parts of the turret were recovered in a limited exploratory excavation in 2001. Further excavation is currently halted for financial reasons. There are plans to fully excavate and restore this Tiger II for a [[Vexin]] battle memorial.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vexinhistoirevivante.com/memorial_tigre.html |title=Memorial Vexin 44 |work=vexinhistoirevivante.com |language=French |accessdate=2009-10-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091021151031/http://www.vexinhistoirevivante.com/memorial_tigre.html |archivedate=2009-10-21 }}</ref>\n* [[Kubinka Tank Museum]], Russia. Tiger II (production turret) with turret number 002 (502) captured at Ogl\u0119d\u00f3w by the Red Army. The museum is open to the public.\n* [[La Gleize#Sights|December 44 Museum]], [[La Gleize]], Belgium. A cosmetically restored Tiger II (production turret) Hull number 280273, built in October 1944. Turret number 213 from ''s.SS Pz.Abt 501.'' Displayed at the entrance to DECEMBER 44 MUSEUM Collections, a museum devoted entirely to the [[Battle of the Bulge]]. This tank was abandoned in La Gleize on 24 December 1944, where the advance of [[Kampfgruppe Peiper]] was halted. The front part, about 1/3, of the gun barrel is restored with a Panther gun barrel and muzzle brake. It also has restored mudguards. It is stripped of exterior and internal fittings and most of the torsion bars are broken, but it still has its gearbox and engine in place.\n* [[Deutsches Panzermuseum]], [[Munster, Lower Saxony|Munster]], Germany. Tiger II (production turret) displayed in interior location accessible to public on payment of entrance fee. Hull number 280101. Turret number 121 from s.SS.Pz.Abt 501.\n* National Armor & Cavalry Heritage Museum, Restoration Shop, [[Fort Benning, GA]], United States. Tiger II (production turret). Hull number 280243, built in September 1944. Turret number 332 from ''s.SS Pz.Abt. 501''. Abandoned near [[Trois-Ponts]], it was captured by the US Army on 24 December 1944. The left side was cut open for educational purposes at the [[Aberdeen Proving Ground]] in the late 1940s. Was on display at the former \"Patton Museum of Cavalry & Armor, Fort Knox KY, then under BRAC transferred to Fort Benning.\n* [[Schweizerisches Milit\u00e4rmuseum Full]], Switzerland. This Tiger II (production turret) was previously displayed in the Thun Tank Museum, and is now on loan to the Schweizerisches Milit\u00e4rmuseum Full (September 2006). It will be completely restored to running condition in a long-term project. This tank was given to Switzerland by France after the war. Hull number 280215 from ''s.H.Pz.Abt 506''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.koenigstiger.ch |title=Tiger II |work=Schweizerisches Milit\u00e4rmuseum Full |accessdate=2009-10-20}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of military vehicles of World War II]]\n* [[List of World War II military vehicles of Germany]]\n* [[List of Sd.Kfz. designations]]\n* [[List of WWII Maybach engines]]\n\n===Tanks of comparable role, performance and era===\n{{Div col|colwidth=25em}}\n* [[Great Britain|British]] [[Centurion tank|Centurion]] main battle tank - developed mid-World War II, entered service 1946\n* British [[Black Prince (tank)|Black Prince]] heavy tank - six prototypes built in May 1945; did not enter service\n* [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] [[IS tank family#IS-2|IS-2 model 1944]] heavy assault tank - entered service in 1944\n* Soviet [[IS tank family#IS-3|IS-3]] heavy tank - entered service in 1945\n* [[United States]] [[T32 heavy tank|T32]] heavy tank - prototype; did not enter service\n* United States [[M26 Pershing#Super Pershing 2|T26E1-1 \"Super Pershing\"]] heavy tank - single prototype M26 Pershing with extra armour and improved T13E1 L/73 90mm gun; fought in Western Europe during 1945\n* United States [[T29 Heavy Tank|T29]] heavy tank - prototype; did not enter service\n* [[France|French]] [[ARL 44]] - produced and served in limited numbers in the late 1940s and early 1950s\n* French [[AMX-50|AMX 50]] - several prototypes produced in the late 1940s and early 1950s\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==References==\n'''Informational notes'''\n{{Reflist|group=notes}}\n\n'''Citations'''\n{{Reflist|20em}}\n\n'''Bibliography'''\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite book | last = Buckley | first = John | title = British Armour in the Normandy Campaign, 1944 | publisher = F. Cass | location = London | year = 2004 | isbn = 978-0-7146-5323-5 }}\n* {{cite book |last=Ford |first=Roger |year=2012 |title=The World's Great Tanks: From 1916 to the Present Day |location=London |publisher=Amber Books Ltd |isbn=9781908696014 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Jarymowycz | first = Roman | title = Tank Tactics: from Normandy to Lorraine | publisher = L. Rienner Publishers | location = Boulder | year = 2001 | isbn = 978-1-55587-950-1 }}\n* {{cite book | last1 = Jentz | first1 = Thomas |last2 =Doyle |first2= Hilary | title = Germany's Tiger Tanks \u2013 Vk45 to Tiger II: Design, Production & Modifications | publisher = Schiffer Publishing | location = West Chester | year = 1997 | isbn = 978-0-7643-0224-4 }}\n* {{cite book | last1 = Jentz |first1 = Thomas |last2 = Doyle |first2= Hilary |title= Kingtiger Heavy Tank, 1942\u201345 |publisher= Osprey |series=New Vangaurd |location= London |year=1993 |isbn=978-1-85532-282-0 }}\n* {{cite book|last= Jentz|first= Thomas|title=Panzertruppen 2: The Complete Guide to the Creation & Combat Employment of Germany's Tank Force 1943\u20131945|publisher=Schiffer|year= 1996|isbn= 978-0-7643-0080-6 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Manchester | first = William | title = The Arms of Krupp, 1587\u20131968: The Rise and Fall of the Industrial Dynasty That Armed Germany at War | publisher = Back Bay Books | location = Boston | year = 2003 | isbn = 978-0-316-52940-2 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Pallud | first = Jean-Paul | title = R\u00fcckmarsch! : the German retreat from Normandy : then and now | publisher = Battle of Britain International Ltd | location = Old Harlow | year = 2006 | isbn = 978-1-870067-57-7 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Perrett | first = Bryan | title = Sturmartillerie and Panzerjager 1939\u201345 | publisher = Osprey | location = London | year = 2000 |series=New Vanguard | isbn = 978-1-84176-004-9 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Schneider | first = Wolfgang | title = Elefant Jagdtiger Sturmtiger: Rarities of the Tiger Family | publisher = Schiffer Publishing | location = West Chester | year = 1990 | isbn = 978-0-88740-239-5 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Schneider | first = Wolfgang | title = Tigers in Combat I | publisher = Stackpole Books | location = Mechanicsburg | year = 2000 | isbn = 978-0-8117-3171-3 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Schneider | first = Wolfgang | title = Tigers in Combat II | publisher = Stackpole Books | location = Mechanicsburg | year = 2005 | isbn = 978-0-8117-3203-1 }}\n* {{citation |last1=Spielberger |first1=Walter |last2= Doyle |first2= Hilary |date=2007 |title=Tigers I and II and their variants |location= Pennsylvania |publisher=Schiffer Publishing Ltd |isbn=978-0-7643-2780-3 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book | last = Sz\u00e1mv\u00e9ber | first = Norbert | title = Neh\u00e9zp\u00e1nc\u00e9losok. A n\u00e9met 503. neh\u00e9zp\u00e1nc\u00e9los-oszt\u00e1ly magyarorsz\u00e1gi harcai. | publisher = Hadt\u00f6rt\u00e9neti Lev\u00e9lt\u00e1r | location = | year = 2000 |language = Hungarian | isbn = 978-963-00-2526-3 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Wilbeck | first = Christopher | title = Sledgehammers: Strengths and Flaws of Tiger Tank Battalions in World War II | publisher = The Aberjona Press | year = 2004 | isbn = 978-0-9717650-2-3 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Zaloga | first = Steven | title = IS-2 Heavy Tank 1944\u20131973 | publisher = Osprey Publishing |series=New Vanguard | location = London | year = 1994 | isbn = 978-1-85532-396-4 }}\n* {{cite book |last=Zaloga |first=Steven J. |year=2015 |title=Armored Champion: The Top Tanks of World War II |location=Mechanicsburg, PA |publisher=Stackpole Books |isbn=978-0-8117-1437-2}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.panzerworld.net/tigerii.html Information about the Pz.Kpfw.Tiger Ausf.B \"Tiger II\" at Panzerworld]\n* [http://www.fprado.com/armorsite/tiger2.htm Tiger II at the Armorsite]\n* [http://www.lonesentry.com/articles/ttt_pantiger/index.html Pantiger, A Redesigned Tiger] (U.S. intelligence report, 1944)\n\n{{WWIIGermanAFVs}}\n{{Subject bar\n| portal1=Military of Germany\n| portal2=Tanks\n| portal3=World War II\n| commons=y\n| commons-search=Panzerkampfwagen VI Tiger II\n}}\n\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tiger Ii}}\n[[Category:Heavy tanks of Germany]]\n[[Category:World War II heavy tanks]]\n[[Category:World War II tanks of Germany]]\n[[Category:History of the tank]]\n", "name_user": "Denniss", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSurviving vehicles", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tiger_II"}
{"title_page": "Intensive care medicine", "text_new": "{{Dablink|Several terms redirect here.  You may be looking for [[Intensive Care Medicine (journal)]], [[Critical Care Medicine (journal)]], [[Intensive Care (album)]] or [[CICU-FM]].}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox medical speciality\n| title        = Intensive care medicine<br/>Critical care medicine\n| image        = [[File:Respiratory therapist.jpg|250px]]\n| caption      = A patient being managed on an intensive care unit\n| focus       = [[Organ dysfunction]], [[life support]]\n| diseases     = [[Respiratory failure]], [[Organ failure]], [[Multiorgan failure]]\n| tests        = \n| specialist   = Intensive care physician<br/>Critical care physician<br/>Intensivist\n| education required   = [[Medical degree]]\n}}\n\n'''Intensive care medicine''', also called '''critical care medicine''', is a medical [[Specialty (medicine)|specialty]] that deals with critically ill patients who have, are at risk of, or are recovering from conditions that may be life-threatening.<ref name=\":6\" /> It includes providing [[life support]], invasive [[Monitoring (medicine)|monitoring]] techniques, [[resuscitation]], and [[end-of-life care]].<ref name=\"ficmabout\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ficm.ac.uk/faculty-membership/about-intensive-care|title=About Intensive Care &#124; the Faculty of Intensive Care Medicine}}</ref> Doctors in this specialty are often called '''intensive care physicians''', '''critical care physicians''' or '''intensivists'''. \n\nIntensive care relies on multidisciplinary teams composed of many different health professionals. Such teams often include doctors, nurses, [[Physical therapy|physical therapists]], [[respiratory therapist]]s, and [[Pharmacist|pharmacists]], among others. They usually work together in [[intensive care unit]]s (ICUs) within a hospital<ref name=\":6\" />.\n\n== Scope ==\nPatients are admitted to the intensive care unit if their medical needs are greater than what the general hospital ward can provide. Indications for the ICU include blood pressure support for cardiovascular instability ([[hypertension]]/[[hypotension]]), [[sepsis]], or certain [[cardiac arrhythmias]].<ref name=\":2\" /> Other ICU needs include airway or [[medical ventilator|ventilator]] support due to [[respiratory compromise]]. The cumulative effects of [[multiple organ failure]], more commonly referred to as [[multiple organ dysfunction syndrome]], also requires advanced care.<ref name=\":2\" /> Patients may also be admitted to the ICU for close monitoring or intensive needs following a major surgery.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|title=Principles of critical care|others=Hall, Jesse B.,, Schmidt, Gregory A.,, Kress, John P.|isbn=9780071738811|edition=Fourth|location=New York|oclc=906700899|date = 2 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nThere are two common ICU structures: closed and open.<ref name=\":3\" /> In a closed unit, the intensivist takes on the primary role for all patients in the unit.<ref name=\":3\" /> In an open ICU, the primary physician, who may or may not be an intensivist, can differ for each patient.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|title=Evidence-based practice of critical care|others=Deutschman, Clifford S.,, Neligan, Patrick J.|isbn=978-0-323-64069-5|edition=Third|location=Philadelphia, PA|oclc=1118693260|date=29 August 2019}}</ref> There is increasingly strong evidence that closed units provide better patient outcomes.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Manthous|first1=CA|last2=Amoateng-Adjepong|first2=Y|last3=Al-Kharrat|first3=T|last4=Jacob|first4=B|last5=Alnuaimat|first5=HM|last6=Chatila|first6=W|last7=Hall|first7=JB|date=1997|title=Effects of a medical intensivist on patient care in a community teaching hospital|journal=[[Mayo Clinic Proceedings]]|type=Abstract|volume=72|issue=5|pages=391\u20139|doi=10.4065/72.5.391|pmid=9146680}}<!--| accessdate = 2006-09-02 --></ref><ref>{{cite journal|author=Hanson CW|last2=Deutschman|first2=CS|last3=Anderson|first3=HL|last4=Reilly|first4=PM|last5=Behringer|first5=EC|last6=Schwab|first6=CW|last7=Price|first7=J|date=1999|title=Effects of an organized critical care service on outcomes and resource utilization: a cohort study|journal=[[Critical Care Medicine]]|type=Abstract|volume=27|issue=2|pages=270\u20134|doi=10.1097/00003246-199902000-00030|pmid=10075049}}<!--| accessdate = 2006-09-02 --></ref> Patient management in intensive care differs between countries. Open units are the most common structure in the United States, but closed units are often found at large academic centers.<ref name=\":3\" /> Intermediate structures that fall between open and closed units also exist.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== Types of intensive care units ===\nIntensive care is usually provided in a specialized unit of a [[hospital]] called the [[intensive care unit]] (ICU) or critical care unit (CCU). Many hospitals also have designated intensive care areas for certain specialities of medicine<ref name=\":5\" />. The naming is not rigidly standardized, and types of units are dictated by the needs and available resources of each hospital. These include:\n\n* coronary intensive care unit (CCU or sometimes CICU) for heart disease\n* medical intensive care unit (MICU)\n* surgical intensive care unit (SICU)\n* pediatric intensive care unit (PICU)\n* neuroscience critical care unit (NCCU)\n* overnight intensive-recovery (OIR) \n* [[Shock (circulatory)|shock]]/trauma intensive-care unit (STICU)\n* neonatal intensive care unit (NICU)\n* ICU in the emergency department (E-ICU)<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Yim |first1=KM |last2=Ko |first2=HF |last3=Yang |first3=Marc LC |last4=Li |first4=TY |last5=Ip |first5=S |last6=Tsui |first6=J |title=A paradigm shift in the provision of improved critical care in the emergency department |journal=Hong Kong Medical Journal |date=20 June 2018 |volume=24 |issue=3 |pages=293\u2013297 |doi=10.12809/hkmj176902 |pmid=29926792 }}</ref> \n\nMedical studies suggest a relation between ICU volume and quality of care for mechanically ventilated patients.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kahn|first1=JM|last2=Goss|first2=CH|last3=Heagerty|first3=PJ|last4=Kramer|first4=AA|last5=O'Brien|first5=CR|last6=Rubenfeld|first6=GD|date=2006|title=Hospital volume and the outcomes of mechanical ventilation|journal=[[The New England Journal of Medicine]]|volume=355|issue=1|pages=41\u201350|doi=10.1056/NEJMsa053993|pmid=16822995}}<!--| accessdate =  2006-08-02  --></ref> After adjustment for severity of illness, demographic variables, and characteristics of the ICUs (including staffing by [[intensivist]]s), higher ICU volume was significantly associated with lower ICU and hospital mortality rates. For example, adjusted ICU mortality (for a patient at average predicted risk for ICU death) was 21.2% in hospitals with 87 to 150 mechanically ventilated patients annually, and 14.5% in hospitals with 401 to 617 mechanically ventilated patients annually. Hospitals with intermediate numbers of patients had outcomes between these extremes. [[ICU delirium]], formerly and inaccurately referred to as ICU psychosis, is a syndrome common in intensive care and cardiac units where patients who are in unfamiliar, monotonous surroundings develop symptoms of delirium (Maxmen & Ward, 1995). This may include interpreting machine noises as human voices, seeing walls quiver, or hallucinating that someone is tapping them on the shoulder.<ref name=\"test\">Nolen-Hoeksema, Susan. \"Neurodevelopmental and Neurocognitive Disorders.\" ''(Ab)normal Psychology''. Sixth ed. New York City: McGraw-Hill Education, 2014. 314. Print.</ref> There exists systematic reviews in which interventions of sleep promotion related outcomes in the ICU have proven impactful in the overall health of patients in the ICU.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Flannery|first=Alexander H.|last2=Oyler|first2=Douglas R.|last3=Weinhouse|first3=Gerald L.|date=December 2016|title=The Impact of Interventions to Improve Sleep on Delirium in the ICU|journal=Critical Care Medicine|volume=44|issue=12|pages=2231\u20132240|doi=10.1097/ccm.0000000000001952|issn=0090-3493|pmid=27509391}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe English nurse [[Florence Nightingale]] pioneered efforts to use a separate hospital area for critically-injured patients. During the [[Crimean War]] in the 1850s, she introduced the practice of moving the sickest patients to the beds directly opposite the nursing station on each ward so that they could be monitored more closely.<ref name=\"Vincent2013\">{{cite journal|last1=Vincent|first1=Jean-Louis|title=Critical care - where have we been and where are we going?|journal=Critical Care|volume=17|issue=S1|pages=S2|year=2013|issn=1364-8535|doi=10.1186/cc11500|pmid=23514264|pmc=3603479}}</ref> In 1923, the American [[neurosurgery|neurosurgeon]] [[Walter Dandy]] created a three-bed unit at the [[Johns Hopkins Hospital]]. In these units, specially-trained nurses cared for critically ill postoperative neurosurgical patients.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Miller's Anesthesia|others=Gropper, Michael A., 1958-, Miller, Ronald D., 1939-|isbn=978-0-323-61264-7|edition=Ninth|location=Philadelphia, PA|oclc=1124935549|date = 7 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=Vincent2013/>\n\nThe Danish [[anesthesiology|anaesthesiologist]] [[Bj\u00f8rn Aage Ibsen]] became involved in the 1952 [[poliomyelitis]] epidemic in [[Copenhagen]], where 2722 patients developed the illness in a 6-month period, with 316 suffering some form of respiratory or airway paralysis.<ref name=\"Woollam1976\">{{cite journal|last1=Woollam|first1=C. H. M.|title=The development of apparatus for intermittent negative pressure respiration (2) 1919\u20131976, with special reference to the development and uses of cuirass respirators|journal=Anaesthesia|volume=31|issue=5|year=1976|pages=666\u2013685|issn=0003-2409|doi=10.1111/j.1365-2044.1976.tb11849.x|pmid=779520}}</ref> Treatment had involved the use of the few negative pressure respirators available, but these devices, while helpful, were limited and did not protect against aspiration of secretions. Ibsen changed management directly, instituting protracted positive pressure ventilation by means of intubation into the trachea, and enlisting 200 medical students to manually pump oxygen and air into the patients' lungs.<ref>Reisner-S\u00e9n\u00e9lar, Louise (2011). [http://xa.yimg.com/kq/groups/16749867/2041687438/name/The+birth+of+intensive+care+medicine.pdf \"The Birth of Intensive Care Medicine: Bj\u00f6rn Ibsen\u2019s Records\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121006125624/http://xa.yimg.com/kq/groups/16749867/2041687438/name/The+birth+of+intensive+care+medicine.pdf |date=6 October 2012 }} ([[Portable Document Format|PDF format]]).''[[Intensive Care Medicine (journal)|Intensive Care Medicine]]''.  Retrieved 2 October 2012.</ref> At this time Carl-Gunnar Engstr\u00f6m had developed one of the first positive pressure volume controlled ventilators, which eventually replaced the medical students. In this fashion, mortality declined from 90% to around 25%.  Patients were managed in three special 35-bed areas, which aided charting and other management. In 1953, Ibsen set up what became the world's first [[intensive care unit]] in a converted student nurse classroom in [[Copenhagen Municipal Hospital]], and provided one of the first accounts of the management of tetanus with muscle relaxants and controlled ventilation.<ref name=\"BerthelsenCronqvist2003\">{{cite journal|last1=Berthelsen|first1=P.G.|last2=Cronqvist|first2=M.|title=The first intensive care unit in the world: Copenhagen 1953|journal=Acta Anaesthesiologica Scandinavica|volume=47|issue=10|year=2003|pages=1190\u20131195|issn=0001-5172|doi=10.1046/j.1399-6576.2003.00256.x|pmid=14616314}}</ref> In 1954 Ibsen was elected Head of the Department of Anaesthesiology at that institution. He jointly authored the first known account of intensive care management principles in the journal ''Nordisk Medicin'', with Tone Dahl Kvittingen from Norway. <ref name=\"pmid13600704\">{{cite journal| last1=Ibsen|first1=B|last2=Kvittingen|first2=T.D.|title=Arbejdet p\u00e5 en An\u00e6sthesiologisk Observationsafdeling|trans-title=Work in an Anaesthesiological Observation Unit|language=Danish| journal=Nordisk Medicin | year= 1958 | volume= 60 | issue= 38 | pages= 1349\u201355 | pmid=13600704}} </ref> For a time in the early 1960s, it was not clear that specialized intensive care units were needed, so intensive care resources were brought to the room of the patient that needed the additional monitoring, care, and resources. It became rapidly evident, however, that a fixed location where intensive care resources and dedicated personnel were available provided better care than ''ad hoc'' provision of intensive care services spread throughout a hospital. In 1962, in the University of Pittsburgh, the first Critical Care Residency was established in the United States. In 1970, the [[Society of Critical Care Medicine]] was formed.<ref>history reference: Brazilian Society of Critical Care [http://www.sobrati.com.br SOBRATI] Video:[http://www.medicinaintensiva.com.br/icu-history.htm ICU History] [http://www.medicinaintensiva.com.br/fotos-semana.htm Historical photos]</ref>\n\n== Monitoring ==\n[[Monitoring (medicine)|Monitoring]] refers to various tools and technologies used to obtain information about a patient's condition. These can include tests to evaluate [[Hemodynamics|blood flow]] and gas exchange in the body, or to assess the function of organs such as the heart and lungs. Broadly, there are two common types of monitoring in the ICU: noninvasive and invasive.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite book|title=Civetta, Taylor, & Kirby's critical care|date=2009|publisher=Lippincott Williams & Wilkins|others=Gabrielli, Andrea., Layon, A. Joseph., Yu, Mihae., Civetta, Joseph M., Taylor, Robert W. (Robert Wesley), 1949-, Kirby, Robert R.|isbn=978-0-7817-6869-6|edition=4th|location=Philadelphia|oclc=253189100}}</ref> \n\n=== Noninvasive Monitoring ===\nNoninvasive monitoring does not require puncturing the skin and usually does not cause pain. These tools are more inexpensive, easier to perform, and faster to result<ref name=\":6\" />. \n\n* [[Vital signs]] which includes heart rate, blood pressure, breathing rate, body temperature\n\n* [[Echocardiography|Echocardiogram]] to evaluate the function and structure of the heart\n*[[Electroencephalography|Electroencephalography (EEG)]] to assess electrical activity of the brain \n*[[Electrocardiography|Electrocardiogram]] to detect abnormal heart rhythms, [[Electrolyte imbalance|electrolyte disturbances]], and coronary blood flow\n* [[Pulse oximetry]] for monitoring oxygen levels in the blood\n*[[Impedance cardiography|Thoracic electric bioimpedance]] (TEB) cardiography to monitor fluid status and heart function \n*[[Ultrasound]] to evaluate internal structures including the heart, lungs, gallbladder, liver, kidneys, bladder, and blood vessels\n\n=== Invasive Monitoring ===\nInvasive monitoring generally provides more accurate measurements, but these tests may require blood draws, puncturing the skin, and can be painful or uncomfortable<ref name=\":6\" />.\n\n* [[Arterial line]] to directly monitor blood pressure and obtain [[Arterial blood gas test|arterial blood gas]] measurements\n*[[Venipuncture|Blood draws or venipucture]] to monitor various blood components as well as administer therapeutic treatments \n*[[Intracranial pressure monitoring]] to assess pressures inside the skull and on the brain\n*Intravesicular manometry (bladder pressure) measurements to assess for intra-abdominal pressure\n\n* [[Central venous catheter|Central line]] and [[peripherally inserted central catheter]] (PICC) lines for drug infusions, fluids or [[total parenteral nutrition]]\n\n* [[Bronchoscopy]] to look at lungs and airways and sample fluid within the lungs\n* [[Pulmonary artery catheter]] to monitor the function of the heart, blood volume, and tissue oxygenation\n\n== Procedures and Treatments  ==\nIntensive care usually takes a system-by-system approach to treatment.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|title=Critical care medicine : principles of diagnosis and management in the adult|date=2008|publisher=Mosby Elsevier|others=Parrillo, Joseph E., Dellinger, R. Phillip.|isbn=978-0-323-07095-9|edition=3rd|location=Philadelphia, PA|oclc=324998024}}</ref> In alphabetical order, the nine key systems considered in the intensive care setting are: [[cardiovascular system]], [[central nervous system]], [[endocrine system]], [[gastro-intestinal tract]] (and nutritional condition), [[hematology]], [[integumentary system]], [[microbiology]] (including sepsis status), [[urinary system|renal]] (and metabolic), and [[respiratory system]]. As such, the nine key systems are each considered on an observation-intervention-impression basis to produce a daily plan. [[File:Sondeintubation.jpg|thumb|right|An endotracheal tube]]\n\n==== Cardiovascular ====\n\n*[[Artificial cardiac pacemaker|Temporary cardiac pacing catheters]] for atrial, ventricular, or dual-chamber pacing \n*[[Intra-aortic balloon pump|Intra-aortic balloon pumping]] to stabilize patients with cardiogenic shock \n*[[Ventricular assist device]] to aid in function of the left ventricle, commonly in patients with advanced heart failure\n\n==== Gastro-intestinal Tract ====\n\n* [[Feeding tube]] for artificial nutrition \n* [[Nasogastric intubation]] can be used to deliver artificial nutrition, but can also be used to remove stomach and intestinal contents\n* [[Diagnostic peritoneal lavage|Peritoneal aspiration and lavage]] to sample fluid in the abdominal cavity\n\n==== Renal ====\n\n* [[Hemofiltration]] for [[acute renal failure|acute kidney injury]]\n\n==== Respiratory ====\n\n* [[Mechanical ventilation]] to assist breathing through an [[Tracheal intubation|endotracheal tube]] or [[tracheotomy]]\n* [[Thoracentesis]] or [[Chest tube|tube thoracostomy]] to remove fluid or air in the pleural cavity\n\n=== Drugs ===\nA wide array of [[pharmacology|drugs]] including but not limited to: [[inotrope]]s, [[sedatives]], broad spectrum [[antibiotics]] and [[analgesics]].\n\n== Common Complications in the ICU ==\nIntensive care units are associated with increased risk of various complications that may lengthen a patient's hospitalization<ref name=\":5\" />. Complications in the ICU include:\n\n* [[Acute kidney injury|Acute renal failure]]\n* Catheter-associated blood stream infection\n* [[Catheter-associated urinary tract infection]]\n* [[Delirium]] \n* [[Gastrointestinal bleeding]] \n* [[Pressure ulcer]]\n* [[Venous thrombosis|Venous thromboembolism]] \n* [[Ventilator-associated pneumonia]] \n* [[Barotrauma|Ventilator-induced barotrauma]] \n\n==Training==\nICU care requires more specialized patient care; this need has led to the use of a multidisciplinary team to provide care for patients.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|title=Basics of anesthesia|others=Pardo, Manuel, Jr., 1965-, Miller, Ronald D., 1939-, Preceded by (work): Miller, Ronald D., 1939-|isbn=9780323401159|edition=Seventh|location=Philadelphia, PA|oclc=989157369|date = 26 June 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":6\" /> Staffing between Intensive care units by country, hospital, unit, or institution.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== Medicine ===\nCritical care medicine is an increasingly important medical specialty. [[Physician]]s with training in critical care medicine are referred to as [[intensivist]]s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hfma.org/forums/What_Intensivist.htm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090927021234/http://www.hfma.org/forums/What_Intensivist.htm |title=What \u2013 or Who -- Is an Intensivist? |archivedate=2009-09-27 |publisher=[[Healthcare Financial Management Association]]}}</ref> In the United States, the specialty requires additional fellowship training for physicians having completed their primary residency training in internal medicine, [[pediatrics]], [[anesthesiology]], [[surgery]] or [[emergency medicine]]. US board certification in critical care medicine is available through all five specialty boards.  Intensivists with a primary training in internal medicine sometimes pursue combined fellowship training in another subspecialty such as pulmonary medicine, cardiology, infectious disease, or nephrology.  The American  [[Society of Critical Care Medicine]] is a well-established multiprofessional society for practitioners working in the ICU including nurses, respiratory therapists, and physicians. Most medical research has demonstrated that ICU care provided by intensivists produces better outcomes and more cost-effective care.<ref>\"Association between Critical Care Physician Management and Patient Mortality in the Intensive Care Unit\".  ''[[Annals of Internal Medicine]]''. 3 June 2008. Volume 148, Issue 11. pp. 801\u2013809.</ref> This has led the [[Leapfrog Group]] to make a primary recommendation that all ICU patients be managed or co-managed by a dedicated intensivist who is exclusively responsible for patients in one ICU. \n\nIn Australia, the training in intensive care medicine is through College of Intensive Care Medicine.\n\nIn the UK doctors can only enter intensive care medicine training after completing two foundation years, and core training in either emergency medicine, anaesthetics, acute medicine or core medicine. Most trainees dual train with one of these specialties however it has recently become possible to train purely in intensive care medicine. It has also possible to train in sub-specialties of intensive care medicine including pre-hospital emergency medicine. \n\n=== Nursing ===\nNurses that work in the critical care setting are typically registered nurses.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Principles of critical care|others=Hall, Jesse B.,, Schmidt, Gregory A.,, Kress, John P.|isbn=9780071738811|edition=Fourth|location=New York|oclc=906700899|date = 2 June 2015}}</ref> [[Nurse]]s may pursue additional education and training in critical care medicine leading to certification as a CCRN by the American Association of Critical Care Nurses a standard that was begun in 1975.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=Pediatric critical care|others=Fuhrman, Bradley P.,, Zimmerman, Jerry J.,, Clark, Robert S. B., 1962-, Relvas, Monica S.,, Thompson, Ann E.,, Tobias, Joseph D.|isbn=978-0-323-37839-0|edition=Fifth|location=Philadelphia, PA|oclc=966447977|date=8 December 2016}}</ref> These certifications became more specialized to the patient population in 1997 by the American Association of Critical care Nurses, to include pediatrics, neonatal and adult.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Nurse practitioners and physician assistants ===\n[[Nurse practitioner]]s and [[physician assistant]]s are other types of non-physician providers that care for patients in ICUs.<ref name=\":2\" /> Outcomes have shown that the use of non-physician providers have been shown to have similar outcomes to those with physician providers.<ref name=\":3\" /> These providers have less years of in school training and typically receive further clinical on the job education.<ref name=\":3\" /> Non-physician providers like nurse practitioners and physician assistants are typically present for longer periods of time than [[resident physician]]<nowiki/>s that rotate off service.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== Pharmacists ===\nCritical care [[pharmacists]] work with the medical team in many aspect but some include, monitoring serum concentrations of medication, past medication use, current medication use, and medication allergies.<ref name=\":4\" /> Their typically round with the team but it may differ by institution.<ref name=\":4\" /> Some pharmacist after attaining their doctorate or pharmacy may pursue additional training in a postgraduate residency and become certified as critical care pharmacists.<ref name=\":4\" /> Pharmacists help manage all aspects of drug therapy and may pursue additional credentialing in critical care medicine as BCCCP by the Board of Pharmaceutical Specialties. Many critical care pharmacist are a part of the multi-professional Society of Critical Care Medicine.<ref name=\":4\" /> Inclusion of pharmacist decreases drug reactions and poor outcomes for patients.<ref name=\":2\" /> \n\n=== Paramedics or emergency medical technicians ===\n[[Paramedic]]s are certified to levels of CCEMT-P, PNCCT-P, CCP-C and/or FP-C depending upon their speciality (e.g. air, ground, adult, pediatric and/or neonatal medicine). \n\n=== Registered dietitians ===\nNutrition in intensive care units presents unique challenges due to changes in patient metabolism and physiology while critically ill.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Current surgical therapy|others=Cameron, John L.,, Cameron, Andrew M. (Andrew MacGregor)|isbn=978-0-323-37691-4|edition=12th|location=Philadelphia, PA|oclc=966447396}}</ref> Critical care nutrition is rapidly becoming a subspecialty for [[dietician]]s who can pursue additional training and achieve certification in enteral and parenteral nutrition through the [[American Society for Parenteral and Enteral Nutrition]] (ASPEN).  \n\n=== Respiratory therapists ===\nRespiratory therapists often work in intensive care units to monitor how well a patient is breathing.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Total burn care|others=Herndon, David N.|isbn=978-0-323-49742-8|edition=Fifth|location=Edinburgh|oclc=1012122839|date = 10 October 2017}}</ref> [[Respiratory therapists]] may pursue additional education and training leading to credentialing in adult critical care (ACCS) and neonatal and pediatric (NPS) specialties. These therapists have been trained to monitor a patient's breathing, provide treatments to help their breathing and evaluate for improvement.<ref name=\":0\" /> They may be involved in emergency care like managing an airway, humidification of oxygen, administering diagnostic test, invasive or non-invasive ventilation management, aerosol therapy, inhaled Nitric oxide therapy, artery blood gas analysis and providing physiotherapy.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Clinician's pocket reference|last=Gomella, Leonard G.|date=2007|publisher=McGraw-Hill Companies, Inc|others=Haist, Steven A., University of Kentucky. College of Medicine.|isbn=978-0-07-145428-5|edition=11th|location=New York|oclc=85841308}}</ref>\n\n== Ethical and medicolegal issues ==\n===Economics===\nIn general, it is the most expensive, technologically advanced and resource-intensive area of medical care. In the [[United States]], estimates of the 2000 expenditure for critical care medicine ranged from US$19\u201355 billion.<!--Is this lower bound given in the full cited article? The abstract suggests it is $55.5bn, which I presume forms the basis for the following figures; perhaps somebody with journal access could check...--> During that year, critical care medicine accounted for 0.56% of [[Gross Domestic Product|GDP]], 4.2% of national health expenditure and about 13% of hospital costs.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Halpern|first1=Neil A.|last2=Pastores|first2=Stephen M.|last3=Greenstein|first3=Robert J.|date=June 2004|title=Critical care medicine in the United States 1985\u20132000: An analysis of bed numbers, use, and costs|journal=[[Critical Care Medicine]]|volume=32|issue=6|pages=1254\u20131259|doi=10.1097/01.CCM.0000128577.31689.4C|pmid=15187502}}<!--|accessdate=7 November 2011 --></ref>\nIn 2011, hospital stays with ICU services accounted for just over one-quarter of all discharges (29.9%) but nearly one-half of aggregate total hospital charges (47.5%) in the [[United States]]. The mean hospital charge was 2.5 times higher for discharges with ICU services than for those without.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hcup-us.ahrq.gov/reports/statbriefs/sb185-Hospital-Intensive-Care-Units-2011.jsp|title=Utilization of Intensive Care Services, 2011|author=Barrett ML|author2=Smith MW|date=December 2014|work=HCUP Statistical Brief #185|publisher=Agency for Healthcare Research and Quality|location=Rockville, MD|author3=Elizhauser A|author4=Honigman LS|author5=Pines JM}}</ref>\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Medicine}}\n* [[Mechanical ventilation]]\n* [[Extracorporeal membrane oxygenation]]\n* [[Telemetry]]\n* [[Chronic critical illness]]\n* [[Critical care nursing]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== References ==\n*[http://www.lww.com/Product/0-7817-3548-3 Intensive Care Medicine by Irwin and Rippe]{{Dead link|date=August 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20151222141626/http://www.lww.com/Product/978-0-7817-6869-6 Civetta, Taylor, and Kirby's Critical Care]\n*[https://shop.lww.com/Marino-s-The-ICU-Book--Print---Ebook-with-Updates/p/9781451121186 The ICU Book by Marino]\n*[http://www.lww.com/Product/0-7817-4334-6 ''Procedures and Techniques in Intensive Care Medicine by Irwin and Rippe'']{{Dead link|date=August 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n*{{cite journal | pmid = 15187502 | doi = 10.1097/01.CCM.0000128577.31689.4C | last1 = Halpern  | name-list-format =vanc | first1 = NA | last2 = Pastores | first2 = SM | last3 = Greenstein | first3 = RJ | title = Critical care medicine in the United States 1985\u20132000: an analysis of bed numbers, use, and costs | journal = [[Critical Care Medicine]]| volume=32 | issue=6 |date=June 2004 | pages=1254\u20139}}.\n*History references:\n**[http://www.sobrati.com.br Brazilian Society of Intensive Care - SOBRATI ]\n**[http://www.medicinaintensiva.com.br/personagens.htm History]\n*[http://www.sccm.org Society of Critical Care Medicine]\n*{{cite journal |first1=H.N. |last1= Reynolds |first2= H.|last2= Rogove |first3= J. |last3= Bander |first4= M. |last4= McCambridge |first5= E. |last5= Cowboy |first6= M. |last6= Niemeier |displayauthors=4 |journal= Telemedicine and E-Health |date= December 2011 |volume= 17|issue= 10 |pages= 773\u2013783 |doi=10.1089/tmj.2011.0045 |pmid= 22029748 |title= A working lexicon for the tele-intensive care unit: We need to define tele-intensive care unit to grow and understand it|hdl= 2027.42/90470 |url= https://deepblue.lib.umich.edu/bitstream/2027.42/90470/1/tmj-2E2011-2E0045.pdf }}\n*{{cite journal |first1=Terrah |last1= Olson |first2= Karen|last2= Brasel |first3= Andrew |last3= Redmann |first4= G. |last4= Alexander |first5= Margaret |last5= Schwarze |journal= JAMA Surgery |date= January 2013 |volume= 148|issue= 1 |pages= 29\u201335 |doi=10.1001/jamasurgery.2013.403 |pmid= 23324837 |title= Surgeon-Reported Conflict With Intensivists About Postoperative Goals of Care|pmc= 3624604 }}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{Cite Q|Q29581786}}.\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Intensive-care medicine}}\n{{Wikibooks |Intensive Care Medicine}}\n* [http://www.cicm.org.au College of Intensive Care Medicine - Australia and New Zealand]\n* [http://www.anzics.com.au Australia and New Zealand Intensive Care Society]\n* [http://www.sccm.org Society of Critical Care Medicine]\n* [http://www.veccs.org Veterinary Emergency And Critical Care Society]\n* [http://www.esicm.org ESICM: European Society of Intensive Care Medicine]\n* [http://espnic-online.org ESPNIC: The society for paediatric and neonatal intensive care healthcare professionals in Europe]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110316113900/http://www.ics.ac.uk/ UK Intensive Care Society]\n* [http://www.scottishintensivecare.org.uk/- Scottish Intensive Care Society]\n* [http://www.hksccm.org Hong Kong Society of Critical Care Medicine]\n* [http://www.csccm.org Chinese Society of Critical Care Medicine]\n* [http://www.tsccm.org.tw/English/eng001.asp Taiwan Society of Critical Care Medicine]\n* [http://richannel.org/from-iron-lungs-to-intensive-care From Iron Lungs to Intensive Care], [[Royal Institution]] debate, February 2012\n\n{{Intensive care medicine}}\n{{Medicine}}\n\n[[Category:Intensive care medicine| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Dablink|Several terms redirect here.  You may be looking for [[Intensive Care Medicine (journal)]], [[Critical Care Medicine (journal)]], [[Intensive Care (album)]] or [[CICU-FM]].}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox medical speciality\n| title        = Intensive care medicine<br/>Critical care medicine\n| image        = [[File:Respiratory therapist.jpg|250px]]\n| caption      = A patient being managed on an intensive care unit\n| focus       = [[Organ dysfunction]], [[life support]]\n| diseases     = [[Respiratory failure]], [[Organ failure]], [[Multiorgan failure]]\n| tests        = \n| specialist   = Intensive care physician<br/>Critical care physician<br/>Intensivist\n| education required   = [[Medical degree]]\n}}\n\n'''Intensive care medicine''', also called '''critical care medicine''', is a medical [[Specialty (medicine)|specialty]] that deals with critically ill patients who have, are at risk of, or are recovering from conditions that may be life-threatening.<ref name=\":6\" /> It includes providing [[life support]], invasive [[Monitoring (medicine)|monitoring]] techniques, [[resuscitation]], and [[end-of-life care]].<ref name=\"ficmabout\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ficm.ac.uk/faculty-membership/about-intensive-care|title=About Intensive Care &#124; the Faculty of Intensive Care Medicine}}</ref> Doctors in this specialty are often called '''intensive care physicians''', '''critical care physicians''' or '''intensivists'''. \n\nIntensive care relies on multidisciplinary teams composed of many different health professionals. Such teams often include doctors, nurses, [[Physical therapy|physical therapists]], [[respiratory therapist]]s, and [[Pharmacist|pharmacists]], among others. They usually work together in [[intensive care unit]]s (ICUs) within a hospital<ref name=\":6\" />.\n\n== Scope ==\nPatients are admitted to the intensive care unit if their medical needs are greater than what the general hospital ward can provide. Indications for the ICU include blood pressure support for cardiovascular instability ([[hypertension]]/[[hypotension]]), [[sepsis]], or certain [[cardiac arrhythmias]].<ref name=\":2\" /> Other ICU needs include airway or [[medical ventilator|ventilator]] support due to [[respiratory compromise]]. The cumulative effects of [[multiple organ failure]], more commonly referred to as [[multiple organ dysfunction syndrome]], also requires advanced care.<ref name=\":2\" /> Patients may also be admitted to the ICU for close monitoring or intensive needs following a major surgery.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|title=Principles of critical care|others=Hall, Jesse B.,, Schmidt, Gregory A.,, Kress, John P.|isbn=9780071738811|edition=Fourth|location=New York|oclc=906700899|date = 2 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nThere are two common ICU structures: closed and open.<ref name=\":3\" /> In a closed unit, the intensivist takes on the primary role for all patients in the unit.<ref name=\":3\" /> In an open ICU, the primary physician, who may or may not be an intensivist, can differ for each patient.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|title=Evidence-based practice of critical care|others=Deutschman, Clifford S.,, Neligan, Patrick J.|isbn=978-0-323-64069-5|edition=Third|location=Philadelphia, PA|oclc=1118693260|date=29 August 2019}}</ref> There is increasingly strong evidence that closed units provide better patient outcomes.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Manthous|first1=CA|last2=Amoateng-Adjepong|first2=Y|last3=Al-Kharrat|first3=T|last4=Jacob|first4=B|last5=Alnuaimat|first5=HM|last6=Chatila|first6=W|last7=Hall|first7=JB|date=1997|title=Effects of a medical intensivist on patient care in a community teaching hospital|journal=[[Mayo Clinic Proceedings]]|type=Abstract|volume=72|issue=5|pages=391\u20139|doi=10.4065/72.5.391|pmid=9146680}}<!--| accessdate = 2006-09-02 --></ref><ref>{{cite journal|author=Hanson CW|last2=Deutschman|first2=CS|last3=Anderson|first3=HL|last4=Reilly|first4=PM|last5=Behringer|first5=EC|last6=Schwab|first6=CW|last7=Price|first7=J|date=1999|title=Effects of an organized critical care service on outcomes and resource utilization: a cohort study|journal=[[Critical Care Medicine]]|type=Abstract|volume=27|issue=2|pages=270\u20134|doi=10.1097/00003246-199902000-00030|pmid=10075049}}<!--| accessdate = 2006-09-02 --></ref> Patient management in intensive care differs between countries. Open units are the most common structure in the United States, but closed units are often found at large academic centers.<ref name=\":3\" /> Intermediate structures that fall between open and closed units also exist.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== Types of intensive care units ===\nIntensive care is usually provided in a specialized unit of a [[hospital]] called the [[intensive care unit]] (ICU) or critical care unit (CCU). Many hospitals also have designated intensive care areas for certain specialities of medicine<ref name=\":5\" />. The naming is not rigidly standardized, and types of units are dictated by the needs and available resources of each hospital. These include:\n\n* coronary intensive care unit (CCU or sometimes CICU) for heart disease\n* medical intensive care unit (MICU)\n* surgical intensive care unit (SICU)\n* pediatric intensive care unit (PICU)\n* neuroscience critical care unit (NCCU)\n* overnight intensive-recovery (OIR) \n* [[Shock (circulatory)|shock]]/trauma intensive-care unit (STICU)\n* neonatal intensive care unit (NICU)\n* ICU in the emergency department (E-ICU)<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Yim |first1=KM |last2=Ko |first2=HF |last3=Yang |first3=Marc LC |last4=Li |first4=TY |last5=Ip |first5=S |last6=Tsui |first6=J |title=A paradigm shift in the provision of improved critical care in the emergency department |journal=Hong Kong Medical Journal |date=20 June 2018 |volume=24 |issue=3 |pages=293\u2013297 |doi=10.12809/hkmj176902 |pmid=29926792 }}</ref> \n\nMedical studies suggest a relation between ICU volume and quality of care for mechanically ventilated patients.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kahn|first1=JM|last2=Goss|first2=CH|last3=Heagerty|first3=PJ|last4=Kramer|first4=AA|last5=O'Brien|first5=CR|last6=Rubenfeld|first6=GD|date=2006|title=Hospital volume and the outcomes of mechanical ventilation|journal=[[The New England Journal of Medicine]]|volume=355|issue=1|pages=41\u201350|doi=10.1056/NEJMsa053993|pmid=16822995}}<!--| accessdate =  2006-08-02  --></ref> After adjustment for severity of illness, demographic variables, and characteristics of the ICUs (including staffing by [[intensivist]]s), higher ICU volume was significantly associated with lower ICU and hospital mortality rates. For example, adjusted ICU mortality (for a patient at average predicted risk for ICU death) was 21.2% in hospitals with 87 to 150 mechanically ventilated patients annually, and 14.5% in hospitals with 401 to 617 mechanically ventilated patients annually. Hospitals with intermediate numbers of patients had outcomes between these extremes. [[ICU delirium]], formerly and inaccurately referred to as ICU psychosis, is a syndrome common in intensive care and cardiac units where patients who are in unfamiliar, monotonous surroundings develop symptoms of delirium (Maxmen & Ward, 1995). This may include interpreting machine noises as human voices, seeing walls quiver, or hallucinating that someone is tapping them on the shoulder.<ref name=\"test\">Nolen-Hoeksema, Susan. \"Neurodevelopmental and Neurocognitive Disorders.\" ''(Ab)normal Psychology''. Sixth ed. New York City: McGraw-Hill Education, 2014. 314. Print.</ref> There exists systematic reviews in which interventions of sleep promotion related outcomes in the ICU have proven impactful in the overall health of patients in the ICU.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Flannery|first=Alexander H.|last2=Oyler|first2=Douglas R.|last3=Weinhouse|first3=Gerald L.|date=December 2016|title=The Impact of Interventions to Improve Sleep on Delirium in the ICU|journal=Critical Care Medicine|volume=44|issue=12|pages=2231\u20132240|doi=10.1097/ccm.0000000000001952|issn=0090-3493|pmid=27509391}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe English nurse [[Florence Nightingale]] pioneered efforts to use a separate hospital area for critically-injured patients. During the [[Crimean War]] in the 1850s, she introduced the practice of moving the sickest patients to the beds directly opposite the nursing station on each ward so that they could be monitored more closely.<ref name=\"Vincent2013\">{{cite journal|last1=Vincent|first1=Jean-Louis|title=Critical care - where have we been and where are we going?|journal=Critical Care|volume=17|issue=S1|pages=S2|year=2013|issn=1364-8535|doi=10.1186/cc11500|pmid=23514264|pmc=3603479}}</ref> In 1923, the American [[neurosurgery|neurosurgeon]] [[Walter Dandy]] created a three-bed unit at the [[Johns Hopkins Hospital]]. In these units, specially-trained nurses cared for critically ill postoperative neurosurgical patients.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Miller's Anesthesia|others=Gropper, Michael A., 1958-, Miller, Ronald D., 1939-|isbn=978-0-323-61264-7|edition=Ninth|location=Philadelphia, PA|oclc=1124935549|date = 7 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=Vincent2013/>\n\nThe Danish [[anesthesiology|anaesthesiologist]] [[Bj\u00f8rn Aage Ibsen]] became involved in the 1952 [[poliomyelitis]] epidemic in [[Copenhagen]], where 2722 patients developed the illness in a 6-month period, with 316 suffering some form of respiratory or airway paralysis.<ref name=\"Woollam1976\">{{cite journal|last1=Woollam|first1=C. H. M.|title=The development of apparatus for intermittent negative pressure respiration (2) 1919\u20131976, with special reference to the development and uses of cuirass respirators|journal=Anaesthesia|volume=31|issue=5|year=1976|pages=666\u2013685|issn=0003-2409|doi=10.1111/j.1365-2044.1976.tb11849.x|pmid=779520}}</ref> Treatment had involved the use of the few negative pressure respirators available, but these devices, while helpful, were limited and did not protect against aspiration of secretions. Ibsen changed management directly, instituting protracted positive pressure ventilation by means of intubation into the trachea, and enlisting 200 medical students to manually pump oxygen and air into the patients' lungs.<ref>Reisner-S\u00e9n\u00e9lar, Louise (2011). [http://xa.yimg.com/kq/groups/16749867/2041687438/name/The+birth+of+intensive+care+medicine.pdf \"The Birth of Intensive Care Medicine: Bj\u00f6rn Ibsen\u2019s Records\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121006125624/http://xa.yimg.com/kq/groups/16749867/2041687438/name/The+birth+of+intensive+care+medicine.pdf |date=6 October 2012 }} ([[Portable Document Format|PDF format]]).''[[Intensive Care Medicine (journal)|Intensive Care Medicine]]''.  Retrieved 2 October 2012.</ref> At this time Carl-Gunnar Engstr\u00f6m had developed one of the first positive pressure volume controlled ventilators, which eventually replaced the medical students. In this fashion, mortality declined from 90% to around 25%.  Patients were managed in three special 35-bed areas, which aided charting and other management. In 1953, Ibsen set up what became the world's first [[intensive care unit]] in a converted student nurse classroom in [[Copenhagen Municipal Hospital]], and provided one of the first accounts of the management of tetanus with muscle relaxants and controlled ventilation.<ref name=\"BerthelsenCronqvist2003\">{{cite journal|last1=Berthelsen|first1=P.G.|last2=Cronqvist|first2=M.|title=The first intensive care unit in the world: Copenhagen 1953|journal=Acta Anaesthesiologica Scandinavica|volume=47|issue=10|year=2003|pages=1190\u20131195|issn=0001-5172|doi=10.1046/j.1399-6576.2003.00256.x|pmid=14616314}}</ref> In 1954 Ibsen was elected Head of the Department of Anaesthesiology at that institution. He jointly authored the first known account of intensive care management principles in the journal ''Nordisk Medicin'', with Tone Dahl Kvittingen from Norway. <ref name=\"pmid13600704\">{{cite journal| last1=Ibsen|first1=B|last2=Kvittingen|first2=T.D.|title=Arbejdet p\u00e5 en An\u00e6sthesiologisk Observationsafdeling|trans-title=Work in an Anaesthesiological Observation Unit|language=Danish| journal=Nordisk Medicin | year= 1958 | volume= 60 | issue= 38 | pages= 1349\u201355 | pmid=13600704}} </ref> For a time in the early 1960s, it was not clear that specialized intensive care units were needed, so intensive care resources were brought to the room of the patient that needed the additional monitoring, care, and resources. It became rapidly evident, however, that a fixed location where intensive care resources and dedicated personnel were available provided better care than ''ad hoc'' provision of intensive care services spread throughout a hospital. In 1962, in the University of Pittsburgh, the first Critical Care Residency was established in the United States. In 1970, the [[Society of Critical Care Medicine]] was formed.<ref>history reference: Brazilian Society of Critical Care [http://www.sobrati.com.br SOBRATI] Video:[http://www.medicinaintensiva.com.br/icu-history.htm ICU History] [http://www.medicinaintensiva.com.br/fotos-semana.htm Historical photos]</ref>\n\n== Monitoring ==\n[[Monitoring (medicine)|Monitoring]] refers to various tools and technologies used to obtain information about a patient's condition. These can include tests to evaluate [[Hemodynamics|blood flow]] and gas exchange in the body, or to assess the function of organs such as the heart and lungs. Broadly, there are two common types of monitoring in the ICU: noninvasive and invasive.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite book|title=Civetta, Taylor, & Kirby's critical care|date=2009|publisher=Lippincott Williams & Wilkins|others=Gabrielli, Andrea., Layon, A. Joseph., Yu, Mihae., Civetta, Joseph M., Taylor, Robert W. (Robert Wesley), 1949-, Kirby, Robert R.|isbn=978-0-7817-6869-6|edition=4th|location=Philadelphia|oclc=253189100}}</ref> \n\n=== Noninvasive Monitoring ===\nNoninvasive monitoring does not require puncturing the skin and usually does not cause pain. These tools are more inexpensive, easier to perform, and faster to result<ref name=\":6\" />. \n\n* [[Vital signs]] which includes heart rate, blood pressure, breathing rate, body temperature\n\n* [[Echocardiography|Echocardiogram]] to evaluate the function and structure of the heart\n*[[Electroencephalography|Electroencephalography (EEG)]] to assess electrical activity of the brain \n*[[Electrocardiography|Electrocardiogram]] to detect abnormal heart rhythms, [[Electrolyte imbalance|electrolyte disturbances]], and coronary blood flow\n* [[Pulse oximetry]] for monitoring oxygen levels in the blood\n*[[Impedance cardiography|Thoracic electric bioimpedance]] (TEB) cardiography to monitor fluid status and heart function \n*[[Ultrasound]] to evaluate internal structures including the heart, lungs, gallbladder, liver, kidneys, bladder, and blood vessels\n\n=== Invasive Monitoring ===\nInvasive monitoring generally provides more accurate measurements, but these tests may require blood draws, puncturing the skin, and can be painful or uncomfortable<ref name=\":6\" />.\n\n* [[Arterial line]] to directly monitor blood pressure and obtain [[Arterial blood gas test|arterial blood gas]] measurements\n*[[Venipuncture|Blood draws or venipucture]] to monitor various blood components as well as administer therapeutic treatments \n*[[Intracranial pressure monitoring]] to assess pressures inside the skull and on the brain\n*Intravesicular manometry (bladder pressure) measurements to assess for intra-abdominal pressure\n\n* [[Central venous catheter|Central line]] and [[peripherally inserted central catheter]] (PICC) lines for drug infusions, fluids or [[total parenteral nutrition]]\n\n* [[Bronchoscopy]] to look at lungs and airways and sample fluid within the lungs\n* [[Pulmonary artery catheter]] to monitor the function of the heart, blood volume, and tissue oxygenation\n\n== Procedures and Treatments  ==\nIntensive care usually takes a system-by-system approach to treatment.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|title=Critical care medicine : principles of diagnosis and management in the adult|date=2008|publisher=Mosby Elsevier|others=Parrillo, Joseph E., Dellinger, R. Phillip.|isbn=978-0-323-07095-9|edition=3rd|location=Philadelphia, PA|oclc=324998024}}</ref> In alphabetical order, the nine key systems considered in the intensive care setting are: [[cardiovascular system]], [[central nervous system]], [[endocrine system]], [[gastro-intestinal tract]] (and nutritional condition), [[hematology]], [[integumentary system]], [[microbiology]] (including sepsis status), [[urinary system|renal]] (and metabolic), and [[respiratory system]]. As such, the nine key systems are each considered on an observation-intervention-impression basis to produce a daily plan. [[File:Sondeintubation.jpg|thumb|right|An endotracheal tube]]\n\n==== Cardiovascular ====\n\n*[[Artificial cardiac pacemaker|Temporary cardiac pacing catheters]] for atrial, ventricular, or dual-chamber pacing \n*[[Intra-aortic balloon pump|Intra-aortic balloon pumping]] to stabilize patients with cardiogenic shock \n*[[Ventricular assist device]] to aid in function of the left ventricle, commonly in patients with advanced heart failure\n\n==== Gastro-intestinal Tract ====\n\n* [[Feeding tube]] for artificial nutrition \n* [[Nasogastric intubation]] can be used to deliver artificial nutrition, but can also be used to remove stomach and intestinal contents\n* [[Diagnostic peritoneal lavage|Peritoneal aspiration and lavage]] to sample fluid in the abdominal cavity\n\n==== Renal ====\n\n* [[Hemofiltration]] for [[acute renal failure|acute kidney injury]]\n\n==== Respiratory ====\n\n* [[Mechanical ventilation]] to assist breathing through an [[Tracheal intubation|endotracheal tube]] or [[tracheotomy]]\n* [[Thoracentesis]] or [[Chest tube|tube thoracostomy]] to remove fluid or air in the pleural cavity\n\n=== Drugs ===\nA wide array of [[pharmacology|drugs]] including but not limited to: [[inotrope]]s, [[sedatives]], broad spectrum [[antibiotics]] and [[analgesics]].\n\n== Common Complications in the ICU ==\nIntensive care units are associated with increased risk of various complications that may lengthen a patient's hospitalization<ref name=\":5\" />. Complications in the ICU include:\n\n* [[Acute kidney injury|Acute renal failure]]\n* Catheter-associated blood stream infection\n* [[Catheter-associated urinary tract infection]]\n* [[Delirium]] \n* [[Gastrointestinal bleeding]] \n* [[Pressure ulcer]]\n* [[Venous thrombosis|Venous thromboembolism]] \n* [[Ventilator-associated pneumonia]] \n* [[Barotrauma|Ventilator-induced barotrauma]] \n\n==Training==\nICU care requires more specialized patient care; this need has led to the use of a multidisciplinary team to provide care for patients.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|title=Basics of anesthesia|others=Pardo, Manuel, Jr., 1965-, Miller, Ronald D., 1939-, Preceded by (work): Miller, Ronald D., 1939-|isbn=9780323401159|edition=Seventh|location=Philadelphia, PA|oclc=989157369|date = 26 June 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":6\" /> Staffing between Intensive care units by country, hospital, unit, or institution.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== Medicine ===\nCritical care medicine is an increasingly important medical specialty. [[Physician]]s with training in critical care medicine are referred to as [[intensivist]]s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hfma.org/forums/What_Intensivist.htm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090927021234/http://www.hfma.org/forums/What_Intensivist.htm |title=What \u2013 or Who -- Is an Intensivist? |archivedate=2009-09-27 |publisher=[[Healthcare Financial Management Association]]}}</ref> In the United States, the specialty requires additional fellowship training for physicians having completed their primary residency training in internal medicine, [[pediatrics]], [[anesthesiology]], [[surgery]] or [[emergency medicine]]. US board certification in critical care medicine is available through all five specialty boards.  Intensivists with a primary training in internal medicine sometimes pursue combined fellowship training in another subspecialty such as pulmonary medicine, cardiology, infectious disease, or nephrology.  The American  [[Society of Critical Care Medicine]] is a well-established multiprofessional society for practitioners working in the ICU including nurses, respiratory therapists, and physicians. Most medical research has demonstrated that ICU care provided by intensivists produces better outcomes and more cost-effective care.<ref>\"Association between Critical Care Physician Management and Patient Mortality in the Intensive Care Unit\".  ''[[Annals of Internal Medicine]]''. 3 June 2008. Volume 148, Issue 11. pp. 801\u2013809.</ref> This has led the [[Leapfrog Group]] to make a primary recommendation that all ICU patients be managed or co-managed by a dedicated intensivist who is exclusively responsible for patients in one ICU. \n\nIn Australia, the training in intensive care medicine is through College of Intensive Care Medicine.\n\nIn the UK doctors can only enter intensive care medicine training after completing two foundation years, and core training in either emergency medicine, anaesthetics, acute medicine or core medicine. Most trainees dual train with one of these specialties however it has recently become possible to train purely in intensive care medicine. It has also possible to train in sub-specialties of intensive care medicine including pre-hospital emergency medicine. \n\n=== Nursing ===\nNurses that work in the critical care setting are typically registered nurses.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Principles of critical care|others=Hall, Jesse B.,, Schmidt, Gregory A.,, Kress, John P.|isbn=9780071738811|edition=Fourth|location=New York|oclc=906700899|date = 2 June 2015}}</ref> [[Nurse]]s may pursue additional education and training in critical care medicine leading to certification as a CCRN by the American Association of Critical Care Nurses a standard that was begun in 1975.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=Pediatric critical care|others=Fuhrman, Bradley P.,, Zimmerman, Jerry J.,, Clark, Robert S. B., 1962-, Relvas, Monica S.,, Thompson, Ann E.,, Tobias, Joseph D.|isbn=978-0-323-37839-0|edition=Fifth|location=Philadelphia, PA|oclc=966447977|date=8 December 2016}}</ref> These certifications became more specialized to the patient population in 1997 by the American Association of Critical care Nurses, to include pediatrics, neonatal and adult.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Nurse practitioners and physician assistants ===\n[[Nurse practitioner]]s and [[physician assistant]]s are other types of non-physician providers that care for patients in ICUs.<ref name=\":2\" /> Outcomes have shown that the use of non-physician providers have been shown to have similar outcomes to those with physician providers.<ref name=\":3\" /> These providers have less years of in school training and typically receive further clinical on the job education.<ref name=\":3\" /> Non-physician providers like nurse practitioners and physician assistants are typically present for longer periods of time than [[resident physician]]<nowiki/>s that rotate off service.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== Pharmacists ===\nCritical care [[pharmacists]] work with the medical team in many aspect but some include, monitoring serum concentrations of medication, past medication use, current medication use, and medication allergies.<ref name=\":4\" /> Their typically round with the team but it may differ by institution.<ref name=\":4\" /> Some pharmacist after attaining their doctorate or pharmacy may pursue additional training in a postgraduate residency and become certified as critical care pharmacists.<ref name=\":4\" /> Pharmacists help manage all aspects of drug therapy and may pursue additional credentialing in critical care medicine as BCCCP by the Board of Pharmaceutical Specialties. Many critical care pharmacist are a part of the multi-professional Society of Critical Care Medicine.<ref name=\":4\" /> Inclusion of pharmacist decreases drug reactions and poor outcomes for patients.<ref name=\":2\" /> \n\n=== Paramedics or emergency medical technicians ===\n[[Paramedic]]s are certified to levels of CCEMT-P, PNCCT-P, CCP-C and/or FP-C depending upon their speciality (e.g. air, ground, adult, pediatric and/or neonatal medicine). \n\n=== Registered dietitians ===\nNutrition in intensive care units presents unique challenges due to changes in patient metabolism and physiology while critically ill.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Current surgical therapy|others=Cameron, John L.,, Cameron, Andrew M. (Andrew MacGregor)|isbn=978-0-323-37691-4|edition=12th|location=Philadelphia, PA|oclc=966447396}}</ref> Critical care nutrition is rapidly becoming a subspecialty for [[dietician]]s who can pursue additional training and achieve certification in enteral and parenteral nutrition through the [[American Society for Parenteral and Enteral Nutrition]] (ASPEN).  \n\n=== Respiratory therapists ===\nRespiratory therapists often work in intensive care units to monitor how well a patient is breathing.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Total burn care|others=Herndon, David N.|isbn=978-0-323-49742-8|edition=Fifth|location=Edinburgh|oclc=1012122839|date = 10 October 2017}}</ref> [[Respiratory therapists]] may pursue additional education and training leading to credentialing in adult critical care (ACCS) and neonatal and pediatric (NPS) specialties. These therapists have been trained to monitor a patient's breathing, provide treatments to help their breathing and evaluate for improvement.<ref name=\":0\" /> They may be involved in emergency care like managing an airway, humidification of oxygen, administering diagnostic test, and providing physiotherapy.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Clinician's pocket reference|last=Gomella, Leonard G.|date=2007|publisher=McGraw-Hill Companies, Inc|others=Haist, Steven A., University of Kentucky. College of Medicine.|isbn=978-0-07-145428-5|edition=11th|location=New York|oclc=85841308}}</ref>\n\n== Ethical and medicolegal issues ==\n===Economics===\nIn general, it is the most expensive, technologically advanced and resource-intensive area of medical care. In the [[United States]], estimates of the 2000 expenditure for critical care medicine ranged from US$19\u201355 billion.<!--Is this lower bound given in the full cited article? The abstract suggests it is $55.5bn, which I presume forms the basis for the following figures; perhaps somebody with journal access could check...--> During that year, critical care medicine accounted for 0.56% of [[Gross Domestic Product|GDP]], 4.2% of national health expenditure and about 13% of hospital costs.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Halpern|first1=Neil A.|last2=Pastores|first2=Stephen M.|last3=Greenstein|first3=Robert J.|date=June 2004|title=Critical care medicine in the United States 1985\u20132000: An analysis of bed numbers, use, and costs|journal=[[Critical Care Medicine]]|volume=32|issue=6|pages=1254\u20131259|doi=10.1097/01.CCM.0000128577.31689.4C|pmid=15187502}}<!--|accessdate=7 November 2011 --></ref>\nIn 2011, hospital stays with ICU services accounted for just over one-quarter of all discharges (29.9%) but nearly one-half of aggregate total hospital charges (47.5%) in the [[United States]]. The mean hospital charge was 2.5 times higher for discharges with ICU services than for those without.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hcup-us.ahrq.gov/reports/statbriefs/sb185-Hospital-Intensive-Care-Units-2011.jsp|title=Utilization of Intensive Care Services, 2011|author=Barrett ML|author2=Smith MW|date=December 2014|work=HCUP Statistical Brief #185|publisher=Agency for Healthcare Research and Quality|location=Rockville, MD|author3=Elizhauser A|author4=Honigman LS|author5=Pines JM}}</ref>\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Medicine}}\n* [[Mechanical ventilation]]\n* [[Extracorporeal membrane oxygenation]]\n* [[Telemetry]]\n* [[Chronic critical illness]]\n* [[Critical care nursing]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== References ==\n*[http://www.lww.com/Product/0-7817-3548-3 Intensive Care Medicine by Irwin and Rippe]{{Dead link|date=August 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20151222141626/http://www.lww.com/Product/978-0-7817-6869-6 Civetta, Taylor, and Kirby's Critical Care]\n*[https://shop.lww.com/Marino-s-The-ICU-Book--Print---Ebook-with-Updates/p/9781451121186 The ICU Book by Marino]\n*[http://www.lww.com/Product/0-7817-4334-6 ''Procedures and Techniques in Intensive Care Medicine by Irwin and Rippe'']{{Dead link|date=August 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n*{{cite journal | pmid = 15187502 | doi = 10.1097/01.CCM.0000128577.31689.4C | last1 = Halpern  | name-list-format =vanc | first1 = NA | last2 = Pastores | first2 = SM | last3 = Greenstein | first3 = RJ | title = Critical care medicine in the United States 1985\u20132000: an analysis of bed numbers, use, and costs | journal = [[Critical Care Medicine]]| volume=32 | issue=6 |date=June 2004 | pages=1254\u20139}}.\n*History references:\n**[http://www.sobrati.com.br Brazilian Society of Intensive Care - SOBRATI ]\n**[http://www.medicinaintensiva.com.br/personagens.htm History]\n*[http://www.sccm.org Society of Critical Care Medicine]\n*{{cite journal |first1=H.N. |last1= Reynolds |first2= H.|last2= Rogove |first3= J. |last3= Bander |first4= M. |last4= McCambridge |first5= E. |last5= Cowboy |first6= M. |last6= Niemeier |displayauthors=4 |journal= Telemedicine and E-Health |date= December 2011 |volume= 17|issue= 10 |pages= 773\u2013783 |doi=10.1089/tmj.2011.0045 |pmid= 22029748 |title= A working lexicon for the tele-intensive care unit: We need to define tele-intensive care unit to grow and understand it|hdl= 2027.42/90470 |url= https://deepblue.lib.umich.edu/bitstream/2027.42/90470/1/tmj-2E2011-2E0045.pdf }}\n*{{cite journal |first1=Terrah |last1= Olson |first2= Karen|last2= Brasel |first3= Andrew |last3= Redmann |first4= G. |last4= Alexander |first5= Margaret |last5= Schwarze |journal= JAMA Surgery |date= January 2013 |volume= 148|issue= 1 |pages= 29\u201335 |doi=10.1001/jamasurgery.2013.403 |pmid= 23324837 |title= Surgeon-Reported Conflict With Intensivists About Postoperative Goals of Care|pmc= 3624604 }}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{Cite Q|Q29581786}}.\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Intensive-care medicine}}\n{{Wikibooks |Intensive Care Medicine}}\n* [http://www.cicm.org.au College of Intensive Care Medicine - Australia and New Zealand]\n* [http://www.anzics.com.au Australia and New Zealand Intensive Care Society]\n* [http://www.sccm.org Society of Critical Care Medicine]\n* [http://www.veccs.org Veterinary Emergency And Critical Care Society]\n* [http://www.esicm.org ESICM: European Society of Intensive Care Medicine]\n* [http://espnic-online.org ESPNIC: The society for paediatric and neonatal intensive care healthcare professionals in Europe]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110316113900/http://www.ics.ac.uk/ UK Intensive Care Society]\n* [http://www.scottishintensivecare.org.uk/- Scottish Intensive Care Society]\n* [http://www.hksccm.org Hong Kong Society of Critical Care Medicine]\n* [http://www.csccm.org Chinese Society of Critical Care Medicine]\n* [http://www.tsccm.org.tw/English/eng001.asp Taiwan Society of Critical Care Medicine]\n* [http://richannel.org/from-iron-lungs-to-intensive-care From Iron Lungs to Intensive Care], [[Royal Institution]] debate, February 2012\n\n{{Intensive care medicine}}\n{{Medicine}}\n\n[[Category:Intensive care medicine| ]]\n", "name_user": "Pony55661", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intensive_care_medicine"}
{"title_page": "Buddhi Vardhak Sabha", "text_new": "The '''Buddhi Vardhak Sabha''' (Society for Advancement of Knowledge), also known as the '''Buddhi Vardhak Hindu Sabha''', was a socio-religious reform organization in [[Bombay]], in [[British India]]. It was founded in 1851 by the members of another Bombay reform association, the Jnayan Prasarak Mandali, whose members included Narmadashankar Dave ([[Narmad]]) and his fellow writers. The Jnayan Prasarak Mandali, in turn, was a branch of the Students' Literary and Scientific Society of [[Elphinstone College]].\n\nThe aim and object of the Buddhi Vardhak Sabha was to work for the social welfare of the [[Gujarati people|Gujarati]] [[Hindus|Hindu]] people, and to awaken public opinion for social change through lectures, debates and writings. Other founding members included Pranlal Mathurdas, Mohanlal Ranchhoddas Jhaveri, [[Karsandas Mulji]], and [[Dalpatram]].\n\n==History==\nThe [[Elphinstone College|Elphinstone Institite]] played an instrumental role in providing an intellectual background for the [[reform movement]]s in Western India. In June 1848, the institute's students started the Students' Literary and Scientific Society. In September 1848, two other branches of this society were established, one Gujarati, and the other [[Marathi people|Marathi]]. The Gujarati branch was known as Jnayan Prasarak Mandali (Society for Promotion of Knowledge), and was presided by Ranchhoddas Girdharbhai Jhaveri. Most of the members of this Mandali were [[Parsis|Parsi]] students.<ref name=\"Raval1983\">{{cite thesis|last=Raval|first=R. L.|title=Socio Religious Reform Movements in Gujarat During the Nineteenth Century|chapter=Reform Controversy and New Approach to Cultural Synthesis|year=1983|chapter-url=https://shodhganga.inflibnet.ac.in/bitstream/10603/46633/7/07_chapter%203.pdf|type=PhD thesis|location=Ahmedabad|publisher=School of Social Sciences, [[Gujarat University]]|pages=117\u2013121|hdl=10603/46633|via=[[Shodhganga]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 1850, the young Hindu members of the Jnayan Prasarak Mandali felt that a special organization was necessary to devote more attention to Hindu welfare.<ref name=\"Ray1984\">{{cite book|last=Karmerkar|first=Mani|editor-last=Ray|editor-first=N. R.|title=Public Associations in India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=d9y1AAAAIAAJ|year=1984|publisher=Institute of Historical Studies|location=Calcutta|pages=216\u2013224|chapter=The Buddhi Vardhak Sabha of Bombay \u2014 Its Contribution to Social Change in the Second Half of the Nineteenth Century|oclc=13671846}}</ref> Accordingly, in June 1850, Narmad, with friends including Mayaram Shambhunath, Kalyanji Shivlal, and Narandas Kalyandas, founded the Juvan Purushoni Anyonya Buddhi Vardhak Sabha with the  aim of furthering Hindu discussion of reforms. Narmad was its president.<ref name=\"Raval1983\"/>\n\nOn 23 March 1851, the decision was made to broaden the society's focus, and change its name to Buddhi Vardhak Hindu Sabha. The first meeting was held that same day, and rules adopted. Pranlal Mathurdas was appointed as the first president of the Buddhi Vardhak Hindu Sabha, with Mohanlal Ranchhoddas Jhaveri and Kishorlal respectively as secretary and treasurer.<ref name=\"Raval1983\"/> 70 members enrolled at the inaugural meeting, for a fee of [[Indian rupee|Rs]]. 2 per month. <!---The founder members were Pranlal Mathurdas, Mohanlal Ranchhoddas Jhaveri, [[Karsandas Mulji]], [[Dalpatram]], and Narmadashankar Dave '[[Narmad]]'.---> According to the Sabha's rules, membership was restricted to Hindu people. Others, however, were invited to take part in the discussion.<ref name=\"Raval1983\"/>\n\nOver the next 20 years, the Buddhi Vardhak Hindu Sabha and its members played an important role in the social reform movements of Bombay city and other cities of Gujarat.<ref name=\"Ray1984\"/> The Sabha's status began to decline after 1876, with the gradual demise of its founders.<ref name=\"Ray1984\"/>\n\n==Publication==\nIn 1851, the  Buddhi Vardhak Sabha began publication of a monthly journal, ''Buddhi Vardhak Granth'', of which Narmad assumed the editorship.<ref name=\"Ray1984\"/> The first issue was published in 1851, the second and third issues appearing in 1953. Regular publication began from March 1856. Articles published dealt mainly with social issues.<ref name=\"Raval1983\"/>\n\n==Activities==\nThe main object of the Buddhi Vardhak Sabha was to awaken the social consciousness of Hindu people through debate, talks and writings. Prominent speakers were to be invited, and each meeting devoted to the discussion of a particular problem and consideration of how to solve it.\n\nIn May 1851, the Sabha's  members started Bombay's first schools for Hindu girls, one in the [[Fort (Mumbai precinct)|Fort]] area, and another near [[Bhuleshwar]]. Members of the Sabha, and students of the [[Elphinstone College|Elphinstone Institute]], volunteered to teach in these girls' schools.<ref name=\"Ray1984\"/> The Buddhi Vardhak Sabha offered prizes for the best essays written on topics of social importance.<ref name=\"Raval1983\"/>\n\nThe Sabha's activities were supported by wealthy Gujarati patrons, including [[Mangaldas Nathubhoy|Sheth Mangaldas Nathubhai]], Laxmidas Khimji, and [[Gokuldas Tejpal]], and by [[Marathi people|Maharashtrian]] reformers like [[Dadoba Pandurang]], [[Atmaram Pandurang]], and [[Bhau Daji]].<ref name=\"Raval1983\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1851 in British India]]\n[[Category:1851 establishments in British India]]\n[[Category:Social history of India]]\n[[Category:History of Maharashtra]]\n", "text_old": "The '''Buddhi Vardhak Sabha''' (Society for Advancement of Knowledge), also known as the '''Buddhi Vardhak Hindu Sabha''', was a socio-religious reform organization in [[Bombay]], in [[British India]]. It was founded in 1851 by the members of another Bombay reform association, the Jnayan Prasarak Mandali, whose members included Narmadashankar Dave ([[Narmad]]) and his fellow writers. The Jnayan Prasarak Mandali, in turn, was a branch of the Students' Literary and Scientific Society of [[Elphinstone College]].\n\nThe aim and object of the Buddhi Vardhak Sabha was to work for the social welfare of the [[Gujarati people|Gujarati]] [[Hindus|Hindu]] people, and to awaken public opinion for social change through lectures, debates and writings. Other founding members included Pranlal Mathurdas, Mohanlal Ranchhoddas Jhaveri, [[Karsandas Mulji]], and [[Dalpatram]].\n\n==History==\nThe [[Elphinstone College|Elphinstone Institite]] played an instrumental role in providing an intellectual background for the [[reform movement]]s in Western India. In June 1848, the institute's students started the Students' Literary and Scientific Society. In September 1848, two other branches of this society were established, one Gujarati, and the other [[Marathi people|Marathi]]. The Gujarati branch was known as Jnayan Prasarak Mandali (Society for Promotion of Knowledge), and was presided by Ranchhoddas Girdharbhai Jhaveri. Most of the members of this Mandali were [[Parsis|Parsi]] students.<ref name=\"Raval1983\">{{cite thesis|last=Raval|first=R. L.|title=Socio Religious Reform Movements in Gujarat During the Nineteenth Century|chapter=Reform Controversy and New Approach to Cultural Synthesis|year=1983|chapter-url=https://shodhganga.inflibnet.ac.in/bitstream/10603/46633/7/07_chapter%203.pdf|type=PhD thesis|location=Ahmedabad|publisher=School of Social Sciences, [[Gujarat University]]|pages=117\u2013121|hdl=10603/46633|via=[[Shodhganga]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 1850, the young Hindu members of the Jnayan Prasarak Mandali felt that a special organization was necessary to devote more attention to Hindu welfare.<ref name=\"Ray1984\">{{cite book|last=Karmerkar|first=Mani|editor-last=Ray|editor-first=N. R.|title=Public Associations in India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=d9y1AAAAIAAJ|year=1984|publisher=Institute of Historical Studies|location=Calcutta|pages=216\u2013224|chapter=The Buddhi Vardhak Sabha of Bombay \u2014 Its Contribution to Social Change in the Second Half of the Nineteenth Century|oclc=13671846}}</ref> Accordingly, in June 1850, Narmad, with friends including Mayaram Shambhunath, Kalyanji Shivlal, and Narandas Kalyandas, founded the Juvan Purushoni Anyonya Buddhi Vardhak Sabha with the  aim of furthering Hindu discussion of reforms. Narmad was its president.<ref name=\"Raval1983\"/>\n\nOn 23 March 1851, the decision was made to broaden the society's focus, and change its name to Buddhi Vardhak Hindu Sabha. The first meeting was held that same day, and rules adopted. Pranlal Mathurdas was appointed as the first president of the Buddhi Vardhak Hindu Sabha, with Mohanlal Ranchhoddas Jhaveri and Kishorlal respectively as secretary and treasurer.<ref name=\"Raval1983\"/> 70 members enrolled at the inaugural meeting, for a fee of [[Indian rupee|Rs]]. 2 per month. <!---The founder members were Pranlal Mathurdas, Mohanlal Ranchhoddas Jhaveri, [[Karsandas Mulji]], [[Dalpatram]], and Narmadashankar Dave '[[Narmad]]'.---> According to the Sabha's rules, membership was restricted only to the Hindu people. Others, however, were invited to take part in the discussion.<ref name=\"Raval1983\"/>\n\nOver the next 20 years, the Buddhi Vardhak Hindu Sabha and its members played an important role in the social reform movements of Bombay city and other cities of Gujarat.<ref name=\"Ray1984\"/> The Sabha's status began to decline after 1876, with the gradual demise of its founders.<ref name=\"Ray1984\"/>\n\n==Publication==\nIn 1851, the  Buddhi Vardhak Sabha began publication of a monthly journal, ''Buddhi Vardhak Granth'', of which Narmad assumed the editorship.<ref name=\"Ray1984\"/> The first issue was published in 1851, the second and third issues appearing in 1953. Regular publication began from March 1856. Articles published dealt mainly with social issues.<ref name=\"Raval1983\"/>\n\n==Activities==\nThe main object of the Buddhi Vardhak Sabha was to awaken the social consciousness of Hindu people through debate, talks and writings. Prominent speakers were to be invited, and each meeting devoted to the discussion of a particular problem and consideration of how to solve it.\n\nIn May 1851, the Sabha's  members started Bombay's first schools for Hindu girls, one in the [[Fort (Mumbai precinct)|Fort]] area, and another near [[Bhuleshwar]]. Members of the Sabha, and students of the [[Elphinstone College|Elphinstone Institute]], volunteered to teach in these girls' schools.<ref name=\"Ray1984\"/> The Buddhi Vardhak Sabha offered prizes for the best essays written on topics of social importance.<ref name=\"Raval1983\"/>\n\nThe Sabha's activities were supported by wealthy Gujarati patrons, including [[Mangaldas Nathubhoy|Sheth Mangaldas Nathubhai]], Laxmidas Khimji, and [[Gokuldas Tejpal]], and by [[Marathi people|Maharashtrian]] reformers like [[Dadoba Pandurang]], [[Atmaram Pandurang]], and [[Bhau Daji]].<ref name=\"Raval1983\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1851 in British India]]\n[[Category:1851 establishments in British India]]\n[[Category:Social history of India]]\n[[Category:History of Maharashtra]]\n", "name_user": "FiveFaintFootprints", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:ce - expression", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Buddhi_Vardhak_Sabha"}
{"title_page": "Derrick Rose", "text_new": "{{Redirect|D Rose|the song by Lil Pump|Lil Pump (album)}}\n{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| image = Rose-20190120 (cropped).jpg\n| caption = Rose with the [[Minnesota Timberwolves]] in 2019\n| alt = Hip length view of man raising the basketball to shoot free throw, with black moustache, beard, and short dreadlocks, thin white headband, wearing navy blue Timberwolves uniform\n| image_size =\n| position = [[Point guard]]\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 2\n| weight_lb = 200\n| league = [[NBA]]\n| team = Detroit Pistons\n| number = 25\n| nationality = American\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1988|10|4}}\n| birth_place = [[Chicago|Chicago, Illinois]]\n| high_school = [[Simeon Career Academy]]<br />(Chicago, Illinois)\n| college = [[Memphis Tigers men's basketball|Memphis]] (2007\u20132008)\n| draft_year = 2008\n| draft_round = 1\n| draft_pick = 1\n| draft_team = [[Chicago Bulls]]\n| career_start = 2008\n| career_end = \n| years1 = {{nbay|2008|start}}\u2013{{nbay|2015|end}}\n| team1 = [[Chicago Bulls]]\n| years2 = {{nbay|2016|full=y}}\n| team2 = [[New York Knicks]]\n| years3 = {{nbay|2017|full=y}}\n| team3 = [[Cleveland Cavaliers]]\n| years4 = {{nbay|2017|end}}\u2013{{nbay|2018|end}}\n| team4 = [[Minnesota Timberwolves]]\n| years5 = {{nbay|2019|start}}\u2013present\n| team5 = [[Detroit Pistons]]\n| highlights =\n* [[NBA Most Valuable Player Award|NBA Most Valuable Player]] ({{nbay|2010|end}})\n* 3\u00d7 [[NBA All-Star]] ({{nasg|2010}}\u2013{{nasg|2012}})\n* [[All-NBA First Team]] ({{nbay|2010|end}})\n* [[NBA Rookie of the Year Award|NBA Rookie of the Year]] ({{nbay|2008|end}})\n*[[NBA All-Rookie First Team]] ({{nbay|2008|end}})\n* Third-team [[NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|All-American]] \u2013 [[Associated Press|AP]], [[National Association of Basketball Coaches|NABC]] ([[2008 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|2008]])\n* [[McDonald's All-American Game|McDonald's All-American]] ([[2007 McDonald's All-American Boys Game|2007]])\n* First-team [[Parade All-America Boys Basketball Team|''Parade'' All-American]] (2007)\n* Third-team ''Parade'' All-American (2005)\n* Fourth-team ''Parade'' All-American (2006)\n* [[Illinois Mr. Basketball]] (2007)\n| nba_profile  = derrick_rose\n| bbr  =  rosede01\n| medal_templates =\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[basketball]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{flagu|United States}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIBA Basketball World Cup|World Championship/World Cup]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2010 FIBA World Championship|2010 Turkey]] | [[2010 United States men's FIBA World Championship team|Team]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2014 FIBA Basketball World Cup|2014 Spain]] | [[2014 United States FIBA Basketball World Cup team|Team]]}}\n}}\n'''Derrick Martell Rose''' (born October 4, 1988) is an American professional [[basketball]] player for the [[Detroit Pistons]] of the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA). He played one year of college basketball for the [[Memphis Tigers men's basketball|Memphis Tigers]] before being drafted [[List of first overall NBA draft picks|first overall]] by his hometown [[Chicago Bulls]] in the [[2008 NBA draft]].<ref name=\"Drafted 1st\">{{cite web |publisher=ESPN  |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/draft2008/news/story?id=3462594 |title=Bulls go with native Chicagoan Rose over Beasley |accessdate=June 26, 2008}}</ref> He was named the [[NBA Rookie of the Year]] and also became the youngest player to win the [[NBA Most Valuable Player Award]] in 2011 at age 22.\n\nRose was born and raised in Chicago, and attended [[Simeon Career Academy]]. He was highly recruited by colleges, eventually choosing to join the [[University of Memphis]] under coach [[John Calipari]]. Rose led the Tigers to the most wins in NCAA history (a 38\u20132 record), their first number 1 ranking in 25 years, and an appearance in the NCAA championship game. In 2009, an NCAA investigation  revealed that Rose's SAT scores had been invalidated, and as a result, the NCAA vacated Memphis' entire 2007\u201308 season.<ref name = \"vacate\">{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/college/mensbasketball/2009-08-20-memphis-ncaa-penalties_N.htm|title=NCAA vacates Memphis' '07\u201308 season record, Final Four run|work=USA Today|accessdate=August 20, 2009|date=August 19, 2009|last=Garci|first=Marlen}}</ref>\n\nRose has struggled with significant knee injuries since his [[2010\u201311 NBA season|2010\u201311]] MVP campaign. In the first round of the [[2012 NBA Playoffs]] against the [[Philadelphia 76ers]], Rose tore his [[Anterior cruciate ligament injury|ACL]] in his left knee. Rose required surgery and was subsequently sidelined for the entire [[2012\u201313 NBA season|2012\u201313 season]].<ref name=andrews>{{cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/chicago/nba/story/_/id/8074004/chicago-bulls-derrick-rose-getting-knee-examined-dr-james-andrews |title=Chicago Bulls Derrick Rose getting knee examined by Dr. James Andrews |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=June 20, 2012}}</ref> Rose returned to play in [[2013\u201314 NBA season|2013\u201314]]. However, on November 22, 2013, during a regular season game against the [[Portland Trail Blazers]], Rose injured his right meniscus which caused him to miss the remainder of the season.<ref name=tribune>{{cite web |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2013-11-25/sports/chi-derrick-rose-surgery-20131124_1_derrick-rose-tom-thibodeau-chicago-bulls |title=Bulls' Rose is likely out for season |work=ChicagoTribune.com |date=November 25, 2013 |accessdate=November 6, 2015}}</ref> Rose returned once again the [[2014\u201315 NBA season|following season]], but knee injuries continued to riddle him, causing him to miss 30 games. In June 2016, he was traded to the [[New York Knicks]]. After one season with the Knicks, Rose joined the [[Cleveland Cavaliers]] in July 2017, but was traded and subsequently released by the [[Utah Jazz]] the following February. In March 2018, he signed with the [[Minnesota Timberwolves]].\n\n==Early life==\nRose was born and raised in the [[Englewood, Chicago|Englewood]] area, one of the most dangerous neighborhoods on [[South Side, Chicago|Chicago's South Side]].<ref name=Englewood>{{cite web|last1=Jensen|first1=Sean|title=Derrick Rose keeps tough Englewood area close to his heart|url=http://www.suntimes.com/sports/basketball/5365750-419/derrick-rose-stays-connected-to-tough-englewood-neighborhood.html|website=Chicago Sun-Times|accessdate=August 4, 2014|date=May 14, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808055234/http://www.suntimes.com/sports/basketball/5365750-419/derrick-rose-stays-connected-to-tough-englewood-neighborhood.html|archive-date=August 8, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> He is  the youngest son of Brenda Rose after Dwayne, Reggie, and Allan. All three were talented basketball players who taught Rose the in and outs of basketball on nearby courts.<ref name=Englewood/><ref name=si>{{cite web|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1114058/index.htm|title=The Well-guarded Guard|publisher=}}</ref>  As his talent for the sport grew, Rose began to attract much more outside attention in Chicago's basketball circles, leading his mother and brothers to restrict outside contact to him. She feared he would be exploited and his path to the NBA diverted by outside parties like street agents, similar to what happened to former Chicago prospect [[Ronnie Fields]].<ref name=\"06sipiece\">{{cite news |url=http://www.sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2006/highschool/11/20/hs.rose1127/1.html |title=The Well-Guarded Guard |author=George Dohrmann |work=Sports Illustrated |date=November 21, 2006 |accessdate=December 26, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090123224700/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2006/highschool/11/20/hs.rose1127/1.html |archive-date=January 23, 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==High school career==\nBy the time Rose enrolled at [[Simeon Career Academy]] in 2003, he was a hot commodity for collegiate coaches. Despite his reputation, he played freshmen and JV basketball for the Wolverines. He wore No. 25 in honor of [[Ben Wilson (basketball)|Ben \"Benji\" Wilson]], a promising player who was murdered by a gang member during his senior year in 1984.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sports.espn.go.com/espn/page2/story?page=jackson/080701&sportCat=nba |title=Spirit of former Chicago high school star lives on in Rose |author=Scoop Jackson |work=ESPN.com |date=July 1, 2008 |accessdate=January 29, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090219222433/http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/page2/story?page=jackson%2F080701&sportCat=nba |archive-date=February 19, 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Rose was not allowed on varsity due to a long-standing tradition that head coach Bob Hambric, who had been with the school since 1980 had no freshmen on the varsity team. That rule did not lessen Rose's play, and he went on to put up 18.5 [[Point (basketball)|points]], 6.6 [[Assist (basketball)|assist]]s, 4.7 [[Rebound (basketball)|rebound]]s and 2.1 [[Steal (basketball)|steal]]s per game and led both the freshmen and sophomores to city championships with a 24\u20131 record.<ref name=\"Bulls.com Draft Profile\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/bulls/news/derrick_rose.html |title=2008 NBA Draft Player Profile : : Derrick Rose |work=Bulls.com |accessdate=December 10, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111217234316/http://www.nba.com/bulls/news/derrick_rose.html |archive-date=December 17, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Hambric softened his stance and allowed the freshman a chance to play on varsity in the state tournament, but Rose declined, wanting the players to get due credit.<ref name=\"Sophomore Scout Article\">{{cite web |url=http://preps.scout.com/2/493015.html |title=Believe The Hype |author=Jon Mahoney |work=Scout |date=January 25, 2005 |accessdate=December 27, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081229202544/http://preps.scout.com/2/493015.html |archive-date=December 29, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The next year Hambric retired and Robert Smith was hired, opening the path to varsity. In Rose's debut, he had 22 points, 7 rebounds and 5 steals over [[Thornwood High School]] in a sold-out game filled with college scouts and coaches.<ref name=\"1st Varsity Game\">{{cite news |url=http://yourseason.suntimes.com/1026724,062608rosedebut.article |title=Flashback: Rose's debut |author=Michael O'Brien |work=Chicago Sun-Times |date=June 30, 2008 |accessdate=December 27, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081229202331/http://yourseason.suntimes.com/1026724,062608rosedebut.article |archive-date=December 29, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He led the Wolverines to a 30\u20135 mark while averaging 19.8 points, 5.1 rebounds, 8.3 assists and 2.4 steals but the season ended after a loss in state regionals. Rose's play garnered him his first national award: a [[Parade All-America Boys Basketball Team|''Parade'' All-American]] third team spot.<ref name=\"2005 3rd parade\">{{cite web |url=http://www.parade.com/articles/editions/2005/edition_04-03-2005/featured_2 |title=Meet PARADE's All-America... Team |accessdate=January 1, 2008 |author=Michael O'Shea |work=Parade.com |date=April 3, 2005}}</ref>\n\nDuring Rose's junior year in 2006, the Simeon Wolverines broke through and won the [[Chicago Public High School League|Chicago Public League]] championship held at the [[United Center]], where Rose starred with 25 points and crowd pleasing dunks. The team advanced through the playoffs and earned a berth in the Class AA state championship against [[Richwoods High School]], where a fourth quarter [[buzzer beater]] by Richwood forced overtime. The score was knotted at 29 late in the extra period when Rose stole the ball and buried the game winning jumper as time expired, giving Simeon its first state title since the Wilson-led Wolverines won in 1984. The team finished 33\u20134 and ranked nationally,<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2006/highschool/04/07/hoops.rankings2/ |title=Final Top 25 Poll |author=Jon Mahoney |work=Sports Illustrated |date=April 6, 2006 |accessdate=March 29, 2009}}</ref> and Rose was awarded with an All-State Illinois mention, [[EA Sports]] All-American Second Team pick<ref name=\"2006 EA Sports 2nd Team\">{{cite web |work=Rivals.com |url=http://ssbasketball.rivals.com/content.asp?SID=1132&CID=537673 |title=2006 EA SPORTS Boys All American Team |accessdate=December 25, 2008}}</ref> and another ''Parade'' All-American selection.<ref name=\"2006 4th parade\">{{cite magazine |work=Parade Magazine |url=http://all-americans.parade.com/2006_boy_basketball/2006_boys_basketball.html |title=All-America Teams |accessdate=December 25, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090212130829/http://all-americans.parade.com/2006_boy_basketball/2006_boys_basketball.html |archivedate=February 12, 2009  }}</ref>\n\nEntering his senior year, Rose was ranked the fifth best prospect in the nation by ''[[Sports Illustrated]]''. In January 2007, Simeon traveled to [[Madison Square Garden]] to play [[Rice High School (New York)|Rice High School]] and star guard [[Kemba Walker]].<ref>{{cite news |work=USA Today |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/preps/basketball/2007-01-11-rose-new-york_x.htm|title=Chicago standout Rose takes stage in New York|author=Christopher Lawlor |date=January 11, 2007 |accessdate=December 28, 2009}}</ref> The Wolverines lost 53\u201351.<ref>{{cite news |work=USA Today |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/preps/basketball/2007-01-15-weekend-roundup_x.htm|title=N.Y.'s Rice topples No. 14 Simeon 53\u201351 despite Rose's 22|author=Christopher Lawlor |date=January 15, 2007 |accessdate=December 28, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2007/highschool/01/15/derrick.rose/ |title=Garden Party|author=Kevin Armstrong |work=Sports Illustrated |date=January 15, 2007 |accessdate=February 8, 2009}}</ref> The season's highlight was a nationally televised contest on [[ESPN]] against [[Virginia]] perennial power [[Oak Hill Academy (Virginia)|Oak Hill Academy]] two weeks later. Matched up with hyped junior guard [[Brandon Jennings]], Rose had 28 points, 9 assists, and 8 rebounds and in a 78\u201375 win.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=Draft Express\n|url=http://www.draftexpress.com/article/Chicago-Simeon-vs.-Oak-Hill-Academy-Breakdown/ |title=Chicago Simeon vs. Oak Hill Academy Breakdown |author=Rodger Bohn and Mike Schmidt |date=January 24, 2007 |accessdate=February 1, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |work=Sports Illustrated |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2007/highschool/01/19/simeon.upset/ |title=Chicago Simeon vs. Oak Hill Academy Breakdown |author=Jon Mahoney |date=January 19, 2007 |accessdate=February 15, 2009}}</ref> For his performance, ''[[USA Today]]'' named him their high school player of the week.<ref>{{cite news |work=USA Today\n|url=http://blogs.usatoday.com/preprally/2007/01/teams_shuffle_p.html |title=Teams shuffle positions in newest Super 25 |author=Various |date=January 25, 2007 |accessdate=February 8, 2009}}</ref> Simeon went on to repeat as Public League champions<ref>{{cite web |work=Chicago Reader |url=http://www.chicagoreader.com/features/stories/sports/070302/ |title=Reaching the Heights |author=Ted Cox |date=March 2, 2007 |accessdate=February 8, 2009 }}{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and defended their state championship, defeating [[O'Fallon Township High School|O'Fallon High School]] 77\u201354.<ref>{{cite web |work=Illinois HS Basketball.com |url=http://illinoishsbasketball.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=465&Itemid=1 |title=2007\u2013 March 17- Simeon Wins State |author=Daniel Poneman |date=March 17, 2007 |accessdate=February 8, 2009}}</ref> In doing so, Simeon became the first Chicago Public League school to win two straight state championships. In his final high school game, Rose scored 2 points, but pulled down 7 rebounds and totaled 8 assists, while Simeon big man Tim Flowers scored 35 points.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2007-03-18/sports/0703180114_1_simeon-rose-wound-repeat|title=Simply The Best|publisher=}}</ref> The Wolverines ended the season 33\u20132 and ranked first in the nation by ''Sports Illustrated''<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2007/highschool/03/20/top25.rankings/index.html |title=Simeon wins Illinois state title, takes top ranking |author=Jon Mahoney |work=Sports Illustrated |date=March 20, 2007 |accessdate=February 8, 2009}}</ref> and 6th on ''USA Today''{{'s}} Super 25.<ref>{{cite news |work=USA Today |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/preps/basketball/poll/super25.htm |title=Super 25: Virginia's Oak Hill Academy finishes on top |author=Super 25: Virginia's Oak Hill Academy finishes on top |date=March 27, 2007 |accessdate=February 8, 2009}}</ref> Rose averaged 25.2 points, 9.1 assists, 8.8 rebounds and 3.4 steals.\n\nOverall, Simeon's record while Rose played was 120\u201312.<ref name=\"Bulls.com Draft Profile\" /> After his senior year, Rose was again All-State after being named [[Illinois Mr. Basketball]]<ref name=\"2007 Mr Basketball\">{{cite news |url=http://archives.chicagotribune.com/2007/mar/31/sports/chi-0703310340mar31 |title=Mr. Basketball of Illinois, 2007: Derrick Rose |author=Bob Sakamoto |work= Chicago Tribune |date=June 26, 2008 |accessdate=June 27, 2008}}</ref> and was named to the [[McDonald's All-American]] team.<ref name=\"2007 McDonald's All-American\">{{cite web\n|url=http://mcdonaldsallamerican.com/stats/2007boys_roster.pdf |title=2007 McDonald's All American High School Basketball Team |publisher=McDonald's All American |accessdate=December 15, 2008 |format=PDF}}</ref> He was also awarded with First Team honors by ''Parade'' selection and ''USA Today''<ref name=\"2007 1st Parade\">{{cite web |publisher=PARADE Magazine\n|url=http://www.parade.com/articles/editions/2007/edition_04-01-2007/Basketball |title=Meet PARADE's 2007 All-America High School Boys Basketball Team |author=Michael O'Shea |date=March 23, 2007 |accessdate=December 15, 2008}}</ref> and ''USA Today'' First Team All-American.\n\nRose was selected to play in the Jordan Brand All-Star Game and [[Nike Hoop Summit]]. In 2009, Rose was named the decade's third greatest high school point guard by ''[[ESPN RISE]]'' magazine behind [[Chris Paul]] and [[T.J. Ford]],<ref>{{cite web|title=ESPN Big names make cut for all-decade team|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/highschool/rise/basketball/boys/news/story?id=3903359|last=Canner-O'Mealy|first=Ryan|last2=Mahoney|first2=Jon|publisher=[[ESPN]], Inc.|date=April 9, 2009|work=[[ESPN RISE]]|accessdate=August 19, 2009 }}</ref> and had his jersey number (#25) retired along with Ben Wilson.<ref>{{cite web|title=Simeon Career Academy retires No. 25 worn by Ben Wilson and Derrick Rose|url=http://www.nba.com/bulls/news/rose_simeon_091114.html|work=www.chicagobulls.com|date=November 11, 2009|accessdate=April 27, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==College career==\n[[File:Derrick-Rose-2008-Final-Four-UCLA.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Rose while playing at the [[University of Memphis]]]]\nRose accepted a scholarship to play for the [[University of Memphis]] [[Memphis Tigers men's basketball|Tigers]] under [[John Calipari]], who recruited him after seeing him play in an [[Amateur Athletic Union|AAU]] game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/draft2008/columns/story?id=3452587 |title=Rose 'chases greatness' with a passion for winning |author=Andy Katz |work=ESPN.com |date=June 30, 2008 |accessdate=January 28, 2009}}</ref> Strong efforts were made by [[Indiana Hoosiers men's basketball|Indiana University]] and in-state [[Illinois Fighting Illini men's basketball|University of Illinois]] to sign Rose to their own programs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.suntimes.com/preps/2006/10/which_school_will_derrick_rose.html |title=Which school will Derrick Rose choose on Saturday? |author=Michael O'Brien |work=Chicago Sun-Times] |date=October 31, 2007 |accessdate=January 22, 2009}}</ref> Illinois in particular planned to pair Rose and their five-star recruit [[Eric Gordon]], who had played AAU basketball with Rose.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.ljworld.com/news/2006/jul/07/keegan_chicagoan_targeted_self/?sports |title=Keegan: Chicagoan targeted by Self |accessdate=January 1, 2008}}</ref> Gordon, however, retracted his verbal commitment from the Fighting Illini, opting to play for Indiana, and Rose subsequently gave his verbal commitment before the start of his senior season.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/recruiting/basketball/national/2006-11-06-basketball.htm |title=Rose commitment highlights busy week |author=Jerry Meyer |work= USA Today |date=November 7, 2007 |accessdate=January 22, 2009}}</ref> Rose chose Memphis because of the school's history of putting players in the NBA and the prospect of [[Rod Strickland]], a 17-year veteran of the league, mentoring him. Rose switched to #23, due to the fact that #25 had been retired by the school in honor of [[Penny Hardaway]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gotigersgo.cstv.com/genrel/082108aac.html |title=Penny Hardaway Sets Record With Assist To Tiger Athletics |work=Memphis Tigers Official Athletic Site |date=August 21, 2008 |accessdate=February 8, 2009}}</ref>\n\nWith the addition of Rose and led by veteran upperclassmen [[Joey Dorsey]] and [[Chris Douglas-Roberts]], the Tigers started out [[2007\u201308 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|the season]] ranked third in the nation. Memphis sprinted to a 26\u20130 start and claimed the number one ranking in the country for the first time in over 25 years before falling to the [[University of Tennessee]] [[Tennessee Volunteers basketball|Volunteers]] 66\u201362 in February.<ref>{{cite news |work=ESPN.com |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=280540235 |title=No. 2 Tennessee likely next No. 1 as Memphis leaves with close loss |agency=Associated Press |date=February 23, 2008 |accessdate=January 22, 2009}}</ref> Memphis was able to bounce back and capture the [[2008 Conference USA Men's Basketball Tournament|Conference USA Tournament]] to qualify for the \"[[2008 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|Big Dance]]\" with a 33\u20131 record.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.commercialappeal.com/news/2008/mar/16/tigers-no-1-seed-ncaa-mens-basketball-tournament/ |title=Tigers earn second No. 1 seed in two seasons |author=Dan Wolken |work=Commercial Appeal |date=March 16, 2008 |accessdate=January 29, 2009}}</ref> Rose averaged 14.9 points per game, 4.7 assists and 4.5 rebounds per game during the regular season and earned [[2008 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|All-American Third Team honors]] among others.<ref name=\"3rd Team All-American\">{{cite web |url=http://www.goduke.com/ViewArticle.dbml?SPSID=22724&SPID=1845&DB_OEM_ID=4200&ATCLID=1434246 |title=Nelson Named NABC Third Team All-American |author=Duke Sports Information |work=Go Duke |date=April 6, 2008 |accessdate=June 27, 2008}}</ref> He finished as a finalist for the [[Bob Cousy Award]] as well as the [[John R. Wooden Award]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://gotigersgo.cstv.com/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/031008aaf.html |title=Douglas-Roberts, Rose Named Wooden Award Finalists |work=Memphis Tigers |date=March 10, 2008 |accessdate=January 29, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080515194538/http://gotigersgo.cstv.com/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/031008aaf.html |archive-date=May 15, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nMemphis was seeded No. 1 in the South Region. Rose earned high praise for his increased focus on defense, hounding [[University of Texas|Texas Longhorn]] guard [[D. J. Augustin]] into a low-percentage game in the Elite Eight.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/college/mensbasketball/finalfour/2008-04-01-rose-memphis_N.htm |title=Freshman Rose blooming at the right time for Memphis |author=Steve Wieberg |work=USA Today |date=April 2, 2008 |accessdate=January 23, 2009}}</ref> In a match-up against [[University of California-Los Angeles|UCLA]] in the Final Four, Rose finished with 25 points and 9 rebounds to lead the Tigers to an 85\u201367 win and a trip to the NCAA championship game against the [[University of Kansas|Kansas]] [[Kansas Jayhawks men's basketball|Jayhawks]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/college/2008/04/05/2008-04-05_derrick_rose_puts_on_dazzling_show_leads.html |title=Derrick Rose puts on dazzling show, leads Memphis past UCLA, 78\u201363 |author=Roger Rubin |work=New York Daily News |date=April 5, 2008 |accessdate=February 26, 2012}}</ref> The win set a NCAA mark for most wins in a season (38).<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2008-04-05/sports/17896067_1_darren-collison-ucla-college-basketball |title=Memphis' Derrick Rose would look great planted at the Garden |work=New York Daily News |date=April 5, 2008 |accessdate=February 26, 2012}}</ref> [[2008 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament#National Championship Game|Against Kansas]], Rose scored 17 points on 7\u2013of\u201317 shooting, along with six rebounds and seven assists, but missed a critical free throw at the end of the second half as Memphis fell in overtime, 75\u201368.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=284000063 |title=After 20-year drought, Kansas rallies to beat Memphis for NCAA title |agency=Associated Press |work=ESPN.com |date=April 7, 2007 |accessdate=June 26, 2008}}</ref> Memphis concluded the season 38\u20132. Rose was named to the All-Final Four team after averaging 20.8 points, 6.5 rebounds and 6.0 assists per game.<ref name=\"allffteam\">{{cite web |url=http://gotigersgo.cstv.com/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/040808aaf.html |title=NCAA All-Tournament Team, Tournament Leaders |accessdate=January 29, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080922184208/http://gotigersgo.cstv.com/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/040808aaf.html |archive-date=September 22, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nOn April 15, Rose announced he would forgo his final three seasons at Memphis and declared for the [[2008 NBA draft]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/draft2008/news/story?id=3347737 |title=Memphis freshman Rose says he's leaving, will enter NBA draft |work=ESPN.com |date=April 15, 2008 |accessdate=January 29, 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Grading controversy===\nAccording to Sheri Lipman of the University of Memphis legal counsel, a month after the loss to Kansas, the NCAA sent a letter to the school stating that Rose had \"an invalidated standardized test score the previous year at Chicago's Simeon High School.\" The next January, the NCAA sent another letter, charging Memphis with knowing that Rose had someone else take his SAT for him.<ref>\n{{cite web|url=http://www.commercialappeal.com/news/2009/may/27/ncaa-alleges-major-violations-memphis-basketball-p/|title=NCAA alleges major violations in Memphis basketball program under John Calipari : GoMemphisTigers : Your leading source for The University of Memphis Tigers |work=Commercial Appeal |accessdate=August 20, 2009|date=May 28, 2009|last=Wolken|first=Dan}}</ref> Memphis started its own investigation and sent its response back on April 24.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/news/story?id=4213427|title=Memphis works to resolve dispute|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=August 20, 2009|date=May 29, 2009|last=Katz|first=Andy}}</ref>\n\nOn May 28, 2009, the ''[[Memphis Commercial Appeal]]'' obtained the letter through the [[Freedom of Information Act (United States)|Freedom of Information Act]] and released it. Although the player's name was redacted due to privacy laws, [[process of elimination]], and sources revealed the player as Derrick Rose. The next day, in a separate investigation, James Sullivan, Inspector General of the Chicago Public Schools district's Board of Education, released a report of his investigation stating that four student-athletes of a CPS school had one-month grade boosts to alter their college transcripts.<ref name = \"CST grade\">{{cite news|url=http://www.suntimes.com/news/education/1596666,derrick-rose-simeon-grades-cheat-memphis.article|title=Derrick Rose's grade was changed at Simeon High|work=Chicago Sun-Times|accessdate=August 20, 2009|last= Rossi|first= Rosalina|first2= Michael |last2= O'Brien|date=May 28, 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090530202010/http://www.suntimes.com/news/education/1596666,derrick-rose-simeon-grades-cheat-memphis.article|archivedate=May 30, 2009}}</ref> The ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' revealed the school as Simeon Career Academy and that three of the four were Rose and his former teammates Kevin Johnson and Tim Flowers, prominent members of the back-to-back championship teams.<ref name = \"CST grade\"/> The newspaper claimed that Rose's grade was changed from a D to a C.<ref name = \"CST grade\"/> Another part of the report stated that \"high school staff lost the original permanent records for three of the above mentioned students athletes\" (including the unknown four).<ref name = \"CST grade 2\">{{cite web|url=http://csnchicago.com/pages/landing?IHSA-Looks-at-Simeon-Grade-Change-Revela=1&blockID=56385&feedID=629|title=IHSA Looks at Simeon Grade-Change Revelation|work=Chicago Sun-Times|accessdate=August 20, 2009|date=May 28, 2008|first=Michael|last=O'Brien|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090907023303/http://csnchicago.com/pages/landing?IHSA-Looks-at-Simeon-Grade-Change-Revela=1&blockID=56385&feedID=629|archive-date=September 7, 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref> Sullivan started the investigation because \"none of the grade changes were supported by any documentation.\" He also failed to find a suspect as \"at least seven people at Simeon had the ability to access student grades and records.\"<ref name = \"CST grade\"/> [[Illinois High School Association]] (IHSA) executive director Marty Hickman reacted by saying, \"It is obvious that this is worth taking a look into.\"<ref name = \"CST grade 2\"/> Robert Smith, who coached the Wolverines from 2004 to 2007, denied any wrongdoing.<ref name = \"CST grade\"/> District spokeswoman Monique Bond said the students involved probably did not know about the grade change.\n\nAllegations surfaced that Rose's brother, Reggie, had been allowed to travel with the team for free on several occasions.<ref>O'Neil, Dana. [http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/news/story?id=4412279 Memphis also gets 3 years' probation]. [[ESPN]], August 21, 2009.</ref>\n\nMemphis contended that it had learned of the allegations about Rose's SAT score shortly after he enrolled at the school. It conducted its own investigation, in which Rose was questioned by four school officials. Ultimately, Memphis was unable to find any evidence that Rose had cheated based on what was available at the time and cleared him to play.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.commercialappeal.com/news/2009/aug/20/memphis-tigers-found-guilty-ncaa-must-forfeit-2007/|title=Memphis Tigers found guilty by NCAA; must vacate 2007\u201308 basketball season, will appeal \u00bb<!-- Bot generated title -->|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nRose released a statement through his lawyer Daniel E. Reidy: \"Mr. Rose is aware of the allegations reported in the press. Mr. Rose cooperated fully with the University of Memphis' athletic and legal departments\u2019 investigation of this issue when he was a student, and that investigation uncovered no wrongdoing on his part.\"\n\nOn August 20, 2009, the NCAA vacated Memphis' 2007\u201308 season. It took the position that because the [[Educational Testing Service]] voided Rose's [[SAT Reasoning Test|SAT]] score after Rose's freshman year at Memphis, [[strict liability]] required that Rose be retroactively declared ineligible.<ref name=probation>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/news/story?id=4412279|title=NCAA: Memphis must vacate all 2007-08 wins|date=August 20, 2009|website=ESPN.com}}</ref> It also determined that even without the questions about his test score, Rose would have lost his eligibility in December 2007 due to Reggie Rose being allowed to travel for free.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web1.ncaa.org/LSDBi/exec/miSearch?miSearchSubmit=publicReport&key=672&publicTerms=THIS%20PHRASE%20WILL%20NOT%20BE%20REPEATED|title=University of Memphis public infractions report|date=August 20, 2009|publisher=NCAA|accessdate=May 17, 2014|quote=In addition to issues surrounding the academic eligibility of [Derrick Rose], the investigation also revealed that [Rose]'s brother (\"the brother\") had received impermissible benefits in the form of cost-free airline transportation and lodging while traveling with the institution's men's basketball team to road games during the 2007\u201308 season....the violations involving [Rose]'s brother would also have rendered [Rose] ineligible, beginning in mid-December 2007.|pages=1, 15}}</ref>\n\nOn May 28, 2010, Rose, former Memphis basketball coach [[John Calipari]], and Memphis athletic director R.C. Johnson reached a $100,000 [[settlement (litigation)|out-of-court settlement]] with three attorneys who represented Memphis season ticket holders and threatened a lawsuit over the vacated 2007\u201308 season. The Memphis ''[[The Commercial Appeal|Commercial Appeal]]'' first reported on this settlement in October 2011.<ref>{{cite web|author=Veazey, Kyle|url=http://www.commercialappeal.com/news/2011/oct/06/deal-put-price-tag-memphis-tiger-disgrace/|title=Threat of lawsuit brings bonus repayment from John Calipari, R.C. Johnson, donation from Derrick Rose|work=Memphis Commercial Appeal|date=October 7, 2011|accessdate=May 16, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\n\n===Chicago Bulls (2008\u20132016)===\n\n====2008\u201309: Rookie of the Year====\n[[Image:Derrick Rose 02.jpg|thumb|left|Derrick Rose during his rookie season]]\nRose was selected with the first overall pick in the 2008 draft by the [[Chicago Bulls]].<ref name=\"Drafted 1st\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Bulls to pick first in draft; Heat, Wolves round out Top 3|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/draft2008/news/story?id=3405648|agency=Associated Press|publisher=ESPN|date=May 21, 2008|accessdate=January 22, 2009}}</ref> He was selected to the U.S. Select Team to scrimmage against and prepare the [[United States men's national basketball team|National Team]] for the Olympics in Beijing.<ref>{{cite news|title=Select-ive service good for Bulls' Rose, U.S.|url=http://www.suntimes.com/sports/derrickrose/1060547,CST-SPT-bull17.stng|author=Clyde Travis and John Jackson|work=Chicago Sun-Times|date=July 17, 2008|accessdate=February 1, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081204183749/http://www.suntimes.com/sports/derrickrose/1060547,CST-SPT-bull17.stng|archive-date=December 4, 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Hefty praise for Rose|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Basketball/NBA/2009/01/24/8133921-sun.html|author=Mike Ganter|website=slam.canoe.ca|publisher=SLAM! Sports|date=January 24, 2009|accessdate=February 1, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Bulls' Rose learns on the go|url=http://www.suntimes.com/sports/derrickrose/1072443,CST-SPT-1psep24.article|author=Clyde Travis|work=Chicago Sun-Times|date=July 24, 2008|accessdate=February 1, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080727041031/http://www.suntimes.com/sports/derrickrose/1072443,CST-SPT-1psep24.article|archive-date=July 27, 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> In mid-July, he played two games in the [[Orlando Pro Summer League]] until forced out by tendinitis in his right knee, ending his summer,<ref>{{cite news|title=Bulls top pick Rose out with injury|url=http://www.nwherald.com/articles/2008/07/14/sports/nba/bulls/doc4875766d0549b639551119.txt|agency=Associated Press|work=Northwest Herald|date=July 14, 2007|accessdate=July 14, 2008}}{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> but returned in October to play all eight preseason games.<ref>{{cite news|author=Marty Burns|title=Ahead of schedule? No. 1 pick Rose already turning heads with Bulls|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2008/writers/marty_burns/10/27/rose.bulls/index.html|work=Sports Illustrated|date=October 27, 2007|accessdate=February 14, 2006}}</ref>\n\nRose became the first Bulls draftee to score 10 points or more in his first 10 games since [[Michael Jordan]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Early bloomer: Rose already a quiet leader for young Bulls|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/basketball/nba/bulls/2008-12-15-rose-cover_N.htm|author=Mike Dodd|work=USA Today|date=December 15, 2008|accessdate=December 22, 2008}}</ref> and earned Eastern Conference [[NBA Rookie of the Month Award|Rookie of the Month]] honors for November and December.<ref name=\"Nov.08 RoM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnetwork.com/merge/tsnform.aspx?c=sportsnetwork&page=nba/news/news.aspx?id=4195033|title=Rose, Mayo earn NBA rookie honors|author=Information|publisher=Sports Network|date=December 1, 2008|accessdate=December 1, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110622082758/http://www.sportsnetwork.com/merge/tsnform.aspx?c=sportsnetwork&page=nba%2Fnews%2Fnews.aspx%3Fid%3D4195033|archive-date=June 22, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"Dec.08 RoM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/2009/news/01/02/010209rom.release/index.html|title=Bulls' Rose, Thunder's Westbrook named Rookies of the Month|author=NBA Press Release|publisher=NBA|date=January 2, 2009|accessdate=January 3, 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090115124954/http://www.nba.com/2009/news/01/02/010209rom.release/index.html|archivedate=January 15, 2009}}</ref> During [[2009 NBA All-Star Game|the All-Star Weekend]], Rose played in the [[NBA All-Star Weekend Rookie Challenge|Rookie Challenge]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Rose, Mayo top list on Rookie Challenge rosters|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/basketball/nba/bulls/2008-12-15-rose-cover_N.htm|last=Dodd|first=Mike|work=USA Today|date=January 28, 2009|accessdate=November 10, 2009}}</ref> and won the [[NBA All-Star Weekend Skills Challenge|Skills Challenge]], where he beat out several All-Stars to become the first rookie to claim the trophy.<ref name=\"Skills Challenge Victory\">{{cite news|author=John Jacksons|title=Rose shows off mad skills|url=http://www.suntimes.com/sports/basketball/1432070,CST-SPT-skills15.article|work=Chicago Sun-Times|date=February 15, 2009|accessdate=March 14, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090218130327/http://www.suntimes.com/sports/basketball/1432070,CST-SPT-skills15.article|archive-date=February 18, 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref> Overcoming a January and February slump, Rose returned to form and won monthly rookie honors in March. Meanwhile, the Bulls, re-energized by the trade deadline acquisitions of [[John Salmons]] and [[Brad Miller (basketball)|Brad Miller]], finished the regular season on a 12\u20134 spurt to qualify as the seventh seed in the Eastern Conference. Rose won [[NBA Rookie of the Year Award|Rookie of the Year]], joining [[Michael Jordan]] (1985) and [[Elton Brand]] (2000) as the only Bulls to do so.<ref name=\"Rookie of the Year\">{{cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/basketball/bulls/chi-090423-derrick-rose-chicago-bulls-rookie-year,0,4035550.story|title=Chicago Bulls' Derrick Rose named NBA Rookie of the Year|date=April 22, 2009|work=Chicago Tribune|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090423071248/http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/basketball/bulls/chi-090423-derrick-rose-chicago-bulls-rookie-year,0,4035550.story|archivedate=April 23, 2009|access-date=April 22, 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref> He was also the first number-one draft pick since LeBron James to win the award. He averaged 16.8 points on 47.5% field goal shooting, 6.3 assists (leading all rookies) and 3.9 rebounds per game and was also named to the [[NBA All-Rookie First Team]].<ref name=\"All-Rookie Team\">{{cite web|title=Bulls' Derrick Rose a unanimous selection to the 2008\u201309 NBA All-Rookie First Team|url=http://www.nba.com/bulls/news/rose_rookieteam_090430.html|work=Chicago Tribune|date=April 30, 2009|accessdate=May 3, 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090506044213/http://www.nba.com/bulls/news/rose_rookieteam_090430.html|archivedate=May 6, 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn his playoff debut against the defending champion [[Boston Celtics]], Rose recorded 36 points (tying [[Kareem Abdul-Jabbar]]'s NBA record for points scored by a rookie in his playoff debut, set in [[1970 NBA Playoffs|1970]]), 11 assists, and 4 rebounds as the Bulls prevailed in a 105\u2013103 overtime win on the road.<ref>{{cite news|author=Chris Mannix|title=Rose, Rondo put on Game 1 show|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/writers/chris_mannix/04/18/bulls.celtics.game.1/index.html|work=Sports Illustrated|date=April 18, 2009 |accessdate=November 10, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Rose testing Celtics' ailing defense|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/writers/chris_mannix/04/20/celtics.bulls.preview/index.html|author=Chris Mannix|work=Sports Illustrated|date=April 20, 2009|accessdate=November 10, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/writers/steve_aschburner/04/18/day1.analysis/index.html|title=Rose testing Celtics' ailing defense|author=Steve Aschburner|work=Sports Illustrated|date=April 20, 2009|accessdate=November 10, 2009}}</ref> Rose became the second player in NBA history to record 35 points and 10 assists in his playoff debut, after [[Chris Paul]]. Rose averaged 19.7 points on 47.5% shooting, 6.3 assists and 4.9 rebounds per game in his first playoff series, as the Bulls were defeated by the Celtics in seven games.<ref>nba.com, [http://www.nba.com/playerfile/derrick_rose/career_stats.html Derrick Rose Career Stats Page] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120530005556/http://www.nba.com/playerfile/derrick_rose/career_stats.html |date=May 30, 2012 }}, accessed October 29, 2009.</ref>\n\n====2009\u201311: All-Star season and MVP campaign====\nRose's sophomore season started off with an ankle injury in his first preseason game. Rose would go on to miss the rest of the preseason. Rose started the Bulls' season opener against the [[San Antonio Spurs]] but played limited minutes. Rose's ankle bothered him for most of November, but as his ankle healed, his game improved. On January 28, 2010, Rose was elected to his first career [[2010 NBA All-Star Game|All-Star Game]] as a reserve for the Eastern Conference, making him the first Bulls player to be selected since [[Michael Jordan]] in 1998.<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/chicago/nba/news/story?id=4867386 Bulls' Rose selected to All-Star team], accessed January 28, 2010.</ref> Rose ended up with eight points, four assists and three steals in the game. On April 13, 2010, Rose scored 39 points against the Celtics, making 15\u201322 field goals and 9\u201310 free throws. The Bulls once again made the playoffs in the 2009\u201310 season, finishing with a 41\u201341 record. In the playoffs Rose averaged 26.8 points and 7.2 assists, but the Bulls lost in five games to the [[Cleveland Cavaliers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/playerfile/derrick_rose/index.html|title=Official NBA bio of Derrick Rose - NBA.com|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:Derrick Rose 2.jpg|thumb|right|Rose led the Bulls to 62 wins, and the best record overall, during the 2010\u201311 NBA season.]]\nOn October 30, 2010, in the Bulls' second game of the season, Rose scored 39 points in a 101\u201391 win against the [[Detroit Pistons]]. Two days after, Rose contributed 13 assists, helping [[Luol Deng]] score a career high 40 points in a win against the [[Portland Trail Blazers]]. On December 10, Rose scored 29 points and had 9 assists, leading the Bulls to their first victory over the [[Los Angeles Lakers]] since December 19, 2006.\n\nOn January 17, 2011, Rose recorded his first career [[triple-double]] with 22 points, 10 rebounds and 12 assists in a 96\u201384 win over the [[Memphis Grizzlies]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/games/20110117/CHIMEM/gameinfo.html|title=Bulls at Grizzlies|publisher=}}</ref> On January 27, he was announced as a starting guard on the [[2011 NBA All-Star Game|2011 NBA All-Star Team]] for the East squad.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/allstar/2011/|title=NBA.com - 2011 All-Star Events|website=www.nba.com|access-date=January 28, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110221215029/http://www.nba.com/allstar/2011/|archive-date=February 21, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn February 17, in the Bulls' last game before the All-Star break, Rose set a career-high with 42 points, while also recording 8 assists and 5 rebounds, as the Bulls beat the [[San Antonio Spurs]] 109\u201399. On March 26, Rose had a career high 17 assists, along with 30 points, in a 95\u201387 victory over the [[Milwaukee Bucks]].\n\nAt the end of the [[2010\u201311 NBA season]] the Bulls finished with a league leading record of 62\u201320.<ref>{{cite news|title=NBA Standings&nbsp;\u2013 2010\u201311|url=http://espn.go.com/nba/standings/_/year/2011/seasontype/2|newspaper=ESPN}}</ref> Their 60+ wins was the Bulls' first such season since [[1997\u201398 NBA season|1997\u201398]] and sixth 60+ win in franchise history.<ref>{{cite news|title=Chicago Bulls Power Rankings&nbsp;\u2013 2010\u201311|url=http://espn.go.com/nba/standings/_/year/2011/seasontype/2|newspaper=ESPN}}</ref> At season's end, Rose became only the third player since the [[1972\u201373 NBA season]] to record 2,000 points and 600 assists in a single season. The other two players were [[LeBron James]] and [[Michael Jordan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/654658-derrick-rose-the-surprisingly-historic-numbers-of-his-mvp-seeason|title=Derrick Rose: The Surprisingly Historic Numbers of His MVP Season|first=Kelly|last=Scaletta|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nOn May 3, Rose was named the [[NBA Most Valuable Player]], joining [[Michael Jordan]] as the only players to receive the award in Chicago Bulls history.<ref name=\"NBA.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/2011/news/05/03/mvp-award/index.html?ls=iref:nbahpt1|title=Chicago's Derrick Rose Wins 2010\u201311 Kia NBA MVP Award|publisher=NBA.com|accessdate=May 3, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110505081553/http://www.nba.com/2011/news/05/03/mvp-award/index.html?ls=iref%3Anbahpt1|archivedate=May 5, 2011}}</ref> At 22 years and 6 months old, Rose also became the youngest player to receive the award ([[Wes Unseld]], formerly the youngest MVP, won the award in 1968\u201369 at age 23 years, 2 months).\n\nIn the 2011 NBA Playoffs, the Bulls defeated the [[2010\u201311 Indiana Pacers season|Indiana Pacers]] and [[2010\u201311 Atlanta Hawks season|Atlanta Hawks]] in the first two rounds. In the Eastern Conference Finals, the Bulls faced the [[2010\u201311 Miami Heat season|Miami Heat]], led by [[LeBron James]], [[Dwyane Wade]] and [[Chris Bosh]]. The Bulls lost the series in five games. During the 2011 playoffs, Rose averaged 27.1 points per game, but only shot 39% from the field and 24% for three-pointers.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chicago Bulls-Miami Heat recap|url=http://espn.go.com/nba/recap/_/id/310306014/chicago-bulls-vs-miami-heat}}</ref>\n\n====2011\u201312: ACL tear====\nIn December 2011, Rose signed a five-year contract extension with the Bulls for $94.8 million. The contract was 30&nbsp;percent of the Bulls' salary cap, the maximum allowed under a rule dubbed the \"[[Derrick Rose Rule]]\" from the 2011 [[NBA Collective Bargaining Agreement]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Source: New deal for Derrick Rose |date=December 21, 2011 |work=ESPNChicago.com |url=http://espn.go.com/chicago/nba/story/_/id/7374147/source-chicago-bulls-derrick-rose-agrees-five-year-extension |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/64YlYlGVi?url=http://espn.go.com/chicago/nba/story/_/id/7374147/source-chicago-bulls-derrick-rose-agrees-five-year-extension |archivedate=January 9, 2012 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\nRose was voted as an All-Star Game starter for the second consecutive year. He was the second leading vote getter behind Orlando Magic center [[Dwight Howard]]. He averaged 21.8 ppg, along with a career high 7.9 apg in 35.3 mpg, but played a career low 39 games due to injuries. He helped [[Luol Deng]] become an All-Star for the first time in his career.\n\nDuring Game 1 of the first round of the [[2012 NBA Playoffs|playoffs]] against the [[2011\u201312 Philadelphia 76ers season|Philadelphia 76ers]], Rose injured his left knee while trying to jump. He was immediately helped off the court. The injury occurred when the Bulls were leading by 12 points with 1:22 left to play. Rose came up just short of a triple-double, finishing with 23 points, 9 assists, and 9 rebounds in 37 minutes of action.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://sports.espn.go.com/chicago/nba/news/story?id=7868184|title=Tom Thibodeau defends decision|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|accessdate=April 28, 2012|date=April 28, 2012|first=Roman |last=Modrowski}}</ref> An [[Magnetic resonance imaging|MRI]] later revealed that Rose tore the [[Anterior cruciate ligament|ACL]] in his left knee and would miss the rest of the playoffs.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://espn.go.com/chicago/nba/story/_/id/7866701/2012-nba-playoffs-chicago-bulls-derrick-rose-suffers-torn-acl-philadelphia-76ers|title=Bulls' Derrick Rose tears ACL|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|accessdate=April 28, 2012|date=April 28, 2012|first=Scott|last=Powers}}</ref> Rose had surgery performed on May 12, 2012, with an estimated recovery period of 8\u201312 months.<ref name=\"andrews\" />\n\n====2012\u201313: Year absence====\nRose returned to full contact practice in January 2013,<ref name=\"Return to full contact\">{{cite news|url=http://espn.go.com/chicago/nba/story/_/id/8897736/derrick-rose-chicago-bulls-taking-full-contact-practice|title=Derrick Rose taking full contact|last=Friedell|first=Nick|date=January 31, 2013|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=February 9, 2013}}</ref> and was cleared by doctor to play that March,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://espn.go.com/chicago/nba/story/_/id/9031045/derrick-rose-chicago-bulls-cleared-play-waiting-dunk-confidently-left-foot-source-says|title=Source: Derrick Rose cleared to play|last=Isaacson|first=Melissa|date=March 9, 2013|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=November 25, 2013}}</ref> but he did not appear in a game during the [[2012\u201313 NBA season]]. Despite Rose's absence, the Bulls advanced to the Eastern Conference Semifinals, where they lost to the eventual champions, the [[2012\u201313 Miami Heat season|Miami Heat]].\n\n====2013\u201314: Return and torn meniscus====\nRose's much awaited return came on October 5, 2013, in a pre-season game against the [[2013\u201314 Indiana Pacers season|Indiana Pacers]]. He had a slow start but scored his first point in the first quarter. He finished the game with 13 points in 20 minutes of play.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/chicago/nba/story/_/id/9778651/derrick-rose-returns-chicago-bulls-first-knee-injury|title=Derrick Rose agrressive in return|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|accessdate=October 6, 2013|date=October 5, 2013|first=Nick|last=Friedell}}</ref> On October 16, 2013, Rose returned to play in Chicago for the first time, scoring 22 points against the [[2013\u201314 Detroit Pistons season|Detroit Pistons]]. \"I think I'm way more explosive now. Like getting to the rim. I think I can take contact a little bit better. And as far as jumping-wise, I think I can jump even higher. They tested my vertical -- I increased it by 5 inches\", Rose said after the win.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/chicago/nba/story/_/id/9837096/derrick-rose-says-way-more-explosive-following-recovery|title=Derrick Rose: I'm more explosive now|date=October 17, 2013|accessdate=November 23, 2013|work=ESPN.com|first=Nick|last=Friedell}}</ref> During the pre-season, Rose averaged 20.7 points and 5 assists.\n\nHis first official game was in 107\u201395 loss against the defending champions [[2013\u201314 Miami Heat season|Miami Heat]] on October 29. Rose was limited to 12 points, while having 4 assists in 34 minutes of play. He played his usual minutes, but was inefficient from the field, shooting 4\u201315.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=400488875|title=Heat get championship rings, spoil Derrick Rose's return|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|accessdate=October 29, 2013|date=October 29, 2013|first=Nick|last=Friedell}}</ref> Two days later, he played his first official home game against the [[2013\u201314 New York Knicks season|New York Knicks]] where he hit the game-winning floater in an 82\u201381 win. He had 18 points, 6 rebounds and 3 assists.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=400488891|title=Derrick Rose's floater lifts Bulls over Knicks in home opener|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|accessdate=October 31, 2013|date=October 31, 2013|first=Jon|last=Greenburg}}</ref> On November 3, 2013, Rose scored 13 points and committed 8 turnovers in the loss against the [[2013\u201314 Philadelphia 76ers season|Philadelphia 76ers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=400488907|title=Sixers (3-0) stun Bulls to continue surprising start to season|date=November 3, 2013|accessdate=November 23, 2013|work=ESPN.com}}</ref> He struggled in his return, shooting 28.8% from the field and averaging 5.7 turnovers in his first three games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/basketball/bulls/chi-derrick-rose-chicago-bulls-turnovers-20131103,0,5091853.story|title=Bulls' Rose unfazed by his slow start|date=November 3, 2013|accessdate=November 23, 2013|work=Chicago Tribune|first=K. C. |last=Johnson}}</ref>\n\nOn November 22, Rose injured his right knee during a game against the [[2013\u201314 Portland Trail Blazers season|Portland Trail Blazers]]. An MRI the next day confirmed that Rose tore his right knee meniscus and that surgery was required.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/chicago/nba/story/_/id/10025640/derrick-rose-chicago-bulls-indefinitely-needs-surgery-torn-medial-meniscus-knee|title=Derrick Rose out indefinitely|work=ESPN.com|accessdate=November 23, 2013|date=November 23, 2013}}</ref> At the time, Rose was averaging 15.9 points and 4.3 assists in 31.1 minutes per game. On November 25, Rose underwent surgery on the torn meniscus in his right knee.<ref name=\"tribune\" /> The same day, the Bulls announced Rose was out for the season, after a successful surgery.<ref>K.C. Johnson, [http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/basketball/bulls/chi-derrick-rose-knee-surgery-bulls-20131125,0,7186905.story \"Bulls' Derrick Rose out for season after knee surgery\"], ''Chicago Tribune'', November 25, 2013.</ref>\n\n====2014\u201315: Back to the playoffs====\n[[File:Derrick Rose during a timeout.jpg|thumbnail|Rose during a timeout in 2015]]\nRose returned from injury to play in the Bulls' season opener against the New York Knicks on October 29, 2014 and recorded 13 points and 5 assists in 21 minutes of action. He went on to score a season-high 32 points on January 14 against the Washington Wizards,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=400578871|title=Wizards vs. Bulls - Game Recap - January 14, 2015 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com}}</ref> before being ruled out again with another knee injury a month later. He appeared in 51 games, the most he'd played since the 2010\u201311 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/r/rosede01/gamelog/2015/|title=Derrick Rose 2014-15 Game Log - Basketball-Reference.com|website=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref>\n\nOn February 24, it was announced Rose required another round of surgery on his right knee and was ruled out indefinitely. An exam and subsequent MRI confirmed a medial meniscus tear of the right knee, the same injury he sustained on November 22, 2013 against the Portland Trail Blazers.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cohen|first1=Jay|title=Bulls' Rose to have surgery on torn meniscus|url=http://www.nba.com/2015/news/02/24/bulls-rose-meniscus-knee-surgery-wire.ap/index.html|work=NBA.com|date=February 24, 2015|accessdate=February 25, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Derrick Rose to have knee repaired|url=http://espn.go.com/chicago/nba/story/_/id/12378016/chicago-bulls-guard-derrick-rose-undergo-surgery-repair-torn-meniscus-table-uncertain|work=ESPN.com|date=February 25, 2015|accessdate=February 25, 2015}}</ref> On February 27, he was deemed a possibility of returning toward the end of the season after he underwent successful surgery and was ruled out for just four to six weeks.<ref>{{cite news|last=Johnson|first=K. C.|title=Bulls expect Derrick Rose back this season after successful surgery|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/basketball/bulls/chi-derrick-rose-knee-surgery-update-20150227-story.html|date=February 27, 2015|accessdate=February 27, 2015|work=ChicagoTribune.com}}</ref>\n\nRose returned to action on April 8 after a 20-game absence, and working on a minutes restriction, he was 3-of-9 from the field and finished with nine points in 19 minutes as the Bulls lost to the Orlando Magic.<ref>{{cite news|title=Magic, Oladipo spoil Rose's return in 105-103 win over Bulls|url=http://www.nba.com/games/20150408/CHIORL/gameinfo.html|date=April 8, 2015|accessdate=April 9, 2015|work=NBA.com}}</ref>\n\nOn April 18, Rose played in his first playoff game since Game 1 of the 2012 playoffs (the game where he tore his left ACL). Rose finished with 23 points and 7 assists on 9-of-16 shooting.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rose scores 23, Bulls beat Bucks 103-91|url=http://www.nba.com/games/20150418/MILCHI/gameinfo.html|work=NBA.com|date=April 18, 2015|accessdate=May 9, 2015}}</ref> During the Bulls' first round series against the Bucks, Rose averaged 21.5 points per game. On May 8, Rose banked in a three-pointer at the buzzer and scored 30 points to give the Bulls a 99-96 victory over the Cleveland Cavaliers and a 2-1 lead in the Eastern Conference semi-finals.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rose banks in 3 at buzzer to lift Bulls over Cavaliers 99-96|url=http://www.nba.com/games/20150508/CLECHI/gameinfo.html|work=NBA.com|date=May 9, 2015|accessdate=May 9, 2015}}</ref> However, the Cavaliers won the final three games to take the series in six games.\n\n====2015\u201316: Final season with the Bulls====\nA preseason left orbital bone fracture saw Rose begin the regular season wearing a face mask.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/bulls/news/derrick-rose-injury-update-0|title=Derrick Rose injury update - Chicago Bulls|publisher=}}</ref> On November 5, 2015, Rose scored a then season-high 29 points on 12-of-25 shooting in a 104\u201398 win over the Oklahoma City Thunder. He showed signs of his old MVP self as he scored 10 points over the final three and a half minutes to lift the Bulls after they blew a 10-point lead in the fourth quarter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/games/20151105/OKCCHI/gameinfo.html|title=Thunder vs Bulls|publisher=|access-date=November 6, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160330131313/http://www.nba.com/games/20151105/OKCCHI/gameinfo.html|archive-date=March 30, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> On December 18, he scored a season-high 34 points in a 147\u2013144 quadruple overtime loss to the Detroit Pistons.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/games/20151218/DETCHI/gameinfo.html|title=Drummond leads way, Pistons beat Bulls 147-144 in 4 OT|work=NBA.com|date=December 18, 2015|accessdate=December 18, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151220053332/http://www.nba.com/games/20151218/DETCHI/gameinfo.html|archive-date=December 20, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> On February 5, 2016, he had a season-best game with 30 points, 9 rebounds and 8 assists in a 115\u2013110 loss to the Denver Nuggets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/games/20160205/CHIDEN/gameinfo.html|title=Nuggets rally for win after Bulls lose Butler to injury|work=NBA.com|date=February 5, 2016|accessdate=February 5, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160401182618/http://www.nba.com/games/20160205/CHIDEN/gameinfo.html|archive-date=April 1, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===New York Knicks (2016\u20132017)===\n[[File:Kyrie Irving (30602635845).jpg|thumb|Rose defending [[Kyrie Irving]] in 2016]]\nOn June 22, 2016, Rose was traded, along with [[Justin Holiday]] and a 2017 second-round draft pick, to the [[New York Knicks]] in exchange for future teammate [[Jos\u00e9 Calder\u00f3n (basketball)|Jos\u00e9 Calder\u00f3n]], [[Jerian Grant]] and [[Robin Lopez]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/knicks/knicks-acquire-derrick-rose|title=Knicks Acquire Derrick Rose|work=NBA.com|date=June 22, 2016|accessdate=June 22, 2016}}</ref> He made his debut for the Knicks in the team's season opener on October 25 against the [[Cleveland Cavaliers]]. In 29 minutes of action, he scored 17 points on 7-of-17 shooting in a 117\u201388 loss.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400899375|title=James has triple-double as Cavs rout Knicks 117-88 in opener|work=ESPN.com|date=October 25, 2016|accessdate=October 25, 2016}}</ref> On November 4, Rose returned to Chicago for the first time as a member of the Knicks, recording 15 points and 11 assists in a 117\u2013104 win over the Bulls.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400899523|title=Knicks rally past Bulls 117-104 in Rose, Noah homecoming|work=ESPN.com|date=November 4, 2016|accessdate=November 5, 2016}}</ref> On November 17, he scored a season-high 27 points in a 119\u2013112 loss to the [[Washington Wizards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbssports.com/fantasy/basketball/news/knicks-derrick-rose-sets-season-high-with-27-points/|title=Knicks' Derrick Rose: Sets season high with 27 points|work=cbssports.com|date=November 17, 2016|accessdate=November 18, 2016}}</ref> He topped that mark on November 28, scoring 30 points in a 112\u2013103 loss to the [[Oklahoma City Thunder]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400899705|title=Westbrook with another triple-double as Thunder stop Knicks|work=ESPN.com|date=November 28, 2016|accessdate=November 29, 2016}}</ref> On January 10, 2017, Rose was fined an undisclosed amount after he reportedly flew to Chicago to be with his mother but did not notify team officials ahead of their game against the [[New Orleans Pelicans]] on January 9.<ref>{{cite web|last=Begley|first=Ian|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/18445112/new-york-knicks-derrick-rose-returns-team-going-awol|title=Derrick Rose: Missed Knicks game to tend to Chicago family issue|work=ESPN.com|date=January 10, 2017|accessdate=January 10, 2017}}</ref> Eight days later, he matched his season high with 30 points in a 117\u2013106 win over the [[Boston Celtics]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400900051|title=Rose powers slumping Knicks past Celtics 117-106|work=ESPN.com|date=January 18, 2017|accessdate=January 19, 2017}}</ref> On April 2, 2017, he was ruled out for the rest of the season after tearing the meniscus in his left knee, necessitating a fourth round of knee surgery for Rose in his nine-year career.<ref>{{cite web|last=Carbaugh|first=Dane|url=http://nba.nbcsports.com/2017/04/02/report-knicks-g-derrick-rose-tears-meniscus-in-knee-will-miss-rest-of-the-season/|title=Report: Knicks G Derrick Rose tears meniscus in knee, will miss rest of the season|work=NBCSports.com|date=April 2, 2017|accessdate=April 2, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Cleveland Cavaliers (2017\u20132018)===\n[[File:Derrick Rose (37670935991) (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|Rose with the Cavaliers in 2017]]\nOn July 25, 2017, Rose signed with the [[Cleveland Cavaliers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/cavaliers/releases/rose-signing-2017|title=Cavaliers Sign Derrick Rose|work=NBA.com|date=July 25, 2017|accessdate=July 25, 2017}}</ref> In his debut for the Cavaliers in their season opener against the [[Boston Celtics]] on October 17, 2017, Rose scored 14 points in a 102\u201399 win.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400974437|title=Hayward breaks ankle, Cavs hold off Celtics 102-99 in opener|work=ESPN.com|date=October 17, 2017|accessdate=October 17, 2017}}</ref> On November 24, 2017, Rose left the team to re-evaluate his future in the NBA. His increasing frustration with injuries caused him to question his desire to continue playing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/21540075/derrick-rose-away-cleveland-cavaliers-evaluating-future-nba|title=Derrick Rose away from Cavs, evaluating future in NBA|work=ESPN.com|date=November 24, 2017|accessdate=November 25, 2017}}</ref> He returned to working with the Cavaliers' medical staff in early December in hopes of recovering from a sprained left ankle and bone spurs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/article/2018/01/17/cleveland-cavaliers-derrick-rose-thinks-he-will-play-thursday-vs-orlando-magic#/|title=Derrick Rose thinks he will be OK to play Thursday vs. Orlando Magic|work=NBA.com|date=January 17, 2018|accessdate=January 18, 2018}}</ref> On January 18, 2018, Rose returned to the line-up after missing more than two months with ankle injuries and scored nine points in 13 minutes in a 104\u2013103 win over the [[Orlando Magic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400975410|title=Cavaliers blow big lead, hang on to beat Magic 104-103|work=ESPN.com|date=January 18, 2018|accessdate=January 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn February 8, 2018, Rose was acquired by the [[Utah Jazz]] in a three-team trade that also involved the Cavaliers and the [[Sacramento Kings]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/jazz/news/jazz-acquire-jae-crowder-and-derrick-rose-three-team-trade|title=Jazz Acquire Jae Crowder and Derrick Rose in Three-Team Trade|work=NBA.com|date=February 8, 2018|accessdate=February 8, 2018}}</ref> Two days later, he was waived by the Jazz.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/jazz/news/jazz-waive-derrick-rose|title=Jazz Waive Derrick Rose|work=NBA.com|date=February 10, 2018|accessdate=February 10, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Minnesota Timberwolves (2018\u20132019)===\nOn March 8, 2018, Rose signed with the [[Minnesota Timberwolves]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/timberwolves/timberwolves-sign-derrick-rose|title=TIMBERWOLVES SIGN DERRICK ROSE|work=NBA.com|date=March 8, 2018|accessdate=March 8, 2018}}</ref> reuniting him with [[Tom Thibodeau]], [[Jimmy Butler]] and [[Taj Gibson]]. In the playoffs, Rose averaged 14.2 points in 23.8 minutes per game, as the Timberwolves lost 4\u20131 to the [[Houston Rockets]] in the first round.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/r/rosede01/gamelog/2018/|title=Derrick Rose 2017-18 Game Log|work=Basketball-Reference.com|accessdate=May 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn July 4, 2018, Rose re-signed with the Timberwolves for the [[2018\u201319 Minnesota Timberwolves season|2018\u201319 season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nba.com/timberwolves/news/timberwolves-sign-derrick-rose|title=TIMBERWOLVES SIGN DERRICK ROSE|work=NBA.com|date=July 4, 2018|accessdate=July 4, 2018}}</ref> On October 31, in his first start of the season, Rose scored a career-high 50 points in a 128\u2013125 win over the [[Utah Jazz]], securing the victory with a block on Utah's final shot as time expired.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401070788|title=Rose scores career-high 50 as Timberwolves top Jazz 128-125|work=ESPN.com|date=October 31, 2018|accessdate=October 31, 2018}}</ref> On December 26, he had 24 points and eight assists and received MVP chants in a 119\u201394 win over the Bulls in Chicago. It was just his second career game in the [[United Center]] against his former team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401071183|title=Rose returns to Chicago, leads T-Wolves over Bulls 119-94|work=ESPN.com|date=December 26, 2018|accessdate=December 27, 2018}}</ref> On January 15 against the [[Philadelphia 76ers]], Rose reached 10,000 career points.<ref>{{cite web|last=Andrews|first=Julian|url=https://www.nba.com/timberwolves/news/derrick-rose-reaches-10000-point-milestone-0|title=DERRICK ROSE REACHES 10,000-POINT MILESTONE|work=NBA.com|date=January 15, 2019|accessdate=January 20, 2019}}</ref> On January 20, he scored 29 of his 31 points in the second half and hit an 18-footer with 0.6 seconds left to give the Timberwolves a 116\u2013114 victory over the [[Phoenix Suns]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401071365|title=Rose hits last-second, Timberwolves beat Suns 116-114|work=ESPN.com|date=January 20, 2019|accessdate=January 20, 2019}}</ref> Right ankle trouble saw Rose miss 11 of 19 games spanning late December to late January.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401071456|title=Jokic's triple-double helps Nuggets beat Wolves 107-106|work=ESPN.com|date=February 2, 2019|accessdate=February 2, 2019}}</ref> He missed an additional three games in early February.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401071518|title=Healthy Rose, Teague lead Timberwolves past Clippers 130-120|work=ESPN.com|date=February 11, 2019|accessdate=February 12, 2019}}</ref> On March 21, he was ruled out for the rest of the season with a right elbow injury.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nba.com/timberwolves/news/minnesota-timberwolves-medical-updates|title=MINNESOTA TIMBERWOLVES MEDICAL UPDATES|work=NBA.com|date=March 21, 2019|accessdate=March 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Detroit Pistons (2019\u2013present)===\nOn July 7, 2019, Rose signed with the [[Detroit Pistons]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nba.com/pistons/news/detroit-pistons-sign-free-agent-derrick-rose|title=Detroit Pistons Sign Free Agent Derrick Rose|work=NBA.com|date=July 7, 2019|accessdate=July 7, 2019}}</ref>  Rose became the first player in Pistons\u2019 history to record seven consecutive 20+ point games as a reserve which also coincides in his career-high 14-streak of scoring 20 points or more.<ref>https://pistonpowered.com/2020/01/16/rose-historic-streak-detroit-pistons/</ref>  The streak ended after suffering a groin injury during a game with the Denver Nuggets.<ref>https://clutchpoints.com/pistons-news-derrick-roses-career-high-20-point-streak-over-due-to-groin-injury/</ref> In his third game after returning from Injury, Rose scored a season high 31 points en route to a win against the [[Phoenix Suns]].<ref>https://theathletic.com/1643761/2020/02/29/being-derrick-rose-one-game-through-the-eyes-of-the-pistons-point-guard/</ref><ref>https://clutchpoints.com/pistons-news-kendrick-perkins-perplexed-why-derrick-rose-is-still-on-detroit/</ref>\n\n==National team career==\nRose was a member of the [[United States men's national basketball team]]s that won gold medals at the [[2010 United States men's FIBA World Championship team|2010]] and [[2014 United States FIBA Basketball World Cup team|2014 FIBA World Cup]].\n\n==Player profile==\nStanding at {{convert|6|ft|2|in|m|abbr=}} and weighing {{convert|200|lb||abbr=}}, Rose plays mostly at the [[point guard]] position. He averages 18.8 points per game for his career.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/playerfile/derrick_rose/career_stats.html |title=Derrick Rose Career statistics Page |publisher=NBA.com |date=October 4, 1988 |accessdate=August 10, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120530005556/http://www.nba.com/playerfile/derrick_rose/career_stats.html |archive-date=May 30, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He has never been a knock-down shooter from the arc, shooting 30 percent for his career.<ref>{{cite web|last=Cahill|first=Dan|url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/sports/derrick-rose-shooting-problems-begin-at-the-rim/|title=Derrick Rose shooting problems begin at the rim|work=chicago.suntimes.com|date=December 9, 2015|accessdate=January 18, 2018}}</ref> He developed into a bank-shot shooter during the 2015\u201316 season after struggling with his jump shot due to what he attributes to depth perception issues following eye surgery in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|last=Schwerha|first=Matthew|url=http://chicago.suntimes.com/sports/7/71/1107949/derrick-rose-bank-shot|title=Derrick Rose has found a go-to move in his bank shot|work=chicago.suntimes.com|date=November 17, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151120045816/http://chicago.suntimes.com/sports/7/71/1107949/derrick-rose-bank-shot|archivedate=November 20, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Cahill|first=Dan|url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/sports/derrick-rose-is-shooting-70-percent-on-bank-shots/|title=Derrick Rose is shooting 70 percent on bank shots|work=chicago.suntimes.com|date=February 22, 2016|accessdate=January 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{NBA player statistics legend}}\n\n===NBA===\n====Regular season====\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{nbay|2008}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2008\u201309 Chicago Bulls season|Chicago]]\n| '''81''' || 80 || 37.0 || .475 || .222 || .788 || 3.9 || 6.3 || .8 || .2 || 16.8\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{nbay|2009}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2009\u201310 Chicago Bulls season|Chicago]]\n| 78 || 78 || 36.8 || '''.489''' || .267 || .766 || 3.8 || 6.0 || .7 || .3 || 20.8\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{nbay|2010}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2010\u201311 Chicago Bulls season|Chicago]]\n| '''81''' || '''81''' || '''37.4''' || .445 || .332|| .858 || '''4.1''' || 7.7 || '''1.0''' || .6 || '''25.0'''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{nbay|2011}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2011\u201312 Chicago Bulls season|Chicago]]\n| 39 || 39 || 35.3 || .435 || .312 || .812 || 3.4 