ulls|Chicago]]\n| 7 || 7 || '''44.7''' || .492 || .000 || .800 || 6.3 || 6.4 || .6 || .7 || 19.7\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2010 NBA Playoffs|2010]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Chicago Bulls|Chicago]]\n| 5 || 5 || 42.4 || .456 || .333 || .818 || 3.4 || 7.2 || .8 || .0 || 26.8\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2011 NBA Playoffs|2011]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Chicago Bulls|Chicago]]\n| '''16''' || '''16''' || 40.6 || .396 || .248 || .828 || 4.3 || 7.7 || '''1.4''' || .7 || '''27.1'''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2012 NBA Playoffs|2012]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Chicago Bulls|Chicago]]\n| 1 || 1 || 37.0 || .391 || .500 || '''1.000''' || '''9.0''' || '''9.0''' || 1.0 || '''1.0''' || 23.0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2015 NBA Playoffs|2015]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2014\u201315 Chicago Bulls season|Chicago]]\n| 12 || 12 || 37.8 || .396 || .348 || .897 || 4.8 || 6.5 || 1.2 || .5 || 20.3\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2018 NBA Playoffs|2018]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2017\u201318 Minnesota Timberwolves season|Minnesota]]\n| 5 || 0 || 23.8 || '''.509''' || '''.700''' || .857 || 1.8 || 2.6 || .4 || .0 || 14.2\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=\"2\"| Career\n| 46 || 41 || 38.8 || .423 || .311 || .838 || 4.5 || 6.6 || 1.0 || .5 || 22.7\n{{S-end}}\n\n===College===\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2007\u201308 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2007\u201308]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2007\u201308 Memphis Tigers men's basketball team|Memphis]]\n| 40 || 40 || 29.2 || .477 || .337 || .712 || 4.5 || 4.7 || 1.2 || .4 || 14.9\n{{S-end}}\n\n==Accomplishments and awards==\n\n===NBA===\n* '''NBA Most Valuable Player''': 2011<ref name=\"NBA.com\"/>\n* '''NBA All-Star Selection''': 2010,<ref>[http://www.nba.com/2010/allstar/2010/01/28/reserves.release/index.html NBA.com: Nowitzki leads parade of reserves to Dallas<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100131181722/http://www.nba.com/2010/allstar/2010/01/28/reserves.release/index.html |date=January 31, 2010 }}</ref> 2011,<ref name=autogenerated1 /> 2012<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/chicago/nba/story/_/id/7534419/2012-nba-all-star-game-miami-heat-los-angeles-teams-fill-all-star-starters|title=Heat, LA teams fill All-Star starting rosters|publisher=}}</ref>\n* '''All-NBA First Team''': 2011<ref name=\"ant\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/2011/news/05/12/all-nba-release/index.html|title=LeBron James, Derrick Rose highlight 2010\u201311 All-NBA squad|date=May 12, 2011|work=NBA.com|accessdate=May 12, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110514194754/http://www.nba.com/2011/news/05/12/all-nba-release/index.html|archivedate=May 14, 2011}}</ref>\n* '''NBA Rookie of the Year''': 2009<ref name=\"Rookie of the Year\" />\n* '''NBA All-Rookie First Team''': 2009<ref name=\"All-Rookie Team\" />\n* '''Skills Challenge Champion''': 2009\n* '''Conference Rookie of the Month''': November, December, March<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/awards/rom.html|title=NBA Rookies of the Month - Basketball-Reference.com|website=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref>\n* '''Conference Player of the Month''': April 2010, March 2011<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/awards/pom.html|title=NBA Players of the Month - Basketball-Reference.com|website=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref>\n\n===College===\n*'''Freshman year (2007\u201308)'''\n** NCAA Tournament All-Final Four Team<ref name=\"allffteam\" />\n** NCAA Tournament South Region MVP<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Sports/wireStory?id=4551903|title=Memphis Rolls Past Texas Into Final Four|author=Jaime Aron|publisher=ABC News|date=March 30, 2008|accessdate=January 29, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080402002508/http://abcnews.go.com/Sports/wireStory?id=4551903|archivedate=April 2, 2008}}</ref>\n** [[National Association of Basketball Coaches|NABC]] 3rd Team All-American<ref name=\"3rd Team All-American\" />\n**NABC All-District 7 First Team\n**All-[[Conference USA]] First Team<ref name=\"awards\">{{cite web|author=Information|url=http://conferenceusa.cstv.com/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/062608aaf.html|title=Memphis' Derrick Rose Selected No. 1 In 2008 NBA Draft By Chicago Bulls|website=conferenceusa.cstv.com/|publisher=Conference USA Official Athletic Website|date=April 6, 2008|accessdate=June 27, 2008}}</ref>\n** [[Conference USA]] Freshman of the Year<ref name=\"awards\" />\n**Conference USA All Freshman Team 1st Team<ref name=\"awards\" />\n**Sporting News All-Freshman Team<ref name=\"Sporting News All-Freshman\">{{cite web|url=http://gotigersgo.cstv.com/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/031208aac.html|title=Douglas-Roberts Named To Sporting News, Sports Illustrated All-America teams|website=gotigersgo.cstv.com|publisher=Memphis Tigers Official Athletic Website|date=March 12, 2008|accessdate=January 13, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080515194832/http://gotigersgo.cstv.com/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/031208aac.html|archive-date=May 15, 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n**Conference USA Player of the Week for games between December 17 through the 23rd<ref name=\"1207pow\">{{cite web|title=Douglas-Roberts Named To Sporting News, Sports Illustrated All-America teams|url=http://gotigersgo.cstv.com/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/031208aac.html|publisher=WREG-TV|accessdate=January 26, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080515194832/http://gotigersgo.cstv.com/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/031208aac.html|archive-date=May 15, 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n** [[2K Sports]] College Hoops Classic MVP<ref>{{cite web|author=Scott Wright|title=Sooners will take on several star freshmen|url=http://newsok.com/article/3169225|publisher=NewsOK|date=November 15, 2007|accessdate=January 26, 2009}}</ref>\n**2K Sports College Hoops Classic All-Tournament Team\n\n===High school===\n*'''Senior year (2006\u201307)'''\n**Class AA State Championship\n**Class AA Tournament MVP\n** [[Illinois Mr. Basketball]] 2007<ref name=\"2007 Mr Basketball\" />\n**2007 McDonald's All-American<ref name=\"2007 McDonald's All-American\" />\n**''[[USA Today]]'' 2007 All-USA First Team<ref>{{cite news|author=Various|title=Love leads way on 2007 All-USA boys hoops team|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/preps/basketball/2007-04-17-all-usa-boys_N.htm|work=USA Today|date=April 17, 2007|accessdate=April 13, 2009}}</ref>\n**2007 First-team [[Parade All-America Boys Basketball Team|''Parade'' All-American]]<ref name=\"2007 1st Parade\" />\n**EA Sports 2007 All-American First Team<ref name=\"2007 EA Sports 1st Team\">{{cite web|title=2007 EA SPORTS Boys All American Team|url=http://ssbasketball.rivals.com/content.asp?SID=1132&CID=664465|publisher=Rivals.com|accessdate=December 15, 2008}}</ref>\n**All State Illinois 2007<ref name=\"07allstate\">{{cite news|title=Derrick Rose unanimous selection to AP's All-State team|url=http://www.register-news.com/sports/local_story_071224554.html|publisher=Mt. Vernon Register News|agency=Associated Press|date=March 12, 2007|accessdate=December 21, 2008|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130201073611/http://www.register-news.com/sports/local_story_071224554.html|archive-date=February 1, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n**MaxPreps.com All-America First Team\n**''[[Slam Magazine]]'' 2007 First Team\n**MidStateHoops.com 2007 Class AA Player of the Year<ref name=\"MSH.com POY 2007\">{{cite web|author=Pat Benninger|title=MidStateHoops.com 2006\u20132007 Class A All-State Team|url=http://www.midstatehoops.com/articles/2007/classaaallstate.html|publisher=MidStateHoops|date=March 20, 2007|accessdate=December 21, 2008}}</ref>\n*'''Junior year (2005\u201306)'''\n**Class AA State Championship\n**Class AA Tournament MVP\n**2006 ''Parade'' All-American Fourth Team<ref name=\"2006 4th parade\" />\n**All State Illinois 2006\n**EA Sports 2006 All-American Second Team<ref name=\"2006 EA Sports 2nd Team\"/>\n*'''Sophomore year (2004\u201305)'''\n**2005 ''[[Parade (magazine)|Parade]]'' All-American Third Team<ref name=\"2005 3rd parade\" />\n**''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' All-Area<ref>{{cite web|url=http://highschoolelite.com/ticker/3-5.html|title=Chicago all-area players|publisher=High School Elite|date=March 5, 2005|accessdate=February 8, 2009}}</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Personal life==\nHis agent is former Bulls guard [[B. J. Armstrong]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Derrick Rose's Agent a Big Assist Man Then and Now|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/22/sports/basketball/22bulls.html|publisher=New York Times|date=April 21, 2009|accessdate=August 7, 2012}}</ref>\n\nRose is a [[Christianity|Christian]]. Rose has spoken about his faith saying, \"... [[God in Christianity|God]] does everything for a reason.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Rose rallies Bulls, then beats self up for not finishing job|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2012-01-29/sports/ct-spt-0130-bulls-heat-chicago--20120130_1_derrick-rose-tom-thibodeau-bulls}}</ref> Rose wears a wristband that says \"In [[Jesus]] Name I Play\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Timberwolves' Tolliver keeps faith with business venture|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/sports/basketball/nba/twolves/2011-07-12-tolliver_n.htm}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Lin's rise sparks Active Faith's success|url=http://msn.foxsports.com/nba/story/jeremy-lin-tim-tebow-success-helps-athlete-owned-christian-apparel-company-active-faith-prosper-032912}}</ref> and has several tattoos about his faith.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tattoo U: Inking of the Chicago Bulls' Derrick Rose|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eTLCaWAG0uc}}</ref>\n\nOn October 9, 2012, Rose's girlfriend, Mieka Reese, gave birth to their son, Derrick Jr.<ref>{{cite web|author=Jeff Zillgitt|title=Derrick Rose: From agony of injury to joy of fatherhood|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nba/bulls/2013/02/12/derrick-rose-injury-acl-return-chicago-fatherhood/1913639/|publisher=Usatoday.com|date=February 13, 2013|accessdate=March 27, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Rose introduced The Rose Scholars, a scholarship program to help students achieve a higher education.<ref>[https://pippenainteasy.com/2018/08/03/derrick-rose-continues-make-chicago-proud/ Derrick Rose continues to make Chicago proud]</ref><ref>[https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2789073-derrick-rose-announces-400k-rose-scholars-college-tuition-program Derrick Rose Announces $400K 'Rose Scholars' College Tuition Program]</ref>\n\n===Rape allegation and lawsuit===\nIn 2016, Rose was involved in a federal [[civil procedure|civil lawsuit]] to \"assess whether he and two friends raped his former girlfriend\" in August 2013.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/10/06/sports/basketball/derrick-rose-trial-rape-lawsuit.html |date=October 5, 2016 |title=Knicks' Derrick Rose Expected in Court as Civil Trial in Rape Case Begins |work=The New York Times |first=Mike |last=Tierney}}</ref> In the months before the alleged gang-rape, Rose's accuser, referred to as \"Jane Doe\" in court transcripts, testified that Rose made her uncomfortable by asking her to perform sexual acts for him or to involve other people in their sex life; he would sometimes get angry when she refused. Jane Doe also mentioned that on the day of the incident, she was drugged against her consent, and alternated in and out of consciousness.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/bulls/ct-pdf-derrick-rose-lawsuit-20150827-htmlstory.html|title=PDF: Full text of lawsuit against Derrick Rose (Warning: Graphic Content)|website=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=August 27, 2015|accessdate=September 27, 2019}}</ref> During the trial, Rose expressed difficulty and uncertainty with the definition of the word \"consent\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/espnw/voices/article/17877518/the-unacceptable-glee-followed-derrick-rose-verdict|title=The unacceptable glee that followed the Derrick Rose verdict|website=[[ESPN]]|last=Davidson|first=Kavitha A.|date=October 25, 2016|accessdate=September 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2016, he was found not liable by an eight-member jury.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/10/20/sports/basketball/derrick-rose-rape-trial-new-york-knicks.html|title=Jury Clears Knicks\u2019 Derrick Rose of Liability in Rape Suit|date=October 19, 2016|work=The New York Times|first=Mike|last=Tierney}}</ref> An appeal in 2018 was denied.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://blacksportsonline.com/2018/12/details-on-why-derrick-rose-rape-accusers-appeal-was-denied-rose-officially-cleared-in-civil-case-doesnt-have-to-pay-accuser-21-million-vids-texts-court-docs/|title=Details on Why Derrick Rose Rape Accuser\u2019s Appeal Was Denied; Rose Officially Cleared in Civil Case & Doesn\u2019t Have to Pay Accuser $21 Million (Vids-Texts-Court Docs)|author=Littal, Robert|date=December 14, 2018|accessdate=January 22, 2019|publisher=BSO: USA Today (Gannett)}}</ref>\n\n==Endorsements==\nRose was the cover athlete of ''[[NBA 2K13]]'' alongside fellow NBA players [[Kevin Durant]] and [[Blake Griffin]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Robinson|first=Jon|title='NBA 2K13' cover features 3 superstars|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/playbook/tech/post/_/id/1067/nba-2k13-cover-features-3-superstars|work=espn.go.com|accessdate=December 22, 2012}}</ref>\n\nRose was the lone cover athlete for the [[2K Sports]] Downloadable Content game, ''[[NBA 2K10 Draft Combine]]'', which was released on [[Xbox Live Arcade]] for the [[Xbox 360]] and [[PlayStation Network]] for the [[PlayStation 3]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://2ksports.com/news/nba2k10dc/336|title=2K Sports Signs the Chicago Bulls\u2019 Derrick Rose as Spokesman for the NBA 2K10: Draft Combine Downloadable Game|publisher=2K Sports|date=August 11, 2009|accessdate=August 17, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090818221634/http://www.2ksports.com/news/nba2k10dc/336|archive-date=August 18, 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nRose is a part-owner and spokesman for the Chicago-based [[Giordano's Pizzeria]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Derrick Rose buys stake in Chicago Pizza company, will have his own pie|url=http://www.cbssports.com/nba/blog/eye-on-basketball/20092446/derrick-rose-buys-stake-in-chicago-pizza-company-will-have-his-own-pie/|publisher=CBS Sports|date=September 12, 2012|accessdate=August 7, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Rose signed a shoe deal with [[Adidas]] for $1 million per year.<ref>[http://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/article/122678 Rose signs Adidas Shoe Deal] Accessed 2009-02-2009</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://larrybrownsports.com/basketball/blake-griffin-underpaid-nike-shoe-deal/57257|title=Blake Griffin Is Severely Underpaid by Nike in His Shoe Deal|date=March 8, 2011|publisher=}}</ref> He has also signed with [[Wilson Sporting Goods]].<ref>[http://www.suntimes.com/sports/derrickrose/1246134,rose-wilson-102808-CST-SPT.stng Rose signs with Wilson]{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Accessed 2009-02-2009</ref> Other endorsement deals include [[Skullcandy]] headphones, [[Powerade]], Force Factor sports drinks and a suburban Chicago [[Nissan]] dealership.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chicago.cbslocal.com/2011/02/04/is-there-anyone-better-than-derrick-rose/|title=Is There Anyone Better Than Derrick Rose? \u00ab CBS Chicago|publisher=Chicago.cbslocal.com|date=February 4, 2011|accessdate=August 10, 2012}}</ref> In May 2018, it was announced that the Adidas D Rose 9's would be released in July 2018.<ref>[https://www.vibe.com/2018/05/derrick-rose-adidas-9-sneakers/ Derrick Rose Plots Summer Release For Adidas Signature Sneakers]</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Rose was estimated by ''Crain's Chicago Business'' to earn $1.5\u2013$2.5 million annually in endorsements, ranking just outside the top 10 NBA players in that category.<ref>[http://www.chicagobusiness.com/article/20110416/ISSUE01/304169973/rose-in-bloom-bulls-star-shoots-to-be-the-next-michael-jordan Can Derrick Rose Shape Off-Court Brand To Mirror On-Court Success?]</ref> In 2012, it was reported that Rose signed a contract extension with Adidas, worth $185 million over 14 years.<ref>{{cite web|last=Blackburn|first=Pete|url=https://www.cbssports.com/nba/news/derrick-rose-and-his-friends-are-still-making-an-insane-amount-of-money-from-adidas/|title=Derrick Rose and his friends are still making an insane amount of money from Adidas|publisher=cbssports.com|accessdate=February 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Sports}}\n* [[2006 high school boys basketball All-Americans]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n{{basketballstats|nba=derrick_rose|bbr=r/rosede01}}\n* [http://drosehoops.com/ Official website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120430050416/http://www.gotigersgo.com/sports/m-baskbl/mtt/rose_derrick00.html Memphis Tigers bio]\n\n{{Detroit Pistons current roster}}\n{{Navboxes|list=\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box\n| title = [[Illinois Mr. Basketball]]\n| before = [[Jon Scheyer]]\n| after = [[Kevin Dillard]]\n|years = 2007\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{2008 NBA Draft}}\n{{NBA MVPs}}\n{{NBA NumberOne Draft Picks}}\n{{NBA Rookies of the Year}}\n{{United States Squad 2010 FIBA World Championship}}\n{{United States Squad 2014 FIBA World Championship}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rose, Derrick}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American basketball players]]\n[[Category:All-American college men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Basketball players at the 2008 NCAA Men's Division I Final Four]]\n[[Category:Basketball players from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Chicago Bulls draft picks]]\n[[Category:Chicago Bulls players]]\n[[Category:Cleveland Cavaliers players]]\n[[Category:Detroit Pistons players]]\n[[Category:College basketball controversies in the United States]]\n[[Category:FIBA Basketball World Cup-winning players]]\n[[Category:FIBA World Championship-winning players]]\n[[Category:McDonald's High School All-Americans]]\n[[Category:Memphis Tigers men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Minnesota Timberwolves players]]\n[[Category:National Basketball Association All-Stars]]\n[[Category:New York Knicks players]]\n[[Category:Parade High School All-Americans (boys' basketball)]]\n[[Category:Point guards]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Chicago]]\n[[Category:United States men's national basketball team players]]\n[[Category:2010 FIBA World Championship players]]\n[[Category:2014 FIBA Basketball World Cup players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|D Rose|the song by Lil Pump|Lil Pump (album)}}\n{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| image = Rose-20190120 (cropped).jpg\n| caption = Rose with the [[Minnesota Timberwolves]] in 2019\n| alt = Hip length view of man raising the basketball to shoot free throw, with black moustache, beard, and short dreadlocks, thin white headband, wearing navy blue Timberwolves uniform\n| image_size =\n| position = [[Point guard]]\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 2\n| weight_lb = 200\n| league = [[NBA]]\n| team = Detroit Pistons\n| number = 25\n| nationality = American\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1988|10|4}}\n| birth_place = [[Chicago|Chicago, Illinois]]\n| high_school = [[Simeon Career Academy]]<br />(Chicago, Illinois)\n| college = [[Memphis Tigers men's basketball|Memphis]] (2007\u20132008)\n| draft_year = 2008\n| draft_round = 1\n| draft_pick = 1\n| draft_team = [[Chicago Bulls]]\n| career_start = 2008\n| career_end = \n| years1 = {{nbay|2008|start}}\u2013{{nbay|2015|end}}\n| team1 = [[Chicago Bulls]]\n| years2 = {{nbay|2016|full=y}}\n| team2 = [[New York Knicks]]\n| years3 = {{nbay|2017|full=y}}\n| team3 = [[Cleveland Cavaliers]]\n| years4 = {{nbay|2017|end}}\u2013{{nbay|2018|end}}\n| team4 = [[Minnesota Timberwolves]]\n| years5 = {{nbay|2019|start}}\u2013present\n| team5 = [[Detroit Pistons]]\n| highlights =\n* [[NBA Most Valuable Player Award|NBA Most Valuable Player]] ({{nbay|2010|end}})\n* 3\u00d7 [[NBA All-Star]] ({{nasg|2010}}\u2013{{nasg|2012}})\n* [[All-NBA First Team]] ({{nbay|2010|end}})\n* [[NBA Rookie of the Year Award|NBA Rookie of the Year]] ({{nbay|2008|end}})\n*[[NBA All-Rookie First Team]] ({{nbay|2008|end}})\n* Third-team [[NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|All-American]] \u2013 [[Associated Press|AP]], [[National Association of Basketball Coaches|NABC]] ([[2008 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|2008]])\n* [[McDonald's All-American Game|McDonald's All-American]] ([[2007 McDonald's All-American Boys Game|2007]])\n* First-team [[Parade All-America Boys Basketball Team|''Parade'' All-American]] (2007)\n* Third-team ''Parade'' All-American (2005)\n* Fourth-team ''Parade'' All-American (2006)\n* [[Illinois Mr. Basketball]] (2007)\n| nba_profile  = derrick_rose\n| bbr  =  rosede01\n| medal_templates =\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[basketball]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{flagu|United States}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIBA Basketball World Cup|World Championship/World Cup]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2010 FIBA World Championship|2010 Turkey]] | [[2010 United States men's FIBA World Championship team|Team]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2014 FIBA Basketball World Cup|2014 Spain]] | [[2014 United States FIBA Basketball World Cup team|Team]]}}\n}}\n'''Derrick Martell Rose''' (born October 4, 1988) is an American professional [[basketball]] player for the [[Detroit Pistons]] of the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA). He played one year of college basketball for the [[Memphis Tigers men's basketball|Memphis Tigers]] before being drafted [[List of first overall NBA draft picks|first overall]] by his hometown [[Chicago Bulls]] in the [[2008 NBA draft]].<ref name=\"Drafted 1st\">{{cite web |publisher=ESPN  |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/draft2008/news/story?id=3462594 |title=Bulls go with native Chicagoan Rose over Beasley |accessdate=June 26, 2008}}</ref> He was named the [[NBA Rookie of the Year]] and also became the youngest player to win the [[NBA Most Valuable Player Award]] in 2011 at age 22.\n\nRose was born and raised in Chicago, and attended [[Simeon Career Academy]]. He was highly recruited by colleges, eventually choosing to join the [[University of Memphis]] under coach [[John Calipari]]. Rose led the Tigers to the most wins in NCAA history (a 38\u20132 record), their first number 1 ranking in 25 years, and an appearance in the NCAA championship game. In 2009, an NCAA investigation  revealed that Rose's SAT scores had been invalidated, and as a result, the NCAA vacated Memphis' entire 2007\u201308 season.<ref name = \"vacate\">{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/college/mensbasketball/2009-08-20-memphis-ncaa-penalties_N.htm|title=NCAA vacates Memphis' '07\u201308 season record, Final Four run|work=USA Today|accessdate=August 20, 2009|date=August 19, 2009|last=Garci|first=Marlen}}</ref>\n\nRose has struggled with significant knee injuries since his [[2010\u201311 NBA season|2010\u201311]] MVP campaign. In the first round of the [[2012 NBA Playoffs]] against the [[Philadelphia 76ers]], Rose tore his [[Anterior cruciate ligament injury|ACL]] in his left knee. Rose required surgery and was subsequently sidelined for the entire [[2012\u201313 NBA season|2012\u201313 season]].<ref name=andrews>{{cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/chicago/nba/story/_/id/8074004/chicago-bulls-derrick-rose-getting-knee-examined-dr-james-andrews |title=Chicago Bulls Derrick Rose getting knee examined by Dr. James Andrews |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=June 20, 2012}}</ref> Rose returned to play in [[2013\u201314 NBA season|2013\u201314]]. However, on November 22, 2013, during a regular season game against the [[Portland Trail Blazers]], Rose injured his right meniscus which caused him to miss the remainder of the season.<ref name=tribune>{{cite web |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2013-11-25/sports/chi-derrick-rose-surgery-20131124_1_derrick-rose-tom-thibodeau-chicago-bulls |title=Bulls' Rose is likely out for season |work=ChicagoTribune.com |date=November 25, 2013 |accessdate=November 6, 2015}}</ref> Rose returned once again the [[2014\u201315 NBA season|following season]], but knee injuries continued to riddle him, causing him to miss 30 games. In June 2016, he was traded to the [[New York Knicks]]. After one season with the Knicks, Rose joined the [[Cleveland Cavaliers]] in July 2017, but was traded and subsequently released by the [[Utah Jazz]] the following February. In March 2018, he signed with the [[Minnesota Timberwolves]].\n\n==Early life==\nRose was born and raised in the [[Englewood, Chicago|Englewood]] area, one of the most dangerous neighborhoods on [[South Side, Chicago|Chicago's South Side]].<ref name=Englewood>{{cite web|last1=Jensen|first1=Sean|title=Derrick Rose keeps tough Englewood area close to his heart|url=http://www.suntimes.com/sports/basketball/5365750-419/derrick-rose-stays-connected-to-tough-englewood-neighborhood.html|website=Chicago Sun-Times|accessdate=August 4, 2014|date=May 14, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808055234/http://www.suntimes.com/sports/basketball/5365750-419/derrick-rose-stays-connected-to-tough-englewood-neighborhood.html|archive-date=August 8, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> He is  the youngest son of Brenda Rose after Dwayne, Reggie, and Allan. All three were talented basketball players who taught Rose the in and outs of basketball on nearby courts.<ref name=Englewood/><ref name=si>{{cite web|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1114058/index.htm|title=The Well-guarded Guard|publisher=}}</ref>  As his talent for the sport grew, Rose began to attract much more outside attention in Chicago's basketball circles, leading his mother and brothers to restrict outside contact to him. She feared he would be exploited and his path to the NBA diverted by outside parties like street agents, similar to what happened to former Chicago prospect [[Ronnie Fields]].<ref name=\"06sipiece\">{{cite news |url=http://www.sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2006/highschool/11/20/hs.rose1127/1.html |title=The Well-Guarded Guard |author=George Dohrmann |work=Sports Illustrated |date=November 21, 2006 |accessdate=December 26, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090123224700/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2006/highschool/11/20/hs.rose1127/1.html |archive-date=January 23, 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==High school career==\nBy the time Rose enrolled at [[Simeon Career Academy]] in 2003, he was a hot commodity for collegiate coaches. Despite his reputation, he played freshmen and JV basketball for the Wolverines. He wore No. 25 in honor of [[Ben Wilson (basketball)|Ben \"Benji\" Wilson]], a promising player who was murdered by a gang member during his senior year in 1984.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sports.espn.go.com/espn/page2/story?page=jackson/080701&sportCat=nba |title=Spirit of former Chicago high school star lives on in Rose |author=Scoop Jackson |work=ESPN.com |date=July 1, 2008 |accessdate=January 29, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090219222433/http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/page2/story?page=jackson%2F080701&sportCat=nba |archive-date=February 19, 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Rose was not allowed on varsity due to a long-standing tradition that head coach Bob Hambric, who had been with the school since 1980 had no freshmen on the varsity team. That rule did not lessen Rose's play, and he went on to put up 18.5 [[Point (basketball)|points]], 6.6 [[Assist (basketball)|assist]]s, 4.7 [[Rebound (basketball)|rebound]]s and 2.1 [[Steal (basketball)|steal]]s per game and led both the freshmen and sophomores to city championships with a 24\u20131 record.<ref name=\"Bulls.com Draft Profile\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/bulls/news/derrick_rose.html |title=2008 NBA Draft Player Profile : : Derrick Rose |work=Bulls.com |accessdate=December 10, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111217234316/http://www.nba.com/bulls/news/derrick_rose.html |archive-date=December 17, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Hambric softened his stance and allowed the freshman a chance to play on varsity in the state tournament, but Rose declined, wanting the players to get due credit.<ref name=\"Sophomore Scout Article\">{{cite web |url=http://preps.scout.com/2/493015.html |title=Believe The Hype |author=Jon Mahoney |work=Scout |date=January 25, 2005 |accessdate=December 27, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081229202544/http://preps.scout.com/2/493015.html |archive-date=December 29, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The next year Hambric retired and Robert Smith was hired, opening the path to varsity. In Rose's debut, he had 22 points, 7 rebounds and 5 steals over [[Thornwood High School]] in a sold-out game filled with college scouts and coaches.<ref name=\"1st Varsity Game\">{{cite news |url=http://yourseason.suntimes.com/1026724,062608rosedebut.article |title=Flashback: Rose's debut |author=Michael O'Brien |work=Chicago Sun-Times |date=June 30, 2008 |accessdate=December 27, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081229202331/http://yourseason.suntimes.com/1026724,062608rosedebut.article |archive-date=December 29, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He led the Wolverines to a 30\u20135 mark while averaging 19.8 points, 5.1 rebounds, 8.3 assists and 2.4 steals but the season ended after a loss in state regionals. Rose's play garnered him his first national award: a [[Parade All-America Boys Basketball Team|''Parade'' All-American]] third team spot.<ref name=\"2005 3rd parade\">{{cite web |url=http://www.parade.com/articles/editions/2005/edition_04-03-2005/featured_2 |title=Meet PARADE's All-America... Team |accessdate=January 1, 2008 |author=Michael O'Shea |work=Parade.com |date=April 3, 2005}}</ref>\n\nDuring Rose's junior year in 2006, the Simeon Wolverines broke through and won the [[Chicago Public High School League|Chicago Public League]] championship held at the [[United Center]], where Rose starred with 25 points and crowd pleasing dunks. The team advanced through the playoffs and earned a berth in the Class AA state championship against [[Richwoods High School]], where a fourth quarter [[buzzer beater]] by Richwood forced overtime. The score was knotted at 29 late in the extra period when Rose stole the ball and buried the game winning jumper as time expired, giving Simeon its first state title since the Wilson-led Wolverines won in 1984. The team finished 33\u20134 and ranked nationally,<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2006/highschool/04/07/hoops.rankings2/ |title=Final Top 25 Poll |author=Jon Mahoney |work=Sports Illustrated |date=April 6, 2006 |accessdate=March 29, 2009}}</ref> and Rose was awarded with an All-State Illinois mention, [[EA Sports]] All-American Second Team pick<ref name=\"2006 EA Sports 2nd Team\">{{cite web |work=Rivals.com |url=http://ssbasketball.rivals.com/content.asp?SID=1132&CID=537673 |title=2006 EA SPORTS Boys All American Team |accessdate=December 25, 2008}}</ref> and another ''Parade'' All-American selection.<ref name=\"2006 4th parade\">{{cite magazine |work=Parade Magazine |url=http://all-americans.parade.com/2006_boy_basketball/2006_boys_basketball.html |title=All-America Teams |accessdate=December 25, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090212130829/http://all-americans.parade.com/2006_boy_basketball/2006_boys_basketball.html |archivedate=February 12, 2009  }}</ref>\n\nEntering his senior year, Rose was ranked the fifth best prospect in the nation by ''[[Sports Illustrated]]''. In January 2007, Simeon traveled to [[Madison Square Garden]] to play [[Rice High School (New York)|Rice High School]] and star guard [[Kemba Walker]].<ref>{{cite news |work=USA Today |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/preps/basketball/2007-01-11-rose-new-york_x.htm|title=Chicago standout Rose takes stage in New York|author=Christopher Lawlor |date=January 11, 2007 |accessdate=December 28, 2009}}</ref> The Wolverines lost 53\u201351.<ref>{{cite news |work=USA Today |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/preps/basketball/2007-01-15-weekend-roundup_x.htm|title=N.Y.'s Rice topples No. 14 Simeon 53\u201351 despite Rose's 22|author=Christopher Lawlor |date=January 15, 2007 |accessdate=December 28, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2007/highschool/01/15/derrick.rose/ |title=Garden Party|author=Kevin Armstrong |work=Sports Illustrated |date=January 15, 2007 |accessdate=February 8, 2009}}</ref> The season's highlight was a nationally televised contest on [[ESPN]] against [[Virginia]] perennial power [[Oak Hill Academy (Virginia)|Oak Hill Academy]] two weeks later. Matched up with hyped junior guard [[Brandon Jennings]], Rose had 28 points, 9 assists, and 8 rebounds and in a 78\u201375 win.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=Draft Express\n|url=http://www.draftexpress.com/article/Chicago-Simeon-vs.-Oak-Hill-Academy-Breakdown/ |title=Chicago Simeon vs. Oak Hill Academy Breakdown |author=Rodger Bohn and Mike Schmidt |date=January 24, 2007 |accessdate=February 1, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |work=Sports Illustrated |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2007/highschool/01/19/simeon.upset/ |title=Chicago Simeon vs. Oak Hill Academy Breakdown |author=Jon Mahoney |date=January 19, 2007 |accessdate=February 15, 2009}}</ref> For his performance, ''[[USA Today]]'' named him their high school player of the week.<ref>{{cite news |work=USA Today\n|url=http://blogs.usatoday.com/preprally/2007/01/teams_shuffle_p.html |title=Teams shuffle positions in newest Super 25 |author=Various |date=January 25, 2007 |accessdate=February 8, 2009}}</ref> Simeon went on to repeat as Public League champions<ref>{{cite web |work=Chicago Reader |url=http://www.chicagoreader.com/features/stories/sports/070302/ |title=Reaching the Heights |author=Ted Cox |date=March 2, 2007 |accessdate=February 8, 2009 }}{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and defended their state championship, defeating [[O'Fallon Township High School|O'Fallon High School]] 77\u201354.<ref>{{cite web |work=Illinois HS Basketball.com |url=http://illinoishsbasketball.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=465&Itemid=1 |title=2007\u2013 March 17- Simeon Wins State |author=Daniel Poneman |date=March 17, 2007 |accessdate=February 8, 2009}}</ref> In doing so, Simeon became the first Chicago Public League school to win two straight state championships. In his final high school game, Rose scored 2 points, but pulled down 7 rebounds and totaled 8 assists, while Simeon big man Tim Flowers scored 35 points.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2007-03-18/sports/0703180114_1_simeon-rose-wound-repeat|title=Simply The Best|publisher=}}</ref> The Wolverines ended the season 33\u20132 and ranked first in the nation by ''Sports Illustrated''<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2007/highschool/03/20/top25.rankings/index.html |title=Simeon wins Illinois state title, takes top ranking |author=Jon Mahoney |work=Sports Illustrated |date=March 20, 2007 |accessdate=February 8, 2009}}</ref> and 6th on ''USA Today''{{'s}} Super 25.<ref>{{cite news |work=USA Today |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/preps/basketball/poll/super25.htm |title=Super 25: Virginia's Oak Hill Academy finishes on top |author=Super 25: Virginia's Oak Hill Academy finishes on top |date=March 27, 2007 |accessdate=February 8, 2009}}</ref> Rose averaged 25.2 points, 9.1 assists, 8.8 rebounds and 3.4 steals.\n\nOverall, Simeon's record while Rose played was 120\u201312.<ref name=\"Bulls.com Draft Profile\" /> After his senior year, Rose was again All-State after being named [[Illinois Mr. Basketball]]<ref name=\"2007 Mr Basketball\">{{cite news |url=http://archives.chicagotribune.com/2007/mar/31/sports/chi-0703310340mar31 |title=Mr. Basketball of Illinois, 2007: Derrick Rose |author=Bob Sakamoto |work= Chicago Tribune |date=June 26, 2008 |accessdate=June 27, 2008}}</ref> and was named to the [[McDonald's All-American]] team.<ref name=\"2007 McDonald's All-American\">{{cite web\n|url=http://mcdonaldsallamerican.com/stats/2007boys_roster.pdf |title=2007 McDonald's All American High School Basketball Team |publisher=McDonald's All American |accessdate=December 15, 2008 |format=PDF}}</ref> He was also awarded with First Team honors by ''Parade'' selection and ''USA Today''<ref name=\"2007 1st Parade\">{{cite web |publisher=PARADE Magazine\n|url=http://www.parade.com/articles/editions/2007/edition_04-01-2007/Basketball |title=Meet PARADE's 2007 All-America High School Boys Basketball Team |author=Michael O'Shea |date=March 23, 2007 |accessdate=December 15, 2008}}</ref> and ''USA Today'' First Team All-American.\n\nRose was selected to play in the Jordan Brand All-Star Game and [[Nike Hoop Summit]]. In 2009, Rose was named the decade's third greatest high school point guard by ''[[ESPN RISE]]'' magazine behind [[Chris Paul]] and [[T.J. Ford]],<ref>{{cite web|title=ESPN Big names make cut for all-decade team|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/highschool/rise/basketball/boys/news/story?id=3903359|last=Canner-O'Mealy|first=Ryan|last2=Mahoney|first2=Jon|publisher=[[ESPN]], Inc.|date=April 9, 2009|work=[[ESPN RISE]]|accessdate=August 19, 2009 }}</ref> and had his jersey number (#25) retired along with Ben Wilson.<ref>{{cite web|title=Simeon Career Academy retires No. 25 worn by Ben Wilson and Derrick Rose|url=http://www.nba.com/bulls/news/rose_simeon_091114.html|work=www.chicagobulls.com|date=November 11, 2009|accessdate=April 27, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==College career==\n[[File:Derrick-Rose-2008-Final-Four-UCLA.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Rose while playing at the [[University of Memphis]]]]\nRose accepted a scholarship to play for the [[University of Memphis]] [[Memphis Tigers men's basketball|Tigers]] under [[John Calipari]], who recruited him after seeing him play in an [[Amateur Athletic Union|AAU]] game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/draft2008/columns/story?id=3452587 |title=Rose 'chases greatness' with a passion for winning |author=Andy Katz |work=ESPN.com |date=June 30, 2008 |accessdate=January 28, 2009}}</ref> Strong efforts were made by [[Indiana Hoosiers men's basketball|Indiana University]] and in-state [[Illinois Fighting Illini men's basketball|University of Illinois]] to sign Rose to their own programs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.suntimes.com/preps/2006/10/which_school_will_derrick_rose.html |title=Which school will Derrick Rose choose on Saturday? |author=Michael O'Brien |work=Chicago Sun-Times] |date=October 31, 2007 |accessdate=January 22, 2009}}</ref> Illinois in particular planned to pair Rose and their five-star recruit [[Eric Gordon]], who had played AAU basketball with Rose.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.ljworld.com/news/2006/jul/07/keegan_chicagoan_targeted_self/?sports |title=Keegan: Chicagoan targeted by Self |accessdate=January 1, 2008}}</ref> Gordon, however, retracted his verbal commitment from the Fighting Illini, opting to play for Indiana, and Rose subsequently gave his verbal commitment before the start of his senior season.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/recruiting/basketball/national/2006-11-06-basketball.htm |title=Rose commitment highlights busy week |author=Jerry Meyer |work= USA Today |date=November 7, 2007 |accessdate=January 22, 2009}}</ref> Rose chose Memphis because of the school's history of putting players in the NBA and the prospect of [[Rod Strickland]], a 17-year veteran of the league, mentoring him. Rose switched to #23, due to the fact that #25 had been retired by the school in honor of [[Penny Hardaway]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gotigersgo.cstv.com/genrel/082108aac.html |title=Penny Hardaway Sets Record With Assist To Tiger Athletics |work=Memphis Tigers Official Athletic Site |date=August 21, 2008 |accessdate=February 8, 2009}}</ref>\n\nWith the addition of Rose and led by veteran upperclassmen [[Joey Dorsey]] and [[Chris Douglas-Roberts]], the Tigers started out [[2007\u201308 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|the season]] ranked third in the nation. Memphis sprinted to a 26\u20130 start and claimed the number one ranking in the country for the first time in over 25 years before falling to the [[University of Tennessee]] [[Tennessee Volunteers basketball|Volunteers]] 66\u201362 in February.<ref>{{cite news |work=ESPN.com |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=280540235 |title=No. 2 Tennessee likely next No. 1 as Memphis leaves with close loss |agency=Associated Press |date=February 23, 2008 |accessdate=January 22, 2009}}</ref> Memphis was able to bounce back and capture the [[2008 Conference USA Men's Basketball Tournament|Conference USA Tournament]] to qualify for the \"[[2008 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|Big Dance]]\" with a 33\u20131 record.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.commercialappeal.com/news/2008/mar/16/tigers-no-1-seed-ncaa-mens-basketball-tournament/ |title=Tigers earn second No. 1 seed in two seasons |author=Dan Wolken |work=Commercial Appeal |date=March 16, 2008 |accessdate=January 29, 2009}}</ref> Rose averaged 14.9 points per game, 4.7 assists and 4.5 rebounds per game during the regular season and earned [[2008 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|All-American Third Team honors]] among others.<ref name=\"3rd Team All-American\">{{cite web |url=http://www.goduke.com/ViewArticle.dbml?SPSID=22724&SPID=1845&DB_OEM_ID=4200&ATCLID=1434246 |title=Nelson Named NABC Third Team All-American |author=Duke Sports Information |work=Go Duke |date=April 6, 2008 |accessdate=June 27, 2008}}</ref> He finished as a finalist for the [[Bob Cousy Award]] as well as the [[John R. Wooden Award]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://gotigersgo.cstv.com/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/031008aaf.html |title=Douglas-Roberts, Rose Named Wooden Award Finalists |work=Memphis Tigers |date=March 10, 2008 |accessdate=January 29, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080515194538/http://gotigersgo.cstv.com/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/031008aaf.html |archive-date=May 15, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nMemphis was seeded No. 1 in the South Region. Rose earned high praise for his increased focus on defense, hounding [[University of Texas|Texas Longhorn]] guard [[D. J. Augustin]] into a low-percentage game in the Elite Eight.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/college/mensbasketball/finalfour/2008-04-01-rose-memphis_N.htm |title=Freshman Rose blooming at the right time for Memphis |author=Steve Wieberg |work=USA Today |date=April 2, 2008 |accessdate=January 23, 2009}}</ref> In a match-up against [[University of California-Los Angeles|UCLA]] in the Final Four, Rose finished with 25 points and 9 rebounds to lead the Tigers to an 85\u201367 win and a trip to the NCAA championship game against the [[University of Kansas|Kansas]] [[Kansas Jayhawks men's basketball|Jayhawks]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/college/2008/04/05/2008-04-05_derrick_rose_puts_on_dazzling_show_leads.html |title=Derrick Rose puts on dazzling show, leads Memphis past UCLA, 78\u201363 |author=Roger Rubin |work=New York Daily News |date=April 5, 2008 |accessdate=February 26, 2012}}</ref> The win set a NCAA mark for most wins in a season (38).<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2008-04-05/sports/17896067_1_darren-collison-ucla-college-basketball |title=Memphis' Derrick Rose would look great planted at the Garden |work=New York Daily News |date=April 5, 2008 |accessdate=February 26, 2012}}</ref> [[2008 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament#National Championship Game|Against Kansas]], Rose scored 17 points on 7\u2013of\u201317 shooting, along with six rebounds and seven assists, but missed a critical free throw at the end of the second half as Memphis fell in overtime, 75\u201368.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=284000063 |title=After 20-year drought, Kansas rallies to beat Memphis for NCAA title |agency=Associated Press |work=ESPN.com |date=April 7, 2007 |accessdate=June 26, 2008}}</ref> Memphis concluded the season 38\u20132. Rose was named to the All-Final Four team after averaging 20.8 points, 6.5 rebounds and 6.0 assists per game.<ref name=\"allffteam\">{{cite web |url=http://gotigersgo.cstv.com/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/040808aaf.html |title=NCAA All-Tournament Team, Tournament Leaders |accessdate=January 29, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080922184208/http://gotigersgo.cstv.com/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/040808aaf.html |archive-date=September 22, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nOn April 15, Rose announced he would forgo his final three seasons at Memphis and declared for the [[2008 NBA draft]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/draft2008/news/story?id=3347737 |title=Memphis freshman Rose says he's leaving, will enter NBA draft |work=ESPN.com |date=April 15, 2008 |accessdate=January 29, 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Grading controversy===\nAccording to Sheri Lipman of the University of Memphis legal counsel, a month after the loss to Kansas, the NCAA sent a letter to the school stating that Rose had \"an invalidated standardized test score the previous year at Chicago's Simeon High School.\" The next January, the NCAA sent another letter, charging Memphis with knowing that Rose had someone else take his SAT for him.<ref>\n{{cite web|url=http://www.commercialappeal.com/news/2009/may/27/ncaa-alleges-major-violations-memphis-basketball-p/|title=NCAA alleges major violations in Memphis basketball program under John Calipari : GoMemphisTigers : Your leading source for The University of Memphis Tigers |work=Commercial Appeal |accessdate=August 20, 2009|date=May 28, 2009|last=Wolken|first=Dan}}</ref> Memphis started its own investigation and sent its response back on April 24.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/news/story?id=4213427|title=Memphis works to resolve dispute|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=August 20, 2009|date=May 29, 2009|last=Katz|first=Andy}}</ref>\n\nOn May 28, 2009, the ''[[Memphis Commercial Appeal]]'' obtained the letter through the [[Freedom of Information Act (United States)|Freedom of Information Act]] and released it. Although the player's name was redacted due to privacy laws, [[process of elimination]], and sources revealed the player as Derrick Rose. The next day, in a separate investigation, James Sullivan, Inspector General of the Chicago Public Schools district's Board of Education, released a report of his investigation stating that four student-athletes of a CPS school had one-month grade boosts to alter their college transcripts.<ref name = \"CST grade\">{{cite news|url=http://www.suntimes.com/news/education/1596666,derrick-rose-simeon-grades-cheat-memphis.article|title=Derrick Rose's grade was changed at Simeon High|work=Chicago Sun-Times|accessdate=August 20, 2009|last= Rossi|first= Rosalina|first2= Michael |last2= O'Brien|date=May 28, 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090530202010/http://www.suntimes.com/news/education/1596666,derrick-rose-simeon-grades-cheat-memphis.article|archivedate=May 30, 2009}}</ref> The ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' revealed the school as Simeon Career Academy and that three of the four were Rose and his former teammates Kevin Johnson and Tim Flowers, prominent members of the back-to-back championship teams.<ref name = \"CST grade\"/> The newspaper claimed that Rose's grade was changed from a D to a C.<ref name = \"CST grade\"/> Another part of the report stated that \"high school staff lost the original permanent records for three of the above mentioned students athletes\" (including the unknown four).<ref name = \"CST grade 2\">{{cite web|url=http://csnchicago.com/pages/landing?IHSA-Looks-at-Simeon-Grade-Change-Revela=1&blockID=56385&feedID=629|title=IHSA Looks at Simeon Grade-Change Revelation|work=Chicago Sun-Times|accessdate=August 20, 2009|date=May 28, 2008|first=Michael|last=O'Brien|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090907023303/http://csnchicago.com/pages/landing?IHSA-Looks-at-Simeon-Grade-Change-Revela=1&blockID=56385&feedID=629|archive-date=September 7, 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref> Sullivan started the investigation because \"none of the grade changes were supported by any documentation.\" He also failed to find a suspect as \"at least seven people at Simeon had the ability to access student grades and records.\"<ref name = \"CST grade\"/> [[Illinois High School Association]] (IHSA) executive director Marty Hickman reacted by saying, \"It is obvious that this is worth taking a look into.\"<ref name = \"CST grade 2\"/> Robert Smith, who coached the Wolverines from 2004 to 2007, denied any wrongdoing.<ref name = \"CST grade\"/> District spokeswoman Monique Bond said the students involved probably did not know about the grade change.\n\nAllegations surfaced that Rose's brother, Reggie, had been allowed to travel with the team for free on several occasions.<ref>O'Neil, Dana. [http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/news/story?id=4412279 Memphis also gets 3 years' probation]. [[ESPN]], August 21, 2009.</ref>\n\nMemphis contended that it had learned of the allegations about Rose's SAT score shortly after he enrolled at the school. It conducted its own investigation, in which Rose was questioned by four school officials. Ultimately, Memphis was unable to find any evidence that Rose had cheated based on what was available at the time and cleared him to play.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.commercialappeal.com/news/2009/aug/20/memphis-tigers-found-guilty-ncaa-must-forfeit-2007/|title=Memphis Tigers found guilty by NCAA; must vacate 2007\u201308 basketball season, will appeal \u00bb<!-- Bot generated title -->|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nRose released a statement through his lawyer Daniel E. Reidy: \"Mr. Rose is aware of the allegations reported in the press. Mr. Rose cooperated fully with the University of Memphis' athletic and legal departments\u2019 investigation of this issue when he was a student, and that investigation uncovered no wrongdoing on his part.\"\n\nOn August 20, 2009, the NCAA vacated Memphis' 2007\u201308 season. It took the position that because the [[Educational Testing Service]] voided Rose's [[SAT Reasoning Test|SAT]] score after Rose's freshman year at Memphis, [[strict liability]] required that Rose be retroactively declared ineligible.<ref name=probation>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/news/story?id=4412279|title=NCAA: Memphis must vacate all 2007-08 wins|date=August 20, 2009|website=ESPN.com}}</ref> It also determined that even without the questions about his test score, Rose would have lost his eligibility in December 2007 due to Reggie Rose being allowed to travel for free.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web1.ncaa.org/LSDBi/exec/miSearch?miSearchSubmit=publicReport&key=672&publicTerms=THIS%20PHRASE%20WILL%20NOT%20BE%20REPEATED|title=University of Memphis public infractions report|date=August 20, 2009|publisher=NCAA|accessdate=May 17, 2014|quote=In addition to issues surrounding the academic eligibility of [Derrick Rose], the investigation also revealed that [Rose]'s brother (\"the brother\") had received impermissible benefits in the form of cost-free airline transportation and lodging while traveling with the institution's men's basketball team to road games during the 2007\u201308 season....the violations involving [Rose]'s brother would also have rendered [Rose] ineligible, beginning in mid-December 2007.|pages=1, 15}}</ref>\n\nOn May 28, 2010, Rose, former Memphis basketball coach [[John Calipari]], and Memphis athletic director R.C. Johnson reached a $100,000 [[settlement (litigation)|out-of-court settlement]] with three attorneys who represented Memphis season ticket holders and threatened a lawsuit over the vacated 2007\u201308 season. The Memphis ''[[The Commercial Appeal|Commercial Appeal]]'' first reported on this settlement in October 2011.<ref>{{cite web|author=Veazey, Kyle|url=http://www.commercialappeal.com/news/2011/oct/06/deal-put-price-tag-memphis-tiger-disgrace/|title=Threat of lawsuit brings bonus repayment from John Calipari, R.C. Johnson, donation from Derrick Rose|work=Memphis Commercial Appeal|date=October 7, 2011|accessdate=May 16, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\n\n===Chicago Bulls (2008\u20132016)===\n\n====2008\u201309: Rookie of the Year====\n[[Image:Derrick Rose 02.jpg|thumb|left|Derrick Rose during his rookie season]]\nRose was selected with the first overall pick in the 2008 draft by the [[Chicago Bulls]].<ref name=\"Drafted 1st\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Bulls to pick first in draft; Heat, Wolves round out Top 3|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/draft2008/news/story?id=3405648|agency=Associated Press|publisher=ESPN|date=May 21, 2008|accessdate=January 22, 2009}}</ref> He was selected to the U.S. Select Team to scrimmage against and prepare the [[United States men's national basketball team|National Team]] for the Olympics in Beijing.<ref>{{cite news|title=Select-ive service good for Bulls' Rose, U.S.|url=http://www.suntimes.com/sports/derrickrose/1060547,CST-SPT-bull17.stng|author=Clyde Travis and John Jackson|work=Chicago Sun-Times|date=July 17, 2008|accessdate=February 1, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081204183749/http://www.suntimes.com/sports/derrickrose/1060547,CST-SPT-bull17.stng|archive-date=December 4, 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Hefty praise for Rose|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Basketball/NBA/2009/01/24/8133921-sun.html|author=Mike Ganter|website=slam.canoe.ca|publisher=SLAM! Sports|date=January 24, 2009|accessdate=February 1, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Bulls' Rose learns on the go|url=http://www.suntimes.com/sports/derrickrose/1072443,CST-SPT-1psep24.article|author=Clyde Travis|work=Chicago Sun-Times|date=July 24, 2008|accessdate=February 1, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080727041031/http://www.suntimes.com/sports/derrickrose/1072443,CST-SPT-1psep24.article|archive-date=July 27, 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> In mid-July, he played two games in the [[Orlando Pro Summer League]] until forced out by tendinitis in his right knee, ending his summer,<ref>{{cite news|title=Bulls top pick Rose out with injury|url=http://www.nwherald.com/articles/2008/07/14/sports/nba/bulls/doc4875766d0549b639551119.txt|agency=Associated Press|work=Northwest Herald|date=July 14, 2007|accessdate=July 14, 2008}}{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> but returned in October to play all eight preseason games.<ref>{{cite news|author=Marty Burns|title=Ahead of schedule? No. 1 pick Rose already turning heads with Bulls|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2008/writers/marty_burns/10/27/rose.bulls/index.html|work=Sports Illustrated|date=October 27, 2007|accessdate=February 14, 2006}}</ref>\n\nRose became the first Bulls draftee to score 10 points or more in his first 10 games since [[Michael Jordan]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Early bloomer: Rose already a quiet leader for young Bulls|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/basketball/nba/bulls/2008-12-15-rose-cover_N.htm|author=Mike Dodd|work=USA Today|date=December 15, 2008|accessdate=December 22, 2008}}</ref> and earned Eastern Conference [[NBA Rookie of the Month Award|Rookie of the Month]] honors for November and December.<ref name=\"Nov.08 RoM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnetwork.com/merge/tsnform.aspx?c=sportsnetwork&page=nba/news/news.aspx?id=4195033|title=Rose, Mayo earn NBA rookie honors|author=Information|publisher=Sports Network|date=December 1, 2008|accessdate=December 1, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110622082758/http://www.sportsnetwork.com/merge/tsnform.aspx?c=sportsnetwork&page=nba%2Fnews%2Fnews.aspx%3Fid%3D4195033|archive-date=June 22, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"Dec.08 RoM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/2009/news/01/02/010209rom.release/index.html|title=Bulls' Rose, Thunder's Westbrook named Rookies of the Month|author=NBA Press Release|publisher=NBA|date=January 2, 2009|accessdate=January 3, 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090115124954/http://www.nba.com/2009/news/01/02/010209rom.release/index.html|archivedate=January 15, 2009}}</ref> During [[2009 NBA All-Star Game|the All-Star Weekend]], Rose played in the [[NBA All-Star Weekend Rookie Challenge|Rookie Challenge]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Rose, Mayo top list on Rookie Challenge rosters|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/basketball/nba/bulls/2008-12-15-rose-cover_N.htm|last=Dodd|first=Mike|work=USA Today|date=January 28, 2009|accessdate=November 10, 2009}}</ref> and won the [[NBA All-Star Weekend Skills Challenge|Skills Challenge]], where he beat out several All-Stars to become the first rookie to claim the trophy.<ref name=\"Skills Challenge Victory\">{{cite news|author=John Jacksons|title=Rose shows off mad skills|url=http://www.suntimes.com/sports/basketball/1432070,CST-SPT-skills15.article|work=Chicago Sun-Times|date=February 15, 2009|accessdate=March 14, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090218130327/http://www.suntimes.com/sports/basketball/1432070,CST-SPT-skills15.article|archive-date=February 18, 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref> Overcoming a January and February slump, Rose returned to form and won monthly rookie honors in March. Meanwhile, the Bulls, re-energized by the trade deadline acquisitions of [[John Salmons]] and [[Brad Miller (basketball)|Brad Miller]], finished the regular season on a 12\u20134 spurt to qualify as the seventh seed in the Eastern Conference. Rose won [[NBA Rookie of the Year Award|Rookie of the Year]], joining [[Michael Jordan]] (1985) and [[Elton Brand]] (2000) as the only Bulls to do so.<ref name=\"Rookie of the Year\">{{cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/basketball/bulls/chi-090423-derrick-rose-chicago-bulls-rookie-year,0,4035550.story|title=Chicago Bulls' Derrick Rose named NBA Rookie of the Year|date=April 22, 2009|work=Chicago Tribune|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090423071248/http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/basketball/bulls/chi-090423-derrick-rose-chicago-bulls-rookie-year,0,4035550.story|archivedate=April 23, 2009|access-date=April 22, 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref> He was also the first number-one draft pick since LeBron James to win the award. He averaged 16.8 points on 47.5% field goal shooting, 6.3 assists (leading all rookies) and 3.9 rebounds per game and was also named to the [[NBA All-Rookie First Team]].<ref name=\"All-Rookie Team\">{{cite web|title=Bulls' Derrick Rose a unanimous selection to the 2008\u201309 NBA All-Rookie First Team|url=http://www.nba.com/bulls/news/rose_rookieteam_090430.html|work=Chicago Tribune|date=April 30, 2009|accessdate=May 3, 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090506044213/http://www.nba.com/bulls/news/rose_rookieteam_090430.html|archivedate=May 6, 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn his playoff debut against the defending champion [[Boston Celtics]], Rose recorded 36 points (tying [[Kareem Abdul-Jabbar]]'s NBA record for points scored by a rookie in his playoff debut, set in [[1970 NBA Playoffs|1970]]), 11 assists, and 4 rebounds as the Bulls prevailed in a 105\u2013103 overtime win on the road.<ref>{{cite news|author=Chris Mannix|title=Rose, Rondo put on Game 1 show|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/writers/chris_mannix/04/18/bulls.celtics.game.1/index.html|work=Sports Illustrated|date=April 18, 2009 |accessdate=November 10, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Rose testing Celtics' ailing defense|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/writers/chris_mannix/04/20/celtics.bulls.preview/index.html|author=Chris Mannix|work=Sports Illustrated|date=April 20, 2009|accessdate=November 10, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/writers/steve_aschburner/04/18/day1.analysis/index.html|title=Rose testing Celtics' ailing defense|author=Steve Aschburner|work=Sports Illustrated|date=April 20, 2009|accessdate=November 10, 2009}}</ref> Rose became the second player in NBA history to record 35 points and 10 assists in his playoff debut, after [[Chris Paul]]. Rose averaged 19.7 points on 47.5% shooting, 6.3 assists and 4.9 rebounds per game in his first playoff series, as the Bulls were defeated by the Celtics in seven games.<ref>nba.com, [http://www.nba.com/playerfile/derrick_rose/career_stats.html Derrick Rose Career Stats Page] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120530005556/http://www.nba.com/playerfile/derrick_rose/career_stats.html |date=May 30, 2012 }}, accessed October 29, 2009.</ref>\n\n====2009\u201311: All-Star season and MVP campaign====\nRose's sophomore season started off with an ankle injury in his first preseason game. Rose would go on to miss the rest of the preseason. Rose started the Bulls' season opener against the [[San Antonio Spurs]] but played limited minutes. Rose's ankle bothered him for most of November, but as his ankle healed, his game improved. On January 28, 2010, Rose was elected to his first career [[2010 NBA All-Star Game|All-Star Game]] as a reserve for the Eastern Conference, making him the first Bulls player to be selected since [[Michael Jordan]] in 1998.<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/chicago/nba/news/story?id=4867386 Bulls' Rose selected to All-Star team], accessed January 28, 2010.</ref> Rose ended up with eight points, four assists and three steals in the game. On April 13, 2010, Rose scored 39 points against the Celtics, making 15\u201322 field goals and 9\u201310 free throws. The Bulls once again made the playoffs in the 2009\u201310 season, finishing with a 41\u201341 record. In the playoffs Rose averaged 26.8 points and 7.2 assists, but the Bulls lost in five games to the [[Cleveland Cavaliers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/playerfile/derrick_rose/index.html|title=Official NBA bio of Derrick Rose - NBA.com|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:Derrick Rose 2.jpg|thumb|right|Rose led the Bulls to 62 wins, and the best record overall, during the 2010\u201311 NBA season.]]\nOn October 30, 2010, in the Bulls' second game of the season, Rose scored 39 points in a 101\u201391 win against the [[Detroit Pistons]]. Two days after, Rose contributed 13 assists, helping [[Luol Deng]] score a career high 40 points in a win against the [[Portland Trail Blazers]]. On December 10, Rose scored 29 points and had 9 assists, leading the Bulls to their first victory over the [[Los Angeles Lakers]] since December 19, 2006.\n\nOn January 17, 2011, Rose recorded his first career [[triple-double]] with 22 points, 10 rebounds and 12 assists in a 96\u201384 win over the [[Memphis Grizzlies]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/games/20110117/CHIMEM/gameinfo.html|title=Bulls at Grizzlies|publisher=}}</ref> On January 27, he was announced as a starting guard on the [[2011 NBA All-Star Game|2011 NBA All-Star Team]] for the East squad.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/allstar/2011/|title=NBA.com - 2011 All-Star Events|website=www.nba.com|access-date=January 28, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110221215029/http://www.nba.com/allstar/2011/|archive-date=February 21, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn February 17, in the Bulls' last game before the All-Star break, Rose set a career-high with 42 points, while also recording 8 assists and 5 rebounds, as the Bulls beat the [[San Antonio Spurs]] 109\u201399. On March 26, Rose had a career high 17 assists, along with 30 points, in a 95\u201387 victory over the [[Milwaukee Bucks]].\n\nAt the end of the [[2010\u201311 NBA season]] the Bulls finished with a league leading record of 62\u201320.<ref>{{cite news|title=NBA Standings&nbsp;\u2013 2010\u201311|url=http://espn.go.com/nba/standings/_/year/2011/seasontype/2|newspaper=ESPN}}</ref> Their 60+ wins was the Bulls' first such season since [[1997\u201398 NBA season|1997\u201398]] and sixth 60+ win in franchise history.<ref>{{cite news|title=Chicago Bulls Power Rankings&nbsp;\u2013 2010\u201311|url=http://espn.go.com/nba/standings/_/year/2011/seasontype/2|newspaper=ESPN}}</ref> At season's end, Rose became only the third player since the [[1972\u201373 NBA season]] to record 2,000 points and 600 assists in a single season. The other two players were [[LeBron James]] and [[Michael Jordan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/654658-derrick-rose-the-surprisingly-historic-numbers-of-his-mvp-seeason|title=Derrick Rose: The Surprisingly Historic Numbers of His MVP Season|first=Kelly|last=Scaletta|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nOn May 3, Rose was named the [[NBA Most Valuable Player]], joining [[Michael Jordan]] as the only players to receive the award in Chicago Bulls history.<ref name=\"NBA.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/2011/news/05/03/mvp-award/index.html?ls=iref:nbahpt1|title=Chicago's Derrick Rose Wins 2010\u201311 Kia NBA MVP Award|publisher=NBA.com|accessdate=May 3, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110505081553/http://www.nba.com/2011/news/05/03/mvp-award/index.html?ls=iref%3Anbahpt1|archivedate=May 5, 2011}}</ref> At 22 years and 6 months old, Rose also became the youngest player to receive the award ([[Wes Unseld]], formerly the youngest MVP, won the award in 1968\u201369 at age 23 years, 2 months).\n\nIn the 2011 NBA Playoffs, the Bulls defeated the [[2010\u201311 Indiana Pacers season|Indiana Pacers]] and [[2010\u201311 Atlanta Hawks season|Atlanta Hawks]] in the first two rounds. In the Eastern Conference Finals, the Bulls faced the [[2010\u201311 Miami Heat season|Miami Heat]], led by [[LeBron James]], [[Dwyane Wade]] and [[Chris Bosh]]. The Bulls lost the series in five games. During the 2011 playoffs, Rose averaged 27.1 points per game, but only shot 39% from the field and 24% for three-pointers.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chicago Bulls-Miami Heat recap|url=http://espn.go.com/nba/recap/_/id/310306014/chicago-bulls-vs-miami-heat}}</ref>\n\n====2011\u201312: ACL tear====\nIn December 2011, Rose signed a five-year contract extension with the Bulls for $94.8 million. The contract was 30&nbsp;percent of the Bulls' salary cap, the maximum allowed under a rule dubbed the \"[[Derrick Rose Rule]]\" from the 2011 [[NBA Collective Bargaining Agreement]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Source: New deal for Derrick Rose |date=December 21, 2011 |work=ESPNChicago.com |url=http://espn.go.com/chicago/nba/story/_/id/7374147/source-chicago-bulls-derrick-rose-agrees-five-year-extension |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/64YlYlGVi?url=http://espn.go.com/chicago/nba/story/_/id/7374147/source-chicago-bulls-derrick-rose-agrees-five-year-extension |archivedate=January 9, 2012 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\nRose was voted as an All-Star Game starter for the second consecutive year. He was the second leading vote getter behind Orlando Magic center [[Dwight Howard]]. He averaged 21.8 ppg, along with a career high 7.9 apg in 35.3 mpg, but played a career low 39 games due to injuries. He helped [[Luol Deng]] become an All-Star for the first time in his career.\n\nDuring Game 1 of the first round of the [[2012 NBA Playoffs|playoffs]] against the [[2011\u201312 Philadelphia 76ers season|Philadelphia 76ers]], Rose injured his left knee while trying to jump. He was immediately helped off the court. The injury occurred when the Bulls were leading by 12 points with 1:22 left to play. Rose came up just short of a triple-double, finishing with 23 points, 9 assists, and 9 rebounds in 37 minutes of action.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://sports.espn.go.com/chicago/nba/news/story?id=7868184|title=Tom Thibodeau defends decision|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|accessdate=April 28, 2012|date=April 28, 2012|first=Roman |last=Modrowski}}</ref> An [[Magnetic resonance imaging|MRI]] later revealed that Rose tore the [[Anterior cruciate ligament|ACL]] in his left knee and would miss the rest of the playoffs.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://espn.go.com/chicago/nba/story/_/id/7866701/2012-nba-playoffs-chicago-bulls-derrick-rose-suffers-torn-acl-philadelphia-76ers|title=Bulls' Derrick Rose tears ACL|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|accessdate=April 28, 2012|date=April 28, 2012|first=Scott|last=Powers}}</ref> Rose had surgery performed on May 12, 2012, with an estimated recovery period of 8\u201312 months.<ref name=\"andrews\" />\n\n====2012\u201313: Year absence====\nRose returned to full contact practice in January 2013,<ref name=\"Return to full contact\">{{cite news|url=http://espn.go.com/chicago/nba/story/_/id/8897736/derrick-rose-chicago-bulls-taking-full-contact-practice|title=Derrick Rose taking full contact|last=Friedell|first=Nick|date=January 31, 2013|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=February 9, 2013}}</ref> and was cleared by doctor to play that March,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://espn.go.com/chicago/nba/story/_/id/9031045/derrick-rose-chicago-bulls-cleared-play-waiting-dunk-confidently-left-foot-source-says|title=Source: Derrick Rose cleared to play|last=Isaacson|first=Melissa|date=March 9, 2013|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=November 25, 2013}}</ref> but he did not appear in a game during the [[2012\u201313 NBA season]]. Despite Rose's absence, the Bulls advanced to the Eastern Conference Semifinals, where they lost to the eventual champions, the [[2012\u201313 Miami Heat season|Miami Heat]].\n\n====2013\u201314: Return and torn meniscus====\nRose's much awaited return came on October 5, 2013, in a pre-season game against the [[2013\u201314 Indiana Pacers season|Indiana Pacers]]. He had a slow start but scored his first point in the first quarter. He finished the game with 13 points in 20 minutes of play.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/chicago/nba/story/_/id/9778651/derrick-rose-returns-chicago-bulls-first-knee-injury|title=Derrick Rose agrressive in return|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|accessdate=October 6, 2013|date=October 5, 2013|first=Nick|last=Friedell}}</ref> On October 16, 2013, Rose returned to play in Chicago for the first time, scoring 22 points against the [[2013\u201314 Detroit Pistons season|Detroit Pistons]]. \"I think I'm way more explosive now. Like getting to the rim. I think I can take contact a little bit better. And as far as jumping-wise, I think I can jump even higher. They tested my vertical -- I increased it by 5 inches\", Rose said after the win.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/chicago/nba/story/_/id/9837096/derrick-rose-says-way-more-explosive-following-recovery|title=Derrick Rose: I'm more explosive now|date=October 17, 2013|accessdate=November 23, 2013|work=ESPN.com|first=Nick|last=Friedell}}</ref> During the pre-season, Rose averaged 20.7 points and 5 assists.\n\nHis first official game was in 107\u201395 loss against the defending champions [[2013\u201314 Miami Heat season|Miami Heat]] on October 29. Rose was limited to 12 points, while having 4 assists in 34 minutes of play. He played his usual minutes, but was inefficient from the field, shooting 4\u201315.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=400488875|title=Heat get championship rings, spoil Derrick Rose's return|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|accessdate=October 29, 2013|date=October 29, 2013|first=Nick|last=Friedell}}</ref> Two days later, he played his first official home game against the [[2013\u201314 New York Knicks season|New York Knicks]] where he hit the game-winning floater in an 82\u201381 win. He had 18 points, 6 rebounds and 3 assists.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=400488891|title=Derrick Rose's floater lifts Bulls over Knicks in home opener|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|accessdate=October 31, 2013|date=October 31, 2013|first=Jon|last=Greenburg}}</ref> On November 3, 2013, Rose scored 13 points and committed 8 turnovers in the loss against the [[2013\u201314 Philadelphia 76ers season|Philadelphia 76ers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=400488907|title=Sixers (3-0) stun Bulls to continue surprising start to season|date=November 3, 2013|accessdate=November 23, 2013|work=ESPN.com}}</ref> He struggled in his return, shooting 28.8% from the field and averaging 5.7 turnovers in his first three games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/basketball/bulls/chi-derrick-rose-chicago-bulls-turnovers-20131103,0,5091853.story|title=Bulls' Rose unfazed by his slow start|date=November 3, 2013|accessdate=November 23, 2013|work=Chicago Tribune|first=K. C. |last=Johnson}}</ref>\n\nOn November 22, Rose injured his right knee during a game against the [[2013\u201314 Portland Trail Blazers season|Portland Trail Blazers]]. An MRI the next day confirmed that Rose tore his right knee meniscus and that surgery was required.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/chicago/nba/story/_/id/10025640/derrick-rose-chicago-bulls-indefinitely-needs-surgery-torn-medial-meniscus-knee|title=Derrick Rose out indefinitely|work=ESPN.com|accessdate=November 23, 2013|date=November 23, 2013}}</ref> At the time, Rose was averaging 15.9 points and 4.3 assists in 31.1 minutes per game. On November 25, Rose underwent surgery on the torn meniscus in his right knee.<ref name=\"tribune\" /> The same day, the Bulls announced Rose was out for the season, after a successful surgery.<ref>K.C. Johnson, [http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/basketball/bulls/chi-derrick-rose-knee-surgery-bulls-20131125,0,7186905.story \"Bulls' Derrick Rose out for season after knee surgery\"], ''Chicago Tribune'', November 25, 2013.</ref>\n\n====2014\u201315: Back to the playoffs====\n[[File:Derrick Rose during a timeout.jpg|thumbnail|Rose during a timeout in 2015]]\nRose returned from injury to play in the Bulls' season opener against the New York Knicks on October 29, 2014 and recorded 13 points and 5 assists in 21 minutes of action. He went on to score a season-high 32 points on January 14 against the Washington Wizards,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=400578871|title=Wizards vs. Bulls - Game Recap - January 14, 2015 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com}}</ref> before being ruled out again with another knee injury a month later. He appeared in 51 games, the most he'd played since the 2010\u201311 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/r/rosede01/gamelog/2015/|title=Derrick Rose 2014-15 Game Log - Basketball-Reference.com|website=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref>\n\nOn February 24, it was announced Rose required another round of surgery on his right knee and was ruled out indefinitely. An exam and subsequent MRI confirmed a medial meniscus tear of the right knee, the same injury he sustained on November 22, 2013 against the Portland Trail Blazers.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cohen|first1=Jay|title=Bulls' Rose to have surgery on torn meniscus|url=http://www.nba.com/2015/news/02/24/bulls-rose-meniscus-knee-surgery-wire.ap/index.html|work=NBA.com|date=February 24, 2015|accessdate=February 25, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Derrick Rose to have knee repaired|url=http://espn.go.com/chicago/nba/story/_/id/12378016/chicago-bulls-guard-derrick-rose-undergo-surgery-repair-torn-meniscus-table-uncertain|work=ESPN.com|date=February 25, 2015|accessdate=February 25, 2015}}</ref> On February 27, he was deemed a possibility of returning toward the end of the season after he underwent successful surgery and was ruled out for just four to six weeks.<ref>{{cite news|last=Johnson|first=K. C.|title=Bulls expect Derrick Rose back this season after successful surgery|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/basketball/bulls/chi-derrick-rose-knee-surgery-update-20150227-story.html|date=February 27, 2015|accessdate=February 27, 2015|work=ChicagoTribune.com}}</ref>\n\nRose returned to action on April 8 after a 20-game absence, and working on a minutes restriction, he was 3-of-9 from the field and finished with nine points in 19 minutes as the Bulls lost to the Orlando Magic.<ref>{{cite news|title=Magic, Oladipo spoil Rose's return in 105-103 win over Bulls|url=http://www.nba.com/games/20150408/CHIORL/gameinfo.html|date=April 8, 2015|accessdate=April 9, 2015|work=NBA.com}}</ref>\n\nOn April 18, Rose played in his first playoff game since Game 1 of the 2012 playoffs (the game where he tore his left ACL). Rose finished with 23 points and 7 assists on 9-of-16 shooting.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rose scores 23, Bulls beat Bucks 103-91|url=http://www.nba.com/games/20150418/MILCHI/gameinfo.html|work=NBA.com|date=April 18, 2015|accessdate=May 9, 2015}}</ref> During the Bulls' first round series against the Bucks, Rose averaged 21.5 points per game. On May 8, Rose banked in a three-pointer at the buzzer and scored 30 points to give the Bulls a 99-96 victory over the Cleveland Cavaliers and a 2-1 lead in the Eastern Conference semi-finals.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rose banks in 3 at buzzer to lift Bulls over Cavaliers 99-96|url=http://www.nba.com/games/20150508/CLECHI/gameinfo.html|work=NBA.com|date=May 9, 2015|accessdate=May 9, 2015}}</ref> However, the Cavaliers won the final three games to take the series in six games.\n\n====2015\u201316: Final season with the Bulls====\nA preseason left orbital bone fracture saw Rose begin the regular season wearing a face mask.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/bulls/news/derrick-rose-injury-update-0|title=Derrick Rose injury update - Chicago Bulls|publisher=}}</ref> On November 5, 2015, Rose scored a then season-high 29 points on 12-of-25 shooting in a 104\u201398 win over the Oklahoma City Thunder. He showed signs of his old MVP self as he scored 10 points over the final three and a half minutes to lift the Bulls after they blew a 10-point lead in the fourth quarter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/games/20151105/OKCCHI/gameinfo.html|title=Thunder vs Bulls|publisher=|access-date=November 6, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160330131313/http://www.nba.com/games/20151105/OKCCHI/gameinfo.html|archive-date=March 30, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> On December 18, he scored a season-high 34 points in a 147\u2013144 quadruple overtime loss to the Detroit Pistons.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/games/20151218/DETCHI/gameinfo.html|title=Drummond leads way, Pistons beat Bulls 147-144 in 4 OT|work=NBA.com|date=December 18, 2015|accessdate=December 18, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151220053332/http://www.nba.com/games/20151218/DETCHI/gameinfo.html|archive-date=December 20, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> On February 5, 2016, he had a season-best game with 30 points, 9 rebounds and 8 assists in a 115\u2013110 loss to the Denver Nuggets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/games/20160205/CHIDEN/gameinfo.html|title=Nuggets rally for win after Bulls lose Butler to injury|work=NBA.com|date=February 5, 2016|accessdate=February 5, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160401182618/http://www.nba.com/games/20160205/CHIDEN/gameinfo.html|archive-date=April 1, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===New York Knicks (2016\u20132017)===\n[[File:Kyrie Irving (30602635845).jpg|thumb|Rose defending [[Kyrie Irving]] in 2016]]\nOn June 22, 2016, Rose was traded, along with [[Justin Holiday]] and a 2017 second-round draft pick, to the [[New York Knicks]] in exchange for future teammate [[Jos\u00e9 Calder\u00f3n (basketball)|Jos\u00e9 Calder\u00f3n]], [[Jerian Grant]] and [[Robin Lopez]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/knicks/knicks-acquire-derrick-rose|title=Knicks Acquire Derrick Rose|work=NBA.com|date=June 22, 2016|accessdate=June 22, 2016}}</ref> He made his debut for the Knicks in the team's season opener on October 25 against the [[Cleveland Cavaliers]]. In 29 minutes of action, he scored 17 points on 7-of-17 shooting in a 117\u201388 loss.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400899375|title=James has triple-double as Cavs rout Knicks 117-88 in opener|work=ESPN.com|date=October 25, 2016|accessdate=October 25, 2016}}</ref> On November 4, Rose returned to Chicago for the first time as a member of the Knicks, recording 15 points and 11 assists in a 117\u2013104 win over the Bulls.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400899523|title=Knicks rally past Bulls 117-104 in Rose, Noah homecoming|work=ESPN.com|date=November 4, 2016|accessdate=November 5, 2016}}</ref> On November 17, he scored a season-high 27 points in a 119\u2013112 loss to the [[Washington Wizards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbssports.com/fantasy/basketball/news/knicks-derrick-rose-sets-season-high-with-27-points/|title=Knicks' Derrick Rose: Sets season high with 27 points|work=cbssports.com|date=November 17, 2016|accessdate=November 18, 2016}}</ref> He topped that mark on November 28, scoring 30 points in a 112\u2013103 loss to the [[Oklahoma City Thunder]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400899705|title=Westbrook with another triple-double as Thunder stop Knicks|work=ESPN.com|date=November 28, 2016|accessdate=November 29, 2016}}</ref> On January 10, 2017, Rose was fined an undisclosed amount after he reportedly flew to Chicago to be with his mother but did not notify team officials ahead of their game against the [[New Orleans Pelicans]] on January 9.<ref>{{cite web|last=Begley|first=Ian|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/18445112/new-york-knicks-derrick-rose-returns-team-going-awol|title=Derrick Rose: Missed Knicks game to tend to Chicago family issue|work=ESPN.com|date=January 10, 2017|accessdate=January 10, 2017}}</ref> Eight days later, he matched his season high with 30 points in a 117\u2013106 win over the [[Boston Celtics]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400900051|title=Rose powers slumping Knicks past Celtics 117-106|work=ESPN.com|date=January 18, 2017|accessdate=January 19, 2017}}</ref> On April 2, 2017, he was ruled out for the rest of the season after tearing the meniscus in his left knee, necessitating a fourth round of knee surgery for Rose in his nine-year career.<ref>{{cite web|last=Carbaugh|first=Dane|url=http://nba.nbcsports.com/2017/04/02/report-knicks-g-derrick-rose-tears-meniscus-in-knee-will-miss-rest-of-the-season/|title=Report: Knicks G Derrick Rose tears meniscus in knee, will miss rest of the season|work=NBCSports.com|date=April 2, 2017|accessdate=April 2, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Cleveland Cavaliers (2017\u20132018)===\n[[File:Derrick Rose (37670935991) (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|Rose with the Cavaliers in 2017]]\nOn July 25, 2017, Rose signed with the [[Cleveland Cavaliers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/cavaliers/releases/rose-signing-2017|title=Cavaliers Sign Derrick Rose|work=NBA.com|date=July 25, 2017|accessdate=July 25, 2017}}</ref> In his debut for the Cavaliers in their season opener against the [[Boston Celtics]] on October 17, 2017, Rose scored 14 points in a 102\u201399 win.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400974437|title=Hayward breaks ankle, Cavs hold off Celtics 102-99 in opener|work=ESPN.com|date=October 17, 2017|accessdate=October 17, 2017}}</ref> On November 24, 2017, Rose left the team to re-evaluate his future in the NBA. His increasing frustration with injuries caused him to question his desire to continue playing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/21540075/derrick-rose-away-cleveland-cavaliers-evaluating-future-nba|title=Derrick Rose away from Cavs, evaluating future in NBA|work=ESPN.com|date=November 24, 2017|accessdate=November 25, 2017}}</ref> He returned to working with the Cavaliers' medical staff in early December in hopes of recovering from a sprained left ankle and bone spurs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/article/2018/01/17/cleveland-cavaliers-derrick-rose-thinks-he-will-play-thursday-vs-orlando-magic#/|title=Derrick Rose thinks he will be OK to play Thursday vs. Orlando Magic|work=NBA.com|date=January 17, 2018|accessdate=January 18, 2018}}</ref> On January 18, 2018, Rose returned to the line-up after missing more than two months with ankle injuries and scored nine points in 13 minutes in a 104\u2013103 win over the [[Orlando Magic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400975410|title=Cavaliers blow big lead, hang on to beat Magic 104-103|work=ESPN.com|date=January 18, 2018|accessdate=January 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn February 8, 2018, Rose was acquired by the [[Utah Jazz]] in a three-team trade that also involved the Cavaliers and the [[Sacramento Kings]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/jazz/news/jazz-acquire-jae-crowder-and-derrick-rose-three-team-trade|title=Jazz Acquire Jae Crowder and Derrick Rose in Three-Team Trade|work=NBA.com|date=February 8, 2018|accessdate=February 8, 2018}}</ref> Two days later, he was waived by the Jazz.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/jazz/news/jazz-waive-derrick-rose|title=Jazz Waive Derrick Rose|work=NBA.com|date=February 10, 2018|accessdate=February 10, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Minnesota Timberwolves (2018\u20132019)===\nOn March 8, 2018, Rose signed with the [[Minnesota Timberwolves]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/timberwolves/timberwolves-sign-derrick-rose|title=TIMBERWOLVES SIGN DERRICK ROSE|work=NBA.com|date=March 8, 2018|accessdate=March 8, 2018}}</ref> reuniting him with [[Tom Thibodeau]], [[Jimmy Butler]] and [[Taj Gibson]]. In the playoffs, Rose averaged 14.2 points in 23.8 minutes per game, as the Timberwolves lost 4\u20131 to the [[Houston Rockets]] in the first round.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/r/rosede01/gamelog/2018/|title=Derrick Rose 2017-18 Game Log|work=Basketball-Reference.com|accessdate=May 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn July 4, 2018, Rose re-signed with the Timberwolves for the [[2018\u201319 Minnesota Timberwolves season|2018\u201319 season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nba.com/timberwolves/news/timberwolves-sign-derrick-rose|title=TIMBERWOLVES SIGN DERRICK ROSE|work=NBA.com|date=July 4, 2018|accessdate=July 4, 2018}}</ref> On October 31, in his first start of the season, Rose scored a career-high 50 points in a 128\u2013125 win over the [[Utah Jazz]], securing the victory with a block on Utah's final shot as time expired.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401070788|title=Rose scores career-high 50 as Timberwolves top Jazz 128-125|work=ESPN.com|date=October 31, 2018|accessdate=October 31, 2018}}</ref> On December 26, he had 24 points and eight assists and received MVP chants in a 119\u201394 win over the Bulls in Chicago. It was just his second career game in the [[United Center]] against his former team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401071183|title=Rose returns to Chicago, leads T-Wolves over Bulls 119-94|work=ESPN.com|date=December 26, 2018|accessdate=December 27, 2018}}</ref> On January 15 against the [[Philadelphia 76ers]], Rose reached 10,000 career points.<ref>{{cite web|last=Andrews|first=Julian|url=https://www.nba.com/timberwolves/news/derrick-rose-reaches-10000-point-milestone-0|title=DERRICK ROSE REACHES 10,000-POINT MILESTONE|work=NBA.com|date=January 15, 2019|accessdate=January 20, 2019}}</ref> On January 20, he scored 29 of his 31 points in the second half and hit an 18-footer with 0.6 seconds left to give the Timberwolves a 116\u2013114 victory over the [[Phoenix Suns]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401071365|title=Rose hits last-second, Timberwolves beat Suns 116-114|work=ESPN.com|date=January 20, 2019|accessdate=January 20, 2019}}</ref> Right ankle trouble saw Rose miss 11 of 19 games spanning late December to late January.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401071456|title=Jokic's triple-double helps Nuggets beat Wolves 107-106|work=ESPN.com|date=February 2, 2019|accessdate=February 2, 2019}}</ref> He missed an additional three games in early February.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401071518|title=Healthy Rose, Teague lead Timberwolves past Clippers 130-120|work=ESPN.com|date=February 11, 2019|accessdate=February 12, 2019}}</ref> On March 21, he was ruled out for the rest of the season with a right elbow injury.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nba.com/timberwolves/news/minnesota-timberwolves-medical-updates|title=MINNESOTA TIMBERWOLVES MEDICAL UPDATES|work=NBA.com|date=March 21, 2019|accessdate=March 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Detroit Pistons (2019\u2013present)===\nOn July 7, 2019, Rose signed with the [[Detroit Pistons]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nba.com/pistons/news/detroit-pistons-sign-free-agent-derrick-rose|title=Detroit Pistons Sign Free Agent Derrick Rose|work=NBA.com|date=July 7, 2019|accessdate=July 7, 2019}}</ref>  Rose became the first player in Pistons\u2019 history to record seven consecutive 20+ point games as a reserve which also coincides in his career-high 14-streak of scoring 20 points or more.<ref>https://pistonpowered.com/2020/01/16/rose-historic-streak-detroit-pistons/</ref>  The streak ended after suffering a groin injury during a game with the Denver Nuggets.<ref>https://clutchpoints.com/pistons-news-derrick-roses-career-high-20-point-streak-over-due-to-groin-injury/</ref> In his third game after returning from Injury, Rose scored a season high 31 points en route to a win against the [[Phoenix Suns]].<ref>https://theathletic.com/1643761/2020/02/29/being-derrick-rose-one-game-through-the-eyes-of-the-pistons-point-guard/</ref><ref>https://clutchpoints.com/pistons-news-kendrick-perkins-perplexed-why-derrick-rose-is-still-on-detroit/</ref>\n\n==National team career==\nRose was a member of the [[United States men's national basketball team]]s that won gold medals at the [[2010 United States men's FIBA World Championship team|2010]] and [[2014 United States FIBA Basketball World Cup team|2014 FIBA World Cup]].\n\n==Player profile==\nStanding at {{convert|6|ft|2|in|m|abbr=}} and weighing {{convert|200|lb||abbr=}}, Rose plays mostly at the [[point guard]] position. He averages 18.8 points per game for his career.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/playerfile/derrick_rose/career_stats.html |title=Derrick Rose Career statistics Page |publisher=NBA.com |date=October 4, 1988 |accessdate=August 10, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120530005556/http://www.nba.com/playerfile/derrick_rose/career_stats.html |archive-date=May 30, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He has never been a knock-down shooter from the arc, shooting 30 percent for his career.<ref>{{cite web|last=Cahill|first=Dan|url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/sports/derrick-rose-shooting-problems-begin-at-the-rim/|title=Derrick Rose shooting problems begin at the rim|work=chicago.suntimes.com|date=December 9, 2015|accessdate=January 18, 2018}}</ref> He developed into a bank-shot shooter during the 2015\u201316 season after struggling with his jump shot due to what he attributes to depth perception issues following eye surgery in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|last=Schwerha|first=Matthew|url=http://chicago.suntimes.com/sports/7/71/1107949/derrick-rose-bank-shot|title=Derrick Rose has found a go-to move in his bank shot|work=chicago.suntimes.com|date=November 17, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151120045816/http://chicago.suntimes.com/sports/7/71/1107949/derrick-rose-bank-shot|archivedate=November 20, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Cahill|first=Dan|url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/sports/derrick-rose-is-shooting-70-percent-on-bank-shots/|title=Derrick Rose is shooting 70 percent on bank shots|work=chicago.suntimes.com|date=February 22, 2016|accessdate=January 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{NBA player statistics legend}}\n\n===NBA===\n====Regular season====\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{nbay|2008}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2008\u201309 Chicago Bulls season|Chicago]]\n| '''81''' || 80 || 37.0 || .475 || .222 || .788 || 3.9 || 6.3 || .8 || .2 || 16.8\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| 